const CARDS = [{"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What is the Caprini score and what organization formally recommends its use for plastic surgery patients?", "answer": "The 2005 Caprini score is a widely validated VTE risk stratification tool that creates an aggregate risk score based on ~40 individual risk factors. It is formally recommended by the American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) and the American College of Chest Physicians (ACCP).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "For plastic surgery inpatients, what is the approximate range of VTE risk identified by the Caprini score?", "answer": "The Caprini score identifies approximately a 20-fold variation in VTE risk among plastic surgery inpatients, ranging from 0.3% to 8.5%.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "A patient on warfarin for atrial fibrillation needs elective plastic surgery. Based on Level I evidence from the BRIDGE trial, describe the perioperative anticoagulation management.", "answer": "Warfarin should be stopped 5 days prior to the procedure and re-initiated 24 hours after surgery (or at surgeon discretion). Bridging therapy with LMWH should NOT be routinely performed, as it did not significantly reduce arterial thromboembolism (0.3% vs 0.4%) but did increase major bleeding (3.2% vs 1.3%).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "How long before and after surgery should oral contraceptives or hormone replacement therapy be discontinued to reduce VTE risk?", "answer": "3 weeks before and 3 weeks after surgery to allow VTE risk to return to normal levels. However, patients must be counseled about unintended consequences (menstrual irregularity, unintended pregnancy, menopausal symptoms).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Describe the mechanism by which sequential compression devices (SCDs) reduce VTE risk, including both local and systemic effects.", "answer": "Locally, SCDs recapitulate the calf muscle pump and physically propel blood out of the lower extremities, reducing venous stasis. Systemically, they augment head-to-toe fibrinolysis through increased fibrinolytic tPA (tissue plasminogen activator) and decreased PAI-1 (plasminogen activator inhibitor-1) levels.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "At what Caprini score threshold do plastic surgery inpatients benefit from postoperative enoxaparin prophylaxis? What are the specific VTE risk reductions?", "answer": "Caprini score >= 7. Per the VTEPS study: Caprini >8 patients had 60-day VTE decrease from 8.5% to 4.1%; Caprini 7-8 patients decreased from 2.6% to 1.2%. Routine anticoagulation carries a 0.7% increased risk for re-operative hematoma.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What Level I evidence supports weight-based dosing of enoxaparin for VTE prophylaxis, and what is the recommended dose?", "answer": "The FIVE (Fixed or Variable Enoxaparin) trial showed that weight-based dosing at 0.5 mg/kg BID optimizes pharmacokinetics compared to one-size-fits-all dosing.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "A patient is traveling by air 1 week after cosmetic surgery. What does the evidence say about DVT risk during long flights, and what is recommended?", "answer": "Duplex ultrasound studies show 4.5% of asymptomatic travelers develop DVT during trans-Pacific flights (Coach Class Syndrome). Level I evidence shows 20-30 mmHg compression stockings decrease asymptomatic DVT risk from 4.5% to 0.25%.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Why does abdominal wall plication increase DVT risk? Include the specific pressure changes.", "answer": "Plication increases intra-abdominal pressure (2-6 mmHg in abdominoplasty, 4-8 mmHg in DIEP). This increased pressure is transmitted to the inferior vena cava, causing increased common femoral vein pressure, resulting in bilateral lower extremity venous stasis and dilation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Compare the VTE risk with abdominoplasty vs the overall aesthetics population.", "answer": "Abdominoplasty patients have a VTE rate of ~0.2% vs ~0.09% in the overall aesthetics population - more than double the baseline risk, likely due to plication, longer operative times, and concurrent procedures.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What is the relationship between OR time and VTE risk?", "answer": "A linear relationship exists between time spent in the operating room and risk for VTE. Similarly, combined procedures carry increased VTE risk compared to single procedures.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Malignant hyperthermia awareness", "question": "What is malignant hyperthermia (MH), what triggers it, and what are the initial signs vs late signs?", "answer": "MH is an autosomal dominant disorder causing a life-threatening reaction to succinylcholine and volatile anesthetics, resulting in uncontrolled skeletal muscle metabolism. Initial signs: increased end-tidal CO2, tachycardia, and/or muscle rigidity. Increased body temperature is a LATE sign. Treatment: IV dantrolene and removal of the offending agent, plus cardiovascular support.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Fire risk in OR", "question": "What three factors combine to create the fire triad in the operating room? Give examples of each.", "answer": "The fire triad (per AORN) consists of: (1) Ignition sources: electrocautery, laser beams, frayed cords; (2) Fuel sources: draping material, hair, clothes, mattresses, foam padding, alcohol-based skin prep; (3) Oxidizers: oxygen delivered via nasal cannula or open masks that builds up underneath drapes.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Fire risk in OR", "question": "What strategies reduce fire risk in the operating room?", "answer": "Set audible activation tones for electrocautery units, keep electrocautery in a holster, and avoid grounding pad failure (from fluid on pad, dryness of adhesive gel, or inappropriate location over metal, tattoos, or bony prominence).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Pressure injury prevention in long cases", "question": "What temperature defines intraoperative hypothermia, and what are its consequences?", "answer": "Hypothermia = core body temperature below 36 degrees C (98.6 F). It is correlated with increased risk of postoperative surgical site infection and platelet dysfunction. Regional and general anesthesia interfere with homeostatic temperature maintenance, requiring active warming.", "notes": "Closest match; content relates to intraoperative temperature management", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Local anesthetic toxicity", "question": "What is the standard acceptable lidocaine dose, and how does this differ in the tumescent liposuction setting?", "answer": "Standard: 5-7 mg/kg. For liposuction with tumescent technique (paired with epinephrine): up to 35 mg/kg. The higher dose is safe because fat is poorly vascularized, slowing absorption, and epinephrine further vasoconstricts.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Local anesthetic toxicity", "question": "Describe the progression of lidocaine toxicity symptoms by plasma level.", "answer": "3-6 mcg/mL: light-headedness, tinnitus, slurred speech, metallic taste, lip/tongue numbness. Above 10 mcg/mL: CNS depression. Above 20 mcg/mL: respiratory depression and cardiac arrest.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Local anesthetic toxicity", "question": "When performing multi-site liposuction, why does the timing of peak plasma lidocaine levels matter?", "answer": "In fat (poorly vascularized), plasma lidocaine peaks ~12 hours after infiltration with epinephrine. In more vascular areas like the head and neck, levels peak ~6 hours after infiltration. This difference is critical for multi-site procedures to avoid toxicity.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Gluteal fat grafting safety awareness", "question": "What is the mortality rate associated with gluteal fat grafting, and what is the mechanism of death?", "answer": "Published mortality rates: 1:2,351 to 1:6,241, the highest of any aesthetic procedure. 3% of surgeons report a patient death from fat embolism. Mechanism: grafted fat placed intravascularly travels through superior/inferior gluteal veins to iliac vein to central circulation, causing pulmonary fat embolism.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Gluteal fat grafting safety awareness", "question": "What are the current safety guidelines for gluteal fat grafting to minimize fat embolism risk?", "answer": "Subcutaneous fat injection ONLY (avoid intramuscular), use a constantly moving single-hole cannula 4.1 mm or larger diameter, cannula trajectory should avoid the muscle, and avoid excessively high graft fill pressures.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Liposuction", "question": "What defines large-volume liposuction and what are the ASPS recommendations for its management?", "answer": "Large-volume liposuction = removal of more than 5,000 mL of aspirate in a single setting. ASPS recommends it be performed only in a hospital or accredited/licensed facility, with postoperative admission to monitor for dehydration and fluid overload as fluid transitions from extra- to intravascular space.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "List the components of multimodal analgesia in plastic surgery and their key benefits.", "answer": "(1) NSAIDs: reduce opioid use by 40%, given around the clock; (2) Acetaminophen: safe profile, up to 4000 mg/day (1000 mg q6h), can start night before surgery; (3) Gabapentin: reduces opioid use by 35%, decreases pain/nausea (avoid in elderly); (4) Local anesthetics: lidocaine/bupivacaine for 8-12h, liposomal bupivacaine for 72+ hours; (5) Dexamethasone: single 8 mg IV dose reduces opioid use and PONV (avoid in poorly controlled diabetes).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "Why should patients receiving scheduled acetaminophen NOT also receive combination narcotics (e.g., Percocet)?", "answer": "To avoid acetaminophen overdose, as combination narcotics contain acetaminophen. If a patient is already receiving scheduled acetaminophen (up to 4000 mg/day), adding combination narcotics could exceed safe hepatotoxic limits.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Patient optimization before reconstruction", "question": "Describe the ASA physical status classification system (classes I-VI) and its relevance to outpatient plastic surgery.", "answer": "ASA I: Normal healthy patient. ASA II: Mild systemic disease (e.g., controlled HTN). ASA III: Severe systemic disease. ASA IV: Severe systemic disease, constant threat to life. ASA V: Moribund, not expected to survive without surgery. ASA VI: Brain-dead for organ donation. Foley et al. found an 89-fold increase in mortality in ASA IV vs I patients in ambulatory surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Is routine anticoagulation recommended for aesthetic/ambulatory plastic surgery patients? What does the evidence show?", "answer": "No. Meta-analysis showed an unfavorable risk-benefit relationship for routine anticoagulation of abdominoplasty patients with no significant VTE risk reduction. While one study showed benefit with fondaparinux in body contouring, multiple other studies using similar regimens did not confirm this. Routine anticoagulation of the aesthetic population is not advisable.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What type of anesthesia is protective against postoperative VTE, and what is the evidence?", "answer": "Regional anesthesia, MAC, or local anesthesia rather than general anesthesia. Meta-analyses show that avoiding general anesthesia is protective against postoperative VTE. General anesthesia is a recognized independent risk factor for VTE.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Time-out and site marking", "question": "What is the evidence for surgical safety checklists, and what did the WHO Surgical Safety Checklist demonstrate?", "answer": "In simulations, checklists produce higher adherence to gold-standard care. In low-income countries, the WHO Surgical Safety Checklist decreased overall and infection-specific complication rates. In childbirth settings, checklist use increased compliance with essential practices.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What are the clinical consequences of inadequate postoperative pain control across organ systems?", "answer": "Cardiovascular: increased cardiac work, ischemia, infarction. Pulmonary: splinting, decreased ambulation/vital capacity, atelectasis, hypoventilation, pneumonia. GI: reduced motility, ileus, nausea/vomiting. Hematologic: decreased ambulation, venostasis, DVT risk. Immunologic: altered immune response, increased wound infections. Neurologic: persistent chronic postoperative pain. Psychological: anxiety, fear, depression, poor satisfaction.", "notes": "Closest match; content is about pain management consequences", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Compare acetaminophen, NSAIDs, and COX-2 inhibitors in terms of mechanism, platelet effects, and key contraindications.", "answer": "Acetaminophen: inhibits COX-1/2 centrally and peripherally, NO significant platelet effects, hepatotoxicity risk at high doses. NSAIDs: inhibit COX-1 and COX-2, impair platelet function/hemostasis, risk of GI bleeding, renal insufficiency (especially with hypovolemia), cardiovascular risk (diclofenac highest, naproxen lowest). COX-2 inhibitors: selective COX-2 inhibition, negligible platelet effect, lower GI bleeding risk, but increased thromboembolic/cardiovascular risk (avoid in ischemic heart disease). Celecoxib contraindicated in sulfa allergy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Maximum dosing concepts", "question": "What is the maximum daily dose of acetaminophen in adults without hepatic disease, and what formulations are available?", "answer": "Maximum 4 grams (4000 mg) per day in adults without hepatic or renal disease. Available in oral, rectal, and IV formulations. Dose reduction recommended in patients with liver insufficiency.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is ketamine's mechanism of action, and what makes it uniquely favorable for hemodynamically unstable patients?", "answer": "Ketamine is a noncompetitive NMDA-receptor antagonist. It preserves respiratory drive, maintains hemodynamic stability, and has sympathomimetic effects (catecholamine release, inhibition of noradrenaline reuptake) leading to increased heart rate, stroke volume, and mean arterial pressure. It also preserves upper airway muscle tone, pharyngeal, and laryngeal reflexes. At subanesthetic doses (0.1 mg/kg/h), it reduces opioid requirements. Half-life: 180 minutes.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What are the dose-dependent side effects of ketamine, and at what doses are they most commonly seen?", "answer": "Neuropsychiatric effects include dysphoria, hallucinations, vivid unpleasant dreams, and catatonia/psychoses. These are dose-dependent and most common at anesthetic doses (1-5 mg/kg). At subanesthetic doses (0.1 mg/kg/h), these effects are considerably less common and generally well tolerated.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is the mechanism of gabapentinoids, and what is the FDA Black Box warning regarding their use?", "answer": "Gabapentin and pregabalin are GABA analogues that bind voltage-gated calcium channels on cortical and dorsal horn neurons, attenuating release of glutamate, norepinephrine, and substance P. They also activate descending inhibitory noradrenergic pathways. The FDA issued a Black Box warning (Dec 2019): when combined with other CNS depressants (benzodiazepines, opioids), respiratory depression can occur, especially in elderly, COPD patients, and those on chronic opioids.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Maximum dosing concepts", "question": "Fill in the blank: For subcutaneous infiltration, the maximum dose of lidocaine with epinephrine is ___ mg/kg, bupivacaine with epinephrine is ___ mg/kg, and ropivacaine with epinephrine is ___ mg/kg.", "answer": "Lidocaine with epi: 5-7 mg/kg. Bupivacaine with epi: 2-3 mg/kg. Ropivacaine with epi: 2-3 mg/kg.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "Describe Klein's Solution for tumescent anesthesia and its components.", "answer": "500 mg lidocaine + 1 mg epinephrine + 12.5 mEq sodium bicarbonate in 1000 mL of normal saline. Epinephrine prolongs analgesia, reduces bleeding, and reduces absorption of local anesthetic.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "What is the maximal hemostatic effect timing of epinephrine in tumescent analgesia, and what dosing concerns exist?", "answer": "Maximal hemostatic effects occur at 25 minutes after administration (not 7-10 minutes as commonly believed), with minimal improvement after 15 minutes. Epinephrine has a 2-3 minute half-life. An upper limit of 10 mcg/kg has been suggested. Under general anesthesia with volatile agents, arrhythmias can develop in adults with as little as 2-3 mcg/kg. Avoid in pheochromocytoma, hyperthyroidism, severe HTN, cardiac disease, or PVD.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Recognition of local anesthetic systemic toxicity", "question": "A patient develops cardiac arrest from local anesthetic toxicity during liposuction. Walk through the step-by-step management.", "answer": "(1) Stop infusion of fluids with local anesthetic; (2) Assure airway management and oxygenation; (3) Call for help; (4) Prepare for seizure suppression with benzodiazepines; (5) Administer 20% Intralipid 1.5 mL/kg (may repeat up to 10 mL/kg), then infuse 0.25 mL/kg/h if cardiac effects persist; (6) Manage arrhythmias per ACLS but do NOT use lidocaine, reduce epinephrine to 1 mcg/kg; (7) For isolated seizures: benzodiazepines or propofol (propofol NOT as lipid substitute for cardiac arrest).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "Why is bupivacaine generally not recommended for tumescent anesthesia, and which organizations advise against it?", "answer": "Both the American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) and American Academy of Dermatology (AAD) in 2013 guidelines advise against use of bupivacaine for tumescent anesthesia. While it has been used in combination with lidocaine without reported complications, there is little guidance on upper limits of dosing when used in combination, creating safety concerns.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "List at least 8 plastic surgery procedures where tumescent analgesia can be used.", "answer": "Liposuction, subcutaneous mass excision/scar revisions, excisional body contouring (abdominoplasty, body lifts, brachioplasty, thigh lifts), breast augmentation/reduction/mastopexy/gynecomastia, mastectomy, burn excision and skin grafting, face/neck lifts, hair grafting, skin procedures (dermabrasion, laser resurfacing), and lymph node dissections.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "What electrolyte abnormalities can occur with large-volume tumescent infiltration during liposuction?", "answer": "Mild hyponatremia and hypokalemia may occur in large-volume liposuction. Rarely clinically significant but must be monitored. Additionally, large volumes of room temperature tumescent fluid can lower body temperature; fluid should be warmed to 37 degrees C in cases prone to hypothermia.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is liposomal bupivacaine (Exparel), and what are its pharmacologic properties?", "answer": "Liposomal bupivacaine provides sustained delivery via a vesicular network that opens successively over time. 3% of bupivacaine is initially free at injection for immediate effect; the remainder is in vesicles for gradual delivery. FDA approved in 2011 for wound infiltration and 2018 for interscalene nerve block. Can provide 72+ hours of pain relief, though well-designed plastic surgery studies have not consistently found benefit over properly dosed traditional local anesthetics.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "List 9 techniques for minimizing pain during injection of local anesthesia with sharp needles.", "answer": "(1) Buffer lidocaine/epi with 8.4% sodium bicarbonate; (2) Warm the local anesthetic; (3) Distract patient or area (pinch/pressure near injection); (4) Use smaller 27- or 30-gauge needles; (5) Stabilize syringe with both hands; (6) Inject 0.5 mL perpendicularly subdermally, pause until patient reports no needle pain; (7) Inject 2 mL before moving needle, then advance slowly with 1 cm anesthetic ahead of needle; (8) Reinsert within 1 cm of blanched areas; (9) Have patients provide feedback and pain scores during injection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "WALANT principles", "question": "What does WALANT stand for and in what procedures has wide-awake local anesthesia been proven effective?", "answer": "Wide-Awake Local Anesthesia No Tourniquet. It has been proven effective in hand surgery, cosmetic surgery, facial skin cancer reconstruction, and adult cleft lip repair, among others. The approach uses local anesthesia without sedation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Describe the PEC 1 and PEC 2 nerve blocks: what nerves do they target, what is the typical anesthetic, and when are they used?", "answer": "PEC 1: targets medial and lateral pectoral nerves (from brachial plexus, C5-T1) as they travel between pec major and minor. Provides analgesia for pectoralis muscles. Typical: 10 mL 0.5% bupivacaine. PEC 2: targets intercostal nerves (1-7) as they exit serratus anterior. Provides analgesia for overlying skin and breast tissue. Typical: 20 mL 0.2% bupivacaine. Both performed together with ultrasound guidance for breast surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Describe the transversus abdominis plane (TAP) block: where is the local anesthetic placed, what nerves are targeted, and what are the anatomic boundaries of the injection site?", "answer": "Local anesthetic is placed in the fascial plane between the transversus abdominis and internal oblique muscles. Targets T10-L1 terminal branches of intercostal nerves. Injection site is within the lumbar triangle of Petit (boundaries: costal margin superiorly, iliac crest inferiorly, external oblique anteriorly, latissimus dorsi posteriorly). Subcostal approach targets T7-9. Rare complications: hematoma and intraperitoneal injection with organ injury.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is an erector spinae block (ESP), how does it work, and how does it compare to PEC blocks for breast surgery?", "answer": "ESP is placed just inferior to the erector spinae muscle overlying the transverse process. The mechanism is debated - it may block dorsal root nerves or enter the paravertebral space. Provides analgesia along the lateral thoracic or abdominal wall. Used for thoracic, breast, and abdominal surgery. For breast surgery, PEC blocks appear to have an advantage over ESP.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Compare paravertebral blocks and epidural anesthesia: anatomy, advantages, and complications.", "answer": "Paravertebral: injection into triangular paravertebral space (bordered by parietal pleura anteriorly, vertebral column medially, superior costotransverse ligament posteriorly). Provides ipsilateral dermatomal analgesia while avoiding CNS complications. Main risk: pneumothorax (<1%). Epidural: injection outside subarachnoid space with catheter for continuous infusion. Allows multilevel coverage. Complications: hypotension (up to 33%), bradycardia, spinal headaches, epidural abscess/hematoma, respiratory compromise if intercostal/abdominal muscles blocked.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "What special considerations apply to opioid management in patients with obstructive sleep apnea (OSA)?", "answer": "OSA patients have increased soft tissue in pharynx/larynx leading to upper airway obstruction. Opioids exacerbate this via: dose-dependent decrease in genioglossus tone, sedative effects promoting airway closure, altered arousal thresholds, and reduced postoperative lung volumes. Recommendations: reduce opioid dose by half or increase dosing interval, continuous pulse oximetry, prolonged PACU observation, early postoperative positive airway pressure therapy, and multimodal non-opioid alternatives.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "What percentage of hand surgery patients continued opioid use at 90-120 days postoperatively?", "answer": "8-13% of hand surgery patients continued to use opioids at 90-120 days, highlighting the risk of acute postoperative opioid prescriptions leading to chronic use.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Compare morphine, fentanyl, and hydromorphone: equipotent IV doses, durations, and key side effects.", "answer": "Morphine: 0.1 mg/kg IV, duration 3-4h, oral bioavailability 20-40% (give 3-5x IV dose orally). Causes histamine release/vasodilation; avoid in asthmatics/circulatory compromise. Fentanyl: 0.001 mg/kg IV, duration 0.5-1h. Vagotonic (can cause bradycardia), minimal hemodynamic alterations, but can cause chest wall rigidity from glottic closure. Hydromorphone: 0.01-0.02 mg/kg IV, duration 3-4h, oral bioavailability 50-70%. No histamine release; used when morphine produces too many side effects.", "notes": "Closest match; opioid pharmacology relevant to anesthesia/pain management", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Why is codeine no longer recommended, and what is the specific FDA warning?", "answer": "Codeine is a prodrug that must be converted by CYP2D6 to morphine for analgesia. Ultra-rapid metabolizers produce excessive morphine (dangerous), while slow metabolizers get no analgesia. It has a Black Box warning and is contraindicated in pediatric tonsillectomy patients.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is the current recommendation for managing buprenorphine perioperatively?", "answer": "Previous guidelines suggested tapering buprenorphine before surgery, but current evidence suggests this can lead to harm. The home dose should be CONTINUED perioperatively, and may need to be increased postoperatively. Standard opioid regimens will NOT be effective because buprenorphine tightly binds opioid receptors but elicits low activity. Multimodal therapy including regional anesthesia is often required. Discussion with anesthesiologist and prescribing physician is essential.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What advantage does epidural anesthesia offer specifically for microvascular lower extremity reconstruction?", "answer": "The sympathectomy from epidural anesthesia may enhance blood flow to the extremity, which is beneficial for microvascular flap perfusion. Additionally, thoracic epidurals may spare motor nerves to the lower extremities and micturition pathways, allowing early ambulation and avoidance of prolonged urinary catheter use.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "Define R0, R1, and R2 resections in cancer surgery.", "answer": "R0: tumor excision with no evidence of tumor cells (gross or microscopic) at any resection margin on pathological examination. R1: positive microscopic margins. R2: positive macroscopic margins.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "What is the approximate size at which a tumor first becomes clinically detectable, and what does this imply about the timeline for evaluation?", "answer": "Tumors are generally not detectable until they reach approximately 1 cm in diameter (~10^9 cells). Depending on doubling time (2-200 days), a tumor may be present for years before becoming palpable. This affords the oncologic team sufficient time to evaluate newly diagnosed patients thoroughly without rushing therapy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "TNM staging awareness", "question": "Describe the TNM staging system: what does each component represent?", "answer": "T (Tumor): extent of primary tumor measured by size, depth of invasion, or degree of anatomic involvement. N (Node): involvement of lymph nodes, including number of affected nodes or node size. M (Metastasis): involvement of distant organs. Various TNM combinations are aggregated into stage groups (I-IV) with different treatment tailored for each stage.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Compare Clark's and Breslow's classification systems for melanoma.", "answer": "Clark's morphologic classification categorizes melanoma into: lentigo maligna, superficial spreading, nodular, acral, and desmoplastic variants, and histologically by level of invasion into papillary/reticular dermis and subcutaneous fat (subjective, poor inter-rater reliability). Breslow's system objectively quantitates tumor thickness by measurement with a micrometer (more reproducible and clinically relevant for prognosis).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Sentinel lymph node biopsy concepts", "question": "Describe the sentinel lymph node concept: how is it performed, what are the false-negative rates, and what are the advantages over elective lymph node dissection?", "answer": "After injection of radioactive colloid or blue dye into the tumor, the first (sentinel) node draining the basin is excised and examined. The sentinel node status is representative of the entire regional nodal chain. False-negative rates: 0-11%. Advantages: minimizes morbidity (lymphedema rates decreased to 5% vs 35% for complete lymphadenectomy), allows more thorough histologic evaluation of a single node, and avoids unnecessary extensive dissections.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "Why do tumors sometimes recur locally despite negative margins on pathologic evaluation?", "answer": "Microscopic tumor deposits may not be detected on routine histology. Studies show cancer cells can be successfully grown in vitro from specimens with negative routine histology. Additionally, if malignant cells represent less than 0.1% of a specimen, identification is challenging unless immunohistochemistry or molecular techniques (PCR) are used. This justifies multimodality treatment even with negative margins.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "BCC/SCC high-risk features", "question": "Describe Lund's classification for basal cell carcinoma and its prognostic significance.", "answer": "Based on descriptive/morphologic features: nodular (well-defined margins), ulcerative, morphea, and sclerosing patterns (indistinct margins). The presence of morphea or sclerosing features is associated with a more aggressive and problematic course.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Pathology", "subtopic": "Breast cancer receptor status at a basic level: ER/PR/HER2 awareness", "question": "What is triple-negative breast cancer and why is it clinically significant?", "answer": "Triple-negative breast cancer is absent for ER (estrogen receptor), PR (progesterone receptor), and HER2 receptors. It has a reproducible and highly specific molecular signature that is clinically aggressive. It lacks targets for hormonal therapy or HER2-directed therapy, making treatment more challenging.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is neoadjuvant therapy, and how does it affect reconstructive planning?", "answer": "Neoadjuvant therapy = chemotherapy and/or radiation administered BEFORE tumor excision. Goals: shrink unresectable tumors to make them resectable, or decrease magnitude of ablation needed for negative margins. Impact on reconstruction: Mehrara et al. showed neoadjuvant chemo is an independent risk factor for postoperative complications in microvascular breast reconstruction, with increased wound complications if surgery is performed less than 6 weeks after completion of chemotherapy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Compare the advantages and disadvantages of neoadjuvant vs adjuvant therapy.", "answer": "Neoadjuvant advantages: can downstage tumors, convert unresectable to resectable, facilitate organ preservation (e.g., sphincter preservation in rectal cancer, breast conservation), response predicts outcome and guides postop chemo. Disadvantages: disease progression before surgery, increased surgical complications from chemoradiation side effects. Adjuvant advantages: decreases locoregional recurrence and systemic disease by treating microscopic deposits after surgery. Both: all attempts should be made for negative margins at surgery regardless.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects on wound healing", "question": "Why is radiation most effective at tumor periphery and least effective at the center?", "answer": "Radiation produces free radicals from water, and oxygen increases the half-life of reactive radical species, making radiation most effective in oxygen-rich environments. The periphery of tumors is well-oxygenated, while the avascular center of necrotic tumor masses has poor oxygen tension, making radiation least effective there.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects on wound healing", "question": "What is the mechanism by which radiation causes increased wound healing complications?", "answer": "While traditionally thought to be related to harmful effects on local blood supply, the exact cause remains unknown. Recent studies suggest radiation injury causes depletion of local tissue stem cells, and that restitution with stem cell injections can improve tissue healing. Radiation is also an independent risk factor for post-surgical lymphedema and secondary skin malignancies.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects on wound healing", "question": "Explain the principle of fractionated radiation therapy and the concept of sublethal damage.", "answer": "Ionizing radiation causes DNA strand breaks. Single-strand breaks are efficiently repaired by cells, but double-strand breaks are less easily handled. When the interval between doses is increased, more cells can repair DNA breaks (sublethal damage). Radiation is therefore delivered in fractionated daily doses (1.8-2.5 Gy) because normal cells have greater ability to repair sublethal damage between fractions than tumor cells.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "Compare excisional biopsy, incisional biopsy, core-needle biopsy (CNB), and fine-needle aspiration (FNA).", "answer": "Excisional: removes entire tumor mass with margin of normal tissue, often with curative intent. Incisional: excises a portion of tumor for diagnosis. CNB: obtains less tissue but often sufficient for surgical planning. FNA: minimally invasive, obtains only cells; a positive FNA may guide treatment, but a negative FNA cannot definitively rule out malignancy. Incisional biopsy incisions should be oriented to allow excision with the tumor specimen (e.g., for sarcomas).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is the evidence regarding melanoma surgical margins? What margin has shown no additional benefit?", "answer": "Margins greater than 2 cm have shown no benefit in the treatment of cutaneous melanoma. This represents the paradigm shift from Halsted-era radical resections to evidence-based conservative approaches combined with multimodality therapy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Immediate vs delayed reconstruction", "question": "Does breast reconstruction (implant or autologous) delay detection of recurrent disease?", "answer": "No. Data do not support the contention that reconstruction obscures recurrence detection. Neither implant nor autologous reconstruction has been associated with a delay in diagnosis of recurrent disease. Recurrences after TRAM flap reconstruction can be managed with local excision and flap salvage in 80% of cases. Recurrent disease is detectable on physical exam, not mammography.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Sentinel lymph node biopsy concepts", "question": "Compare elective lymph node dissection (ELND) vs therapeutic lymph node dissection (TLND) vs sentinel lymph node biopsy.", "answer": "ELND: performed prophylactically at initial tumor excision. Not routinely recommended because (1) increased morbidity (lymphedema, nerve damage) and (2) no clear survival benefit over TLND for melanoma. TLND: performed when tumor subsequently recurs in a nodal basin. Sentinel lymph node biopsy: minimally invasive staging technique with much lower lymphedema rates (5% vs 35%) that identifies which patients may benefit from further dissection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What types of immunotherapy are used in melanoma treatment? Describe passive, adoptive, and active approaches.", "answer": "Passive: monoclonal antibodies against tumor antigens (e.g., checkpoint inhibitors like pembrolizumab targeting PD-1, ipilimumab targeting CTLA-4). Adoptive: ex vivo manipulation of autologous tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes with IL-2 to increase cytolytic potential, then reinfusion. Active nonspecific: BCG, cytokines (IL-2, interferon-alpha) - melanoma is the most immunogenic tumor. Active specific: vaccines derived from antigens on patients' cancer cells using dendritic cell presentation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Timing of reconstruction: immediate vs delayed", "question": "How has the availability of reconstructive techniques influenced cancer treatment paradigms? Give two examples.", "answer": "(1) Breast cancer: availability of autologous and implant-based reconstruction may influence decisions to proceed with mastectomy vs lumpectomy+radiation. Nipple-sparing mastectomy, once unthinkable, is now used with increasing indications. (2) Limb sarcoma: limb preservation for osteosarcomas became possible through neoadjuvant chemotherapy combined with functional reconstructions (allografts/endoprostheses), replacing amputation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "What is the recurrence rate for basal cell cancer with positive margins, and what does this suggest about the body's immune capacity?", "answer": "Recurrence rates are only 20-30% despite positive margins, suggesting the body's immune system has the capacity to destroy small numbers of residual cancerous cells.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "List the four phases of wound healing and their approximate timelines.", "answer": "(1) Hemostasis: seconds to minutes after injury. (2) Inflammation: begins immediately, lasts ~2-3 days. (3) Proliferation: starts ~3 days, lasts up to 3 weeks. (4) Maturation/Remodeling: begins ~2-3 weeks after injury, can last up to 2 years.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "Describe the hemostasis phase of wound healing. What forms the provisional matrix?", "answer": "Hemostasis begins within seconds to minutes. A coagulation cascade is activated by fibrin binding platelets. The blood clot serves as a physical barrier to bleeding and induces local vasoconstriction. The clot (consisting of thrombin, fibronectin, collagen, and platelets) serves as a provisional matrix for neutrophils, monocytes, fibroblasts, and endothelial cells to migrate into the wound.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "Describe the sequence of inflammatory cell arrival during wound healing. What is the role of each cell type?", "answer": "Neutrophils arrive first (within 24-48 hours), activate the complement system, clear pathogens/damaged matrix/cells, then are extruded with eschar or phagocytosed by macrophages. Monocytes infiltrate at ~72 hours, recruited by TGF-beta, ECM fragments, and degraded bacteria products. They differentiate into macrophages which phagocytose dead cells/debris and produce growth factors (TGF-alpha, TGF-beta, PDGF, IGF, IL-1) to transition to the proliferative phase.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "What are M1 and M2 macrophages, and why is their transition important for wound healing?", "answer": "M1 (proinflammatory) macrophages are responsible for phagocytosis of cells and debris during the inflammatory phase. M2 (anti-inflammatory) macrophages are necessary to transition to the proliferative phase, increasing collagen and ground substance production. Failure of macrophages to transition from M1 to M2 phenotype is associated with the development of chronic wounds.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "What three essential processes occur during the proliferative phase of wound healing?", "answer": "(1) Granulation tissue deposition: fibroplasia (increased fibroblasts, collagen, elastin, fibronectin production) and angiogenesis (new blood vessels), driven by FGF, VEGF, PDGF, TGF-beta. Granulation tissue established by day 5. (2) Re-epithelialization: basal keratinocytes proliferate and migrate over granulation tissue; epidermal stem cells from hair follicle bulge regions also contribute. (3) Wound contraction: macrophages induce fibroblasts to differentiate into alpha-SMA-expressing myofibroblasts that pull wound edges together.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "During the maturation phase, what happens to collagen and what is the maximum tensile strength achieved?", "answer": "Type III collagen (produced during proliferation) is remodeled to type I collagen over months 6-12. Collagen fibers become increasingly parallel in orientation, orchestrated by matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) from fibroblasts and macrophages. Wound tensile strength increases but will NEVER return to pre-wounded skin strength.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Angiogenesis and epithelialization", "question": "What is the role of HIF-1-alpha in wound healing, and how do its expression levels affect outcomes?", "answer": "HIF-1-alpha is a transcription factor that stimulates pro-angiogenic pathways through VEGF and nitric oxide signaling. It is crucial for appropriate inflammatory and angiogenic responses and granulation tissue formation. Downregulation leads to chronic wounds; overexpression contributes to fibrosis and excessive scarring. Levels are regulated by oxygen tension.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Acute vs chronic wound", "question": "What defines a chronic wound, and what is the pathophysiology that keeps it from healing?", "answer": "A chronic wound has not shown significant progress toward healing within 30 days (or remains open at 3 months). Chronic wounds are trapped in the inflammatory phase and cannot progress to proliferation/maturation. They demonstrate excessive neutrophils and macrophages, prolonged overexpression of proinflammatory cytokines, excess reactive oxygen species (ROS) damaging cell membranes/ECM, and untimely overexpression of MMPs creating a proteolytic environment that degrades necessary growth factors.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "Compare hypertrophic scars and keloids: growth pattern, regression, and histologic features.", "answer": "Hypertrophic scars: raised but do NOT grow beyond boundaries of the original wound; tend to regress over several years. Keloids: extend beyond the original wound border, grow without limitation, and rarely regress. Keloids exhibit increased fibroblast numbers and can form dermal nodules. Both are related to disorders in the inflammatory process. Patients with pigmented skin (Africans, Asians) have higher propensity for keloids (up to 10% following incisions).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "How does diabetes impair each phase of wound healing?", "answer": "Peripheral vascular disease leads to poor circulation with deficient oxygen and nutrition delivery, especially to extremities. Decreased complement activation and lower cytokine production impair immune response. Hyperglycemia impairs leukocyte function and provides nutrients for bacterial growth. Chronic hypoxia amplifies early inflammatory response, increases oxidative stress, and alters HIF-1-alpha function. Collectively, all four phases of wound healing are impaired.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "How do systemic corticosteroids impair wound healing, and what can counteract this effect?", "answer": "Corticosteroids inhibit ALL phases: in inflammation, they downregulate cytokines (TGF-beta, PDGF, TNF, IL-1-alpha) and inhibit macrophage infiltration. In proliferation, they reduce TGF-beta and KGF, mitigating fibroblast proliferation and re-epithelialization. In maturation, they impair collagen transformation, disrupt dermal-epidermal junctions, and decrease tensile strength by reducing collagen accumulation. Vitamin A administration can counteract this by stimulating macrophages.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "What nutritional factors affect wound healing? List the role of key vitamins, minerals, and amino acids.", "answer": "Vitamin A: stimulates fibroblast collagen synthesis, counteracts steroid effects. Vitamin C: supports hydroxylation of proline to hydroxyproline for collagen cross-linking; deficiency reduces collagen synthesis and causes capillary fragility. Vitamin E: protects against oxidative stress, may prevent excessive scarring. Zinc: cofactor for DNA/RNA polymerase, essential for cell division, protein/collagen synthesis. Glutamine: energy source for proliferating cells, improves wound strength. Arginine: promotes immune function, angiogenesis, collagen deposition. Proteins are key building blocks; deficiency decreases leukocyte phagocytosis and increases infection susceptibility.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Labs", "subtopic": "Albumin/prealbumin limitations and nutrition assessment", "question": "How can protein levels be assessed in wound healing patients?", "answer": "Serum albumin and pre-albumin laboratory tests. Protein deficiency affects the immune system by decreasing leukocyte phagocytosis and increasing infection susceptibility, and inhibits angiogenesis, fibroblast proliferation, proteoglycan synthesis, and collagen synthesis. Correction of protein deficiencies improves wound healing.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Culture interpretation: colonization vs infection", "question": "Distinguish between wound colonization and wound infection. What is the most common causative organism?", "answer": "Colonization: bacteria exist within the wound without causing overt infection; common from normal flora, other body areas, or external environment. Colonization can shift the immune system to a more inflammatory state. Infection: bacteria multiply and cause tissue damage, prolonged inflammation, and impaired healing. Staphylococcus aureus is the most common infection-causing organism. Bacteria may form biofilms (complex colonies enclosed in protective extracellular polymeric substance) making eradication difficult.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "When a wound is ready for grafting or closure", "question": "Describe primary, secondary, and tertiary intention wound closure and their indications.", "answer": "Primary intention: wound edges approximated with sutures/staples/adhesives; for clean wounds, ideally closed within 4-6 hours (up to 12 hours possible). Secondary intention: wound left open to heal by re-epithelialization and contraction; for grossly contaminated wounds or those with excessive tension from tissue loss (e.g., deep puncture wounds, heavily soiled lacerations, bite puncture wounds >24 hours). Tertiary intention (delayed primary closure): wound initially treated with dressing changes, then closed later once tissue is confirmed healthy and can be reapproximated without tension.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Burn depth: superficial, superficial partial, deep partial, full thickness", "question": "Compare first-degree, superficial second-degree, deep second-degree, third-degree, and fourth-degree burns in terms of depth, sensation, and treatment.", "answer": "First-degree: epithelial layer only; erythematous, painful; heals without sequelae. Superficial second-degree: epidermis + superficial dermis; painful, erythematous, weeping; heals without surgery (topical antimicrobials, daily washing, moist dressings); regeneration from dermal appendages. Deep second-degree: through most of dermis; LESS painful (nerve endings destroyed); requires debridement and grafting. Third-degree: entire dermis; insensate; requires debridement and grafting. Fourth-degree: into subcutaneous tissue and deeper; requires specialized composite reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Diabetic foot ulcers", "question": "Outline the treatment algorithm for diabetic foot ulcers (DFUs).", "answer": "(1) Sharp debridement, dressing changes, pressure off-loading, optimize glucose levels. (2) Assess for infection: if present, serial debridement and directed antibiotic therapy. (3) Assess vascular flow (ABI, foot pulses): if not optimized, vascular surgery consult for stent/bypass. (4) If not healing within 1 month: consider NPWT, hyperbaric oxygen, growth factors, skin substitutes. (5) After healing: annual monitoring is necessary as most DFUs recur within 2 years.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Arterial ulcers", "question": "What defines an ischemic ulcer, and what is critical for their treatment?", "answer": "Ischemic ulcers are skin ulcerations (usually lower extremity) in the setting of poor arterial flow, defined by ABI <1, non-compressible arteries, or absent/abnormal waveforms at the ankle. Correction of blood flow (balloon angioplasty or bypass grafting) is critical and dramatically improves healing rates. Complete closure may take >6 months. Patients with ischemic ulcers complicated by osteomyelitis or end-stage renal disease have very poor healing and significantly higher amputation rates.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Venous stasis ulcers", "question": "What are the key treatments for venous stasis ulcers?", "answer": "Lifestyle interventions: leg elevation above heart (~120 min daily) and exercise (daily walking) promote healing. For persistent ulcers: debridement if infected with culture-directed antibiotics (NOT prophylactic systemic antibiotics, which create resistant organisms). Compression therapy improves healing rates and prevents recurrent cellulitis. Moist dressing environment promotes healing but no dressing type (including silver) is proven superior. Skin substitutes may improve closure rate after clean debridement.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Sacral, ischial, trochanteric ulcers", "question": "Where do pressure sores commonly occur, and what is the treatment approach?", "answer": "Common locations: sacrum, ischium, trochanter, calcaneus - overlying bony prominences in patients with limited mobility. Treatment: (1) Address external pressure by off-loading (rotation in bed/wheelchair, cushioning bony prominences). (2) Debride to viable bleeding tissue. (3) Treat infections with biopsy-directed antibiotic therapy. (4) For non-healing wounds with good compliance: surgical debridement with flap reconstruction (though recurrence rates can be as high as 60%).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What are the current treatment options for keloids?", "answer": "Silicone sheets: worn 24h/day for 3-6 months; improves appearance but not complete resolution. Intralesional corticosteroid injection (triamcinolone): mainstay of treatment; improves scar appearance, height, and symptoms (pain, pruritis). Surgical excision: option but recurrence is common. Radiation therapy: can be used as adjunct. Excision alone has high recurrence rates; best results typically combine excision with adjuvant therapy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Vascularity of wound bed", "question": "What is the relationship between oxygen tension and chronic wound healing? What are the critical oxygen levels?", "answer": "Chronic wounds are remarkably hypoxic (transcutaneous oxygen pressure 5-20 mmHg). Lower extremity wounds will NOT heal if partial oxygen pressure is <30 mmHg. Oxygen promotes angiogenesis, collagen synthesis, growth factor production, ROS generation for bacterial killing, and leucocyte/fibroblast function. Acute hypoxia temporarily increases cell proliferation (beneficial), but prolonged hypoxia leads to abnormal healing through excess ROS, protein/lipid/DNA damage, and impaired progression through healing phases.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "Negative-pressure wound therapy: indications, contraindications, complications", "question": "What are the benefits of negative pressure wound therapy (NPWT) for diabetic foot ulcers compared to standard dressings?", "answer": "NPWT demonstrates faster rates of wound closure and lessens the rate of amputation compared to dressings when applied to adequately debrided wounds in the absence of infection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "How does obesity impair wound healing?", "answer": "Obesity causes: (1) general hypovascularity and impaired oxygen delivery, (2) proinflammatory environment, (3) oxidative stress with free radical/antioxidant imbalance, (4) malnutrition (high fat/carb diet missing micronutrients), (5) depleted adiponectin levels (compromising perfusion and re-epithelialization), (6) increased cellular senescence in skin. Common wound complications in obese patients include infections, seromas, wound dehiscence, pressure ulcers, and venous stasis ulcers.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Differences in healing of skin, tendon, bone, nerve, cartilage, and vessels", "question": "How does aging affect each phase of wound healing?", "answer": "Hemostasis: increased platelet aggregation. Inflammation: decreased macrophage and B-lymphocyte infiltration, declined macrophage function. Proliferation: delayed re-epithelialization (keratinocyte migration takes nearly twice as long), slower angiogenesis and collagen synthesis. Maturation: prolonged with diminished healed tissue strength. Additionally, aged skin has flattened rete ridges (decreased dermal-epidermal mechanical strength), reduced dermal collagen/elastin, decreased microcirculation, and increased cellular senescence (fibroblasts/keratinocytes become unresponsive to growth factors).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What is the Vancouver Scar Scale (VSS) and what four parameters does it assess?", "answer": "The Vancouver Scar Scale is one of the most commonly used scar assessment tools. It evaluates four parameters: (1) Pigmentation (0=normal, 1=hypopigmented, 2=mixed, 3=hyperpigmented), (2) Vascularity (0=normal, 1=pink, 2=red, 3=purple), (3) Pliability (0=normal to 5=contracture), and (4) Height (0=flat to 3= >5mm). Higher total scores indicate worse scarring.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "Name and describe at least three scar assessment scales beyond the Vancouver Scar Scale.", "answer": "(1) POSAS (Patient and Observer Scar Assessment Scale): includes both patient and observer components, assessing vascularity, pigmentation, thickness, relief, pliability, and surface area. (2) VAS (Visual Analogue Scale): simple linear scale for overall scar appearance. (3) SBSES (Stony Brook Scar Evaluation Scale): evaluates width, height, color, suture marks, and overall appearance. (4) MCFONTZL: assesses matte/shiny, contour, flexibility, opacity, numbness, texture, zero point, and level.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What is the role of fibroblast heterogeneity in scar formation? Describe the difference between papillary and reticular dermal fibroblasts.", "answer": "Fibroblasts are heterogeneous even within the same tissue. Papillary (superficial) dermal fibroblasts are associated with less scarring and more regenerative healing. Reticular (deep) dermal fibroblasts produce more collagen and are associated with fibrotic/scarring responses. Deep dermal injuries that damage the papillary dermis and recruit reticular fibroblasts tend to produce worse scars. The engrailed-1 (En1) fibroblast lineage has been identified as particularly pro-fibrotic.", "notes": "Scar biology detail from Ch16; closest match is collagen/scar maturation", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What is the maximum tensile strength a healed wound can achieve compared to unwounded skin?", "answer": "A healed wound reaches approximately 80% of the tensile strength of unwounded skin. It never returns to full pre-injury strength regardless of the duration of remodeling.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "Compare hypertrophic scars and keloids across seven clinical and biological features: boundaries, regression, recurrence, symptoms, collagen pattern, genetics, and common locations.", "answer": "Hypertrophic scars: stay within wound boundaries, may regress over 1-2 years, lower recurrence after excision, related to wound tension/inflammation, collagen in organized parallel bundles, no strong genetic predisposition, occur at high-tension sites. Keloids: extend beyond wound boundaries, rarely regress spontaneously, high recurrence after excision alone (45-100%), often symptomatic (pain/pruritis), collagen in thick disorganized whorls, strong genetic/familial component (higher in African and Asian populations), common on earlobes/chest/shoulders/upper back.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "Outline the first-line, second-line, and third-line treatments for hypertrophic scars.", "answer": "First-line: silicone-based therapy (sheets or gel, worn 12-24 hours/day for 3-6 months) and pressure therapy (pressure garments at 24-30 mmHg). Second-line: intralesional corticosteroid injection (triamcinolone acetonide 10-40 mg/mL, repeated every 4-6 weeks). Third-line: surgical excision combined with adjuvant therapy (intralesional steroids, silicone, or other modalities to prevent recurrence).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What is the proposed mechanism of action of silicone-based scar therapy?", "answer": "The exact mechanism is not fully understood. Leading theories include: (1) hydration and occlusion of the stratum corneum, which reduces transepidermal water loss and decreases capillary activity/collagen deposition; (2) static electricity generated by silicone may influence collagen alignment; (3) temperature regulation of the scar. Silicone sheets should be worn 12-24 hours/day for at least 3-6 months for optimal effect.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What are the side effects of intralesional corticosteroid (triamcinolone) injection for abnormal scars?", "answer": "Side effects include: skin/fat atrophy at injection site, hypopigmentation (especially in darker skin), telangiectasia, pain during injection, and potential for rebound scar growth if treatment is discontinued prematurely. Systemic effects are rare but can include menstrual irregularities and adrenal suppression with frequent/high-dose injections.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "Describe the treatment algorithm for keloids, including the role of radiotherapy.", "answer": "First-line: silicone therapy and intralesional corticosteroids (triamcinolone). Second-line: combination therapy with intralesional 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) Â± corticosteroids, cryotherapy, or intralesional bleomycin. Third-line: surgical excision followed by adjuvant radiotherapy (typically within 24-48 hours postop). Radiotherapy is particularly important for keloids because excision alone has recurrence rates of 45-100%, while excision + radiotherapy reduces recurrence to approximately 10-20%. Other adjuncts include verapamil and imiquimod.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "How does intralesional cryotherapy work for keloid treatment, and what are its advantages?", "answer": "Intralesional cryotherapy involves inserting a cryoprobe directly into the keloid to freeze tissue from the inside out, causing vascular damage and ischemic necrosis of the scar tissue. Advantages over external spray cryotherapy include: more uniform freezing of deeper scar tissue, less damage to overlying epidermis (reduced risk of hypopigmentation), and potentially better cosmetic outcomes. It can be combined with intralesional corticosteroid injection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What is the role of 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) in keloid and hypertrophic scar treatment?", "answer": "5-FU is an antimetabolite that inhibits fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis by blocking thymidylate synthase. It is administered as intralesional injection (50 mg/mL), often combined with triamcinolone to reduce side effects. The combination of 5-FU + triamcinolone has shown superior results compared to triamcinolone alone for keloids. Side effects include pain at injection site, hyperpigmentation, and rarely tissue necrosis.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What types of lasers are used for scar treatment, and what are their mechanisms?", "answer": "Pulsed dye laser (PDL, 585-595 nm): targets hemoglobin in scar vasculature, reduces erythema and may decrease scar volume by altering collagen remodeling; best for early erythematous/immature scars. Fractional CO2 laser (10,600 nm): creates micro-columns of thermal injury that stimulate wound healing cascade and collagen remodeling; useful for atrophic scars and mature hypertrophic scars. Nd:YAG laser (1064 nm): deeper penetration for thicker scars. Laser therapy is often used as adjunct to other treatments.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "Describe the Z-plasty technique: what are its components, how does it work, and what theoretical length gains are achieved at different angles?", "answer": "Z-plasty consists of a central limb (along the scar) and two peripheral limbs of equal length angled from each end, creating two triangular flaps that are transposed. Theoretical length gains by angle: 30Â° â†’ 25% gain, 45Â° â†’ 50% gain, 60Â° â†’ 75% gain (most commonly used), 75Â° â†’ 100% gain, 90Â° â†’ 120% gain. The technique reorients the central scar line, breaks up linear scars, and recruits adjacent tissue to lengthen contracted areas.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What are the four fundamental functions of Z-plasty?", "answer": "(1) Lengthen a contracted scar or tight structure (the primary indication for scar contractures). (2) Change the direction/orientation of a scar to better align with relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs). (3) Break up a straight-line scar into an irregular pattern that is less conspicuous. (4) Transpose tissue (move tissue from an area of relative excess to an area of deficiency).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "Compare Z-plasty and W-plasty: when would you use each technique for scar revision?", "answer": "Z-plasty: best for scar contractures requiring lengthening, scars crossing concavities, and scars that need reorientation to RSTLs. Provides actual tissue lengthening along the central limb. W-plasty: best for long linear scars on flat/convex surfaces where the primary goal is to break up the scar line (camouflage) without significant lengthening. Creates interdigitating triangular flaps that prevent a straight-line shadow. W-plasty does NOT provide lengthening, so it is NOT appropriate for contractures.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What is the geometric broken line closure (GBLC) technique, and when is it preferred?", "answer": "GBLC uses randomly arranged geometric shapes (triangles, rectangles, semicircles) on alternating sides of the scar to create an irregular closure line. It is preferred for long scars on convex or flat surfaces, particularly on the face, where a highly irregular line better camouflages the scar by preventing the eye from tracking a single line. It is more technically demanding than W-plasty but may provide superior camouflage in experienced hands.", "notes": "Scar revision technique from Ch16; closest subtopic is Z/W-plasty design", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What are Langer's lines and relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs)? Why are they important for scar prevention?", "answer": "Langer's lines were described by Karl Langer in 1861 by puncturing cadaver skin with a round awl and observing the resulting elliptical patterns. Relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs), described by Borges, represent the lines of minimal skin tension in living tissue, generally perpendicular to the direction of underlying muscle contraction. Scars oriented parallel to RSTLs experience less tension and tend to heal with thinner, less noticeable scars. Surgical incisions should be planned parallel to RSTLs whenever possible.", "notes": "Scar prevention principle; closest match is hypertrophic/keloid prevention", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What is the recommended timing for scar revision surgery, and why?", "answer": "Scar revision should generally wait until the scar has matured, typically at least 12-18 months after the original wound. Reasons: (1) Scars continue to remodel and improve during maturation, and early revision may be unnecessary. (2) Mature scars are softer, flatter, and less vascular, making surgical revision technically easier. (3) The inflammatory response is diminished in mature tissue. Exceptions include functionally limiting contractures (especially in children) that may warrant earlier intervention.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What is the role of pressure therapy in scar management? What pressure is recommended and for how long?", "answer": "Pressure therapy (custom-fitted compression garments) is a first-line treatment for hypertrophic scars, especially after burns. Recommended pressure is 24-30 mmHg, worn 23 hours/day for 6-12 months or until scar maturation. Mechanism: reduces blood flow to the scar, creates local hypoxia that decreases fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis, and mechanically remodels collagen fibers. Compliance is the major limitation, as garments are uncomfortable and must be worn continuously.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What is the engrailed-1 (En1) fibroblast lineage, and what is its significance in scarring?", "answer": "Engrailed-1 positive (En1+) fibroblasts are a specific fibroblast lineage identified as being pro-fibrotic and primarily responsible for connective tissue deposition during scarring. Research has shown that inhibiting or depleting En1+ fibroblasts can promote regenerative (scarless) healing. This discovery has implications for potential future anti-scarring therapies. En1+ fibroblasts are primarily found in the reticular dermis.", "notes": "Advanced scar biology from Ch16; closest match is collagen/scar maturation", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What factors increase the risk of developing abnormal (hypertrophic or keloid) scars?", "answer": "Patient factors: darker skin pigmentation (African, Asian descent), age (higher risk in younger patients, ages 10-30), genetic predisposition/family history, hormonal changes (puberty, pregnancy). Wound factors: wounds crossing joints or high-tension areas, wounds perpendicular to RSTLs, deep dermal injury, prolonged inflammation, infection, wounds healing by secondary intention, foreign body reaction. Anatomic sites: anterior chest/sternum, shoulders, upper back, earlobes are high-risk locations.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "Describe the use of bleomycin for keloid treatment. What is the typical administration technique?", "answer": "Bleomycin is an antineoplastic antibiotic that inhibits DNA synthesis in fibroblasts. It is administered via multiple needle puncture technique: the keloid surface is punctured with a needle dipped in bleomycin solution (1.5 IU/mL), allowing the drug to penetrate the scar tissue. This is repeated every 4-6 weeks. Advantages: effective for steroid-resistant keloids. Side effects: hyperpigmentation, pain, skin atrophy, and rarely pulmonary fibrosis with systemic absorption (dose-dependent).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What is the subunit principle in scar revision, and who described it?", "answer": "Described by Burget and Menick (1985) for nasal reconstruction, the subunit principle states that scars are less conspicuous when placed at the borders of aesthetic subunits rather than within them. When planning scar revision (especially on the face), incisions and closures should be designed to fall along natural boundaries between aesthetic subunits (e.g., alar groove, nasolabial fold, lid-cheek junction). This principle extends to placing scars in natural creases or at hairline boundaries.", "notes": "Scar revision principle from Ch16", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Acute vs chronic wound", "question": "What non-surgical treatments can be used for depressed or atrophic scars?", "answer": "Options include: (1) Dermal fillers (hyaluronic acid, calcium hydroxylapatite) for volume restoration â€” temporary effect. (2) Autologous fat grafting â€” provides volume and potentially regenerative stem cell effects. (3) Fractional CO2 laser â€” stimulates collagen remodeling to raise depressed scars. (4) Microneedling â€” induces controlled micro-injury to promote collagen induction. (5) Acellular dermal matrix â€” can be placed beneath depressed scars. (6) Chemical peels â€” for superficial atrophic scars (acne scars).", "notes": "Depressed scar treatments from Ch16; assigned to wound assessment as closest match", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What are the key planning principles when designing a Z-plasty for scar revision?", "answer": "Key principles: (1) The central limb is placed along the scar to be revised. (2) Peripheral limbs should be equal in length to the central limb. (3) Standard angle is 60Â° (provides 75% lengthening with good transposition). (4) Flaps must include adequate subcutaneous tissue thickness to ensure blood supply. (5) The final scar orientation should be planned to fall along RSTLs. (6) Multiple small Z-plasties in series are often better than one large Z-plasty. (7) Flaps should not be undermined too thinly to avoid tip necrosis.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What is a serial (multiple) Z-plasty, and when is it preferred over a single Z-plasty?", "answer": "A serial Z-plasty uses multiple small Z-plasties arranged along a long scar instead of one large Z-plasty. Advantages: (1) Better distribution of tension across the scar. (2) Each individual flap is smaller and has more reliable blood supply. (3) Less distortion of surrounding tissue. (4) The final scar has a more natural, broken-up appearance. Preferred for: long linear scar contractures, web space contractures, and areas where a single large Z-plasty would create excessive tissue distortion.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Compare split-thickness skin grafts (STSG) and full-thickness skin grafts (FTSG) in terms of composition, contraction, donor site healing, and indications.", "answer": "STSG: contains epidermis + partial dermis; greater secondary contraction at recipient site; donor site heals by re-epithelialization from remaining dermal appendages (7-21 days); used for large wounds, burns, and areas where contraction is acceptable. FTSG: contains epidermis + entire dermis; minimal secondary contraction; donor site must be closed primarily; used for aesthetically (face) or functionally (hand) important areas. Thicker grafts = less contraction but more demanding recipient bed requirements.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What are the three subtypes of split-thickness skin grafts based on thickness, and what are their eponymous names?", "answer": "Thin STSG (Thiersch-Ollier graft): 0.15-0.3 mm. Intermediate STSG (Blair-Brown graft): 0.3-0.45 mm. Thick STSG (deep graft): 0.45-0.6 mm. Thinner grafts heal faster at the donor site and allow repeat harvest (~2 weeks), but result in more recipient site contraction and typically do not transfer functional appendages. Thicker grafts transfer hair follicles and glands but cause more donor site morbidity.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "Describe the three phases of skin graft 'take' and the timeline for each.", "answer": "(1) Serum imbibition (days 0-2): graft survives via diffusion of plasma/nutrients from wound bed through fibrin layer. (2) Revascularization (begins ~24-48 hours): occurs by three mechanisms - anastomosis (reconnection of existing vessels between graft and bed), neovascularization (new vessel ingrowth from recipient into graft), and endothelial cell ingrowth (recipient endothelial cells proliferate along pre-existing graft vascular basal lamina as graft endothelial cells degenerate). (3) Maturation (weeks to years): remodeling, collagen deposition/cross-linking, fibroblast repopulation, myofibroblast-driven contraction, and regression of immature blood vessels.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "What are the three causes of skin graft failure, and how can each be prevented?", "answer": "(1) Hematoma/seroma: fluid collection separates graft from wound bed, preventing imbibition and revascularization. Prevention: meticulous hemostasis, meshing or pie-crusting the graft for fluid egress, compressive/bolster dressings, or vacuum-assisted closure. (2) Infection: bacteria destroy graft tissue and prevent vascular ingrowth. Prevention: adequate wound bed debridement, antimicrobial dressings, topical agents (silver nitrate, mafenide acetate). (3) Shearing/instability: disrupts fragile new blood vessels. Prevention: bolster dressings, splinting, immobilization, fibrin glue, conscientious postoperative handling.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What tissues are NOT suitable as recipient beds for skin grafts, and why? What is the exception?", "answer": "Tissues with inadequate blood supply cannot support graft revascularization: irradiated tissue, ischemic tissue, scar tissue, exposed bone, and exposed tendon. The exception is when intact vascularized periosteum or peritenon is present â€” grafting can sometimes succeed over these surfaces. For areas of exposed bone/tendon without periosteum/peritenon, vacuum-assisted closure can encourage granulation tissue formation before grafting, or dermal substitutes can be applied.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Meshing ratios and indications", "question": "What is skin graft meshing? Describe the available ratios and the trade-offs of increasing mesh expansion.", "answer": "Meshing involves placing systematic slits in an STSG to allow expansion, with templates ranging from 1:1 to 1:9. Benefits: covers larger wound areas with limited donor skin, allows fluid egress preventing seroma/hematoma. Trade-offs of increasing mesh ratio: greater wound contracture, longer re-epithelialization time (keratinocytes must fill wider gaps), higher risk of hypertrophic scarring, uneven cobblestone-like skin relief, and increased graft fragility. For functional/aesthetic areas, surgeons typically prefer 1:1.5 to 1:2 maximum.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Meshing ratios and indications", "question": "What is the Meek technique, and when is it indicated?", "answer": "The Meek technique involves dividing a skin graft into small skin squares (originally 0.8 x 0.8 mm using a Meek-Wall microdermatome) that can be spread out to cover a much larger surface area, with expansion ratios up to 1:100. It is indicated when donor skin is extremely scarce, such as in massive burns with limited unburned skin. The technique can be combined with aerosolized epithelial cells (RECELL) to improve healing time between graft islands.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is a composite graft? Where is it most commonly used?", "answer": "A composite graft includes epidermis, dermis, AND a layer of subcutaneous fat tissue. The fat is less vascularized and more prone to ischemia, so optimal wound bed vascularity is critical for survival. Composite grafts are most frequently used for reconstruction of the nasal tip, nasal alar, and columella in patients with cleft lip. Due to their thickness, they have the highest nutritional demands of any graft type.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Donor site selection and healing", "question": "Describe common donor sites for STSG and FTSG, and the principles guiding donor site selection.", "answer": "STSG donor sites: lateral thighs and trunk (areas easily covered by clothing). FTSG donor sites: lower abdomen, inguinal crease, retro-auricular region; for facial defects, scalp, neck, and supraclavicular areas provide the best color match. Selection principles: (1) choose sites that allow good color/texture match to recipient, (2) FTSG donors must have enough laxity for primary closure, (3) consider aesthetic implications of donor scarring, (4) for burns, use whatever donor site is available, sparing face and hands.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "What is serum imbibition, and why is it critical for early skin graft survival?", "answer": "Serum imbibition is the first phase of graft take (days 0-2) during which the graft receives oxygen and nutrients via passive diffusion through the plasma/fibrin layer between the graft and wound bed. This is the sole means of graft survival before revascularization begins. Any barrier that disrupts this process (hematoma, seroma, infection, necrotic tissue) will result in graft ischemia and failure. Excessive serum accumulation (seroma) is also harmful, which is why grafts are meshed or pie-crusted.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "How does skin graft thickness affect the transfer of cutaneous appendages (hair, sweat glands, nerves)?", "answer": "Thin STSGs: do NOT transfer whole cutaneous appendages â€” no hair growth or sweat gland function. Thick STSGs: transfer some hair follicles and glandular structures; may develop hair growth and sweat gland function months after grafting. FTSGs: transfer the full complement of appendages. Neural regrowth occurs in grafted skin with similar histologic structures, but patients often report abnormal sensation (hypersensitivity, decreased sensation, pain) for prolonged periods. Sweat glands can reactivate ~3 months post-grafting after neural reconnection but remain abnormal compared to native skin.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft fixation: bolster, tie-over, NPWT", "question": "Describe the methods of skin graft fixation and when each is preferred.", "answer": "(1) Absorbable sutures: for smaller grafts or patients who cannot tolerate removal. (2) Skin staples: efficient for large grafts but painful on removal. (3) Bolster (tie-over) dressing: bulky dressing secured by sutures tied over it; ideal for difficult-to-dress areas, concavities, and small grafts (face, hand). (4) Vacuum-assisted closure (VAC): provides continuous compression and fluid removal over a petroleum gauze/silicone interface; excellent for large or uneven grafts over joints. (5) Fibrin glue: sprayed on wound bed before graft placement, acts as provisory extracellular matrix. Dressings are left 3-8 days to minimize shearing.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Why should FTSG be 'defatted' before application, and how is this done?", "answer": "Defatting removes subcutaneous fat from the dermal surface of the FTSG. This is necessary because fat is poorly vascularized and acts as a barrier to revascularization from the wound bed, compromising graft take. Technique: the graft is spread dermis-side-up over a finger or basin, and fat tissue is trimmed tangentially from the dermis using scissors. Care must be taken not to damage dermal appendages or the dermal-hypodermal junction during defatting.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Donor site selection and healing", "question": "How does a split-thickness skin graft donor site heal, and what factors affect healing time?", "answer": "STSG donor sites heal by re-epithelialization from residual dermal appendages (hair follicles, eccrine glands, sebaceous glands) left in the remaining dermis. Epidermal stem cells in the hair follicle bulge region and glandular epithelium proliferate and migrate to resurface the wound. Healing time: 7-21 days depending on graft thickness taken, size of harvest, and patient age. Thinner grafts allow faster donor healing and repeat harvest (~2 weeks). Children and elderly require thinner harvests due to thinner native skin.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "Compare four skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, Epicel, and RECELL. Include their composition, origin, and application.", "answer": "Integra: bovine tendon type I collagen on a silicone sheet (xenogeneic); applied to wound bed, vascularizes in ~3 weeks, silicone removed and STSG placed on top. AlloDerm: human acellular lyophilized cadaver dermis (allogeneic); off-the-shelf, skin graft placed after vascularization. Epicel: cultured epidermal autograft (autologous); keratinocytes expanded from patient biopsy over several weeks in lab, then grafted. RECELL: autologous cell suspension (epidermis + dermis); bedside kit creates spray from patient donor skin in ~30 minutes for immediate application.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "What is the role of acellular dermal matrices (ADMs) in wound reconstruction? What are the key considerations?", "answer": "ADMs are decellularized human, animal, or synthetic tissues that serve as scaffolds for host cell migration and tissue regeneration. They minimize antigenicity while providing structural support. Indications: wounds where contracture prevention is critical, protection of exposed sensitive structures, and cosmesis. ADMs come as powders, suspensions, woven sheets, or full decellularized tissue. Key considerations: (1) they require vascularization before skin grafting, (2) they have significant additional cost, (3) composition and architecture vary widely between products.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "What is the role of cadaveric allograft skin, and why does it ultimately fail?", "answer": "Cadaveric allograft serves as a temporary biologic dressing, particularly valuable in acute treatment of large thermal burns where it minimizes mortality and enhances healing. However, allogeneic tissue is antigenic and will ultimately elicit an immunogenic rejection response. Tissue matching can extend survival, but without immunosuppression, all allografts are eventually rejected. Additional concerns: differing harvest, processing, and preservation techniques between tissue banks can affect viability and contamination risk.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is 'pie-crusting' of a skin graft, and when is it performed?", "answer": "Pie-crusting is the creation of multiple small perforations in a non-meshed skin graft using a scalpel. Purpose: allows egress of blood and serum from beneath the graft, preventing hematoma/seroma formation that would separate the graft from the wound bed and compromise take. It is performed on sheet (unmeshed) grafts, particularly when grafting functional areas such as the hands where a meshed appearance would be aesthetically unacceptable but fluid drainage is still needed.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Describe the five layers of the epidermis from superficial to deep and their key features.", "answer": "(1) Stratum corneum: terminally differentiated anuclear corneocytes; primary permeability barrier. (2) Stratum lucidum: only in glabrous skin (palms/soles); contributes to thickness. (3) Stratum granulosum: rich in keratohyaline; keratinocytes transition to corneocytes and release lipid-rich ECM. (4) Stratum spinosum: keratinocytes anchored by tonofilaments to desmosomes; contains Langerhans cells (tissue-resident macrophages for antigen presentation). (5) Stratum basale (germinal layer): proliferative keratinocytes, melanocytes, and Merkel cells; semi-differentiated stem cells with self-renewal capacity; turnover cycle ~40-60 days.", "notes": "Skin anatomy relevant to grafting depth from Ch17", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Describe the dermal-epidermal junction: its layers, key components, and why it matters for skin grafts.", "answer": "The DEJ consists of: (1) Basal lamina - lamina lucida (integrins, laminins) and lamina densa (collagen IV). (2) Basal reticularis - meshwork of collagen III interacting with basal lamina via collagen VII and fibrillin anchoring fibrils. Keratinocytes anchor via hemidesmosomes; papillary dermis anchors through basal reticularis. The DEJ has a corrugated cross-section (interlocking papillae) increasing surface area for shear resistance and diffusion. Significance for grafts: absence of intact DEJ in skin grafts makes them unstable against mechanical forces, contributing to graft fragility and susceptibility to shearing.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is the difference between papillary and reticular dermis, and why is this relevant for skin grafting?", "answer": "Papillary dermis: superficial, interfaces with basement membrane, responsible for anchoring DEJ and metabolic exchange with epidermis. Reticular dermis: deeper, thicker, composed of dense irregular connective tissue rich in collagen and elastic fibers; provides primary elasticity; contains most dermal appendages (glands, Pacinian and Ruffini corpuscles, nerves, vascular perforators). Relevance to grafting: graft thickness determines how much dermis is included â€” thin STSGs take only papillary dermis, thick STSGs include some reticular dermis, and FTSGs include the full dermis to the dermal-hypodermal junction.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What considerations guide the choice between STSG and FTSG for facial reconstruction?", "answer": "FTSGs are preferred for facial reconstruction because they provide: (1) minimal secondary contraction (preventing distortion), (2) better color and texture match (especially from supraclavicular, retro-auricular, upper eyelid, or scalp donors), (3) transfer of functional appendages, and (4) superior aesthetic outcome. STSGs on the face result in significant contracture and poor cosmesis but may be necessary when FTSG donor sites are unavailable (e.g., large burn patients). For full-thickness defects, the subunit principle should guide graft placement at aesthetic unit borders.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is the expected blood loss during wound excision for skin grafting, and how is hemostasis achieved?", "answer": "Blood loss of 100-200 mL is expected for every 1% of body surface area excised. Hemostasis methods: cautery or suture ligation for larger vessels; topical agents of thrombin and epinephrine for general oozing; tumescent solution of dilute epinephrine injected pre-excision to reduce bleeding. Hemostasis must be achieved before graft placement, as any blood collection (hematoma) between graft and wound bed will impair graft take.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "How does autologous fat grafting improve previously grafted skin?", "answer": "Penetrating (percutaneous) fat grafts beneath previously grafted or scarred skin have been demonstrated to: (1) enhance overlying skin quality, (2) improve vascularity, (3) increase skin mobility by releasing tethered scars, (4) improve contour irregularities, and (5) improve resistance to shear and trauma. The mechanism is thought to involve both volume restoration and regenerative effects from adipose-derived stem cells within the fat graft.", "notes": "Soft tissue augmentation after grafting from Ch17; assigned to graft physiology as closest match", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "What is RECELL and how does it differ from cultured epidermal autograft (Epicel)?", "answer": "RECELL: a bedside kit that creates an autologous cell suspension (keratinocytes and other cells) from a small donor skin sample in ~30 minutes, delivered as a spray. Can be used immediately intraoperatively. Epicel: requires a skin biopsy to be sent to a lab where keratinocytes are cultured and expanded over several weeks before being returned as sheets for grafting. Key difference: RECELL provides immediate intraoperative use with minimal delay, while Epicel requires weeks of lead time but provides more organized epithelial sheets. RECELL is particularly useful as an adjunct over widely meshed grafts to accelerate re-epithelialization.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three types of cartilage? Describe their composition, properties, and where each is found.", "answer": "(1) Hyaline cartilage: most common type, composed of type II collagen and rich in glycosaminoglycans, providing stiffness for compressional loading. Found in costal cartilage, articular surfaces, trachea, and nose. Covered by perichondrium (except articular cartilage). (2) Fibrocartilage: bundles of thick collagen fibers (types I and II) with intervenient cartilage islands, providing high tensile strength. Found in meniscus, intervertebral discs, symphyseal joints, bone-tendon junctions. (3) Elastic cartilage: abundant elastic fibers forming a network with collagen, providing great flexibility and resistance to repeated bending. Found in external ear, larynx, and epiglottis. Covered by perichondrium.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Why does cartilage graft survive relatively easily when transplanted compared to other tissue grafts?", "answer": "Cartilage is a unique tissue with a low metabolic rate due to: (1) sparse cell population (chondrocytes are few), (2) avascular structure â€” cartilage has no intrinsic blood supply, and (3) near-anaerobic glycolytic metabolism with low oxygen consumption. Because cartilage is nourished by tissue fluid diffusion rather than direct blood supply, a transplanted cartilage graft can survive by diffusion from the surrounding recipient bed without requiring revascularization. Additionally, cartilage is considered 'immunologically privileged,' meaning allogeneic cartilage elicits less immune rejection than other tissue types.", "notes": "Cartilage graft biology from Ch19; closest match in topic list", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the perichondrium? Describe its structure and role in cartilage repair.", "answer": "The perichondrium is a layer of dense irregular connective tissue surrounding most cartilage (except articular cartilage). It consists of two layers: (1) Outer fibrous layer: composed of collagen fibers and fibroblasts. (2) Inner chondrogenic layer: contains partially undifferentiated mesenchymal stem cells and chondrogenic progenitor cells. The inner layer can generate new cartilage (neochondrogenesis), which is why perichondrial grafts are used for cartilage reconstruction. Free perichondrial grafts can regenerate cartilage tissue when transplanted to appropriate recipient sites.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare the three autologous cartilage graft donor sites: auricular, nasal septal, and rib cartilage. Include advantages, limitations, and applications for each.", "answer": "Auricular (elastic) cartilage: most versatile graft; easily fashioned/contoured; harvested under local anesthesia with minimal donor deformity if technique is careful; limited quantity. Used for ear reconstruction, nasal reconstruction, tarsal/nipple reconstruction. Nasal septal (hyaline) cartilage: limited amount available; accessed via hemitransfixion incision; MUST preserve L-shaped strut for nasal support. Used for dorsal augmentation, eyelid reconstruction, tip grafts. Rib (hyaline) cartilage: greatest available quantity and mechanical strength; can be contoured into any shape; higher donor morbidity (pain, chest wall deformity, pneumothorax risk). Used for total ear framework, major nasal reconstruction, tracheal repair.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the L-shaped strut in septal cartilage harvesting, and why must it be preserved?", "answer": "The L-shaped strut is a structural support of septal cartilage that must be maintained during harvesting of nasal septal cartilage grafts. It consists of: (1) a dorsal strut along the nasal dorsum, and (2) a caudal strut along the anterior nasal septum. Preservation is critical to maintain nasal structural support and prevent nasal collapse (saddle nose deformity). The amount of L-strut cartilage needed varies depending on the strength, thickness, and dimensions of the native septum and other nasal support structures (upper/lower lateral cartilages, nasal bones). Only the non-supportive posterior quadrangular cartilage can be freely harvested.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the potential complications of rib (costal) cartilage graft harvesting?", "answer": "Complications include: (1) Pneumothorax â€” the most serious intraoperative complication, occurring during posterior perichondrial dissection. (2) Chest wall pain â€” most common complaint, peaks in first week and gradually diminishes over 3 months. (3) Chest wall clicking. (4) Donor site scarring. (5) Chest wall contour deformity â€” particularly with Nagata's method requiring harvest of 4-6 costal cartilages. Prevention: careful technique keeping elevator tip against cartilage during posterior dissection, preserving perichondrium, intercostal nerve block with 0.25% bupivacaine, and returning unused cartilage fragments to the perichondrial sleeve.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the five techniques for managing the auricular donor site after composite graft harvest, based on graft size?", "answer": "Technique 1 (<1 cm graft): harvest from root of helix, primary closure with dog-ear run anteriorly into hairline. Technique 2 (1-1.5 cm): larger graft from helical base, closure by running dog-ear anteriorly and posteriorly with cartilage wedge removed from triangular fossa. Technique 3 (wide but short): harvest from anteroinferior helical rim, dog-ear run superiorly and inferiorly. Technique 4 (1-1.2 cm): helical base harvest with helical rim advancement and postauricular scaphomastoid suture to prevent overprojection. Technique 5 (>1.5 cm): V-shaped wedge with half-star cartilage pattern at apex plus postauricular incision with scaphomastoid suture to prevent ear cupping/distortion.", "notes": "Surgical technique for auricular composite graft donor management from Ch19", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three major components required for tissue-engineered cartilage?", "answer": "(1) Seed cells: the cellular component responsible for matrix production, deposition, and tissue formation (chondrocytes, or stem cells induced to chondrogenic lineage). (2) Scaffold: a three-dimensional structure (e.g., PGA nonwoven fibers, polylactic acid, fibrin polymer) providing architecture for cells to reside, proliferate, and produce matrix. The scaffold degrades over time as new tissue forms. (3) Tissue formation environment: the appropriate in vitro or in vivo conditions (culture medium, growth factors, mechanical stimuli) needed for cell proliferation, matrix production, scaffold degradation, and tissue remodeling into mature engineered tissue.", "notes": "Cartilage tissue engineering from Ch19; closest match is reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is a composite chondrocutaneous graft, and what limits its available size as a free graft?", "answer": "A composite chondrocutaneous graft contains both cartilage and overlying skin harvested as a single unit, most commonly taken from the ear for nasal reconstruction. The size of free auricular composite grafts is limited by the lack of immediate blood supply after transplantation â€” the graft must survive initially by diffusion until revascularization occurs. Larger grafts have greater risk of central necrosis. To overcome this size limitation, microvascularly transferred auricular composite grafts based on the superficial temporal vessels can be used, with reported flap survival rates of 97% even for large nasal defects.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "How has CAD/CAM technology been applied to cartilage tissue engineering for auricular reconstruction?", "answer": "The process: (1) CT scan of patient's normal ear collects 3D geometric data. (2) CAD system generates mirror-image data of the normal ear. (3) CAM system 3D-prints a mold with the ear's 3D structure. (4) Scaffold material (PGA fibers coated with polylactic acid) is shaped using the mold, achieving >97% structural similarity to the original ear. (5) Chondrocytes are seeded onto the scaffold and cultured in vitro for 12 weeks, forming mature cartilage tissue with ~82.6% morphological similarity. This approach potentially allows patient-specific auricular reconstruction without the need for costal cartilage harvest.", "notes": "Tissue engineering application from Ch19", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare intramembranous and endochondral ossification. Where does each occur?", "answer": "Intramembranous ossification: direct condensation of mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) that differentiate into osteoblasts, depositing bone without a cartilaginous intermediate. Creates flat bones of the craniofacial skeleton. Endochondral ossification: MSCs first form a hyaline cartilage template that is subsequently replaced by bone through chondrocyte hypertrophy, calcification, vascular invasion, and osteoblast-driven bone deposition. Creates long bones of the appendicular skeleton, vertebral column, and pelvis. Both processes occur during fracture repair.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare cortical and cancellous bone: structure, location, and function.", "answer": "Cortical (compact) bone: accounts for 80% of skeleton; dense and strong; forms the outer shell; primary unit is the osteon (haversian system) with concentric lamellae around central haversian canals containing vessels/nerves; Volkmann's canals connect horizontally. Covered by periosteum (outer fibrous layer + inner cambium/osteogenic layer) and lined by endosteum. Cancellous (trabecular) bone: 20% of skeleton; porous; located in medullary cavity at ends of long bones; bony trabeculae oriented along lines of stress; greater surface area for remodeling and higher metabolic activity; provides internal support for bone marrow.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three cell types in bone? Describe their morphology, location, and function.", "answer": "Osteoblasts: rounded, basophilic cells on external bone surfaces at areas of active formation. Derived from MSCs. Produce osteoid (bone matrix), facilitate mineralization. 20% become osteocytes; rest undergo apoptosis or become bone-lining cells. Osteocytes: stellate cells with thin processes embedded in lacunae. Communicate via gap junctions through canaliculi. Functions include mechanosensing, mineral homeostasis, and bone resorption regulation. Terminally differentiated from osteoblasts. Osteoclasts: large, multinucleated cells with ruffled border on endosteal/periosteal surfaces. Derived from hematopoietic stem cells. Function: bone resorption. Stain positive for tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase (TRAP).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the chemical composition of bone?", "answer": "Bone is composed of 60% inorganic matter, 30% organic matter, and 10% water. Inorganic phase: primarily hydroxyapatite (Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2) crystals; serves as mineral reservoir (calcium, phosphate, potassium, magnesium, sodium). Organic phase (osteoid): deposited by osteoblasts; primarily type I collagen (two alpha-1 chains + one alpha-2 chain forming right-handed helix); undergoes hydroxylation, glycosylation, and cross-linking by lysyl oxidase (copper-dependent enzyme). Bone strength derives from interactions between collagen fibers and inorganic minerals.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare primary and secondary (callus) bone repair. When does each occur?", "answer": "Primary bone repair: direct cortical healing WITHOUT cartilaginous intermediate (similar to intramembranous ossification). Requires anatomic reduction with rigid internal fixation and minimal interfragmentary strain. Cutting cones of osteoclasts burrow through cortex, followed by MSC-derived osteoblasts creating new haversian systems. Woven bone â†’ lamellar bone over weeks to months. Secondary (callus) bone repair: healing WITH cartilaginous intermediate. Occurs in fractures treated with external/intramedullary fixation, casts, or untreated fractures. Three phases: inflammatory (7 days), reparative (weeks-months, callus formation with endochondral + intramembranous ossification), and remodeling (years, woven â†’ lamellar bone).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the three phases of secondary (callus) bone healing.", "answer": "(1) Inflammatory phase (~7 days, peaks at 48 hours): hematoma forms providing fibrin scaffold and signaling molecules; platelets release PDGF and TGF-beta; neutrophils, lymphocytes, monocytes, and macrophages remove debris and stimulate angiogenesis. (2) Reparative phase (weeks to months, begins day 3-4): fracture callus forms from cartilage, woven bone, osteoid, fibrous tissue, and blood vessels; undergoes endochondral (week 2, cartilage calcification â†’ bone) and intramembranous ossification. (3) Remodeling phase (months to years): woven bone replaced by lamellar bone; osteoclasts resorb poorly located trabeculae; new bone forms along lines of stress via Wolff's law.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Define osteoinduction, osteoconduction, and osseointegration.", "answer": "Osteoinduction: process by which undifferentiated pluripotent cells are stimulated to differentiate into the osteoblast lineage and form new bone. Can occur naturally (fracture repair) or be induced by BMPs, growth factors, or bioactive materials. Osteoconduction: ability of a material to serve as a scaffold onto which bone cells can attach and grow; requires porosity for ingrowth of bone and fibrovascular tissue. Examples: allografts, calcium phosphate, collagen. Osseointegration: stable structural and functional connection between native bone and an implant without cartilaginous intermediate; requires bioinert (e.g., titanium) or bioactive implant surface; enhanced by surface roughness.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare cancellous and cortical bone grafts: properties, incorporation, and indications.", "answer": "Cancellous grafts: little immediate structural strength but HIGHER osteogenic, osteoinductive, and osteoconductive properties; rapidly incorporated and revascularized (~2 weeks) via creeping substitution; indicated for gaps <6 cm in non-stress-bearing areas. Sources: iliac crest, cranial diploe, proximal tibia, distal radius. Cortical grafts: provide IMMEDIATE structural support but limited osteogenic potential; slower incorporation (1-2 months); rely on plasmatic imbibition; can bridge defects up to 12 cm; require rigid fixation to prevent fracture. Used for onlay augmentation. Sources: fibula, rib, iliac crest.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is distraction osteogenesis? Describe its three stages and key parameters.", "answer": "Distraction osteogenesis is the formation of new bone by gradual controlled separation of osteotomized bone segments, pioneered by Ilizarov. Three stages: (1) Latency (1-7 days post-osteotomy): bone healing initiates, periosteal integrity restores, callus begins forming. Shorter in younger patients. (2) Activation/distraction: gradual separation by turning a screw at a predetermined rate, inducing membranous ossification. Mineralization starts 10-14 days from osteotomy fronts, proceeding centrally. (3) Consolidation: immature bone remodels into mature lamellar bone; period from end of distraction to device removal. Success requires: device stability, adequate latency, gradual distraction, and sufficient consolidation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three arterial systems supplying a long bone?", "answer": "(1) Diaphyseal nutrient artery: primary blood supply to the inner two-thirds of cortex and medullary cavity; enters through cortex and divides into ascending and descending medullary branches. (2) Metaphyseal and epiphyseal arteries: arise from arteries supplying adjacent joints; deliver blood to cancellous bone at the ends of long bones. (3) Periosteal arteries: supply the outer one-third of cortex. Blood flows centrifugally through bone (endosteum to periosteum) driven by high intramedullary pressure. These three systems interconnect extensively, providing redundancy.", "notes": "Bone vascular anatomy from Ch20", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "List the autologous bone graft donor sites and their key advantages and complications.", "answer": "Ilium (most common): large amount of corticocancellous bone; versatile; easily accessible. Complications: chronic pain, paresthesias (lateral femoral cutaneous nerve), gait abnormalities. Preserve ASIS by stopping 3 cm posterior. Calvarium: rapid revascularization due to rich diploic vessels; less resorption; ideal for craniofacial/orbital reconstruction. Risk: intracranial injury; stay >1 cm from coronal, >1.5 cm from sagittal suture. Rib: flexible, easy to contour; minimal cancellous bone; pneumothorax risk. Fibula: mainly used as vascularized transfer for mandible reconstruction. Tibia: limited to small cancellous amounts (e.g., alveolar grafting).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What seven principles should be followed when handling bone grafts to optimize survival?", "answer": "(1) Minimize air exposure time (ideally <1 hour to maintain cell viability). (2) Cover graft in blood-soaked sponge with moist saline to extend viability 4-6 hours. (3) Keep grafts cool â€” temperatures >42Â°C cause cell death. (4) Use antibiotic washes cautiously â€” they are also cellucidal. (5) Avoid dead space around the graft. (6) Place cancellous portion of graft in contact with cancellous bone in the bed. (7) Place graft in a previously prepared vascularized bed to increase survival.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is creeping substitution, and how does it differ between cancellous and cortical bone grafts?", "answer": "Creeping substitution is the process by which transplanted bone graft is gradually resorbed and replaced by new bone via vascular ingrowth. In cancellous grafts: occurs rapidly (~2 weeks) because the porous trabecular architecture allows quick vascular ingrowth; viable surface osteoblasts and endosteal cells contribute directly; serves primarily as osteoconductive scaffold. In cortical grafts: occurs slowly (1-2 months) because the dense structure limits vascular penetration; the graft relies on plasmatic imbibition to sustain outer osteocytes initially; replacement proceeds from outside inward; requires rigid fixation during the prolonged incorporation period.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the characteristics of an ideal bone substitute? Name three categories of bone substitutes.", "answer": "Ideal bone substitute characteristics: (1) chemically inert, (2) hypoallergenic/no foreign body reaction, (3) easily contoured, (4) stable and durable shape retention, (5) non-carcinogenic, (6) capable of incorporation into or replacement by living bone. Three categories: (1) Cement pastes: calcium phosphate cements (BoneSource, Norian) â€” malleable, set intraoperatively. (2) Osteoactive materials: bioactive glass (NovaBone) and demineralized bone matrix (DBM) â€” recruit and stimulate osteoprogenitor cells. (3) Prefabricated polymers: synthetic materials shaped prior to implantation. Additionally: the ideal ceramic should be biodegradable, macroporous, mechanically stable, osteoconductive, and suitable as a growth factor carrier.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are bone morphogenetic proteins (BMPs) and their clinical significance in bone repair?", "answer": "BMPs are members of the TGF-beta superfamily with at least 15 known isoforms. They are potent osteoinductive agents that stimulate mesenchymal cells to differentiate into osteoblasts. BMPs are expressed early in fracture repair by mesenchymal cells, osteoblasts, and osteoclasts. Clinical applications: exogenous recombinant BMPs (especially BMP-2 and BMP-7) can heal critical-sized bone defects, stimulate ectopic bone formation, and potentially accelerate fracture repair. BMP-2 combined with VEGF shows synergistic effects on bone formation. BMPs are delivered on carriers/scaffolds (collagen sponges, calcium phosphate) to the defect site.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Why are calvarial bone grafts preferred for craniofacial reconstruction? Describe the harvest technique.", "answer": "Calvarial grafts are ectomesenchymal with a rich diploic vascular system allowing rapid revascularization, less resorption, and better structural maintenance compared to endochondral bone grafts. Technique: coronal incision through scalp and galea; can harvest split-thickness (outer table only) or full-thickness; corticotomy must stay >1 cm from coronal suture and >1.5 cm from sagittal suture; be aware of perforating vessel posteriorly near sagittal suture. Indications: calvarial, midfacial, nasal, and orbital reconstruction. Limitation: split grafts may not be feasible in young children due to thin calvarium.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the role of VEGF in bone repair, and how does it interact with other growth factors?", "answer": "VEGF is a potent regulator of both vasculogenesis and angiogenesis, critical for bone maturation and repair. Hypertrophic chondrocytes at growth plates express high levels of VEGF. Anti-VEGF antibodies inhibit vascular invasion and impair bone formation. VEGF acts synergistically with BMP-2: combined BMP-2 gene therapy + VEGF protein significantly increases bone formation compared to either alone. VEGF deficiency in osteoblast precursors leads to reduced bone mass and increased marrow fat (osteoporosis phenotype). HIF-1-alpha pathway couples angiogenesis with osteogenesis; skeletal angiogenesis may be rate-limiting for bone growth.", "notes": "Bone healing biology from Ch20; best fit under tissue healing differences", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What factors negatively affect fracture healing?", "answer": "Blood supply: disrupted vascularity impairs healing; angiogenesis is critical for bone repair. Motion: excessive movement at fracture site causes delayed/non-union, though controlled micromotion can enhance healing. Age: pediatric fractures heal faster than adult fractures due to superior angiogenic potential, more robust periosteum, and greater MSC activity. Other factors: infection, smoking, diabetes, radiation, malnutrition, corticosteroids. Specific to distraction osteogenesis: insufficient device stability, inadequate latency period, too-rapid distraction rate, and insufficient consolidation time all impair new bone formation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the Seddon and Sunderland classifications of nerve injury. What did Mackinnon add?", "answer": "Seddon (1943) â€” three types: (1) Neurapraxia: focal demyelination/conduction block; full recovery within 3 months. (2) Axonotmesis: direct axonal damage with intact basal lamina; Wallerian degeneration occurs but recovery is possible. (3) Neurotmesis: complete nerve transection; no spontaneous recovery. Sunderland â€” five degrees: 1st (neurapraxia), 2nd (axon damage, basal lamina intact, full recovery at 1mm/day), 3rd (axon + basal lamina damaged, partial recovery), 4th (neuroma-in-continuity, no recovery), 5th (complete transection, no recovery). Mackinnon added 6th degree: combination of different degrees of injury in different fascicles within the same nerve.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is Wallerian degeneration, and in which nerve injury types does it occur?", "answer": "Wallerian degeneration is the degeneration of the axon and myelin sheath DISTAL to the site of nerve injury. It occurs in axonotmetic (Sunderland 2nd-4th degree) and neurotmetic (5th degree) injuries, but NOT in neurapraxia (1st degree). The process involves: axonal fragmentation, myelin breakdown, Schwann cell proliferation to form bands of BÃ¼ngner (guides for regenerating axons), and macrophage recruitment to clear debris. It begins within hours and is largely complete by 3 weeks, which is why electrodiagnostic signs (fibrillations, positive sharp waves) may not appear until 3 weeks post-injury.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the rate of nerve regeneration, and why is 'time is muscle' an important concept?", "answer": "Nerve regeneration occurs at a maximum rate of approximately 1 mm/day (or ~1 inch/month). 'Time is muscle' means that irreversible muscle atrophy occurs as early as one year after denervation â€” the motor endplates degenerate and fibrosis replaces muscle fibers. Therefore, the distance from the site of injury to the target muscle is the most important prognostic factor. 'Time is pathway' is also critical: with advancing time, the quality of cellular support (Schwann cells) for nerve regeneration along the pathway worsens. Patients can lose up to 70-80% of motor units before a clinical deficit is noted, due to collateral sprouting.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the gold standard for nerve repair, and when should repair be performed?", "answer": "Primary neurorrhaphy (direct end-to-end repair) remains the gold standard. Timing: Sharp penetrating injuries with nerve deficit should be explored within 72 hours. Repair within 48 hours = primary repair. Delayed repair (2-7 days) requires freshening of nerve ends. After first week = secondary repair, with decreasing likelihood of achieving primary neurorrhaphy. For closed injuries (crush/traction), wait 3-4 months with serial clinical exam and EMG â€” if no motor unit potentials by 3-4 months, surgical exploration is warranted. The advantage of early repair: cleaner surgical field, distal stimulation still possible, topographic landmarks visible.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare the options for bridging a nerve gap: autograft, acellular allograft, conduit, and nerve transfer.", "answer": "Nerve autograft ('bronze standard'): contains Schwann cells + ECM scaffold; results decrease >6 cm; donor site morbidity/sensory loss. Sural nerve most common donor; alternatives include MABC (up to 28 cm). Acellular nerve allograft (ANA): retains 3D scaffold without immunogenicity; no donor morbidity; limited to small-diameter, non-critical, short gaps (â‰¤3 cm); no Schwann cells; expensive. Conduit (synthetic/biological): guides regeneration; limited to non-critical sensory deficits <3 cm; no Schwann cells or matrix. Nerve transfer: expendable donor fascicle reinnervates recipient closer to target; converts proximal to distal injury; faster recovery; requires knowledge of internal topography.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the importance of tension in nerve repair, and how should it be managed?", "answer": "Excessive tension across a nerve repair increases scarring at the coaptation site and impairs axonal regeneration. In an uninjured nerve, just 15% strain reduces microvascular flow. Clinically, any tension is meticulously avoided. Management: (1) Mobilization of proximal/distal nerve ends can overcome gaps <5 mm. (2) If primary repair cannot be achieved tension-free, two neurorrhaphy sites (with interpositional graft) are preferable to one under tension. (3) Postural manipulation of the extremity to reduce tension is NOT recommended â€” it increases dehiscence risk and stiffness from immobilization. (4) Harvested nerve grafts should be 15-20% longer than the gap to ensure tension-free coaptation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the advantages of nerve transfers over nerve grafting and tendon transfers?", "answer": "Advantages over nerve grafting: (1) Surgery performed outside the zone of injury (cleaner surgical field). (2) Converts proximal high-level injury to distal low-level injury, shortening regeneration distance. (3) Only one neurorrhaphy site (vs. two for graft). (4) Earlier functional recovery. Advantages over tendon transfers: (1) Can restore sensibility in addition to motor function. (2) A single transfer can reinnervate multiple muscle groups. (3) Does not disrupt muscle-tendon insertion/attachment, maintaining original function and tension. (4) Not limited to one function or straight line of pull. Synergistic nerve transfers are preferred for easier rehabilitation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the supercharge end-to-side (SETS) nerve transfer technique, and when is it used?", "answer": "SETS involves transferring a donor nerve fascicle to the side of an injured nerve distally to provide early motor axons while awaiting proximal regeneration from a high-level injury. It does not sacrifice the injured nerve's potential for recovery. Used for: (1) Proximal Sunderland 2nd-3rd degree injuries where long regeneration distance means prolonged time to muscle reinnervation. (2) Severe cubital tunnel syndrome or high ulnar nerve injuries where some spontaneous recovery is anticipated. The distal anterior interosseous nerve (AIN) motor branch is commonly used as the donor for ulnar nerve SETS transfer.", "notes": "Nerve transfer technique from Ch21", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "How are electrodiagnostic studies (nerve conduction study and EMG) used to evaluate nerve injuries?", "answer": "Nerve conduction study: provides quantitative data â€” conduction velocity reflects myelination; CMAP (compound muscle action potential) and SNAP (sensory nerve action potential) amplitudes measure the number of functional axons. EMG: provides qualitative data on nerve-muscle unit function. Key timing: fibrillations and positive sharp waves from axonal injury don't appear until ~3 weeks post-injury (after Wallerian degeneration), so early studies are NOT useful except to document pre-injury pathology. Serial testing is critical: EMG changes precede clinical recovery by months. If no motor unit potentials (MUPs) by 3-4 months in closed injuries, surgical intervention is warranted.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What prognostic factors affect recovery following peripheral nerve injury?", "answer": "Patient factors: age (younger = better recovery), comorbidities. Injury factors: mechanism (sharp transection > crush > avulsion), location (distal injuries have better prognosis â€” shorter distance to target), degree of injury (Sunderland classification). Treatment factors: timing of repair (earlier = better), method of repair (tension-free > tension), alignment accuracy. Distance from injury to end-target muscle is the SINGLE most important prognostic factor (nerve regenerates at maximum 1 mm/day). Additional factors: Schwann cell senescence increases with graft length (poor outcomes >6 cm for autografts, >3 cm for allografts); 50% of regenerating axons may never reach the correct end-target.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the techniques of nerve repair: epineurial vs perineurial. What suture size is optimal?", "answer": "Epineurial repair: preferred method; sutures placed through the outer epineurium to coapt nerve ends. External landmarks (longitudinal vessels, fascicular patterns) used for alignment. Fewest sutures needed for accurate alignment is recommended. Perineurial (fascicular) repair: individual fascicular groups are aligned and sutured through perineurium. Advantage: potentially better alignment. Disadvantages: extensive dissection and permanent intraneural sutures increase fibrosis. Clinical studies show both techniques are equally effective if fascicles are not overlapped. Optimal suture: 9-0 nylon for major peripheral nerves (10-0 snaps under tension, 8-0 pulls through tissue). Fibrin glue can supplement/replace sutures for tension-free repairs.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the beneficial characteristics of autologous fat grafts, and what cell types are present in grafted fat?", "answer": "Beneficial characteristics: low donor site morbidity, procedural simplicity, low cost, results in living autologous tissue, and bioactive properties. Cell types present in cannula-harvested adipose tissue: mature adipocytes, adipose-derived stem cells (ASCs)/preadipocytes, fibroblasts, vascular endothelial cells, pericytes, and various immune cells. The stromal vascular fraction (SVF) â€” the non-adipocyte cellular component â€” contains ASCs that improve graft survival through angiogenic properties and have applications in tissue engineering and regenerative medicine.", "notes": "Fat grafting basics from Ch22", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the Coleman method of structural fat grafting: the three key steps and their principles.", "answer": "(1) Harvesting: gentle extraction using blunt-tip cannula (3-4 mm) with minimal suction to preserve adipocyte architecture; any depot can be used (abdomen, love handles, thighs). Infiltrate with tumescent solution (0.2% lidocaine with 1:200,000 epinephrine, 1:1 superwet ratio). (2) Refinement: centrifugation at 3000 rpm (1200 g) for 3 minutes in 10 mL syringes; remove aqueous layer (blood/anesthetic) from bottom and oil from top; preserves viable fat with near-normal cellular enzyme activity. (3) Placement: inject small aliquots through 17-gauge blunt Coleman cannula in multiple tissue planes during cannula withdrawal; maximize surface area contact with surrounding tissue for revascularization.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Why is fat placed in small aliquots during fat grafting, and what happens when large globules are injected?", "answer": "Small aliquots maximize the contact surface area between grafted fat and surrounding tissue, allowing revascularization from the recipient bed â€” similar to skin graft survival, fat grafts depend on initial diffusion and then neovascularization. Large globules result in central necrosis (the center is too far from blood supply for diffusion), with subsequent resorption and volume loss, or formation of oil cysts and calcifications. Fat should be built up with tiny parcels rather than large deposits that are molded afterward. Molding can displace fat or cause necrosis.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are adipose-derived stem cells (ASCs), and what is their clinical significance?", "answer": "ASCs are multipotent stem cells found within adipose tissue, surrounding blood vessels and in the connective tissue framework. They are isolated from the stromal vascular fraction (SVF) via enzymatic collagenase digestion (~2-5 x 10^5 nucleated SVF cells per gram of fat). ASCs can differentiate into multiple mesenchymal lineages (adipose, bone, cartilage, muscle) and even ectodermal/endodermal lineages. Clinical significance: (1) improve fat graft survival through angiogenic properties, (2) have regenerative effects on damaged/irradiated tissue, (3) do not express MHC-II (potential for immunomodulation), (4) being researched for tolerance induction in vascularized composite transplantation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is the oncologic safety evidence for fat grafting to the breast after cancer surgery?", "answer": "Clinical evidence supports safety: systematic reviews of >3600 patients show fat necrosis is the most common complication (4.4%), biopsy of subsequent lumps needed in 2.7%, and meta-analyses show NO significant difference in oncologic event rates between fat-grafted and non-fat-grafted groups. Local recurrence rates (~2.2%) are LOWER than baseline breast cancer recurrence rates (5.2-10.6%). Fat grafting does not interfere with cancer surveillance. HOWEVER, basic science studies show strong ASC-cancer cell interactions in vitro â€” this discrepancy is attributed to use of immortalized cell lines (from distant metastases) that do not represent primary cancer behavior. The ASPS originally banned breast fat grafting in 1987 but reversed this position.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the indications for fat grafting in reconstructive surgery?", "answer": "Reconstructive indications: (1) Facial rejuvenation and volume restoration. (2) Breast reconstruction after cancer surgery (lumpectomy defects, implant replacement, total breast reconstruction). (3) Mitigating radiation damage â€” irradiated tissue can be restored to more normal consistency/texture. (4) Post-traumatic deformities and scar contracture improvement. (5) Congenital anomalies (hemifacial microsomia, Treacher Collins syndrome). (6) Burn injury reconstruction. (7) Breast capsular contracture. (8) Amputee stump remodeling for prosthetic fit. (9) Iatrogenic deformities from prior cosmetic surgery. Fat grafting has regenerative effects: downregulates TGF-beta pathways in scarred tissue.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the complications of fat grafting, and what is the expected retention rate?", "answer": "Average retention rate: ~63% at 9 months (varies between individuals â€” some are 'good responders,' others are 'poor responders'). Unpredictable resorption is the most significant risk. Complications: fat necrosis, oil cyst formation, calcification, contour irregularities (excess fat visible as lumps under thin skin), overcorrection, scarring. Rare but serious: fat embolism from intravascular injection, allergic reaction to local anesthetic, perioperative bleeding, blood clots, infection. Multiple sessions are often required. Weight loss after grafting leads to volume loss. Unwanted parcels are difficult to remove.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "How does fat grafting differ at different tissue levels, and what effects does placement depth achieve?", "answer": "Subdermal: improves skin quality, decreases wrinkling, reduces pore size, may reduce scarring. Requires caution â€” surface irregularities are more apparent, especially under thin skin (e.g., lower eyelid). Supraperiosteal: changes shape related to underlying bony skeleton; used for skeletal augmentation effects. Intramuscular: builds bulk and volume. The surgeon determines placement level based on desired effect. Fat is deposited in small aliquots during cannula withdrawal, with multiple passes in multiple tissue planes. As tissue quality improves after initial grafting, subsequent sessions may achieve even better results.", "notes": "Fat grafting technique details from Ch22", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What early research by Peer established about fat graft survival, and how does this inform modern technique?", "answer": "Lyndon Peer (1950s) systematically studied transplanted fat and demonstrated: (1) Fat grafts lose about 45% of weight and volume at one year. (2) Surviving fat cells maintain their native volume. (3) Improper handling decreases graft survival. (4) Graft SIZE affects survival â€” a single walnut-sized graft loses volume more rapidly than multiple smaller grafts of similar total weight, because smaller grafts have greater surface area for revascularization. (5) Revascularization is essential for graft survival. These findings directly inform Coleman's principles: gentle handling, small aliquot placement in multiple planes, and maximizing surface area contact with vascularized tissue.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Define an angiosome. What are the two types of connections that link adjacent angiosomes?", "answer": "An angiosome is a composite three-dimensional block of tissue (skin, muscle, bone, and other soft tissues) supplied by a single source (segmental or distributing) artery and its accompanying vein(s). Adjacent angiosomes are linked by: (1) Reduced-caliber choke anastomotic vessels â€” the most common connection, featuring narrowed arteries matched by avalvular (oscillating) veins that allow bidirectional flow. (2) True anastomoses â€” vessels that connect adjacent territories WITHOUT reduction in caliber. True anastomoses are most common along cutaneous nerves or in areas of mobile skin. The body consists of approximately 40-61 angiosomes (depending on subdivisions) that fit together like a jigsaw puzzle.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What are the two types of cutaneous perforators? How do they differ in course and relative proportion?", "answer": "Direct cutaneous perforators (~40%): Pass between deep tissues before piercing the deep fascia; their main destination is the skin. They tend to be larger in diameter with larger vascular territories (e.g., circumflex scapular artery). Subtypes include direct cutaneous (axial) vessels and septocutaneous vessels that follow intermuscular septa. Indirect cutaneous perforators (~60%): Emerge from the deep fascia as terminal branches of arteries that primarily supply muscles and other deep tissues. The majority are musculocutaneous perforators that pass through muscle before reaching the skin. There are approximately 400 cutaneous perforators in the human body (diameter â‰¥0.5 mm).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "List and explain the key anatomic concepts related to flap design (Box 23.1).", "answer": "(1) Vessels follow the connective tissue framework of the body â€” fundamental to fasciocutaneous/septocutaneous flap design. (2) Arteries radiate from fixed to mobile areas; veins converge from mobile to fixed areas â€” perforators emerge where skin is anchored to deep fascia. (3) Vessels 'hitchhike' with nerves â€” basis for neurovascular flaps. (4) Vessel size and orientation are products of tissue growth and differentiation. (5) Vessels interconnect to form a continuous 3D network of vascular arcades. (6) Vessels obey the law of equilibrium â€” if one vessel is small, its neighbor is reciprocally large. (7) Vessels have a relatively constant destination but variable origin. (8) Venous networks consist of linked valvular and avalvular channels. (9) Muscles are prime movers of venous return.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Explain the 'law of equilibrium' as it applies to vascular anatomy. Give a clinical example.", "answer": "The law of equilibrium (described by Debreuil-Chambardel and Salmon) states that the anatomical territories of adjacent arteries bear an inverse (reciprocal) relationship to each other â€” if one vessel is small, its partner is large to compensate, and vice versa. Yet they combine to supply the same region. Clinical example: The superficial inferior epigastric artery (SIEA) and the deep inferior epigastric artery (DIEA) perforators to the lower abdomen. When the SIEA territory is large, the DIEA perforator territory is relatively smaller, and vice versa. This is clinically important: if a large superficial inferior epigastric VEIN is noted, the drainage of the inferior portion of the DIEAP flap may depend on the superficial venous drainage system.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the delay phenomenon? Describe the physiologic mechanism and time course.", "answer": "The delay phenomenon is the only documented method to increase skin flap survival. It involves strategic division of some vascular pedicles to the planned flap before the definitive transfer. Mechanism: When a flap is elevated/delayed, the reduced-caliber choke anastomotic vessels that link adjacent cutaneous perforator territories enlarge to match the caliber of the arteries they connect. This is an ACTIVE process involving multiplication and hypertrophy of cells in each layer of the vessel wall. Time course: Initial vasoconstriction immediately post-elevation â†’ gradual dilation during first 48 hours â†’ dramatic dilation from 48-72 hours (maximal effect) â†’ plateau then gradual continued increase. The effect is PERMANENT and IRREVERSIBLE. Without delay, one adjacent vascular territory can be safely captured; with delay, additional territories can be included.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What determines the survival length of a skin flap?", "answer": "Skin flap survival depends on: (1) The caliber and length of the dominant vessels on which the flap is based. (2) The caliber and span of the adjacent captured artery/arteries and vein(s). (3) The caliber and length of the connecting choke vessels. (4) An anatomically favorable or unfavorable venous return. (5) The volume of flap tissue. Where perforators are large and widely separated, each territory is large and a long flap can be raised safely (characteristic of loose skin areas of torso/scalp). Where perforators are small and close together (e.g., sole of foot), the viable length is short unless the source vessel is included. Flap survival can be extended by strategic delay procedures and by including the underlying source vessels through intramuscular/intermuscular dissection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Why should deep fascia be included in flaps of the extremities but is unnecessary in flaps of the torso?", "answer": "In the extremities (and scalp), the skin is relatively fixed to the deep fascia, and the dominant cutaneous vessels course ON or adjacent to the deep fascia for considerable distances â€” they 'hug' the fascial surface. Therefore, including the deep fascia in a fasciocutaneous flap preserves these vessels and ensures reliable perfusion. In the loose skin areas of the torso (e.g., over pectoralis major, iliac fossa, breast), the direct cutaneous vessels course only briefly near the deep fascia before being 'plastered to' the undersurface of the subcutaneous fat. They pierce the fat obliquely and travel within the integument for long distances in the subdermal plexus. Therefore, the deep fascia is unnecessary in torso flaps because the major cutaneous vessels have already left its surface.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is a propeller flap? Describe its design principles.", "answer": "A propeller flap is a local island fasciocutaneous flap based on a single dissected cutaneous perforator. The flap is likened to the blades of a propeller â€” it has two 'blades' of unequal length on either side of the perforator. Design: The largest adjacent uninjured perforator to the wound is identified (often with Doppler); the longer blade covers the wound while the shorter blade covers the donor site. Key principles: (1) The perforator must not be injured during elevation. (2) The deep fascia around the perforator must be released to prevent kinking during rotation. (3) Gentle tissue handling is critical. (4) The flap can be designed throughout the body in various orientations. The propeller concept is an extension of the perforator flap concept.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the venous architecture affect flap design? Describe the three types of muscle venous drainage.", "answer": "Venous drainage parallels arterial anatomy but consists of linked valvular (directional) and avalvular (oscillating/bidirectional) segments. Where arterial choke vessels define arterial territories, they are matched by oscillating veins. If a flap's venous valves are oriented AWAY from the pedicle, drainage is 'anatomically unfavorable' (risk of congestion). Three muscle types by venous architecture: Type I â€” single venous territory draining in one direction (favorable regardless of skin paddle placement). Type II â€” two territories draining from an oscillating vein in opposite directions. Type III â€” three or more territories draining in multiple directions. For type II/III muscles, a distally-placed skin paddle may have valves oriented opposite to the pedicle drainage, creating unfavorable venous return.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What are the clinical implications of the angiosome concept for flap design?", "answer": "Three key clinical implications: (1) Each angiosome defines the safe anatomic boundary of tissue in each layer that can be transferred as a composite flap (skin + muscle, muscle + bone, etc.) on the source vessels. The adjacent angiosome territory can usually be safely captured. (2) The junctional zone between adjacent angiosomes occurs WITHIN muscles (not between them), so muscles provide important anastomotic bypass shunts if the main source artery or vein is obstructed. (3) Most muscles span two or more angiosomes and receive supply from each territory â€” this enables capture of a skin island from one angiosome by muscle supplied in the adjacent territory, providing the basis for musculocutaneous flap design.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the neurovascular classification of muscles (Types I-IV)? Give examples of each.", "answer": "Based on nerve supply pattern: Type I â€” single unbranched nerve entering the muscle (e.g., latissimus dorsi, extensor indicis, plantaris). Type II â€” single nerve that branches BEFORE entering the muscle (e.g., deltoid, gluteus maximus, trapezius, vastus lateralis, serratus anterior). Type III â€” multiple motor branches from the SAME nerve trunk (e.g., gastrocnemius, sartorius, tibialis anterior, subscapularis, triceps). Type IV â€” multiple motor nerves from DIFFERENT nerve trunks (e.g., rectus abdominis, internal oblique, digastric, erector spinae, levator scapulae). Clinical relevance: This classification helps determine whether a muscle can be subdivided into independent neurovascular functional units for partial muscle transfer while leaving viable muscle behind.", "notes": "Muscle classification from Ch23; best fit under flap vascular anatomy", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Why is the anterior tibial compartment particularly vulnerable to compartment syndrome? How does angiosome anatomy explain this?", "answer": "The anterior tibial compartment is supplied EXCLUSIVELY by the anterior tibial artery â€” all muscles (tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus, extensor hallucis longus, peroneus tertius) lie in ONE territory. The compartment has rigid walls across which vascular connections are sparse. This is particularly true medially, where the tibia is subcutaneous â€” the only connections between anterior and posterior tibial arteries are through the periosteum and the cutaneous network. This isolated single-artery supply within a rigid fascial compartment makes these muscles most vulnerable to ischemia, explaining why the anterior compartment is most commonly affected in exercise-related compartment syndrome ('shin splints').", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What are the three methods of preoperative assessment of cutaneous perforators? Compare their advantages and limitations.", "answer": "(1) Handheld Doppler: Simple, inexpensive, portable; provides limited information; significant inter-observer variability; may detect background vessels; less reliable in obese patients. (2) Color duplex Doppler: Greater resolution; accurately detects vessel diameter and flow velocity; no IV contrast, lower cost, no radiation; requires trained technician. (3) CT angiography (CTA): Most accurate method; identifies perforators as small as 0.3 mm; provides detailed 3D information on perforator position, diameter, and course; enables grid-based reporting for communication between radiologist and surgeon. Disadvantages: cost, radiation exposure, contrast allergy risk, claustrophobia. CTA is more accurate than handheld Doppler. CTA has become the preferred modality, with proponents citing reduced operating time.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the evolution from TRAM flap to DIEAP flap illustrate the progression of flap surgery?", "answer": "The evolution: Pedicled TRAM flap â†’ Free TRAM flap â†’ Muscle-sparing free TRAM flaps â†’ DIEAP (deep inferior epigastric artery perforator) flap. This progression reflects: (1) Greater understanding of the precise anatomy of musculocutaneous perforators. (2) Reduced donor site morbidity â€” the DIEAP flap preserves the entire rectus abdominis muscle and its fascia by dissecting the perforator through the muscle, eliminating the risk of abdominal wall hernia and weakness. (3) The perforator flap concept: large skin flaps can be raised reliably based on musculocutaneous perforators alone, gaining the advantage of large vessel size without unnecessary muscle bulk or function loss. The DIEAP flap is one of the core perforator flaps for breast reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the perforator flap nomenclature system? Explain using the DIEAP flap as an example.", "answer": "The nomenclature system names all perforator flaps according to the source vessel supplying the flap. The letters 'AP' are added to indicate artery perforator. When the perforating vessels can pass through different muscles, a suffix with the muscle initials is added. For septocutaneous perforators, the suffix '-s' is used. Example: DIEAP-ra = Deep Inferior Epigastric Artery Perforator through Rectus Abdominis. Other examples: LCFAP-vl (lateral circumflex femoral artery perforator through vastus lateralis = anterolateral thigh flap), TAP-ld (thoracodorsal artery perforator through latissimus dorsi), SGAP-gm (superior gluteal artery perforator through gluteus maximus), PIOAP-s (posterior interosseous artery perforator, septocutaneous).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Describe the vascular anatomy of the head and neck as it relates to flap design. What makes scalp flaps different from neck flaps?", "answer": "The head/neck has 13 angiosomes from branches of the external carotid, internal carotid, and subclavian arteries. The SMAS/galea/platysma layers form a rich continuous anastomotic vascular layer extending from occiput across the head and face to the neck. Key differences: Scalp â€” rich vascular arcades between occipital, postauricular, superficial temporal (external carotid) and supraorbital, supratrochlear, dorsal nasal (internal carotid) arteries. Most scalp veins are avalvular, so flaps can be based in any direction. Neck â€” blood supply is more sparse; main perforators emerge from fixed skin sites (borders of trapezius and SCM, along hyoid bone, clavicle); platysma provides the vascular link between external carotid (superiorly) and subclavian (inferiorly). The tongue has an avascular midline raphe with poor crossover, risking tip necrosis if ipsilateral lingual artery is sacrificed.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the vascular significance of the soleus muscle in the lower leg?", "answer": "The soleus muscle has critical vascular significance because it receives large branches from the popliteal artery that LINK the branches of the posterior tibial and peroneal vessels within the muscle substance. This makes soleus an important anastomotic link in the leg. This explains Salmon's observation that ligation of the popliteal artery DISTAL to the take-off of its branches to the soleus had little effect on perfusion of the leg â€” the rich intramuscular anastomoses within the soleus provide collateral blood flow. By contrast, ligation of the popliteal artery PROXIMAL to the sural arteries has a major effect on distal leg blood supply because few muscle bellies cross the knee joint and the main anastomoses around the knee are extramuscular (geniculate vessels).", "notes": "Lower leg vascular anatomy from Ch23", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Name the core group of standard perforator flaps and their source vessels.", "answer": "(1) DIEAP flap (deep inferior epigastric artery perforator) â€” workhorse for breast reconstruction. (2) Anterolateral thigh (ALT) flap â€” based on descending branch of lateral circumflex femoral vessels through vastus lateralis; called the 'ideal free flap' for its versatility. (3) Submental artery flap (SMAP). (4) Posterior interosseous flap (PIOAP-s) â€” septocutaneous. (5) Thoracodorsal artery perforator flap (TAP-ld) â€” through latissimus dorsi. (6) Superior gluteal artery perforator flap (SGAP-gm). (7) Inferior gluteal artery perforator flap (IGAP-gm). Additionally, local perforator flaps are increasingly utilized for wound closure, providing good color match and contour while potentially avoiding free tissue transfer.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Explain why pretibial lacerations have a high incidence of skin flap necrosis, using vascular anatomy.", "answer": "The subcutaneous periosteal surface of the tibia contains anastomoses between the posterior tibial and anterior tibial arteries. Most pretibial lacerations occur superficial to the periosteum and 'shear off' the cutaneous arteries that emerge from this periosteal plexus. Because the tibia is subcutaneous in this region (skin is directly fixed to periosteum/bone with no intervening muscle), the cutaneous blood supply relies on these periosteal vessels. When they are disrupted by the shearing mechanism of injury, the overlying skin flap loses its blood supply, resulting in the high incidence of traumatic skin flap necrosis in this area.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Compare axial, random, fasciocutaneous, musculocutaneous, septocutaneous, and perforator flaps.", "answer": "Axial flap: based on a known named cutaneous artery providing reliable blood supply along the flap's axis. Random flap: based on unnamed vessels of the dermal/subdermal plexus without a specific axial vessel; survival limited by length-to-breadth ratios. Fasciocutaneous flap: includes deep fascia; vessels course on or adjacent to deep fascia (useful in limbs/scalp). Septocutaneous flap: based on vessels traveling along intermuscular septa to the skin (a subtype of direct cutaneous supply). Musculocutaneous flap: skin supplied by perforators that pass THROUGH underlying muscle; includes muscle bulk. Perforator flap: skin flap based on any cutaneous perforator (musculocutaneous or septocutaneous), with the perforator dissected free of surrounding tissue to spare muscle/function. All are fundamentally based on the same cutaneous vascular architecture described by Manchot and Salmon.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the vascular anatomy of the forearm relate to safe harvest of a radial forearm flap?", "answer": "When the radial forearm flap is harvested, the only muscles lying solely within the radial artery angiosome are brachioradialis, ECRL, and ECRB (supplied by the radial recurrent branch). However, the radial recurrent branch has an excellent anastomosis with the profunda brachii artery. Therefore, dissection can proceed safely right up to the radial artery origin from the brachial artery with either division of the recurrent branch or inclusion with one of the 'mobile mass' muscles. By contrast, proximal dissection of the ulnar artery to its brachial origin is MORE dangerous â€” the flexor digitorum profundus and FCU are supplied solely by the ulnar artery and its interosseous branches, and collateral pathways are less developed. Most forearm muscles span at least two angiosomes, providing redundant blood supply.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the concept 'vessels hitchhike with nerves' apply to flap design?", "answer": "Throughout the body, cutaneous nerves are accompanied by a longitudinal system of arteries and veins â€” either a single long artery or a chain-linked system of perforators joined by true anastomoses. This neurovascular relationship provides the basis for long axially-oriented neurovascular flaps with the added potential of providing sensation at the repair site. Examples: the saphenous neurovascular flap and sural flap (PontÃ©n's original long fasciocutaneous flaps), supraorbital/infraorbital/occipital neurovascular bundles in the head, intercostal neurovascular bundles on the torso. The veins accompanying nerves are frequently large 'venous freeways' (cephalic, basilic, saphenous systems). Many current 'axial' or 'fasciocutaneous' flaps are in fact neurovascular flaps.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Describe the Mathes-Nahai classification of muscle flaps (Types I-V). Give an example of each.", "answer": "Type I â€” one vascular pedicle (e.g., tensor fascia lata, gastrocnemius, vastus lateralis). Type II â€” dominant pedicle + minor pedicle(s); most common pattern in human muscle (e.g., gracilis, soleus, sternocleidomastoid, trapezius, rectus femoris). Type III â€” two dominant pedicles from separate vascular sources; can be split (e.g., gluteus maximus, rectus abdominis, serratus anterior, temporalis). Type IV â€” segmental vascular pedicles; division of >2-3 pedicles risks distal necrosis (e.g., sartorius, tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus). Type V â€” one dominant pedicle + secondary segmental pedicles; can be elevated on either system, has two arcs of rotation (e.g., latissimus dorsi, pectoralis major).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the Mathes-Nahai classification of fasciocutaneous flaps (Types A, B, C)?", "answer": "Type A â€” direct cutaneous pedicle that courses initially beneath, then superficial to the deep fascia, providing numerous fasciocutaneous perforators. Long, relatively superficial course permits evaluation by palpation/Doppler. Often called 'axial' flaps (e.g., groin flap, scalp flaps, saphenous flap). Type B â€” septocutaneous pedicle coursing between major muscle groups in an intermuscular septum. Fairly constant in location (e.g., anterolateral thigh, radial forearm, lateral arm, scapular flaps). Type C â€” based on dominant musculocutaneous perforators entering the deep fascia, without incorporating the underlying muscle. Increasing pedicle length requires proximal dissection through muscle. This is the anatomic model for perforator flaps in microsurgical transplantation (e.g., DIEP, nasolabial flap).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the 'six Cs' of the complete flap classification system? Briefly explain each.", "answer": "(1) Circulation â€” the source of blood supply (direct vs. indirect vessels); the most important characteristic. (2) Constituents (composition) â€” the tissues included: skin, fascia, muscle, bone, nerve, viscera, etc. (3) Contiguity (destination) â€” local, regional, or distant (free). (4) Construction (flow) â€” unipedicle, bipedicle, antegrade, retrograde (reverse), turbocharged, supercharged, or arterialized venous. (5) Conditioning (preparation) â€” delay, tissue expansion, prefabrication, sensate/functional nerve coaptation, or none. (6) Conformation (shape) â€” special shapes, tubed, combined/compound flaps, or none. Default values (unipedicle, antegrade, no conditioning, no special conformation) can be omitted from the nomenclature.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the 'perforasome' concept? List the four major characteristics described by Saint-Cyr.", "answer": "The perforasome is the vascular territory of a single cutaneous perforator â€” an evolution from the angiosome (territory of a source vessel) to the perforator as the basic vascular unit for flap design. Four characteristics: (1) Each perforasome is linked with adjacent perforasomes by direct linking vessels (communicating directly between adjacent perforators) and indirect linking vessels (communicating through the subdermal plexus). (2) Flap design and skin paddle orientation should follow the direction of linking vessels â€” axial in the extremities, perpendicular to the midline in the trunk. (3) Filling occurs within perforasomes of the SAME source artery first, then to adjacent source arteries. (4) The mass vascularity of a perforator found adjacent to an articulation flows AWAY from that articulation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Define and differentiate: composite, conjoined, and chimeric compound flaps.", "answer": "Composite flap (solitary vascularization) â€” multiple tissue components (e.g., skin + muscle + bone) en bloc, all dependent on a single vascular source. Classic musculocutaneous and osteocutaneous flaps are examples. Conjoined flap (combined vascularization) â€” at least two anatomically distinct territories, each with independent vascular supply, joined by a common physical boundary. Subtypes: perforator-based or branch-based (with independent or common source vessels). Chimeric flap (combined vascularization) â€” multiple independent flaps each with independent vascular supply, but all pedicles linked to a larger common source vessel. Subtypes: perforator-based, branch-based, or fabricated (sequential â€” attached at terminus of source vessel, or internal â€” attached to an indigenous branch). Example: subscapular system chimeric flap combining scapular flap, latissimus dorsi, and serratus anterior.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the five types of perforators defined by the Gent consensus document? How do they differ surgically?", "answer": "Type 1 â€” Direct perforators: perforate the deep fascia ONLY (no traversal of other structural tissues). Type 2 â€” Indirect muscle perforators predominantly supplying subcutaneous tissues (pass through muscle but mainly feed skin). Type 3 â€” Indirect muscle perforators predominantly supplying muscle with secondary branches to subcutaneous tissues. Type 4 â€” Indirect perimysial perforators: travel within the perimysium between muscle fibers before piercing the deep fascia. Type 5 â€” Indirect septal perforators: travel through the intermuscular septum before piercing the deep fascia. Surgical significance: Type 1 requires only fascial dissection; Types 2-4 require intramuscular dissection of varying difficulty and duration; Type 5 requires septal dissection only (generally easier). These distinctions guide the technical approach and expected operative time.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What determines a muscle flap's arc of rotation? How is it inversely related to the number of vascular pedicles?", "answer": "Arc of rotation is determined by: (1) the extent of elevation of the muscle from its anatomic bed, (2) the ability of the muscle to reach adjacent areas without devascularization, (3) the number and location of vascular pedicles relative to the muscle's origin and insertion. The closer the dominant pedicle is to either the origin or insertion, the greater the arc of rotation. Arc of rotation is INVERSELY proportional to the number of pedicles: Type IV muscles (segmental pedicles like sartorius) have limited arc because dividing pedicles risks distal necrosis. Type V muscles (like latissimus dorsi, pectoralis major) have the WIDEST arc â€” their dominant pedicle is near the insertion with additional segmental pedicles near the origin, giving two arcs of rotation (standard arc on dominant pedicle, reverse arc on segmental pedicles).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Compare the reconstructive ladder, reconstructive triangle, and reconstructive elevator concepts.", "answer": "Reconstructive ladder (1982) â€” step-ladder approach from simple to complex: direct closure â†’ skin graft â†’ local flap â†’ distant flap â†’ microvascular flap â†’ tissue expansion. Limitation: assumes simpler is always better; does not consider form and function. Reconstructive triangle â€” emphasizes selecting a technique that safely achieves form AND function. Three sides: flaps, microsurgery, and tissue expansion, balanced by safety, form, and function considerations. Reconstructive elevator (Gottlieb & Krieger) â€” the surgeon 'jumps to the most appropriate floor' based on specific requirements of the patient, wound, and circumstances rather than climbing sequentially. A simpler option may not produce optimal results. Requires creative thought to achieve the best form and function. This paradigm does not eliminate the ladder concept but replaces it for modern reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What is the no-reflow phenomenon? Describe its pathogenesis and clinical significance.", "answer": "The no-reflow phenomenon is the failure to restore blood flow to ischemic tissue despite successful restoration of arterial inflow. After prolonged ischemia, the point of irreversibility is reached (~12 hours) and the flap cannot be salvaged. Pathogenesis: (1) Ischemia causes swelling of endothelial and parenchymal cells, narrowing capillary lumens. (2) Intravascular aggregation of blood cells occurs. (3) Intravascular fluid leaks into interstitial space causing edema. Three mechanisms: (1) Oxygen-derived free radicals damage endothelial and parenchymal cell membranes. (2) Cell membrane damage allows Ca2+ influx causing intracellular overload. (3) Altered arachidonic acid metabolism: decreased vasodilating/antithrombotic PGI2 production by endothelium and increased vasoconstricting/thrombotic TXA2 by platelets. Clinical: tPA injected into the flap artery may help by dissolving microvascular clots, but once true no-reflow is established, the flap cannot be salvaged.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What are the common causes of flap failure? Which is the most common?", "answer": "Technical error is the MOST COMMON cause of flap failure. Mechanical/technical causes include: (1) Kinking of the pedicle. (2) Pressure on the pedicle from tight dressings or an insufficiently wide tunnel. (3) Damage to the pedicle during dissection. (4) Over-tightness of closure. (5) Overstretching of the flap. (6) Placing the drain too close to the pedicle (negative pressure can compress it). Pathophysiologic causes include: vasospasm and thrombosis from surgical trauma, insufficient distal vascularity, and the no-reflow phenomenon. Vasoactive substances released during surgical trauma include norepinephrine (sympathetic nerves), thromboxane A2, leukotriene B4, and serotonin (platelets), and hemoglobin (red blood cells) â€” all causing vasoconstriction. Traumatized endothelium decreases synthesis of vasodilating prostacyclin and nitric oxide (EDRF/NO).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "Explain the difference between supercharging and turbocharging a flap.", "answer": "Supercharging: Using an EXTERNAL (unrelated/distant) vascular source to augment either the inflow or outflow of a flap in addition to its original vascular source. Analogy: using an external power source to boost the engine. Example: A superiorly pedicled TRAM flap salvaged by anastomosing a thoracic or upper extremity vascular source to the CONTRALATERAL deep or superficial inferior epigastric vessels. Turbocharging: Using the flap's own MAIN vascular source to connect to an additional pedicle from the SAME flap, creating direct flow to the vascular territory of the connected branch. Analogy: using the engine's own exhaust for additional power. Example: Directly connecting the ipsilateral and contralateral deep inferior epigastric vessels of a TRAM flap to improve the vascular supply to the whole flap.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is an arterialized venous flap? Describe the three theories of survival and the Woo classification.", "answer": "An arterialized venous flap uses a subcutaneous vein for BOTH arterial inflow and venous outflow â€” replacing the normal artery â†’ capillary â†’ vein pathway. Advantages: no donor site artery needed, very thin harvest, rapid elevation. Three survival theories: (1) A-V shunting â€” retrograde flow from venous system to arterial system via paralyzed arteriovenous shunts. (2) Reverse flow â€” flow from venules into capillaries. (3) Capillary bypass â€” flow through venous system without entering arterial side until neovascularization. Woo classification: Type I â€” 'through-and-along-valve' with straight or Y-shaped pattern (mimics standard vein graft flow). Type II â€” 'against-valve' with arterial inflow against valve through afferent vein (reversed Y or H pattern). Type III â€” mixed pattern, venous outflow drains through efferent veins against intravenous valves. Commonly used for hand/finger soft tissue reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is a retrograde (reverse) flow flap? Give three clinical examples.", "answer": "A retrograde flow flap is one in which the orthograde (antegrade) pedicle is ligated proximally, and the flap survives on reverse flow through the distal portion of the major pedicle, via anastomotic connections. Examples: (1) Distally based radial forearm flap â€” relies on retrograde flow through the deep palmar arch, with rotation point at the wrist; useful for hand reconstruction. (2) Reverse sural flap â€” sural artery/nerve ligated proximally, flap survives on retrograde flow from the peroneal artery via distal anastomoses; covers heel, ankle, and dorsum of foot. (3) Reversed first dorsal metacarpal artery flap â€” for hand reconstruction. Disadvantages: risk of venous congestion (despite venous connections); increased complications in patients with venous insufficiency or advancing age; poor cosmesis of donor site (often requires skin graft).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Compare the advantages and disadvantages of muscle/musculocutaneous flaps versus fasciocutaneous/perforator flaps.", "answer": "Muscle/musculocutaneous ADVANTAGES: reliable specific pedicles, pedicle often outside zone of injury, provides bulk for deep defects, malleable, resistant to bacterial inoculation, often one-stage, can restore motor/sensory function. DISADVANTAGES: donor site function loss, aesthetically undesirable donor site, excessive bulk, muscle atrophy over time, contour deformities. Fasciocutaneous/perforator flap ADVANTAGES: thin and pliable, reliable blood supply, minimal functional donor morbidity, muscle-sparing, ability to restore sensation, many donor sites, reduced donor morbidity, improved recovery. DISADVANTAGES: lack of bulk for deep defects, technically more challenging (pedicle dissection, often requires microvascular techniques), size limitations, arc of rotation sometimes limited, may require skin graft closure, steep learning curve, variable perforator anatomy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the five elevation planes for perforator flaps? How do they differ in thickness?", "answer": "From deep to superficial: (1) Subfascial â€” immediately under and including the deep fascia (same as fasciocutaneous structure); thickest flap. (2) Suprafascial â€” immediately above and excluding the deep fascia. (3) Superthin â€” elevated on the superficial fascia (fascia-like film layer between deep and superficial fat). (4) Ultrathin â€” elevated on a fascia-like pseudofascia within the superficial fat layer. (5) Subdermal (pure skin perforator/PSP) â€” thinnest flap, elevated just beneath the dermis. The subcutaneous fat is divided into a superficial fat layer (small lobules) and a deep fat layer (large lobules) separated by the superficial fascia. Each plane has unique properties and challenges; the surgeon must understand the anatomy and potential pitfalls to safely elevate at each level.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What are the two theories explaining the delay phenomenon, and what is the clinical technique?", "answer": "Two theories: (1) Ischemic tolerance â€” delay acclimatizes the flap to ischemia through adaptive metabolic changes at the cellular level, allowing survival with less blood flow. (2) Vascular reorganization â€” delay improves vascularity by increasing flow through pre-existing vessels and reorganizing blood flow patterns to more ischemic areas. Both mechanisms likely contribute. Clinical technique: Standard delay â€” incisions at the periphery of the planned cutaneous territory with minimal/partial undermining, then closure. Flap elevated after 10-14 days (blood flow maximizes at 1 week). Strategic delay â€” pedicle ligation: incisions at the border of planned flap, dissection to reach and divide selected pedicles, enhancing perfusion through remaining pedicles. Advocated for high-risk patients (smokers, obese, irradiated). Disadvantages: requires preliminary operation, risk of inadvertent pedicle injury, scar tissue may impair subsequent manipulation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Autologous reconstruction options", "question": "Describe the TRAM flap for breast reconstruction: vascular anatomy, advantages, disadvantages, and contraindications.", "answer": "Vascular anatomy: Rectus abdominis is Type III muscle with two dominant pedicles â€” superior epigastric artery (superiorly based) and deep inferior epigastric artery (inferiorly based). Transverse skin island placed between umbilicus and pelvis. Advantages: (1) Sufficient bulk without prosthetic implant. (2) Acceptable suprapubic horizontal donor scar. (3) Single operative position. (4) Large skin dimensions. (5) Simultaneous abdominoplasty with direct closure. Disadvantages: Risk of abdominal hernia/weakness after rectus harvest. Relative contraindications: extremely thin patient, nulliparous woman in childbearing years, history of abdominal hernia, extreme obesity, heavy smoker, lower abdominal scars. Absolute contraindication for superiorly based pedicled TRAM: prior division of superior pedicle (e.g., from superior transverse laparotomy incision).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Autologous reconstruction options", "question": "Trace the evolution of abdominal-based breast reconstruction from TRAM to DIEP flap. What drove each step?", "answer": "Evolution: (1) Pedicled TRAM flap (Hartrampf 1982) â€” entire rectus muscle transferred on superior epigastric pedicle to carry skin island. Issue: sacrifice of entire rectus muscle, abdominal weakness/hernia risk. (2) Free TRAM flap â€” entire rectus transferred on inferior pedicle (dominant blood supply) with microsurgical anastomosis. Improved: perfusion (dominant pedicle used). (3) Muscle-sparing free TRAM â€” partial rectus harvest preserving a portion of muscle. Improved: reduced abdominal wall morbidity. (4) DIEP flap (Koshima/Allen) â€” skin and fat flap based on a single musculocutaneous perforator dissected through the rectus without taking any muscle or fascia. Improved: COMPLETE muscle and fascial preservation, eliminates hernia/weakness risk. Driving force at each step: greater understanding of perforator anatomy â†’ ability to preserve more muscle â†’ reduced donor site morbidity while maintaining reliable flap perfusion.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the free-style perforator flap approach? How does it differ from the classic approach?", "answer": "Classic approach: the source vessel is identified first, then dissection proceeds toward the perforator (from deep to superficial). The flap is designed around a known perforator anatomy. Free-style approach: the skin island is selected first based on the defect requirements, then the most appropriate perforator WITHIN that chosen skin island is identified (often with Doppler), and dissection proceeds from the perforator proximally toward the source vessel. This reverses the classic sequence. Advantages: maximum freedom in flap design â€” not limited to a specific donor site or source artery; can handle unexpected variations; any perforator anywhere on the body can potentially be used. The supermicrosurgery extension (perforator-to-perforator anastomosis) further simplifies this by allowing short-pedicle flaps without extensive proximal dissection. A learning curve is required to be comfortable with this approach.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the commonly transferred vascularized bone flaps? Name the source artery for each.", "answer": "(1) Fibula â€” based on the peroneal artery (multiple arcuate branches along shaft + nutrient vessel to mid-third); head/epiphysis supplied by anterior tibial artery branches. Most widely used bone flap, especially for mandible and long bone reconstruction. Can include skin island. (2) Iliac crest â€” based on deep circumflex iliac artery. (3) Scapula â€” based on circumflex scapular artery or thoracodorsal artery. (4) Radius â€” based on radial artery. (5) Calvarium â€” based on superficial temporal artery or occipital artery. (6) Medial femoral condyle (genicular osseous-periosteal flap) â€” based on articular branch of descending genicular artery; provides periosteum + thin cortical bone for fracture non-union, avascular necrosis, and small bone defects of the hand.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is a keystone flap? Describe its design and blood supply.", "answer": "The keystone flap (described by Behan) is a curvilinear-shaped trapezoidal-design local flap, essentially two V-Y advancement flaps along the long axis of the flap. The longitudinal tension is released, creating laxity and redundancy in the midportion, allowing horizontal movement toward the defect with minimal tension. Blood supply: because of the large size of the flap, identification of a specific vascular source is NOT necessary. It is presumed to have various blood supplies from perforators entering from the deep fascia (essentially a random-pattern concept applied with large flap dimensions). However, when perforators ARE identified using a Doppler, it can be called a 'keystone-design perforator island flap.' Used for larger wounds on the trunk and extremities when a simple random flap would be insufficient.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and postoperative care", "question": "What are the key principles of postoperative flap management and monitoring?", "answer": "Positioning: Avoid pressure on flap base; elevate the flap area when possible; use air-fluidized beds for spinal cord patients. Avoid constricting bandages near pedicle. For head/neck free flaps: NOTHING placed circumferentially around head or neck (no nasal cannulas, oxygen masks, glasses, tracheostomy collars). Immobilization: Splint extremities proximal and distal to inset; avoid circular casts. Monitoring: Clinical observation (skin color, turgor, temperature, capillary refill, pinprick). Adjunctive: laser flowmeter, implantable Doppler, O2 probes, duplex scans. Ideal monitor: reliable, reproducible, sensitive, cost-effective, user-friendly, continuous. Anticoagulation: Evidence shows anticoagulants do NOT make a significant difference in flap outcome; common regimens (aspirin, heparin, dextran) used by many surgeons. Dextran may actually be detrimental. Mobilization: Most patients ambulatory by POD1 (except perineum/lower extremity); extremity elevation/immobilization for 10 days then non-weight-bearing for 6 weeks.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the clinical significance of the Mathes-Nahai muscle classification for flap selection?", "answer": "The classification directly determines: (1) Whether the muscle can survive as a flap â€” Type I (single pedicle) is most reliable; Type IV (segmental) is most precarious with limited arc. (2) Arc of rotation â€” Type V muscles (latissimus, pectoralis major) have widest arc due to pedicle location near insertion. Type IV (sartorius) has most limited arc. (3) Ability to split the muscle â€” Type III muscles (gluteus maximus, rectus abdominis) can be split into two independent segments on separate pedicles, allowing partial harvest while preserving function. (4) Reverse arc of rotation â€” Type V muscles can be elevated on either dominant or segmental pedicles, providing two different arcs. (5) Identifying which pedicle to preserve â€” knowing the dominant vs. minor pedicle guides safe flap elevation and predicts viability after dividing specific vessels.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "How are visceral tissues classified as flaps? Give examples and their Mathes-Nahai type.", "answer": "Visceral flaps fall into the muscle classification system: Jejunum â€” Type I (single vascular arcade); can transfer 7-25 cm on one pedicle; lumen diameter 3-5 cm; used for esophageal and pharyngeal reconstruction. Colon â€” Type I; 20-25 cm length with 8 cm lumen diameter; used for esophageal and vaginal reconstruction. When a longer segment extends beyond one arcade, two arcades (Type III pattern) are included. Omentum â€” Type III (based on either right or left gastroepiploic vessels); variable size up to 40x60 cm; used for extraperitoneal defects; has immunologic and angiogenic properties. The appendix (Type I on appendiceal artery) has been used for urethral and voice reconstruction. Laparoscopic harvest now reduces donor site morbidity. Donor site complications include abdominal wall infection and hernia.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is a nerve flap? How does it differ from a 'vascularized nerve graft'?", "answer": "A nerve flap is a sensory nerve harvested with its vascular supply intact, based on perforating vessels from a proximal source vessel. The nerve has: Extrinsic blood supply â€” arteriae nervorum arising from perforating vessels that enter the nerve intraneurally. Intrinsic blood supply â€” longitudinally oriented arterioles in the epineurium, perineurium, and endoneurium that communicate with the extrinsic arteriae nervorum. The term 'vascularized nerve graft' is a misnomer â€” since the nerve has its own defined vascular source, it is properly called a 'nerve flap.' Examples: superficial radial nerve flap (based on radial artery), saphenous nerve flap (proximally based on femoral artery branches, distally on saphenous artery), sural nerve flap (based on superficial sural artery). When the arterial supply is absent, the accompanying vein can be arterialized.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "List the eight general guidelines for selecting a specific muscle flap for reconstruction.", "answer": "(1) The muscle should be ADJACENT to the defect (for local flaps). (2) Sufficient SIZE and BULK to cover the defect; finalize design only after complete debridement (defects are often larger than anticipated). (3) The muscle should be EXPENDABLE (synergistic muscles can compensate); otherwise use muscle-splitting techniques. (4) Vascular pedicle STATUS must be confirmed preoperatively (arteriography if prior surgery near pedicle, or if motor paralysis noted). (5) Donor site DEFORMITY must be considered (skin graft requirements, scar location preference). (6) Cutaneous territory must be sufficient SIZE and acceptable TEXTURE/match (non-hair-bearing if needed). (7) Select flaps capable of SENSORY or MOTOR restoration if required (e.g., serratus, rectus, latissimus). (8) Consider OSTEOMUSCULOCUTANEOUS flaps if vascularized bone is also needed. (9) The operation should be technically straightforward.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What systemic factors increase the risk of flap complications and failure?", "answer": "Known risk factors: obesity, smoking, hypertension, immunosuppression, heart failure, diabetes, hypercoagulability, peripheral vascular disease, and chronic renal insufficiency. These affect both donor and recipient sites and increase rates of flap failure. However, with continued advances in microsurgical instruments and techniques, these risk factors have become less significant to flap survival outcomes. Nevertheless, they should be controlled preoperatively to minimize complications. Strategic delay (ligation of pedicles before definitive flap elevation) is advocated specifically for patients with risk factors for flap ischemia (smoking history, obesity, radiation therapy, abdominal scars). For flap design, preoperative CT angiography is the gold standard for imaging the vascular anatomy of both donor and recipient sites.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Define microsurgery and supramicrosurgery. What vessel diameters does each address, and what are the primary clinical applications of supramicrosurgery?", "answer": "Microsurgery: surgical coaptation of small vessels (~1 mm diameter) under microscope magnification; also applies to nerves and lymphatics. Supramicrosurgery (Koshima): anastomosis of vessels ~0.5 mm diameter (range 0.3-0.8 mm). Supramicrosurgery applications: (1) lymphatic reconstruction (lymphaticovenular anastomosis), (2) perforator-to-perforator anastomosis/repair, (3) distal digital replantation. Supramicrosurgery requires extremely fine instruments, 11-0 to 12-0 sutures, and high-magnification microscopy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What suture sizes are used for microvascular anastomosis, and how is the choice determined by vessel diameter?", "answer": "9-0 nylon on 100 µm needle: vessels ≥2 mm diameter. 10-0 nylon on 70-100 µm needle: vessels 1-2 mm diameter. 11-0 nylon on 50-75 µm needle and 12-0 nylon on 50 µm needle: vessels <1 mm (supramicrosurgery). The choice is based on vessel wall thickness and diameter. Microneedles are typically three-eighths circle with round, tapered (most common), or spatula tips. Non-resorbable nylon is standard due to low tissue reactivity and knot-holding ability; polypropylene is an alternative preferred by some for better tissue sliding.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Describe the microvascular anastomotic coupling device (Synovis COUPLER): mechanism, indications, contraindications, and patency rates.", "answer": "Mechanism: two disposable high-density polyethylene rings with 6-8 evenly spaced stainless-steel pins (0.16 mm diameter). Vessel ends are threaded through rings and impaled on pins in an everting fashion; rings are approximated via reusable applicator. Sizes: 1-4 mm ring diameter (vessels 0.8-4.3 mm). Patency rates: up to 100% (99.4% in 1000 consecutive venous anastomoses in breast reconstruction). Anastomotic time: 2-6 minutes. Advantages: fast, does not disturb intima. Contraindications: PVD, active radiation therapy, active infection, concurrent diabetes, corticosteroid therapy, thick-walled vessels that don't evert, diameter discrepancy >1.5:1, non-pliable vessels, arteries <1.5 mm. Primarily used for venous anastomoses but also effective for arterial.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Compare end-to-end versus end-to-side microvascular anastomosis: indications, advantages, and patency outcomes.", "answer": "End-to-end: most common method using interrupted sutures. Simple, appropriate for most anastomoses. Preferred in atherosclerotic vessels (less plaque exposure). End-to-side: indicated when (1) significant vessel size or wall thickness discrepancy, (2) need to preserve distal circulation (single-vessel leg), (3) may be less prone to vasospasm in lower extremity. Technique: arteriotomy (triangular, elliptical, or longitudinal slit) in recipient vessel; stay sutures at heel and toe. Godina advocated this technique for higher success rates and technical simplicity. Patency: study of >2000 anastomoses showed both techniques equally effective when properly applied, approaching 100%. End-to-side venous anastomosis may have slightly higher success rate than end-to-end.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What are the key principles of vessel preparation before microvascular anastomosis?", "answer": "(1) Inspect lumens for intimal tears/separation, thrombi, atherosclerotic plaques, friable calcified walls. (2) Remove debris by gentle irrigation or atraumatic removal with microforceps. (3) Cut back to healthy vessel if needed (inadequate debridement is a major cause of flap failure). (4) Trim adventitia 3-4 mm from anastomotic site to improve visualization and prevent adventitia falling into lumen (avoid overly aggressive stripping which causes vessel wall necrosis and false aneurysms). (5) Gently dilate lumens in two planes for 1 second to aid suturing, prevent vasospasm, and flush intraluminal blood. (6) Irrigate with heparinized saline; cover vessels with 2-4% lidocaine or 3% papaverine-soaked gauze to prevent desiccation and vasospasm.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What techniques can be used to manage vessel size discrepancy during microvascular anastomosis, and up to what ratio can end-to-end repair handle?", "answer": "Mismatches up to 4:1 can be anastomosed end-to-end with sufficient skill. Techniques: (1) Gently stretch/dilate the smaller vessel to match, placing sutures further apart on larger vessel. (2) Fish-mouth incision on smaller vessel to increase circumference. (3) Oblique cut on smaller vessel (angle not >30° to avoid kinking). (4) Perform anastomosis distal to a side branch, opening the V-shape as vessel end. For discrepancy >3:1: consider (5) end-to-side anastomosis, (6) vein graft to graduate discrepancy, (7) use side branch of larger vessel as size match. Last resort: dilate smaller vessel maximally, suture as widely as possible, close remaining gap with oblique surgical clip to taper and minimize turbulence.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "What is the gold standard for free flap monitoring? Describe the clinical signs assessed and a typical monitoring schedule.", "answer": "Gold standard: clinical observation by experienced nursing and medical staff. Signs assessed: (1) Color (pink = adequate arterial inflow; white/pale = arterial insufficiency; dark blue/purple = venous congestion). (2) Capillary refill (normal brisk; absent = arterial problem; instant/dark = venous congestion). (3) Turgor. (4) Surface temperature (difference of 1.8°C between flap and control is 98% sensitive and 75% predictive of vascular compromise; temp <30°C indicates failure). (5) Pinprick test for color and speed of bleeding if capillary refill unclear (scratch dermis only). Typical schedule: every 30 minutes for first 24 hours, 1-2 hourly for next 24 hours, then 4-hourly for next 48 hours. Minimum close monitoring for first 72 hours.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "Compare the monitoring methods available for free flaps: implantable Doppler, hand-held Doppler, laser Doppler, and tissue oximetry.", "answer": "Hand-held pencil Doppler: most commonly used technology; applied over marked cutaneous perforator (away from pedicle to avoid false positives); noninvasive. Implantable Doppler: placed around pedicle vessel (most accurate on vein); useful for buried flaps and those without skin perforator; sensitive but HIGH false-positive rate causing unnecessary re-explorations; can differentiate arterial from venous thrombosis by signal pattern. Laser Doppler: measures reflected light waveforms from moving RBCs in capillaries; objective measurement; can distinguish venous obstruction from arterial occlusion; no false positives or negatives when interpreted by experienced clinicians. Tissue oximetry: identifies pulsatile flow and arterial saturation; has GREATEST impact on clinical decision-making — surgeons most willing to act on concerning oximetry findings. All are adjuncts to clinical monitoring, which remains the gold standard.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "A free flap begins to show signs of compromise in the early postoperative period. Outline the systematic approach to assessment and salvage.", "answer": "Step 1 — Address systemic factors at bedside: correct hypotension, hypovolemia, hypothermia, and sympathetic overdrive from pain. Step 2 — Address local factors: release compressive dressings, evacuate hematoma, loosen tight wound closure/release sutures. Step 3 — Reassess flap after corrections. Step 4 — If no improvement, bedside vessel exploration: relieve twist/kink, assess anastomotic patency, open second pedicle vein for congestion. Step 5 — Prompt return to OR if thrombosis confirmed: resection and reanastomosis, or Fogarty balloon thrombectomy. Step 6 — Intraoperative thrombolysis (urokinase or tPA) for refractory cases. Step 7 — For venous congestion refractory to surgical salvage: medicinal leeches (Hirudo medicinalis), which inject hirudin anticoagulant and cause bleeding for up to 10 hours. Give prophylactic antibiotics against Aeromonas hydrophila with leech use. Monitor hemoglobin daily.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Thrombosis and anticoagulation in microsurgery", "question": "Compare the three most commonly used antithrombotic agents in microsurgery: heparin, dextran, and aspirin.", "answer": "HEPARIN: activates antithrombin III (deactivates factors II, IX, X, XI; indirectly V, VIII), reduces platelet aggregation, lowers blood viscosity, has direct vasodilatory properties. Most important for atherosclerotic/injured vessels and vein grafts. Used universally as irrigation solution. Risk: hematoma formation, HIT. DEXTRAN-40: polysaccharide volume expander; increases electronegativity of RBCs/platelets/endothelium (reduces aggregation), decreases factor VIII-Ag, reduces viscosity. Risks: anaphylaxis, volume overload, pulmonary/cerebral edema, acute renal failure; 3.9-7.2x increased systemic complications vs aspirin. ASPIRIN: inhibits cyclooxygenase, reduces thromboxane (vasoconstrictor/platelet aggregator). Low-dose (75 mg/day) selectively inhibits thromboxane while preserving endothelial prostacyclin. Less effective than heparin. Risks: gastric hemorrhage, renal failure, prolonged bleeding. No agent has definitive RCT evidence; protocols vary by surgeon preference.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Thrombosis and anticoagulation in microsurgery", "question": "Describe the pathophysiology of arterial vs venous thrombosis in free flaps: timing, mechanism, and presentation.", "answer": "ARTERIAL thrombosis: majority occur within first 24 hours; mechanism is platelet aggregation at the anastomotic site (white thrombus); presentation = pale/white flap, absent capillary refill, no Doppler signal, longitudinal (non-expansile) pulsation. VENOUS thrombosis: presents later (but most pedicle thromboses occur within 48 hours); mechanism is formation of fibrin clot (red thrombus); more often responsible for flap compromise than arterial thrombosis; presentation = congested/purple flap, rapid/dark capillary refill, engorged secondary veins, continuous dark bleeding from flap edges, blood column darker than recipient vessel. Risk of thrombosis greatest within first 48 hours, decreases to 10% after 72 hours. Anticoagulant goals: interfere with platelet function (arterial), counter thrombin effects on fibrinogen (venous), reduce viscosity/increase flow.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What is vasospasm in microsurgery? Describe its incidence, causes, and treatment options.", "answer": "Incidence: 5-10% of microsurgical procedures. Timing: intraoperatively or up to 72 hours postop (intraoperative more problematic). Veins: less susceptible but harder to resolve and more detrimental once established. General causes: low core temperature (<36°C), hypotension, sympathetic response to pain, hypovolemia. Local causes: vessel trauma, tight adventitia, myogenic response to local hemorrhage, desiccation, vascular disease. Treatment: (1) Wait a few minutes for spontaneous resolution. (2) Pharmacologic — topical papaverine (30 mg/mL, phosphodiesterase inhibitor), lidocaine (2-4%, Na-Ca exchange pump), calcium channel blockers (verapamil, nifedipine, nicardipine — may be more effective than papaverine). (3) Mechanical — gentle dilation with blunt vessel dilator or needle holders. (4) Adventitial stripping (sympathectomy effect). (5) If intractable: aggressively resect vessel until normal vessel reached; may require vein graft or alternate recipient vessel.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Ischemia-reperfusion injury", "question": "Explain ischemia-reperfusion injury and the no-reflow phenomenon in free flap surgery.", "answer": "Ischemia-reperfusion (I/R) injury: after prolonged ischemia, reperfusion compounds the insult through buildup of oxygen free radicals during ischemic period. These cause: (1) cellular membrane damage through oxidizing/reducing potentials, (2) intense inflammatory reaction recruiting leukocytes, neutrophils, platelets, and cytokines (IL-1β, TNF-α), (3) suppression of protective molecules (nitric oxide synthase, prostacyclin, thrombomodulin), (4) increased complement C3 deposition, apoptosis, interstitial edema, decreased total antioxidant capacity. No-reflow phenomenon: severe I/R injury causes irreversible vasoconstriction; inability to reperfuse flap DESPITE PATENT anastomoses. Mechanism: ischemia-induced endothelial injury → cellular swelling → interstitial edema → exposed subendothelial collagen → platelet-leukocyte aggregation → reduced blood flow → thrombosis. Ischemic tolerance varies by tissue (most to least tolerant): skin > nerve > bone > muscle > intestine. Within composite flap, overall tolerance equals LEAST tolerant component. Ischemia beyond 3 hours increases risk.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Recipient and donor vessel selection", "question": "What are the principles for selecting and preparing recipient vessels in free flap surgery?", "answer": "Ideal recipient vessel: (1) healthy with soft wall and easily dissected vascular sheath, (2) away from zones of trauma, irradiation, inflammation, fibrosis, and scarring, (3) appropriate size with good flow, (4) adequate length for tension-free anastomosis. Assessing vessel quality: expansile pulsation suggests adequacy, confirmed by healthy spurting from divided vessel. If poor spurt with normotension: relieve vasospasm first, then cut back until healthy spurting encountered. Veins: should be at least as wide as flap vein (smaller causes bottle-neck effect). Test with flushing heparinized saline through catheter — low resistance confirms adequate drainage. Preoperative assessment: CTA/angiography indicated for abnormal distal pulses or history of trauma, DVT, longstanding diabetes, atherosclerosis. Perforating branches of main vessels can be used as recipients (breast, extremity reconstruction). After dissection, cover vessels with lidocaine/papaverine-soaked gauze.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What are the indications for interpositional vein grafts in microsurgery, and what principles govern their use?", "answer": "Indications: (1) recipient vessel out of pedicle reach or under tension, (2) considerable size mismatch, (3) need to place anastomosis outside zone of injury/radiation, (4) re-explorations, (5) vessel-depleted neck. Principles: Harvest with loupe magnification; caliber should match vessels being anastomosed. Workhorse: great/lesser saphenous vein (advantages: length, two-team approach). Alternatives: cephalic vein, comitant veins of flap, volar forearm veins, dorsal foot veins. Critical: direction must ensure antegrade flow (valves present even in short segments) — mark proximal end with surgical clip. Hydrodilatation stretches graft to length, untwists vein, relieves vasospasm, reveals bleeding points. Anastomose open end first, release clamp to verify correct direction and non-redundant length. Arterial grafts have advantages (no valves, anatomical taper, similar wall thickness, more prostacyclin) but haven't shown significant superiority in microsurgery.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Describe the patency tests used to assess microvascular anastomosis after completion.", "answer": "Clinical assessment: expansile pulsation = good (longitudinal pulsation in vessel's long axis = partial/complete thrombosis). Good venous flow with natural round diameter = patent vein (engorged and dark blood = thrombosed vein). Two formal tests: (1) UPLIFT TEST: gently hook up thin-walled vessel until blood column almost occluded; if patent, alternate filling and collapsing with each pulse is visible. (2) EMPTY-AND-REFILL TEST (Acland): occlude vessel distal to anastomosis, use second forceps to empty a segment by running it in direction of flow, release proximal forceps — immediate refill confirms patency; sluggish or absent refill = not patent. This test is more traumatic and should be performed preferably on veins not arteries (minimize spasm/intima separation). Side branches provide atraumatic alternative. Modern: ICG (indocyanine green) angiography via microscope-mounted infrared cameras or hand-held devices — easier and more accurate.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What patient factors should be evaluated preoperatively for free flap surgery, and which are true contraindications?", "answer": "Age: NOT a contraindication (outcomes comparable in extremes of age, though elderly have more medical complications). Smoking: does not significantly affect vessel patency or flap survival, but increases donor site complications; advise stopping 4 weeks preoperatively. Obesity (BMI >30): increases hemorrhage, hematomas, total flap loss, seromas, donor site complications (TRAM data). Diabetes: NOT an independent risk factor for flap failure, but 1.76x increased perioperative complications. Alcohol: withdrawal related to increased flap failure; identify and treat high-risk patients prophylactically. Liver cirrhosis: risk factor for perioperative complications; higher risk of neck hematoma with advanced disease. Immunosuppression: prednisone correlates with operative morbidity. Collagen vascular diseases (Raynaud, SLE, scleroderma): increased DVT risk but NOT increased microvascular thrombosis risk with standard anticoagulant prophylaxis. Irradiated recipient site: increased risk of reoperation/complications but does not definitively preclude free flap; site anastomosis outside irradiated field when possible.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What is the Godina principle regarding timing of free flap reconstruction, and what does current evidence support?", "answer": "Godina (1986) recommended free flaps within 72 hours of injury for lower extremity reconstruction, reporting lower complication and failure rates with early coverage. Current evidence: retrospective review of 358 soft-tissue free flaps (1979-2016) for below-knee trauma confirmed Godina's findings — early reconstruction within 3 days had superior outcomes compared to delayed (4-90 days), BUT the safe early window can be extended to within 10 days without adverse outcome effects. In practice: timing depends on surgeon experience, wound/patient condition, healthcare logistics. Key principle: adequate debridement creates a fresh surgical wound reconstructable at any time. Immediate cover mandatory if vital structures exposed. For oncologic reconstruction: immediate reconstruction performed at same time as ablation (may modestly delay adjuvant therapy). For breast reconstruction with PMRT: optimal approach is delayed autologous reconstruction after radiation; delayed-immediate with tissue expansion considered when PMRT status uncertain.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What factors determine the choice of free flap for a given defect?", "answer": "First question: 'Does this defect NEED a free flap?' If yes, consider: (1) Size and tissue components of defect (skin, muscle, bone, nerve). (2) Goals of reconstruction — functional vs aesthetic priorities (e.g., young patient with benign mandible tumor: vascularized bone for dental implants; edentulous elderly with poor-prognosis cancer: soft-tissue flap with reconstruction plate). (3) Recipient vessel availability — length and caliber of flap pedicle must match; minimize need for vein grafts. (4) Donor site morbidity — favor sites allowing primary closure; consider muscle weakness, herniation risk, sensory loss, fracture susceptibility. (5) Flap tailorability — free flaps can be customized in size, form, tissue components, and function. (6) Two-team approach feasibility — lower extremity donor flaps advantageous. (7) Patient factors: prior surgery, body habitus, comorbidities. Principle: 'replace like with like' for superior functional and aesthetic results.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "Should the artery or vein be anastomosed first in free flap surgery? What are the arguments for each approach?", "answer": "No consensus exists; dictated by ischemia time and vessel position (deeper/harder-to-reach vessel repaired first). ARTERY FIRST advantages: (1) shortens warm ischemia time, (2) re-establishment of circulation reveals dominant venous drainage aiding vein selection, (3) detects twist/kink/compression in pedicle. ARTERY FIRST disadvantages: flap bleeding during venous repair, venous congestion with free radical buildup (mitigated by intermittently releasing second vein for drainage). VEIN FIRST advantages: (1) better adjustment of pedicle length, (2) no venous congestion/bleeding during arterial repair. VEIN FIRST disadvantage: delays flap revascularization. Practice at high-volume centers (>1000 free flaps/year): routinely repair artery first and leave unclamped during venous repair; temporary congestion managed by allowing less dominant comitant vein to drain freely. Single vs dual venous anastomosis: Khouri reported 4.3% failure with single vs 0% with two veins, but sound judgment required — single adequate vein provides sufficient drainage.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "Describe prefabrication and prelamination of flaps. How do they differ, and what are their applications?", "answer": "PREFABRICATION: Two-stage process. Stage 1: implant an axial vascular pedicle into desired donor tissue to allow neovascularization (~8 weeks). Stage 2: transfer neo-vascularized tissue based on its implanted pedicle to reconstruct the defect. Allows creation of large, thin skin flaps retaining donor site qualities; modifiable with various combinations of vascular pedicles, donor tissues, and geographic locations. PRELAMINATION: Two-stage process. Stage 1: add one or more tissues (skin, bone, cartilage, mucosa) to a reliable vascular bed to create a multilayered composite flap (~2 weeks maturation). Stage 2: transplant the mature composite flap. The delay allows prelaminating layers to heal, stabilize, and assume expected structures. Key difference: prefabrication creates a new vascular supply TO a tissue; prelamination adds tissue components ONTO an existing vascular bed. Applications: reconstruction of esophagus, penis, oral lining, ear, nose, neourethra, trachea, larynx, and complex head/neck defects requiring specific contours.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Perforator flap concepts", "question": "What is a free-style free flap, and how does it differ from a traditional perforator flap?", "answer": "Traditional perforator flap: based on well-described, anatomically studied musculocutaneous perforators (e.g., DIEP, ALT) with known vascular anatomy. Free-style free flap (Wei concept): harvest of a skin paddle based on ANY audible perforator detected by hand-held Doppler (or optimized duplex sonography) in an area that may NOT have been previously studied anatomically. Technique: (1) identify perforator with Doppler at fascia level through exploratory incision, (2) if sizeable (≥0.5 mm with visible pulsation), dissect retrograde to parent vessel, (3) raise flap as free flap. Advantages: can design flap almost anywhere on body, opens door to ~400 potential perforator flaps, alleviates concerns about vascular anomaly, tailored to defect location. Limitations: small-caliber vessels, small-to-medium skin paddles, pedicle length not critical. Requires supramicrosurgery skills for small vessel anastomosis.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Perforator flap concepts", "question": "What are the methods of flap thinning, and what vascular anatomy makes primary thinning possible?", "answer": "Skin is nourished by a subdermal plexus from branches of the main pedicle plus recurrent dermal branches, allowing safe thinning. Three methods: (1) STANDARD THINNING: thin to ~3-4 mm thickness in Asians, leaving unthinned area of 2 cm around pedicle; reduces need for secondary revisions. (2) MICRODISSECTION THINNING: dissect blood vessels in adipose layer under microscopic magnification, remove surrounding adipose tissue while preserving vessels. (3) SCARPA'S FASCIA-LEVEL HARVEST: harvest flap at the level of Scarpa's fascia (superficial circumflex artery perforator flap is flap of choice for this method); utilizes 'hot/cold zone' concept. Color-coded duplex sonography (CCDS) guides harvest at different levels above muscular fascia, allowing accurate assessment of perforator subcutaneous course and planning subfascial/epifascial/suprafascial harvest depth. Thinning avoids secondary debulking procedures and improves aesthetic outcomes.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "What causes anastomotic failure in microvascular surgery? List the principal technical faults.", "answer": "Principal technical faults (Acland): (1) TEARING: from excessive tension at repair site or overly meticulous adventitial stripping (head/neck veins especially fragile). (2) LEAKING: gaps between sutures too large, unnoticed tears, or tiny branches near anastomotic site; even small leaks precipitate intraluminal thrombus. (3) NARROWING: oversized bites, entangled knots, or continuous suture too tight; tight sutures damage media — if ≥1/3 of wall undergoes necrosis, re-endothelialization fails and occlusion follows. (4) THROUGH-STITCHING: inadvertent bite of back wall causes luminal obstruction; prevented by constant luminal irrigation and raising anterior wall with microforceps. (5) ADVENTITIA INCLUSION: prolapsed adventitia from inadequate preparation becomes nidus for thrombus. (6) DESICCATION: drying of vessel wall. Prevention: meticulous technique, constant irrigation, proper adventitial trimming, visualizing lumen at all times, tying knots by SIGHT not feel.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "How are medicinal leeches used in free flap salvage? Describe mechanism, protocol, and required precautions.", "answer": "Indication: venous congested flaps when surgical and pharmacological salvage fails. Mechanism: Hirudo medicinalis leeches bite into congested flap and inject (via saliva): local anesthetic, vasodilator, and hirudin (anticoagulant). They feed on blood, increasing perfusion within congested flaps. After falling away when full, bleeding continues for up to 10 hours due to combined vasodilator and anticoagulant effect. Protocol: apply new leeches when bleeding slows or flap appears congested again. Continue therapy until flap re-establishes effective venous drainage through new vessel ingrowth around flap margins. Precautions: (1) Significant blood loss — usually limit to small-to-medium flaps, monitor hemoglobin DAILY. (2) Prophylactic antibiotics required against Aeromonas hydrophila (present in leech digestive tract). (3) Blood transfusion may be necessary.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What are the advantages of free microvascular tissue transfer over conventional reconstruction methods?", "answer": "Advantages: (1) Freedom of choice of donor tissue components — replace 'like with like' for superior functional and aesthetic results. (2) Flap tailorable to recipient site requirements in size, form, tissue components, and function. (3) Often single-stage procedure (vs. multistage for pedicled/distant flaps) — earlier mobilization, return to work, reduced hospitalization and costs. (4) Better cutaneous blood flow and vascularity — enhances wound healing and reduces infection. (5) Increasing flap repertoire with primary-closure donor sites minimizing donor morbidity. Disadvantages/risks: (1) Long surgery and anesthesia time. (2) Risk of vasospasm and microvascular thrombosis. (3) Potential need for re-exploration. (4) Flap failure (total or partial). Current success rates: 96-100% in experienced centers (vs. 74-91% in earlier era).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "When a free flap fails completely, what systematic approach guides the decision for a second free flap?", "answer": "Three issues to consider (Oliva et al.): (1) REASONS FOR FAILURE: reversible causes (technical error, suboptimal postop management, delayed diagnosis) favor repeat attempt; irreversible factors (systemic vascular disease, radiation, lack of healthy vessels) require careful risk-benefit analysis. (2) INDICATIONS: does the defect need another free flap? Mandatory when: loss would lead to limb loss, expose major neck vessels, delay adjuvant chemo/radiotherapy, or significantly decrease quality of life. (3) CURRENT WOUND STATUS: vital structure exposure = life-threatening, mandates prompt coverage. Planning: choose flap with good vascularity and LONGER pedicle (larger defect after debridement, new recipient vessels likely further from defect). Avoid reusing previous recipient vessels (inflamed, friable). Contralateral same flap preferred when available. Success rates: head/neck 94.1%, extremity 82-87.5%. Downgrade reconstruction only if patient unfit, overwhelming infection, poor prognosis with already low QoL.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What are the key considerations for microvascular anesthesia, and how does anesthetic management differ from standard procedures?", "answer": "Requirements: (1) Stable anesthesia by team FAMILIAR with microsurgery. (2) Good pain, temperature, and sympathetic control throughout — prevents vasospasm and vasoconstriction. (3) Fine-tuned blood pressure: kept LOW during flap dissection (bloodless field), then brought UP gradually during hemostasis and anastomosis (ensures good recipient inflow and flap perfusion). (4) Adequate fluid management: slight hemodilution to maintain high cardiac output and low systemic vascular resistance. (5) Avoid hypothermia (<36°C causes vasospasm); constantly monitor temperature. (6) Avoid tachycardia (sympathetic overdrive causes vasospasm). (7) Blood transfusion: NOT a risk factor for flap failure — decision based on intraoperative blood loss, hemodynamic status, and underlying morbidities. Postop: normalize BP, keep patient warm, hydrated, and pain-free; good hyperglycemic control; prophylactic antibiotics; LMWH for DVT prophylaxis.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "What is mechanotransduction, and how does it apply to tissue expansion? What cellular changes occur?", "answer": "Mechanotransduction is the conversion of mechanical forces into biochemical signals. In tissue expansion, skin stretched beyond physiological limits activates mechanotransduction pathways that increase: (1) mitotic activity, (2) collagen synthesis, (3) cell growth, (4) formation of new tissue and skin surface area. Specific molecular events: mechanical stress activates mechanosensitive ion channels, G-proteins, protein kinases, integrin-matrix interactions. Fibroblasts proliferate in response to mechanical stretch. Collagen and elastin realign in parallel fashion in direction of stretching. VEGF, PDGF, and bFGF are significantly higher in expanded vs non-expanded tissue, leading to increased vascularity and allowing harvest of larger flaps.", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "Describe the different types of tissue expanders and their port systems.", "answer": "Types by valve system: (1) REMOTE VALVE: connected by flexible filling tube to expander; can be palpated under skin; lower risk of puncturing balloon during inflation; beneficial when pocket too firm or overlying skin very thin. (2) INTEGRATED VALVE: inflation reservoir on expander surface; avoids mechanical problems/bacterial colonization of tubing, but higher risk of accidentally piercing expander during inflation; use magnetic metal-finding or ultrasonic devices to locate. (3) SELF-INFLATING: hydrogel (vinyl pyrrolidone and methyl methacrylate) absorbs extracellular fluid via osmosis, expanding over 6-8 weeks; decreases pain and clinic visits; disadvantage: potential expansion beyond tissue vascularity. Also CO2 self-inflating (remote radio-controlled). Special types: BECKER EXPANDER-IMPLANT: double-lumen, inner chamber filled with saline during expansion, outer chamber pre-filled with gel; can be left as permanent implant after detaching remote valve. Shapes: circular, rectangular, crescentic (50-1000 cc).", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Compare smooth versus textured breast implant surfaces: manufacturing, clinical behavior, capsular contracture rates, and BIA-ALCL risk.", "answer": "SMOOTH: produced by dipping mandrel into liquid silicone creating multilayers, cured in laminar flow oven. Can move within capsule without visible change. Massage starts 4-5 days postop. TEXTURED: proprietary processes vary (sodium chloride, sugar, soak/scrub, pressure stamping, loss-salt, imprint stamping with PU foam). Provides friction, reduces malposition. Anatomic implants MUST be textured to prevent rotation. Massage is CONTRAINDICATED (increases fluid around implant). Capsular contracture: theory that irregular surface prevents parallel collagen fiber alignment; preliminary studies supported lower CF rates with textured, but recent long-term studies show negligible difference. BIA-ALCL: textured implants associated with 67-421x increased risk of developing this T-cell lymphoma. Barr classification of texture: macro-, micro-, meso-, and nano-textured surfaces.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the implant placement options in breast augmentation: subglandular, subfascial, and the three types of dual plane.", "answer": "SUBGLANDULAR: over pectoralis muscle, beneath skin/fat/glandular tissue. Advantages: less implant movement during activity, less immediate postop pain. Disadvantages: higher capsular fibrosis risk, visible edges/rippling/wrinkling, causes breast parenchyma atrophy. Choose when pinch test >2 cm. SUBFASCIAL: between pectoral muscle fascia and muscle; better tissue coverage with less visible edges, but fascia is extremely thin and fragile. DUAL PLANE (all partially submuscular): Type I: minimal release of pectoralis from lower attachments at IMF level; classic partial submuscular. Type II: greater pectoralis release up to nipple level; overlying breast parenchyma released partway to nipple; optimal for very slight sagging. Type III: greatest pectoralis release; muscle and parenchyma released all the way to nipple level. Pinch test <2 cm favors subpectoral placement. Submuscular placement causes pectoralis major atrophy but NOT breast parenchyma atrophy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What is breast implant-associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma (BIA-ALCL)? Describe presentation, risk factors, diagnosis, and management.", "answer": "BIA-ALCL: potentially fatal T-cell lymphoma associated with breast implants. Risk factors: TEXTURED implants (67-421x increased risk vs smooth); first reported 1997, incidence increasing (possibly due to improved awareness). Presentation: late-onset seroma (>1 year after implantation, incidence 0.9-1.8%) not explainable by infection or trauma is the hallmark; may also present as mass or lymphadenopathy. Diagnosis: fine-needle aspiration of periprosthetic fluid, flow cytometry, CD30-positive/ALK-negative immunohistochemistry. Management: NCCN guidelines recognized by FDA emphasize critical role of complete surgical ablation (total capsulectomy with implant removal). Adjunct chemotherapy for advanced disease with lymph node involvement. National registries created in multiple countries for tracking. FDA has released report linking ALCL specifically to textured implants.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What are the common malposition complications after breast augmentation, and how do they present?", "answer": "BOTTOMING OUT: inferior implant displacement with high-riding nipple; lower pole longer than it should be. DOUBLE BUBBLE: double convexity of lower pole due to visible disruption of old IMF; two parallel transverse folds across lower breast pole. Caused by spontaneous implant migration, capsular fibrosis, or glandular ptosis. Treatment: capsulorrhaphy, neosubpectoral pocket, acellular dermal matrices, or conversion subpectoral to subglandular. WATERFALL/SNOOPY DEFORMITY: superior implant-to-nipple malposition; full upper pole with natural breast tissue ptosing off the implant inferiorly. SYMMASTIA: rare; excessive midline dissection creating one continuous capsular pocket; implants confluence beyond midline with no natural sinus. Caused by oversized implants or placement too close to midline. Treatment: medial capsulorrhaphy reattaching capsule to sternum, or neosubpectoral pocket. Prevention: anatomical approach during pocket dissection preserving superficial and deep attachments of pectoralis fascia at IMF.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Compare silicone-filled versus saline-filled breast implants: properties, advantages, disadvantages, and rupture presentation.", "answer": "SILICONE-FILLED: medical-grade cohesive silicone gel; cohesiveness varies with cross-linking density (less cross-linked = softer, more elastic; more cross-linked = firmer). Feel more natural and softer. Modern 3rd-5th generation have phenyl/trifluoropropyl groups on shell to reduce gel bleed. Rupture: usually 'silent' (intracapsular, gel remains within scar capsule); best detected by MRI; may not cause symptoms. Larger incision needed. SALINE-FILLED: can use smaller incision (filled after insertion). Subpectoral placement preferred (subglandular shows wrinkling). Rupture/deflation: immediately noticeable (implant collapses as saline leaks via valve leak or shell tear). Can only be used with transumbilical approach. Silicone implant rupture rates increase after 6-8 years; by 13 years, 11.8% have ruptured. Round implants available in both; anatomic implants are silicone-only.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe Tebbetts' 'High Five System' for breast implant selection. What are the five critical preoperative decisions?", "answer": "The High Five System is a tissue-based planning system for breast augmentation. Five critical preoperative decisions: (1) Implant coverage/pocket planning (subglandular vs submuscular vs dual plane, guided by pinch test: <2 cm favors subpectoral). (2) Implant size/volume (based on measurements plus patient wishes; ~100 cc per cup size increase; must respect chest wall width to preserve anterior axillary line, cleavage, intermammary distance). (3) Implant type (round vs anatomic, smooth vs textured, silicone vs saline). (4) Inframammary fold position (predicted from nipple-to-fold distance under maximal stretch compared to reference chart for selected implant; lowering may be required). (5) Incision (inframammary, periareolar [if areola >3.5 cm and volume <300 cc], transaxillary [blunt or endoscopic], transumbilical [limited to saline]). Variables analyzed: patient base width, implant base width, anterior pulled skin stretch, nipple-to-fold distance.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "What is the tissue expansion protocol: timing of initial inflation, serial expansion schedule, and key principles to avoid complications?", "answer": "Initial inflation: performed intraoperatively immediately after skin closure; fill 15-20% of expander volume to ensure full deployment. Serial inflation: begins 1-2 weeks after surgery when skin is completely healed. Technique: 23-gauge or smaller needle; inflate with saline per patient tolerance and tissue vascularity. Repeat weekly until desired size reached and adequate soft tissue generated. For breast expanders: OVERINFLATION is commonly performed to achieve natural ptosis after permanent implant placement. Key principles to avoid complications: (1) preserve major axial vessel in expanded tissue, (2) avoid overly aggressive inflation (risk ischemia/necrosis), (3) incisions along one margin of flap to reduce suture line tension, (4) place valve remote from incision, (5) pocket base should equal expander base (prevent movement), (6) sterile technique during inflation (late infection risk from iatrogenic bacterial introduction).", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What is capsular fibrosis (capsular contracture)? Describe pathophysiology, incidence, risk factors, classification, and treatment.", "answer": "Capsular fibrosis: foreign body response to implant causing fibrotic encapsulation by excessive deposition of collagen and extracellular matrix. Pathophysiology: initial T-cell and macrophage migration, followed by increased (myo-)fibroblast activity leading to fibrosis. Overall incidence: 10.6%. Risk factors (controversially discussed): smooth (vs textured) implants, subglandular (vs submuscular) placement, silicone- (vs saline-) filled implants, bacterial contamination. Baker Classification: Grade I (soft, natural), Grade II (slightly firm, implant palpable), Grade III (firm, implant visible/palpable distortion), Grade IV (hard, painful, obvious distortion). Treatment: surgical â€” implant exchange with capsulectomy or capsulotomy. Modern approach: micro- and nanoscale surface topographies influence cellular behavior and immune response; Barr classification (2017) categorizes textures as macro-, micro-, meso-, nano-textured to guide surface development.", "notes": "Baker classification not explicitly detailed in this chapter text but is standard knowledge referenced", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What is breast implant illness (BII)? Describe the symptoms, proposed mechanisms, and current evidence.", "answer": "BII: a cluster of systemic symptoms associated with breast implants that do not fit any classic disease diagnosis â€” a diagnosis of EXCLUSION. Symptoms: fatigue, dizziness, myalgia, arthralgia, rash (FDA-recognized), plus numbness/tingling in extremities, hair loss, memory loss/cognitive problems, dry eyes/blurred vision, breast pain, food sensitivity/intolerance, flu-like symptoms/low-grade fever, difficulty breathing (Wee et al. 2020). Proposed mechanisms: multifactorial including psychosomatic factors; 'autoimmune/inflammatory syndrome induced by adjuvants' (ASIA/Shoenfeld's syndrome) â€” silicone may induce autoimmune-like phenomena. Variables: material composition, anatomic position, duration of implant, genetics, comorbidities, medications, lifestyle. Current evidence: NO definitive scientific evidence of primary association between implants and rheumatologic/connective tissue diseases. Multiple cohort studies and meta-analyses report associations but not causation. Treatment: explantation often improves or completely resolves symptoms.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "How does tissue expansion differ in head and neck reconstruction compared to other body areas? Describe the surgical technique for scalp expansion.", "answer": "Head/neck expansion differs due to: hair-bearing skin, different textures with varying skin quality, aesthetic subunits of face. Commonly used in children's scalp repair to avoid skin transplantation. Technique: (1) Exact preoperative planning of incision line, depth, positioning with attention to aesthetic subunits and hair-bearing areas. (2) One or two incisions made anteriorly and/or posteriorly to expanded area (use scar for incision if present). (3) Skin bridge of at least 3 cm included if defects expected; incisions adjacent and medial to bone defects. (4) Deepen incision to subgaleal plane â€” scalp easily undermined in this layer. (5) Create pocket with base as large as expander base (prevents movement). (6) Place valve on opposite part of pocket without contact to incision lines. (7) Initial inflation: 15-20% volume intraoperatively. (8) Further filling 1-2 weeks after complete skin healing; amount depends on patient tolerance and skin vascularity.", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Differentiate acute versus late radiation toxicity: timing, mechanism, reversibility, and examples of each.", "answer": "ACUTE toxicity: occurs during treatment or shortly after (peaks 7-10 days post-completion); affects cells with rapid turnover (oral mucosa, skin epithelium); mechanism is depletion of progenitor/stem cells; REVERSIBLE (heals fast after completion). Examples: skin erythema/desquamation, oral mucositis, esophagitis, diarrhea, cystitis. Exception: consequential damage from very high dose destroying basement membrane with complete stem cell depletion (causes chronic ulcers). SUBACUTE: 6 weeks to 6 months after treatment; also reversible (e.g., radiation pneumonitis, Lhermitte's syndrome). LATE toxicity: >6 months after RT; affects cells with slow renewal (connective tissue, nervous tissue, endothelium, osteoblasts, chondroblasts); mechanism is self-perpetuating TGF-beta-driven myofibroblast activity causing IRREVERSIBLE progressive fibrosis; strongly correlated with fraction size. Examples: subcutaneous fibrosis, osteoradionecrosis, brachial plexopathy. Acute toxicity does NOT predict late toxicity.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Describe the molecular mechanism of radiation-induced fibrosis and its implications for surgical wound healing.", "answer": "Radiation causes DNA damage (direct double-strand breaks and indirect via reactive oxygen species). This triggers ATM gene-mediated signal transduction pathway for DNA repair. A cascade of cytokines follows: IL-1, IL-6, TNF-alpha cause inflammatory response and coagulation. TGF-beta is the key driver: (1) causes fibroblast-to-myofibroblast differentiation, (2) stimulates collagen production, (3) modifies extracellular matrix qualitatively and quantitatively, (4) downregulates thrombomodulin in endothelium causing platelet aggregation, (5) platelets release more TGF-beta creating a SELF-PERPETUATING cycle. Unlike traumatic wounds where remodeling occurs over years, irradiated tissue LOSES capacity to remodel and develops reactive fibrosis. Surgical implications: decreased wound-breaking strength, delayed wound healing, damaged microvasculature, decreased cellular elements. Optimal surgical window: 3-10 weeks after RT completion (after acute reaction resolves, before excessive fibrosis develops). Complications related to total dose, dose per fraction, timing and extent of surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the indications for postmastectomy radiation therapy (PMRT)?", "answer": "PMRT indicated when: (1) Tumor >=5 cm (based on prechemotherapy size if neoadjuvant, i.e., cT3). (2) Positive margins or margins <1 mm. (3) Regional lymph node metastases (definitely for >=4 positive nodes; controversial for 1-3 nodes). (4) Lymphovascular invasion (predicts local recurrence). Chest wall irradiation is ALWAYS indicated with nodal involvement even if primary tumor is small, as the most common failure pattern is local chest wall failure. NOT indicated when: tumor <5 cm with negative margins and no nodal spread. Standard dose: 50 Gy in 1.8-2 Gy fractions (conventional fractionation remains standard for PMRT). Boost: additional 10-16 Gy to tumor bed/scar for high-risk features (positive margin, close margin + multiple risk factors). For left-sided cancers: DIBH technique or proton therapy to minimize cardiac dose (7.4% increased ischemic cardiac disease risk per Gy mean heart dose, linear no-threshold relationship).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "How does radiation therapy affect breast reconstruction planning? What is the recommended coordination between radiation oncology and plastic surgery?", "answer": "Key principles: (1) If PMRT indicated/likely, upfront multidisciplinary evaluation (surgical oncology, radiation oncology, medical oncology, plastic surgery, physical therapy) is STRONGLY recommended. (2) Autologous reconstruction (e.g., DIEP, latissimus) preferred over implant-based after radiation (implants more prone to contracture and reconstructive failure in irradiated field). (3) Optimal interval: at least 12 months from RT to autologous reconstruction to minimize complications. (4) If expander placed at mastectomy: expand skin to promote memory, then DEFLATE before RT for improved dosimetry; contralateral expander may also need partial deflation to improve beam angles. (5) For proton therapy: expander port must be OUTSIDE treatment field (causes dose distribution uncertainty with protons; not an issue with photons). (6) Two-stage approach common: expander at mastectomy, RT with deflated expander, then delayed reconstruction. (7) LYMPHA procedure should be coordinated if axillary dissection planned (dramatically lowers lymphedema rates).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Compare preoperative versus postoperative radiation therapy for soft-tissue sarcoma: doses, field sizes, and complication profiles.", "answer": "Based on Canadian NCIC-SR-2 trial: PREOPERATIVE RT: 50 Gy in 25 fractions, shorter duration (5-5.5 weeks), SMALLER field size (just tumor + margin), reduced late fibrosis/edema/joint stiffness. BUT: higher major wound healing complications (35% vs 17%), especially in lower extremity. POSTOPERATIVE RT: 60-66 Gy in 30-33 fractions, longer duration (6-6.5 weeks), LARGER field size (must cover entire operative footprint), increased late fibrosis and edema, decreased wound complications. Higher dose needed postop due to decreased oxygenation/vascularity of tumor bed. LOCAL CONTROL equivalent between approaches. Many institutions favor preoperative because wound complications are reversible while late fibrosis/edema are permanent. IMRT has subsequently reduced wound complications in preop setting. Indications for RT: tumors >5 cm, intermediate/high grade regardless of margins, low-grade with positive margins, local recurrence, or challenging location for salvage. Key: spare longitudinal strip of skin/subcutaneous tissue for lymphatic drainage.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is osteoradionecrosis (ORN)? Describe risk factors, presentation, and the most commonly affected site.", "answer": "ORN: necrotic wound in irradiated bone persisting without healing for 3-6 months, in absence of tumor recurrence. Most commonly affects the MANDIBLE after head and neck cancer RT. Presentation: clinically exposed bone (sometimes painless); radiologic evidence of necrosis on CT/MRI (may mimic disease recurrence) at 1-3 years after radiation. Radiation risk factors: fraction size >2 Gy, volume of bone irradiated, total dose to bone >60 Gy, re-irradiation. Modality matters: particle therapy (electrons, neutrons, protons), brachytherapy, and kilovoltage energy cause higher bone absorbed doses than megavoltage photons. Non-radiation risk factors: poor oral hygiene, dental extraction, concurrent chemotherapy (worsens mucositis/xerostomia), bisphosphonates. Prevention: dental clearance before RT, dental extractions before starting treatment, radiation oncologist delineates mandible/maxilla/salivary glands with dose constraints, life-long daily fluoride treatments post-RT, pristine dental hygiene. Incidence: historically 6.8%, now 0-2% with modern conformal techniques (IMRT, IGRT).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is the Bragg peak, and why is proton beam therapy advantageous over photon therapy for certain tumors?", "answer": "Bragg peak: protons enter the body with low steady-dose deposition, then near the end of their range, dose peaks SHARPLY and falls off rapidly to nearly ZERO. This allows: (1) precise high-dose distribution homogeneously covering target volume, (2) protection of critical structures BEYOND the Bragg peak (no exit dose), (3) dose intensification. Photons by contrast deposit Dmax at ~1.5 cm then attenuate steadily (~5%/cm), always having exit dose. Ideal proton indications: skull base tumors (chordomas, chondrosarcomas â€” high dose needed near optic chiasm/spinal cord), craniospinal irradiation for pediatric cancers (spares heart, kidneys, bowel, lungs, pelvic organs), pelvic sarcomas (fertility preservation), left-sided breast cancer with nodal irradiation (cardiac sparing), re-irradiation. Limitations: dose uncertainty from tissue heterogeneity changes (sinus congestion, postop edema, bowel gas, weight changes); high-Z hardware (titanium) causes dose shadowing (carbon fiber hardware preferred). Skin reaction may be more marked than photons.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Describe the radiation treatment-planning process: from simulation to treatment delivery.", "answer": "Steps: (1) SIMULATION: patient positioned and immobilized (mesh mask for head/neck, vacuum splints for body, casts for extremities); CT scan in treatment position; localizing tattoos placed for daily alignment. (2) CONTOURING: radiation oncologist delineates GTV (gross tumor volume), CTV (clinical target volume including microscopic disease risk), PTV (planning target volume accounting for motion/variation), and OAR (organs-at-risk with dose constraints). (3) TREATMENT PLANNING: dosimetrists and radiation oncologist select beam arrangement to homogeneously cover PTV while sparing OAR; dose-volume histograms calculate constraints (e.g., V20 of lung >35% predicts pneumonitis). (4) QUALITY ASSURANCE: physicist verifies plan is technically feasible. (5) VERIFICATION: dry run with patient in immobilization device; portal imaging compared to DRRs; CBCT for precise alignment (IGRT). (6) TREATMENT: daily fractions with verification (usually daily CBCT). Timeline: 10-14 days for curative setup, 3-10 days complex palliation, 0-3 days simple palliation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the common radiation fractionation schemes, and when is each used?", "answer": "CONVENTIONAL fractionation: 1.8-2 Gy/day, 5 days/week. Used for curative intent (e.g., 66-70 Gy for head/neck SCC, 80 Gy for prostate, 50 Gy for adjuvant breast). HYPOFRACTIONATION: >2 Gy/fraction (typically >2.4 Gy/day). Uses smaller total dose but larger dose per fraction. Used for: breast conservation (40 Gy in 15 or 42.5 Gy in 16 fractions), palliation, melanoma (6 Gy twice/week x 5-6 fractions). HYPERFRACTIONATION: twice daily fractions 6 hours apart. Maximizes normal tissue repair while allowing dose escalation for rapidly dividing tumors; used for head/neck cancers, re-irradiation, patients who can't tolerate cisplatin. SBRT/Radiosurgery: 1-5 (up to 8) fractions of very large doses (10-18+ Gy) using highly conformal planning. For small tumors (lung, liver, spine). PALLIATIVE: 8 Gy x 1, 20 Gy in 5, or 30 Gy in 10 fractions. EQD2 and BED calculations allow comparison between regimens. Key principle: higher dose per fraction increases both tumor kill AND late toxicity risk.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the head and neck-specific acute and late toxicities of radiation therapy?", "answer": "ACUTE (during treatment, reversible): Mucositis (starts weeks 2-3, confluent by end; exacerbated by smoking, alcohol, concurrent chemotherapy; causes dysphagia requiring PEG tube placement before starting treatment); skin erythema (weeks 3-4) progressing to moist desquamation; xerostomia (radiation damages parotid glands, changes saliva consistency to thick mucoid secretions); taste changes; weight loss; fatigue. LATE (>6 months, PERMANENT, progressive): Fibrosis of subcutaneous tissues, musculature, joints causing trismus, neck stiffness, aching, swallowing difficulties; permanent xerostomia if parotid/submandibular receives >26 Gy (exacerbates dental problems); voice changes from laryngeal edema/cartilage damage; osteoradionecrosis (mandible most commonly). Treatment modifications to reduce toxicity: IMRT for parotid sparing reduces permanent xerostomia; submandibular gland-sparing IMRT; proton therapy for unilateral neck minimizes contralateral fibrosis. Key timing: postoperative RT should start within 6 weeks of surgical resection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the risk factors and mechanisms of radiation-induced lymphedema, and what is the incidence after breast cancer treatment?", "answer": "Mechanism: radiation-induced fibrosis compresses lymph vessels, impairing drainage. Always exclude recurrent disease before attributing edema to treatment. Incidence: 42% 5-year cumulative incidence in breast cancer survivors (prospective population-based study), but majority (23%) is mild; only 2% develop chronic severe edema. With modern sentinel lymph node biopsy: ~10% with breast-conserving surgery and axillary RT. Independent risk factors: (1) radiation treatment of the axilla, (2) extent of axillary lymph node dissection, (3) type of breast surgery, (4) presence of regional lymph node metastases, (5) history of infection/injuries, (6) BMI. Greatest risk: COMBINATION of RT and axillary lymph node dissection. Key prevention strategies: AMAROS trial showed axillary RT has less lymphedema than ALND with equivalent survival; LYMPHA procedure (lymphatic microsurgical preventing approach) at time of axillary dissection dramatically lowers rates; spare longitudinal strip of skin/subcutaneous tissue in sarcoma RT.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the relative and absolute contraindications to radiation therapy?", "answer": "ABSOLUTE contraindications: pregnancy (high risk of fetal damage; pregnancy testing required in women of childbearing age). RELATIVE contraindications: (1) Chromosomal fragility syndromes (Li-Fraumeni syndrome, Rb gene carriers, ATM gene carriers) â€” exquisitely susceptible to radiation damage with frequent and earlier secondary malignancies. (2) Previous radiation therapy â€” requires assessment by radiation oncologist of current tumor relationship to prior field, total dose delivered, time interval between treatments, tumor radiosensitivity. (3) Active connective tissue diseases (especially scleroderma) â€” may have increased acute and late toxicities. (4) Multicentric breast disease involving multiple quadrants (breast conservation RT contraindicated â€” significant cosmetic deformity). (5) Inflammatory breast disease (absolute for breast conservation). (6) Poor performance status/patient preference may shift curative intent to observation or non-radical RT. Young age requires weighing benefit against late sequelae including second malignancy risk.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is the risk of radiation-induced secondary malignancy? What factors influence this risk?", "answer": "Three mechanisms: (1) DNA damage and mutation, (2) disturbance of cellular defense/control mechanisms, (3) chronic ongoing damage to irradiated tissue. Timing: rare within first 5 years; typically presents many years later (except leukemia: 5-8 years; solid tumors: much later). Most sensitive organs: bone marrow and thyroid. Dose-response patterns: carcinomas arise at periphery (lower-dose volume); sarcomas arise in heavily irradiated tissue (dose-response effect). Thyroid cancer unlikely if gland received >30 Gy. Age is critical: adolescent girls aged 10-16 have up to 136-FOLD increased breast cancer risk from mantle radiation. Hodgkin lymphoma survivors with mantle RT: 4x breast cancer risk. Smoking markedly increases lung cancer risk even from tiny scattered doses. Genetic predisposition: Li-Fraumeni (p53), ATM, RB gene carriers are exquisitely susceptible. Chemotherapy (especially alkylating agents) is also carcinogenic and additive with RT. IMRT concern: conformal high-dose but larger low-dose volume from multiple beam entry may increase second cancer risk.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Radiation therapy for skin cancers", "question": "Describe the role of radiation therapy in treating skin cancers: BCC, SCC, melanoma, and Merkel cell carcinoma.", "answer": "BCC: primary RT for non-surgical candidates or when surgery risks function/cosmesis; 40-50 Gy in 10-20 fractions; 30-40% of incompletely excised BCCs recur, salvageable with surgery or RT. SCC: higher doses needed (60-66 Gy in 2 Gy fractions); adjuvant RT reduces recurrence risk; assess for perineural invasion (may require treating along neural pathways). MELANOMA: considered relatively radioresistant (broad shoulder on cell survival curve = large capacity for sublethal repair); overcome with hypofractionation â€” 6 Gy twice/week, total 30-36 Gy; adjuvant RT for desmoplastic histology, depth >4 mm with ulceration/satellites, positive margins, recurrent disease; improves local control 50% to 87% without affecting survival. MERKEL CELL CARCINOMA: rare neuroendocrine tumor; adjuvant RT recommended for nearly all non-metastatic patients; 45-50 Gy with boost to 60-66 Gy for residual disease; large treatment fields (3-5 cm) due to propensity for in-transit and regional lymphatic spread. Best superficial delivery: kV equipment (100% dose at surface) or electrons with bolus.", "notes": "Closest topic match; radiation for skin cancers not a standalone subtopic", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the microscopic anatomy of the lymphatic system: how do capillary lymphatics differ from collecting lymphatics in structure and function?", "answer": "CAPILLARY LYMPHATICS: located in dermis; single layer of lymphatic endothelial cells (LECs) with little/no basement membrane; cells tethered to surrounding tissue by ANCHORING FILAMENTS and to each other by overlapping BUTTON-LIKE junctions. When tissue fluid increases, anchoring filaments cause LECs to separate, allowing fluid entry; once fluid enters, overlapping regions reestablish preventing leak. No smooth muscle. COLLECTING LYMPHATICS: located in deeper dermis/subcutaneous tissue; have continuous 'ZIPPER-LIKE' endothelial junctions preventing leak; have BASEMENT MEMBRANE; covered by SMOOTH MUSCLE CELLS that contract to propel fluid forward; have BICUSPID VALVES every 1-2 mm ensuring one-way flow. The functional unit is the LYMPHANGION: segment of collecting lymphatic between two valves.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What are the two types of forces that drive lymphatic flow? How do they differ?", "answer": "1) PASSIVE compressive forces: arise from external sources â€” muscle contractions, respiration, regional arterial pulsation, gravity. Passively propel fluid centrally. In normal limbs, passive forces (massage, muscular contractions) do NOT significantly increase collecting lymphatic pressure or flow. 2) ACTIVE compressive forces: arise from INTRINSIC contraction of smooth muscle cells surrounding collecting lymphatics. These muscle cells have features of BOTH smooth AND striated muscle with basal myogenic activity. Similar to the heart, responsive to preload and afterload changes. Contraction frequency and strength modulated by vasoactive substances (histamine, substance P). Key: increases in preload/afterload increase contraction up to a point; PERSISTENT increases beyond this point lead to PUMP FAILURE and vessel dilatation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Classify primary lymphedema by timing of presentation. What genetic mutations are associated with each?", "answer": "CONGENITAL LYMPHEDEMA (presents at birth): more common in females; more commonly lower extremities; 10-25% of all primary lymphedema. Milroy's disease: sex-linked, inactivating mutations in VEGFR-3 (FLT4 gene); accounts for 2-3%; hypoplastic lymphatic vessels with variable agenesis. LYMPHEDEMA PRAECOX (before age 35): most common form; unilateral lower extremity; 4:1 female:male ratio; often symptomatic at puberty (sex-hormone link); decreased capillary lymphatics, hypoplastic low-caliber collecting vessels. Associated with FOXC2 mutations (lymphedema-distichiasis syndrome â€” also causes double row of eyelashes). LYMPHEDEMA TARDA (after age 35): diagnosis of EXCLUSION; infrequent; most commonly lower extremities in women; associated with FOXC2 loss-of-function mutations. Other genetic syndromes: Hennekam (CCBE1), Emberger (GATA2), Proteus (AKT1).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the most common cause of lymphedema globally versus in high-income countries? What are the incidence rates?", "answer": "GLOBALLY: parasitic infection with Wuchereria bancrofti (filariasis) â€” estimated 200 million affected in low-income countries. Roundworms transmitted by mosquitos; adults grow in tissues and release microfilariae into bloodstream; cause chronic lymphatic obstruction and inflammatory reactions; treatment limited to antiparasitic medications that only kill developing larvae (not adult worms). HIGH-INCOME COUNTRIES: cancer treatment is the most common cause. Breast cancer survivors are the largest affected group. Incidence: 15-40% after axillary lymph node dissection (ALND); 5-7% even after sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) alone. Other tumor incidences: melanoma 16%, sarcoma 30%, gynecologic tumors 20%, genitourinary 10%, head and neck 4%. Meta-analysis: nearly 1 in 6 patients treated for solid tumors develops lymphedema. Lymphedema is the most common long-term complication of cancer treatment.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the role of CD4+ T cells and Th2 differentiation in lymphedema pathophysiology.", "answer": "Lymphedema develops after lymphatic injury in response to induced infiltration and differentiation of CD4+ cells into Th2 cells in tissues. The degree of Th2 inflammatory response correlates with lymphedema severity. CD4+ cell responses are NECESSARY for BOTH initiation and maintenance of lymphedema (demonstrated by antibody depletion studies and knockout mice). Th2 cells regulate FOUR overlapping pathological mechanisms: (1) LYMPHATIC PUMP FAILURE â€” Th2-derived cytokines cause CD4+ T cells to accumulate around lymphatic vessels producing nitric oxide (NO), causing vessel dilatation and decreased pumping force. (2) IMPAIRED COLLATERAL VESSEL FORMATION â€” IL-4, IL-13, IFN-gamma have direct anti-lymphangiogenic effects on LECs; counterbalance upregulated VEGF-C. (3) FIBROADIPOSE DEPOSITION â€” Th2 cytokines (IL-4, IL-13, TGF-beta1) drive fibrosis. (4) EPIDERMAL CHANGES â€” keratinocytes produce Th2-promoting cytokines (TSLP, IL-25, IL-33), creating a positive feedback loop.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Explain the role of TGF-beta1 in lymphedema-associated fibrosis. What is the therapeutic implication?", "answer": "TGF-beta1 is a key driver of lymphedema-induced fibrosis. Mechanism: CD4+ cells differentiate into Th2 cells which produce profibrotic cytokines including IL-4, IL-13, and TGF-beta1. TGF-beta1 promotes: extracellular matrix collagen deposition, fibroblast activity, progressive sclerosis of collecting lymphatics (obliteration of functional parenchyma replaced by scar tissue). Fibrosis independently DECREASES lymphatic vessel regeneration and function (creating a vicious cycle). Macrophages play an opposing antifibrotic role promoting ECM breakdown. Therapeutic implications: inhibition of TGF-beta1 with small-molecule inhibitors was shown to DECREASE fibrosis, INCREASE collateral lymphatic formation, IMPROVE radiation-induced lymphatic dysfunction, and DECREASE lymphedema severity in animal models. However, chronic TGF-beta1 inhibition risks autoimmune responses â€” further studies needed for effective pharmacological interventions.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the pathological progression of collecting lymphatic vessels in lymphedema using the NECST classification.", "answer": "NECST (Koshima classification) describes four progressive histological steps in collecting lymphatics after lymphadenectomy: (1) NORMAL (Step 0): lymphatic vessels are normal and fully functional. (2) ECTASIS (Step 1): endolymphatic pressure increases, causing LECs to flatten; lymphangiectasia (vessel dilation) begins. Early stage: disruption of endogenous NO gradient causes REVERSIBLE dilatation. (3) CONTRACTION (Step 2): smooth muscle cells convert into synthetic cells promoting collagenous fiber growth; lymphatic vessel wall THICKENS; loss of intraluminal diameter. (4) SCLEROSIS (Step 3): lumen of lymphatic vessels narrowed or completely OBSTRUCTED; most tissue is fibrosed; lymphatic vessels have lost transport and concentrating ability. This progressive sclerosis explains why late-stage lymphedema is IRREVERSIBLE â€” permanent collecting lymphatic pumping impairment from both structural obliteration and smooth muscle cell proliferation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Why does lymphedema only develop in a subset of patients who undergo lymphadenectomy, and why is presentation delayed?", "answer": "Key concept: lymphatic injury is NECESSARY but NOT SUFFICIENT for lymphedema. Additional pathological changes are required. After lymph node dissection, acute surgical swelling resolves within weeks and in most patients never recurs. In the early stages, chronic inflammation and subclinical fluid stasis promote PROLIFERATION AND COLLATERALIZATION of capillary lymphatics in the superficial dermis â€” these vessels effectively bypass the zone of obstruction, preventing overt lymphedema. However, in 30-50% of patients, these compensatory mechanisms eventually fail: increased VEGF-C (from macrophages) induces formation of NONFUNCTIONAL hyperplastic, irregularly shaped vessels that do NOT bypass the injury zone. When BOTH superficial AND deep lymphatic systems fail (capillary + collecting), clinically evident lymphedema develops. Average onset: 8 months after breast cancer surgery; 75% diagnosed within first 3 years. Lower extremity onset faster (3-6 months, possibly due to gravity).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "How are obesity and lymphedema related? What is the evidence for a bidirectional relationship?", "answer": "BIDIRECTIONAL RELATIONSHIP: (1) Obesity causes lymphedema: BMI >30 gives â‰¥3-fold increased lymphedema risk after breast cancer surgery (almost linear relationship). Massively obese patients (BMI >59) can SPONTANEOUSLY develop lower extremity lymphedema WITHOUT lymphatic surgery â€” this is PERMANENT with little improvement even after gastric bypass. Obesity causes leaky lymphatics, decreased lymphatic pumping, and lymphatic function inversely proportional to body weight (mouse studies). (2) Lymphedema causes adipose deposition: Prox-1 haploinsufficient mice (impaired lymphatic pumping/leakiness) become obese â€” demonstrating lymphatic abnormalities CAUSE weight gain. Fatty acids in interstitial/lymphatic fluid increase adipocyte proliferation and differentiation. Adiponectin and leptin levels elevated in lymphedema. KEY: adverse effects of obesity on lymphatic system are REVERSIBLE with weight loss, calorie restriction, or exercise. Therefore, weight loss counseling is essential before lymphadenectomy/lymphatic surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of nitric oxide (NO) in lymphedema progression?", "answer": "CD4+ T cells accumulate around lymphatic vessels in lymphedema and produce large amounts of nitric oxide (NO). This EXTRINSIC source of NO causes: (1) Lymphatic vessel DILATATION â€” decreases the force lymphatics generate for pumping. (2) In EARLY disease: disruption of the endogenous NO gradient leads to REVERSIBLE lymphatic vessel dilatation. (3) In LATE disease: IRREVERSIBLE lymphatic obliteration develops, leading to permanent collecting lymphatic pumping impairment. Additionally, NO-mediated dilatation contributes to lymphatic VALVULAR INCOMPETENCE, resulting in localized areas of RETROGRADE FLOW to capillary lymphatics in the superficial dermis (dermal backflow). At this point, collecting lymphatics maintain ability to actively contract but pulsations become more irregular with loss of correlation between pulse amplitude and stroke volume.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "Describe the ISL staging system for lymphedema. What are the clinical, imaging, and histological features of each stage?", "answer": "STAGE 0 (Latent): lymphatic vessels injured but capacity sufficient to drain; no measurable swelling; subclinical interstitial fluid stasis. STAGE I (Spontaneously reversible): pitting edema responsive to compression/elevation; dilated lymphatics with irregular pulsation; localized dermal backflow on ICG; histology shows modest hyperkeratosis, collagen deposition, inflammatory cell infiltration, dilated capillaries/collectors. STAGE II (Spontaneously irreversible): irreversible swelling; no pitting, spongy consistency; limbs harden and enlarge. ICG: loss of major collectors, extensive dermal backflow, decreased/absent pumping. Histology: sclerosed lymphatics, type I collagen accumulation, smooth muscle cell proliferation, adipocyte accumulation. STAGE III (Lymphostatic elephantiasis): severe irreversible swelling; heavily fibrosed, thickened skin. ICG: no recognizable collectors, diffuse dye accumulation. Histology: hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, chronic inflammation, massive adipose/collagen deposition.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "Compare the diagnostic modalities for lymphedema: circumference measurements, volume measurements, bioimpedance, lymphoscintigraphy, MRI, and ICG lymphangiography.", "answer": "CIRCUMFERENCE: measured at distinct anatomic locations; >2 cm difference diagnostic; inter/intra-operator variability; limited in high BMI patients. VOLUME: more sensitive/specific than circumference; methods include water displacement, perometer (infrared scanner using truncated cone formula â€” expensive, not widely available), or 4 cm interval circumference with truncated cone calculation; >200 mL or 10% difference diagnostic. BIOIMPEDANCE (L-DEX): measures electrical current transmission rate; score â‰¥7 indicative of clinical lymphedema, â‰¥6.5 subclinical; variable due to skin temperature/dryness; helpful for early-stage detection. LYMPHOSCINTIGRAPHY: 99mTc uptake in draining nodes; most commonly used radiologic test but LOW sensitivity (0.61) for early disease. MRI LYMPHANGIOGRAPHY: high sensitivity/specificity; visualizes lymphatic vessels, pathologic changes, venous outflow abnormalities, AND fat hypertrophy. ICG LYMPHANGIOGRAPHY: advocated as GOLD STANDARD; nontoxic; visualizes collecting lymphatics, dermal backflow, abnormal vasculature; detects pathology even when volume/bioimpedance are normal.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "What is the Stemmer sign? What is its diagnostic significance?", "answer": "The Stemmer sign (Kaposi-Stemmer sign) is the INABILITY to pinch the skin fold at the base of the second toe on the dorsal aspect of the foot, or the webspace of the hand, in patients with lymphedema. A POSITIVE Stemmer sign is a SENSITIVE predictor for both primary and secondary lymphedema of arms or legs, making it a useful part of the physical examination. However, a positive sign is NOT REQUIRED for diagnosis â€” in some patients with extremity lymphedema, the hands or feet are SPARED from swelling. Described by Stemmer in 1976.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "Describe the M.D. Anderson ICG lymphedema classification system.", "answer": "Four-stage system based on indocyanine green (ICG) findings and degree of dermal backflow: STAGE 1: MANY patent lymphatic vessels present; MINIMAL dermal backflow in localized areas. STAGE 2: MODERATE number of lymphatic vessels; SEGMENTAL dermal backflow. STAGE 3: FEW patent lymphatic vessels; SIGNIFICANT dermal backflow throughout the ENTIRE arm. STAGE 4: NO patent lymphatic vessels; SEVERE dermal backflow throughout entire arm AND hand. Although somewhat subjective, useful for classification and patient selection for lymphovenous bypass procedures. This system complements the Koshima NECST classification which focuses on histological changes in collecting lymphatics (normal â†’ ectasis â†’ contraction â†’ sclerosis).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "List the key genetic syndromes associated with primary lymphedema, their gene mutations, and distinguishing clinical features.", "answer": "1) MILROY DISEASE: FLT4/VEGFR-3 mutation; congenital lower extremity lymphedema; upslanting 'SKI JUMP' toenails from nail bed edema; 2-3% of primary lymphedema. 2) LYMPHEDEMA-DISTICHIASIS: FOXC2 mutation; lower-limb lymphedema at PUBERTY; DOUBLE ROW OF EYELASHES (distichiasis). 3) HYPOTRICHOSIS-LYMPHEDEMA-TELANGIECTASIA: SOX18 mutation; lymphedema + hair loss + dilated superficial blood vessels. 4) MEIGE'S DISEASE: GJC2 (connexin 47); impaired gap junctions; increased breast cancer-related lymphedema risk. 5) HENNEKAM SYNDROME: CCBE1 mutation; severe limb/genital/facial lymphedema; seizures; intellectual disability; often presents in utero. 6) EMBERGER SYNDROME: GATA2 mutation; childhood lower limb lymphedema; severe cutaneous warts; myelodysplasia. 7) PROTEUS SYNDROME: AKT1 mutation; lymphatic malformations + skeletal/cutaneous/CNS abnormalities.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of VEGF-C in lymphedema, and why do functional lymphatic vessels fail to form despite high VEGF-C levels?", "answer": "VEGF-C (mainly produced by macrophages) is HIGHLY UPREGULATED in lymphedematous tissues. It is a key signal for LEC growth, migration, and survival via VEGFR-3 receptor. However, despite high VEGF-C levels, FUNCTIONAL lymphatic vessels fail to form because: (1) T-cell-derived cytokines including IL-4, IL-13, and IFN-gamma have DIRECT ANTI-LYMPHANGIOGENIC effects on LECs. (2) These anti-lymphangiogenic cytokines COUNTERBALANCE the pro-lymphangiogenic effect of VEGF-C, preventing functional lymphatics from forming. (3) The abnormal lymphatic vessels that DO form are NONFUNCTIONAL â€” they are hyperplastic, irregularly shaped vessels that arise from existing collecting vessels and proliferate around them but do NOT bypass the zone of injury. This paradox explains why simply promoting lymphangiogenesis may be insufficient therapy â€” the inflammatory microenvironment must also be addressed.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of adipose deposition in lymphedema progression? How does it affect treatment response?", "answer": "End-stage lymphedema is characterized by PROGRESSIVE ADIPOSE DEPOSITION. Initially, lymphedema involves fluid accumulation (60-70% in subcutaneous tissues between adipose and around small veins; remainder above/below muscular fascia and in dermis). Over time, this fluid promotes chronic fibrofatty tissue deposition. Mechanisms: (1) Fatty acids in lymphatic fluid increase adipocyte PROLIFERATION and DIFFERENTIATION. (2) Lymphatic injury upregulates adipose differentiation genes, causes adipose hypertrophy. (3) Adiponectin and leptin (fat-regulating hormones) are elevated. (4) IL-6, a regulator of adipose homeostasis, is increased â€” paradoxically, inhibiting IL-6 INCREASES adipose deposition. Clinical significance: progressive fibrofatty deposition makes lymphedema MORE RESISTANT to compressive therapies. The irreversible nature of swelling and lack of pitting in stage II/III patients is explained by adipocyte accumulation. This is why LIPOSUCTION-based approaches (e.g., Brorson technique) may be needed for fat-predominant disease.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "What is the differential diagnosis for lymphedema? Why is venous obstruction particularly important to exclude?", "answer": "Differential diagnosis includes: (1) VENOUS INSUFFICIENCY, (2) deep vein thrombosis (DVT), (3) congestive heart failure, (4) recurrent or primary MALIGNANCY causing lymphatic obstruction, (5) medications, (6) infections. VENOUS OBSTRUCTION is particularly critical to exclude because: nearly 70% of interstitial fluid is removed by the VENOUS system (not lymphatics). Venous obstruction from thrombosis or recurrent tumor compressing venous system is a COMMON cause of limb swelling in cancer patients. MRI lymphangiography is valuable because it can also identify venous pathology â€” venous hypertension may not only contribute to swelling but also COMPROMISE the effects of lymphovenous bypass or lymph node transplant. Appropriate imaging to rule out venous obstruction is warranted in patients with unusual disease presentation. Always EXCLUDE RECURRENT DISEASE before attributing edema to lymphedema treatment.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the risk factors for secondary lymphedema. How do radiation and infection each contribute?", "answer": "Risk factors: obesity (BMI >30 = â‰¥3x risk), radiation, infection, extent of lymph node dissection, type of surgery, genetic factors (connexin 47, hepatocyte growth factor mutations increase risk). RADIATION: increases lymphedema risk up to 5-FOLD; effect is ADDITIVE with surgery (lymphedema from radiation alone is unusual, <7%); radiation-induced FIBROSIS independently decreases lymphatic vessel regeneration and function. Lymphedema significantly more prevalent in obese patients treated with surgery + radiation (risk factors are additive). INFECTION: one-third of lymphedema patients develop RECURRENT soft-tissue infections. Unclear if infection causes lymphedema or is a symptom of subclinical lymphedema. Bacteria cause lymphatic dysfunction via loss of lymphatic muscle cells (LMCs). Early postoperative infections significantly increase lymphedema incidence. GENETICS: connexin 47 and hepatocyte growth factor gene mutations increase secondary lymphedema risk â€” challenges the traditional view that secondary lymphedema is solely due to mechanical trauma.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the evidence for anti-Th2 immunotherapy in lymphedema? Describe the phase I clinical trial results.", "answer": "Phase I clinical trial: open-label, single-arm study of 9 breast cancer-related lymphedema patients. Treatment: monthly IL-4 and IL-13 neutralizing antibody injections with 4-month washout. Results: (1) NO effect on limb volumes. (2) SIGNIFICANT decrease in skin stiffness (measured by tonometry). (3) Improved quality of life (validated lymphedema-specific QoL tool). (4) QoL scores returned to baseline after washout period (suggesting NOT placebo effect). Biopsy findings: Th2 blockade significantly decreased: epidermal thickness, skin collagen deposition, mast cell infiltration, T cell infiltration. Additional discovery: keratinocytes produce Th2-promoting cytokines (TSLP, IL-25, IL-33) that promote Th2 differentiation â€” these DECREASED after treatment, suggesting keratinocytes may play a role in lymphedema pathophysiology (active area of investigation). These findings support the Th2-mediated inflammatory model of lymphedema.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of regulatory T cells (Tregs) in lymphedema? Why is their function paradoxical?", "answer": "Tregs have a DUAL (paradoxical) role in lymphedema: (1) BENEFICIAL: Tregs normally suppress inflammatory responses â€” inhibition of Tregs was shown to INCREASE tissue inflammatory responses in a preclinical model, resulting in MORE SEVERE lymphedema phenotype. This is because the Th2-mediated inflammatory cascade that drives lymphedema pathology becomes more intense without Treg suppression. (2) DETRIMENTAL: Lymphatic dysfunction causes increased infiltration of Tregs in lymphedematous tissues. These Tregs SUPPRESS host humoral and innate immunity and peripheral tolerance. Inhibition of Tregs was shown to IMPROVE bacterial clearance and immune responses in lymphedema. This explains why lymphedema patients are prone to recurrent infections â€” Tregs suppress the immune responses needed to fight pathogens. Clinical implication: therapeutic approaches must balance these opposing roles â€” blocking Tregs improves infection clearance but worsens lymphedema inflammation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "What are the main patient-reported outcome measures (PROMs) used in lymphedema? What subscales does each measure?", "answer": "1) LYMQOL (Lymph Quality of Life Measure for Limb Lymphedema): upper and lower extremity; subscales: pain, mood, function, appearance, overall QoL. 2) ULL27 (Upper Limb Lymphedema 27): upper extremity only; subscales: physical, psychological, social. 3) LYMPH-ICF (Lymphedema Functioning, Disability and Health): upper and lower extremity; subscales: physical function, mental function, household activities, mobility activities, life/social activities. 4) LLIS (Lymphedema Life Impact Scale): upper and lower extremity; subscales: physical, psychosocial, functional, infection occurrence. 5) LYMPH-Q: upper extremity; subscales: arm symptoms, function, appearance, psychological function, satisfaction with information and arm sleeves. Developed to address limitations of existing PROMs (low reliability/validity, limited patient input). LYMPH-Q complements BREAST-Q for breast cancer patients. New scales in development for lymphedema burden and work impact.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "What are the recommended surgical margins for wide excision of nonmelanocytic skin tumors: BCC, SCC, Merkel cell carcinoma, and soft-tissue sarcoma?", "answer": "HORIZONTAL MARGINS: BCC: low risk 4 mm, high risk 5-10 mm. SCC: low risk 4-6 mm, high risk 10 mm. Merkel cell carcinoma: 10-20 mm. Sarcoma: low risk 10 mm, high risk 20 mm. VERTICAL MARGINS based on depth of invasion: tumors limited to dermis â†’ excise with fat layer; tumors extending into fat â†’ excise with deep fascia; tumors extending into fascia â†’ excise with skeletal muscle; tumors into muscle â†’ excise with membranes of deeper structures (cartilage/bone); tumors into bone/cartilage membranes â†’ excise with those structures. General principle: at least one layer of barrier structure should be excised beyond the deepest plane of tumor invasion.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "BCC", "question": "Describe the histological classification of basal cell carcinoma (BCC). What are the key subtypes?", "answer": "WHO classification includes 10 types: (1) Multifocal superficial BCC (superficial multicentric), (2) Nodular BCC (solid, adenoid cystic), (3) Infiltrating BCC â€” subdivided into 3a nonsclerosing and 3b sclerosing (desmoplastic, morpheic), (4) Fibroepithelial BCC, (5) BCC with adnexal differentiation â€” 5a with follicular differentiation, 5b with eccrine differentiation, (6) Basosquamous carcinoma, (7) Keratotic BCC, (8) Pigmented BCC, (9) BCC in basal cell nevus syndrome, (10) Micronodular BCC. BCC is the MOST COMMON type of skin cancer. Rarely metastasizes but can invade surrounding tissues causing significant destruction/disfigurement. Most commonly affects head and neck. Treatment: surgical excision; Mohs micrographic surgery for complex cases; CO2 lasers or cryosurgery for selected superficial BCC.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "SCC", "question": "What are the precursor lesions and risk factors for cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (SCC)?", "answer": "SCC arises most commonly on DAMAGED SKIN. Precursor lesions and risk factors: (1) ACTINIC KERATOSIS: intraepidermal early-stage SCC from chronic UV exposure; atypical pleomorphic keratinocytes at basal layer extending upward; progresses to invasive SCC over time. (2) BOWEN'S DISEASE: intraepidermal carcinoma (carcinoma in situ) of keratinocytes; can progress to invasive SCC (then called Bowen's carcinoma, which can metastasize); classic feature: nonsteroid-responsive dermatosis. (3) Postburn scars â†’ MARJOLIN'S ULCER. (4) Traumatic scars. (5) Chronic stasis ulcers. (6) Chronic radiation dermatitis. (7) Lupus erythematosus lesions. (8) Lichen planus of oral mucosa. (9) HPV infection lesions. (10) KERATOACANTHOMA: controversial entity resembling SCC; grows rapidly, sometimes self-heals; atypical squamous cells on histology make it difficult to distinguish from SCC â€” excisional biopsy recommended.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Merkel cell carcinoma", "question": "Describe Merkel cell carcinoma: etiology, clinical features, and management.", "answer": "Merkel cell carcinoma: rare, HIGHLY AGGRESSIVE cancer developing on/beneath skin and in hair follicles. Etiology: majority caused by MERKEL CELL POLYOMAVIRUS (newly discovered). Clinical features: most common on face, head, and neck; appears as firm, PAINLESS nodules or tumors. Management: wide excision with 1-2 cm normal skin margin. Because it tends to METASTASIZE TO LYMPH NODES: sentinel lymph node biopsy and lymph node dissection should be considered. Adjuvant RADIATION THERAPY recommended for nearly all non-metastatic patients. Distant metastasis cases require CHEMOTHERAPY. Treatment fields should be large (3-5 cm margins from Ch27 data) due to propensity for in-transit and regional lymphatic spread.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Explain the TNM classification system for skin carcinoma. How do the T stages differ?", "answer": "TNM system (UICC): T = primary tumor size/invasion; N = regional lymph node involvement; M = distant metastasis. T STAGES for skin carcinoma (excluding eyelid, H&N, perianal, vulva, penis): Tis: carcinoma in situ. T1: â‰¤2 cm greatest dimension. T2: >2 cm and â‰¤4 cm. T3: >4 cm, OR minor bone erosion, OR perineural invasion, OR deep invasion. T4a: gross cortical bone/marrow invasion. T4b: axial skeleton invasion including foraminal and/or vertebral foramen involvement to epidural space. N STAGES: N0: no regional node metastasis. N1: single node â‰¤3 cm. N2: single ipsilateral node >3-6 cm, or multiple ipsilateral nodes â‰¤6 cm. N3: node >6 cm. STAGING: Stage 0 = Tis; Stage I = T1N0; Stage II = T2N0; Stage III = T3N0 or T1-3N1; Stage IVA = T1-3N2-3 or T4; Stage IVB = any M1. Note: pN0 requires â‰¥6 lymph nodes examined.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "What is Mohs micrographic surgery? What are its indications and advantages?", "answer": "Mohs micrographic surgery: technique where tumors undergo HISTOLOGIC ANALYSIS DURING SURGERY so that almost ALL surgical margins can be examined for tumor extensions. Provides COMPLETE MARGIN CONTROL during removal. Advantages: (1) highest cure rate of all treatment modalities for nonmelanoma skin cancer, (2) maximal tissue conservation (removes only involved tissue), (3) real-time margin assessment. Indications: (1) BCC â€” frequently used, especially for complex cases, (2) SCC â€” frequently used (especially on nose/face), (3) Keratoacanthoma â€” especially on nose/face for good margin control with minimal tissue removal, (4) Dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans â€” with continuous histological margin control to reduce local recurrence, (5) Sweat gland carcinoma â€” reduces high recurrence rates of conventional excision, (6) Extramammary Paget's disease â€” helpful for determining normal skin margins for wide excision. Also useful for anatomically complex and cosmetically sensitive regions.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "What is dermoscopy and how is it used in the two-step diagnostic algorithm for skin lesions?", "answer": "Dermoscopy: specialized technique employing a binocular microscope to observe skin surface. STEP 1: differentiate MELANOCYTIC from NONMELANOCYTIC lesions using dermoscopic criteria for melanocytic lesions (pigment network, negative network, aggregated globules, streaks, homogeneous blue pigmentation, pseudonetwork, parallel pattern). If melanocytic â†’ pattern analysis to categorize (malignant melanoma, Clark's nevus, Spitz/Reed nevus, congenital nevus, blue nevus, etc.). STEP 2: If nonmelanocytic â†’ evaluate sequentially for: SEBORRHEIC KERATOSIS (multiple milia-like cysts, comedo-like openings, fingerprint-like structures, fissures/ridges) â†’ BCC (absent pigment network PLUS arborizing vessels, leaf-like areas, large blue-gray ovoid nests, blue-gray globules, spoke wheel areas, ulceration) â†’ VASCULAR LESION (red-blue lacunas, red-bluish to red-black homogeneous areas). Essential for differentiating malignant melanoma from nevus and diagnosing BCC.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Compare the imaging characteristics of benign versus malignant skin tumors on MRI and Doppler ultrasound.", "answer": "MRI: MALIGNANT tumors typically show LOW-TO-ISOINTENSE signal on T2WI and LOW signal on T1WI. BENIGN tumors typically show HIGH signal on T2WI and LOW signal on T1WI. MRI detects soft tissues better than CT; magnetic resonance angiography superior for determining nidus and collateral structures in hemangiomas/vascular malformations. DOPPLER ULTRASOUND: 90% of MALIGNANT skin tumors exhibit HIGH BLOOD FLOW rate (3-20 cm/s) that is NOT observed in >95% of benign tumors. Power Doppler has higher resolution than color Doppler imaging (CDI). CDI useful for detecting blood flow in AVMs. M-mode and duplex scanning useful for hemangiomas/vascular malformations. HIGH-FREQUENCY ULTRASOUND (20-50 MHz): determines tumor thickness, relationship with adjacent structures, lymph node metastasis. For lesions extending >20 mm deep, standard ultrasound (3-10 MHz) should be used. CT: better for detecting bone, lymph node, and lung metastases than MRI.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "What is dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans (DFSP)? Describe its molecular pathology, clinical features, and treatment.", "answer": "DFSP (giant cell fibroblastoma): mesenchymal-origin malignant tumor. Molecular pathology: >90% have chromosomal translocation t(17;22) fusing COLLAGEN GENE COL1A1 with PLATELET-DERIVED GROWTH FACTOR (PDGF) gene. Clinical features: multiple or solitary tumors with RED color, hemispherical elevation, papillary vessels on surface; KELOIDAL APPEARANCE (sometimes misdiagnosed as keloid and treated with steroids). Metastasizes RARELY, but distant metastasis to lung can occur from local recurrence. Treatment: radical resection with 5 cm normal skin margin. MOHS MICROGRAPHIC SURGERY with continuous histological margin control needed to reduce local recurrence rates. Adjuvant chemotherapy and radiation therapy may be useful. Because of the COL1A1-PDGF fusion, imatinib (tyrosine kinase inhibitor targeting PDGF receptor) has shown efficacy in unresectable/metastatic cases.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "Describe angiosarcoma and Kaposi's sarcoma: etiology, clinical features, and management.", "answer": "ANGIOSARCOMA: malignant neoplasm of ENDOTHELIAL CELLS; subdivided into hemangiosarcoma and lymphangiosarcoma. Due to endothelial origin, metastasis to distant sites occurs OFTEN. Treatment: surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, immunotherapy (interleukin-2). Prognosis: generally POOR; superficial lesions have slightly better prognosis due to lower malignancy risk and better accessibility. KAPOSI'S SARCOMA: caused by KSHV (Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus / HHV-8). Became widely known with AIDS epidemic in 1980s. Presentation: red, purple, brown, or black nodules/blotches that are papular (palpable/raised); found on skin but can spread to mouth, GI tract, respiratory tract. Growth ranges from very slow to explosively fast. Treatment: radiation therapy, cryotherapy, chemotherapy; surgery NOT primary choice (useful as supportive therapy); HIGHLY ACTIVE ANTIRETROVIRAL THERAPY (HAART) should be combined with other treatments in HIV-positive patients.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Describe the Leser-TrÃ©lat sign and its clinical significance.", "answer": "The sign of Leser-TrÃ©lat is the dramatic, SUDDEN APPEARANCE of MULTIPLE SEBORRHEIC KERATOSES. It is a PARANEOPLASTIC SYNDROME â€” an ominous sign of an INTERNAL MALIGNANCY. Features: not only do new lesions suddenly appear, but pre-existing lesions also frequently INCREASE IN SIZE and become SYMPTOMATIC. Clinical significance: this sign should NOT be overlooked. When observed, screening for INTERNAL MALIGNANCY should be recommended to the patient. Seborrheic keratosis itself is a benign growth originating from basal and squamous cells in the epidermis; it must be differentiated from nevus cell nevus, senile keratosis, BCC, and malignant melanoma.", "notes": "Closest match for paraneoplastic syndromes under skin cancers", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Pigmented skin lesions", "question": "Classify pigment cell nevi. Which types have malignant potential?", "answer": "Five types of pigmented nevi: (1) LENTIGO SIMPLEX: black-brown, 2-3 mm; proliferation of melanocytes in basal layer; NOT induced by sun; earliest form of acquired nevus. (2) ACQUIRED PIGMENT CELL NEVUS: three subtypes by melanocyte location â€” JUNCTION (epidermis-dermis junction), COMPOUND (junction + dermis), INTRADERMAL (dermis only). Sutton's halo nevus has depigmented area around it. (3) CONGENITAL PIGMENT CELL NEVUS: present at birth; small (<1.5 cm), medium (1.5-20 cm), large/giant (>20 cm). (4) DYSPLASTIC NEVUS (Clark's nevus): resembles early melanoma; familial atypical mole and melanoma syndrome = melanoma in 1st/2nd-degree relative + numerous (>50) nevi + clinically atypical + specific histologic features. (5) SPITZ NEVUS (juvenile melanoma): dome-like, ~1 cm, face/legs of young patients; rapid growth then becomes static. MALIGNANT POTENTIAL: GIANT CONGENITAL NEVI can develop melanoma. De novo carcinogenesis theory: most melanomas arise directly from epidermal melanocytes, NOT from pre-existing nevi.", "notes": "Closest topic match; pigmented lesion classification not a standalone subtopic", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Pigmented skin lesions", "question": "Compare nevus of Ota, nevus of Ito, and mongolian spots: origin, location, demographics, and treatment.", "answer": "All are DERMAL MELANOCYTOSES (melanocyte proliferation in dermis causing blue color). NEVUS OF OTA: distribution along V1 and V2 branches of trigeminal nerve; common in ASIANS, rare in Europeans; women 5x more affected; NOT congenital but appears in infancy and puberty; believed derived from melanocytes that didn't complete migration from neural crest to epidermis; treat with Q-switched ruby or alexandrite laser (4-8 treatments). NEVUS OF ITO: subtype of Ota; located on ACROMIODELTOID region; same treatment as Ota. MONGOLIAN SPOT (congenital dermal melanocytosis): sacral/coccygeal region; >90% Native American, 80% Asian, 70% Hispanic, <10% European infants; results from melanocyte entrapment in dermis during embryonic migration; DISAPPEARS before age 10; treatment usually unnecessary. Key: if a pigmented nevus >7 mm is still GROWING, consider malignant melanoma.", "notes": "Closest topic match; specific dermal melanocytoses not standalone subtopics", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Pigmented skin lesions", "question": "What is the diagnostic significance of cafe-au-lait spots (nevus spilus)? When should neurofibromatosis be suspected?", "answer": "Nevus spilus (cafe-au-lait spot): benign tumor of melanocytes characterized by INCREASED MELANIN GRANULES (not melanocyte proliferation). Uniform cafe-au-lait color. Suspect NEUROFIBROMATOSIS TYPE 1 (NF1, von Recklinghausen's disease) when: â‰¥6 cafe-au-lait spots >5 mm in PREPUBERTY or >15 mm in POSTPUBERTY. NF1: mutation of chromosome band 17q11.2 encoding NEUROFIBROMIN. NF1 features: cutaneous neurofibromas (allow early diagnosis), cafe-au-lait spots. NF2 differences: patients RARELY have cafe-au-lait spots; do NOT have cutaneous neurofibromas but may have cutaneous schwannomas resembling skin tags; symptoms from cranial nerve VIII schwannomas usually begin in 3rd decade; diagnosed LATER than NF1.", "notes": "Closest topic match", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "Describe the clinical features, diagnosis, and management of schwannoma. What are the two histological types?", "answer": "Schwannoma (neurilemmoma): benign proliferation of SCHWANN CELLS in dermis/subcutaneous tissues. Associated with NF2 (multiple schwannomas). Two histological types (Antoni classification): TYPE A: numerous VEROCAY BODIES â€” acellular, eosinophilic areas (oval/linear/serpiginous) surrounded by parallel-lying or palisading bundles of spindled Schwann cells with blunt, elongated nuclei; long axes all oriented toward acellular area. TYPE B: LACKS Verocay bodies; loose, myxomatous stroma with fewer, randomly arranged spindle cells. Neither type contains neurites. Features: typically ENCAPSULATED; associated peripheral nerve visible microscopically. ANCIENT SCHWANNOMAS: older lesions with degenerative changes (hemorrhage, hemosiderin, chronic inflammation, fibrosis, nuclear pleomorphism) â€” benign but must differentiate from neurofibrosarcoma and malignant schwannoma. Treatment: surgical removal.", "notes": "Closest topic match; peripheral nerve tumors not a standalone subtopic", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "What is a glomus tumor? Describe the diagnostic signs and treatment.", "answer": "Glomus tumors arise from the arterial portion of the GLOMUS BODY (Sucquet-Hoyer canal), which is an arteriovenous anastomosis in the dermis involved in TEMPERATURE REGULATION. Presentation: SOLITARY lesions have PAROXYSMAL PAIN that can be severe, exacerbated by PRESSURE or TEMPERATURE CHANGES (especially cold). Multiple glomus tumors are less common; pain usually less severe. Classic location: subungual (under nail). Two diagnostic signs: (1) HILDRETH SIGN: disappearance of pain after a TOURNIQUET is placed on the proximal arm. (2) LOVE TEST: pain elicited by pressing the skin overlying the tumor with the tip of a PENCIL. Treatment: solitary â€” surgical excision (treatment of choice). Multiple â€” excision limited to SYMPTOMATIC lesions due to poor circumscription and large number of lesions.", "notes": "Closest topic match", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Classification of vascular anomalies", "question": "Classify vascular malformations and describe their associated syndromes.", "answer": "CAPILLARY MALFORMATIONS (hemangioma simplex): three types by location â€” (1) Portwine stain (face, limbs, upper body), (2) Salmon patch (medial forehead, glabella, nasal tip, upper lip), (3) Nevus Unna (nape). Only salmon patch can disappear within first year. Associated syndromes: STURGE-WEBER (facial portwine stain) and KLIPPEL-TRENAUNAY (limb). Patients need brain examination. Treatment: dye laser, Nd:YAG laser. STRAWBERRY HEMANGIOMA: endothelial cell proliferation; appears ~3-4 weeks after birth, peaks 6-7 months; volume rarely decreases naturally but color may fade; treat with laser EARLY. VENOUS MALFORMATION (cavernous hemangioma): low-flow blood-storing lesion; NO endothelial cell proliferation; seen in Klippel-Trenaunay syndrome. Treatment: sclerotherapy (ethanol, polidocanol, sodium tetradecyl sulfate). AVM: high-flow pulsating lesion with A-V shunt; Schobinger classification: I (quiescence), II (expansion), III (destruction), IV (decompensation with heart failure â€” PARKES-WEBER syndrome). Incomplete resection â†’ rapid regrowth.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Describe extramammary Paget's disease (EMPD): clinical features, associations, diagnosis, and treatment.", "answer": "EMPD: adenocarcinoma LIMITED TO THE EPIDERMIS (intraepidermal). Key distinction: Mammary Paget's disease is sometimes associated with invasive BREAST CANCER (considered intraepidermal proliferating breast carcinoma). EMPD is only OCCASIONALLY associated with underlying invasive malignancy. Location: vulva, penis, axilla. Clinical features: relatively HIGH INVASIVE SPEED making early detection difficult; often initially misdiagnosed as ECZEMA. Diagnosis and treatment: MOHS MICROGRAPHIC SURGERY or MAPPING BIOPSY to determine normal skin margins for wide excision. Sentinel lymph node biopsy useful for deciding whether to remove lymph nodes. Chemotherapy: 5-FU + mitomycin C; 5-FU + carboplatin + leucovorin; 5-FU + carboplatin + mitomycin C + epirubicin + vincristine.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "Compare epidermoid cyst, dermoid cyst, trichilemmal cyst, and pilomatricoma: origin, location, features, and treatment.", "answer": "EPIDERMOID CYST (atheroma): smooth, dome-shaped, freely movable subcutaneous swelling; attached to skin by CENTRAL PORE; lined with stratified squamous epithelium resembling epidermis; contains keratin. Giant atheromas need pathology to rule out malignancy. Treatment: excision; for large cysts, contents removed first then walls extracted through minimal incision. DERMOID CYST: CONGENITAL subcutaneous cyst along embryonic lines of closure; most common on supraorbital region, brow, upper eyelid, glabella, scalp; contains keratin debris and hair shaft fragments; can undergo malignant change â€” complete removal recommended. TRICHILEMMAL CYST: from outer root sheath of hair follicle; most common on HAIRY SCALP; multiple in 70% of cases; resembles epidermoid cyst. Proliferating type has malignant potential. PILOMATRICOMA (calcifying epithelioma): cystic nodule on head/neck of young patients; CALCIFIED region visible on imaging; multiple pilomatricoma associated with MYOTONIC DYSTROPHY; no clear capsule â€” careful complete excision needed.", "notes": "Closest topic match", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "What is a Marjolin's ulcer? In what clinical settings does SCC arise from chronic wounds or scars?", "answer": "MARJOLIN'S ULCER: squamous cell carcinoma arising in a POSTBURN SCAR. SCC can arise from many chronic wound/scar types: (1) Postburn scars (classic Marjolin's ulcer), (2) Traumatic scars, (3) Chronic stasis ulcers, (4) Chronic radiation dermatitis, (5) Lupus erythematosus lesions, (6) Lichen planus on oral mucosa, (7) HPV infection lesions. SCC characteristics: elevated, indurated lesion with varying degrees of ulceration and crusting; notable BAD SMELL from macerated keratin and bacterially infected necrotic tissues. Key differentiator from BCC: SCC can arise on ANY site but most common on damaged skin. Treatment: surgical excision; Mohs micrographic surgery frequently used; radiotherapy (external-beam or brachytherapy) also effective. Margins: low-risk SCC 4-6 mm, high-risk 10 mm.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Classification of vascular anomalies", "question": "Describe the Schobinger classification for arteriovenous malformations (AVMs). What is the treatment approach?", "answer": "Schobinger classification â€” four clinical stages: STAGE I (Quiescence): AVM present but clinically dormant. STAGE II (Expansion): AVM growing, pulsatile. STAGE III (Destruction): AVM causing tissue destruction, pain, bleeding, ulceration. STAGE IV (Decompensation): high-flow AVM causing CONGESTIVE HEART FAILURE (seen in Parkes-Weber syndrome with huge limb AVMs). AVMs are HIGH-FLOW PULSATING lesions with arteriovenous shunts; either acquired (trauma) or congenital. Color Doppler imaging (CDI) useful for detecting blood flow. Treatment: surgical removal is FIRST CHOICE but often hampered by diffuse vessel distribution and local anatomy (e.g., facial nerve). Critical principle: INCOMPLETE RESECTION results in RAPID REGROWTH of remaining lesion. For cases where surgical removal is difficult, embolosclerosing therapy used as palliative therapy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "Describe nevus sebaceous: what is it, where does it occur, and why should it be excised?", "answer": "Nevus sebaceous: a HAMARTOMA (not neoplasm) essentially confined to HEAD AND NECK regions. Found in sebaceous gland but also involves epidermis, dermis, hair follicles, and sweat glands â€” hence also called ORGANOID NEVUS. Resembles an epidermal nevus in appearance. Key clinical concern: other tumors like BCC and TRICHILEMMOMA can ARISE FROM nevus sebaceous over time â€” therefore complete surgical excision is RECOMMENDED. Surgical technique considerations: if located in hair, the HAIR STREAM should be carefully considered during excision and suturing; dehairing caused by unnecessary buried or dermal sutures should be avoided.", "notes": "Closest topic match", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Scar assessment/treatment/revision", "subtopic": "Keloids/hypertrophic scars", "question": "What is the current understanding of the relationship between keloids and hypertrophic scars? What role do mechanical forces play?", "answer": "Keloids and hypertrophic scars (HTS) are caused by HYPERPRODUCTION OF COLLAGEN due to abnormal, prolonged cutaneous wound healing. MECHANICAL FORCES (skin-stretching tension) and MECHANOTRANSDUCTION signaling pathways are associated with their generation and growth. Differential diagnosis remains difficult â€” they may be manifestations of a FIBROPROLIFERATIVE DISORDER of the skin expressing a CONTINUUM of features. Clinical distinction: HTS improve NATURALLY and gradually (full maturation 2-5 years); KELOIDS RARELY resolve naturally. Treatment: MULTIMODAL therapy recommended â€” steroid ointment/tape/injection, taping fixation, silicone gel sheeting, surgery, radiation, cryotherapy, laser, and 5-FU.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "List the main types of malignant soft-tissue sarcomas of the skin and their key distinguishing features.", "answer": "(1) DFSP: t(17;22) COL1A1-PDGF translocation; keloidal appearance; rarely metastasizes; 5 cm margins. (2) PLEOMORPHIC UNDIFFERENTIATED SARCOMA (formerly MFH): four types (storiform-pleomorphic, myxoid, giant cell, inflammatory); atypical fibroxanthoma is superficial type; many reclassified as liposarcoma/leiomyosarcoma/rhabdomyosarcoma. (3) LIPOSARCOMA: from deep soft tissue fat cells; large bulky tumors with satellites; diagnosis requires LIPOBLASTS (multivacuolated cytoplasm, acentric nucleus). (4) LEIOMYOSARCOMA: from smooth muscle; limbs of middle-aged/older patients; can remain dormant and recur after years; not very responsive to chemo/RT. (5) RHABDOMYOSARCOMA: from skeletal muscle progenitors; three types â€” embryonal (younger children), alveolar (older children/teens), pleomorphic (older patients, rare). (6) OSTEOSARCOMA: mesenchymal origin with osteoblastic differentiation; produces malignant osteoid; radical en bloc resection. (7) CHONDROSARCOMA: not responsive to chemo/RT; proton beam RT showing promise.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Describe the axillary lymph node levels and the key structures to preserve during axillary lymph node dissection.", "answer": "Axillary lymph nodes classified by relationship to PECTORALIS MINOR MUSCLE: LEVEL I: lateral to (below lower edge of) pectoralis minor muscle. LEVEL II: deep to (underneath) pectoralis minor muscle. LEVEL III: medial to (above) pectoralis minor muscle. Structures that MUST be preserved during dissection: (1) Pectoral nerves (medial and lateral), (2) LONG THORACIC NERVE (injury â†’ winged scapula), (3) Intercostobrachial nerves (sensory to medial arm), (4) Axillary artery and veins, (5) Thoracoacromial artery and veins, (6) Subscapular artery and veins. Indications for axillary dissection include metastatic SCC and positive sentinel lymph node biopsy. With widespread use of sentinel lymph node biopsy, fewer occasions for preventive dissection.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the histologic subtypes of melanoma? Describe their relative frequency, clinical features, and molecular characteristics.", "answer": "Traditional classification: (1) SUPERFICIAL SPREADING (SSM): 80% of melanomas; significant radial epidermal growth component; occurs in younger patients; frequently has BRAFV600E mutation; fulfills ABCDE criteria (asymmetry, border irregular, color variegated, diameter >6 mm, evolution). (2) NODULAR (NM): 14%; frequently ulcerated and AMELANOTIC (pink, raised papules); mitotically active throughout; grows rapidly with considerable depth relative to diameter; defined as no in situ component extending >3 rete ridges from invasive component. (3) LENTIGO MALIGNA MELANOMA (LMM): 5%; occurs in areas of chronic sun damage (solar elastosis); poorly circumscribed; may be amelanotic; majority have NEITHER BRAF NOR NRAS mutation. (4) ACRAL LENTIGINOUS (ALM): 1% in Europeans but EQUAL INCIDENCE across all skin types; occurs on glabrous skin (palms, soles) and nailbeds; NOT related to UVR (protected by thick stratum corneum); frequent copy number variations, few point mutations (low mutational burden).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the recommended wide local excision margins for primary cutaneous melanoma at different Breslow thicknesses?", "answer": "Based on multiple randomized controlled trials: MELANOMA IN SITU: 5-10 mm margin recommended (5 mm may be inadequate in up to 50% of cases, particularly lentigo maligna subtype; 10 mm recommended where feasible). MELANOMAS â‰¤2 mm Breslow thickness: 1 cm surgical margin. MELANOMAS >2 mm Breslow thickness: 2 cm surgical margin. No data exist that margins WIDER than 2 cm result in superior disease-specific outcomes. Key distinctions: 1 cm margins usually allow PRIMARY CLOSURE under local anesthesia with minimal morbidity; 2 cm margins often require general anesthesia and may need SKIN GRAFT or complex locoregional flap reconstruction. Important: all margins refer to SURGICAL (in vivo) margins, not pathologic margins â€” there is typically ~14% tissue shrinkage after excision and formalin fixation. MELMART-II trial (ongoing) investigating 1 cm vs 2 cm for pT2b-pT4b melanomas.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the AJCC 8th Edition melanoma staging system: T categories, N categories, and M categories.", "answer": "T CATEGORY (Breslow thickness + ulceration): T1: â‰¤1.0 mm (a: <0.8 mm without ulceration; b: <0.8 mm with ulceration or 0.8-1.0 mm). T2: >1.0-2.0 mm. T3: >2.0-4.0 mm. T4: >4.0 mm. Each subdivided into a (without ulceration) and b (with ulceration). N CATEGORY: includes regional nodal disease AND in-transit/satellite/microsatellite disease (all represent intralymphatic metastases). Microsatellites: within 2 cm of primary; satellites: clinically detected within 2 cm; in-transit: beyond 2 cm but proximal to regional nodes. Subcategory 'a' = clinically occult (SLNB-detected); 'b' = clinically detected; 'c' = intralymphatic without nodal disease. M CATEGORY: M1a = distant skin/soft tissue/nonregional nodes; M1b = lung; M1c = non-CNS visceral sites; M1d = CNS metastases (NEW in 8th edition â€” worst prognosis). LDH suffix: (0) normal, (1) elevated. For T2-T4, SLNB required for accurate N staging (clinical exam detects only ~24% of SLNB-positive patients).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) in melanoma? Describe the technique, indications, and key trial evidence.", "answer": "SLNB: technique first described by Donald Morton and Alistair Cochrane's team. Identifies sentinel lymph nodes (first nodes draining the primary site) using DUAL lymphatic mapping: (1) preoperative LYMPHOSCINTIGRAPHY (Tc99m-labeled colloid), (2) intraoperative BLUE DYE. Combined technique identifies sentinel nodes in >99% of patients with ~96% accuracy for nodal basin status. SPECT/CT hybrid imaging provides precise 3D anatomical localization. Indications (NCCN): routinely offered when risk of positive node >10% (generally melanomas >1.0 mm thick); considered when risk 5-10%. Increasing age is a NEGATIVE predictor of SN positivity. KEY TRIALS: MSLT-I: no overall survival difference, but subgroup analysis showed improved MSS in SN-positive intermediate-thickness melanomas (HR 0.56). MSLT-II and DeCOG-SLT: completion lymphadenectomy (CLND) for SN-positive patients increased nodal basin control but did NOT improve MSS â†’ CLND largely abandoned in favor of observation with ultrasound surveillance + adjuvant systemic therapy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the immune checkpoint inhibitors used in melanoma: mechanisms, agents, and key efficacy data.", "answer": "ANTI-CTLA-4: IPILIMUMAB (FDA approved 2011). Mechanism: CTLA-4 and CD28 compete for B7-1/B7-2 ligands on antigen-presenting cells. CTLA-4 provides INHIBITORY signals; CD28 provides STIMULATORY signals. Ipilimumab blocks CTLA-4, suppressing inhibitory signals and enhancing anti-tumor T-cell response. ANTI-PD-1: NIVOLUMAB and PEMBROLIZUMAB (FDA approved 2015). Mechanism: melanoma cells express PD-L1; when PD-1 on cytotoxic T-cells binds PD-L1, T-cell enters ANERGY (tumor-mediated immune suppression). Anti-PD-1 antibodies prevent this binding, enhancing antitumor response. EFFICACY: both nivolumab and pembrolizumab are SUPERIOR to ipilimumab alone for advanced melanoma. Nivolumab + ipilimumab COMBINATION is superior to nivolumab alone. Stage IV: 5-year OS up to 52% with modern ICI therapy. ADJUVANT: pembrolizumab and nivolumab show significant improvement in relapse-free survival for resected stage III melanoma.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is BRAF/MEK targeted therapy in melanoma? Describe the pathway, agents, and when it is indicated.", "answer": "The MAPK pathway (RAS â†’ BRAF â†’ MEK â†’ ERK) is constitutively activated in ~40% of advanced melanomas by BRAFV600E/K driver mutations, leading to unregulated cell growth. BRAF INHIBITORS: vemurafenib, dabrafenib, encorafenib. Single-agent BRAF inhibitor is NOT recommended because resistance inevitably develops via MAPK pathway reactivation. COMBINED BRAF/MEK treatment (e.g., dabrafenib + trametinib) shows increased efficacy with improved response rate, progression-free survival, and overall survival. INDICATIONS: (1) Metastatic/unresectable stage III/IV melanoma with BRAFV600E/K mutation. (2) Adjuvant therapy for resected stage IIIA-C BRAFV600-mutant melanoma. (3) NEOADJUVANT therapy showing promise â€” pathologic complete response in up to 58%. Toxicity: pyrexia/chills, fatigue, diarrhea, hypertension, vomiting â€” generally RESOLVE RAPIDLY after discontinuation (unlike some ICI toxicities which can be permanent).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is desmoplastic melanoma? Describe its clinical features, diagnostic challenges, and management.", "answer": "Desmoplastic melanoma (DM): rare (~1%) subtype usually found in areas of HIGH cumulative sun damage, especially HEAD AND NECK. Clinical features: firm 'SCAR-LIKE' lesions with minimal or no pigmentation â€” often NOT in the differential diagnosis of melanoma. Due to clinical and histological subtlety, DMs typically have HIGHER Breslow thickness at diagnosis than other subtypes. Histology: sparse BLAND SPINDLE CELLS separated by abundant collagen â€” can be misdiagnosed as 'scar' (a 'scar' diagnosis without clear trauma history should raise suspicion). Classification: 'PURE' DM (â‰¥90% desmoplastic component) = lower risk of sentinel node positivity. 'MIXED' DM (10-89%) = higher risk. Neurotropism: most commonly found in DM (perineural, intraneural, or neural transforming); increases likelihood of close/involved margins and local recurrence risk. Management: wide excision; if adequate margins cannot be achieved, adjuvant RADIOTHERAPY may be indicated.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the ABCDE rule and dermoscopy for melanoma diagnosis. What sensitivity/specificity do they provide?", "answer": "ABCDE rule: A = ASYMMETRICAL lesion, B = BORDER irregular, C = COLOR multiple/variegated, D = DIAMETER >6 mm, E = EVOLUTION (history of change). When used by dermatologists: sensitivity 73%, specificity 78%. DERMOSCOPY: 10-16x magnification with polarized light; 'TWO-STEP APPROACH': Step 1 = classify lesion as melanocytic or nonmelanocytic. Step 2 = for melanocytic lesions, assess specific features to determine benign vs malignant. Melanoma features include: atypical network, streaks, negative pigment network, crystalline structures (shiny white lines), atypical dots/globules, off-centered blotches, blue-white veil, regression structures, atypical vascular structures. Dermoscopy increases sensitivity to 90% while maintaining specificity AND reduces benign-to-malignant biopsy rate by up to 64%. REFLECTANCE CONFOCAL MICROSCOPY: 3-5 Î¼m slice thickness, up to 350 Î¼m depth; sensitivity 91-100%, specificity 68-91%; especially useful for amelanotic lesions and delineating lentigo maligna margins.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the risk factors for developing melanoma? Describe the genetic predisposition syndromes.", "answer": "Risk factors: UVR exposure (especially intermittent high doses), fair skin, previous melanoma/NMSC, immunosuppression, family history, high total nevus count, solariums. GENETIC: MC1R high-penetrance variants: biallelic = red hair phenotype + OR 4.4 for melanoma; single allele = no red hair but OR 2.6. Total nevus count (TNC) â‰¥20 nevi >5mm: more significant than MC1R variants; OR 4.8 (even without MC1R variants). INTERACTION IS MULTIPLICATIVE: high TNC + biallelic MC1R = OR 25.1. FAMILIAL MELANOMA (~15% report family history, but most due to shared sun exposure/phenotypes): CDKN2A or CDK4 germline mutations account for ~45% of true familial cases. These genes linked to FAMMM syndrome (familial atypical mole multiple melanoma, formerly 'dysplastic nevus syndrome'). Features: early age of melanoma onset, multiple melanomas, family history, many dysplastic nevi, PANCREATIC CANCER. Development of acquired nevi appears initiated by BRAFV600E gene mutation.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe acral and subungual melanoma: etiology, clinical features, dermoscopic findings, and biopsy considerations.", "answer": "ACRAL MELANOMA (AM): occurs on GLABROUS (non-hair-bearing) skin of palms, soles, and nailbeds. Etiology: NOT related to UVR (thick stratum corneum scatters UV, protecting melanocytes); trauma postulated; equal incidence across ALL SKIN TYPES. Genomic profile: frequent copy number variations, few point mutations (low mutational burden) â€” different from CSD-related melanomas. Clinical features on palmar/plantar skin: follows ABCDE criteria; starts as spreading patch; may not appear raised due to thick stratum corneum; frequently POORLY CIRCUMSCRIBED. Dermoscopy: PARALLEL RIDGE PATTERN is 86% sensitive and 98% specific for early AM. SUBUNGUAL: arises from germinal matrix (must include in biopsy); HUTCHINSON'S SIGN = hyperpigmentation of proximal nailfold. Concerning features: streak wider at base than distally (rapid growth), blurred edges, sudden darkening/widening, nail dystrophy, single digit in 4th-6th decade. Biopsy: punch/incisional may be necessary for large lesions to avoid morbidity.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are Clark's levels? Are they still used for staging?", "answer": "Clark's levels describe the anatomical depth of melanoma invasion: LEVEL I: confined to epidermis (melanoma in situ). LEVEL II: into the papillary dermis but does NOT fill or expand this layer. LEVEL III: FILLS or EXPANDS the papillary dermis and reaches the junction with the reticular dermis. LEVEL IV: into the RETICULAR dermis. LEVEL V: into SUBCUTANEOUS tissue. Clark's level was REMOVED from the AJCC staging system in the 7th Edition (2009) after it was found to have the LOWEST independent prognostic significance on multivariable analysis for survival that included tumor mitotic rate. Breslow thickness (measured from granular layer of epidermis to deepest tumor in mm, perpendicular to skin surface) is the primary measurement used for T staging. Reported to nearest 0.1 mm in AJCC 8th Edition.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the important histopathological features reported in melanoma beyond Breslow thickness and ulceration?", "answer": "NEUROTROPISM: melanoma cells abutting nerve sheaths at tumor periphery; three forms: perineural, intraneural, neural transformation. Most common in desmoplastic melanoma. Increases likelihood of close/involved margins â†’ increased local recurrence risk. May warrant adjuvant radiotherapy if greater margins not feasible. LYMPHOVASCULAR INVASION (LVI): melanoma cells within lymphatic or blood vessel lumina; generally a POOR prognostic factor; detection enhanced by staining with endothelial markers (CD31, CD34) and lymphatic markers (D2-40, LYVE-1). TUMOR INFILTRATING LYMPHOCYTES (TILs): lymphocytes opposing or infiltrating tumor cell nests; graded as absent, non-brisk (focal), or brisk (diffuse/entire base). Brisk TIL infiltrate is a GOOD prognostic factor. MICROSATELLITOSIS: tumor deposits in cutaneous/subcutaneous tissue within 2 cm of primary, truly separate from main mass (not just fibrosis/inflammation); rare (5-10% in intermediate thickness); classified as N1c in AJCC staging.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the biopsy recommendations for suspected melanocytic lesions? Why are incomplete biopsies problematic?", "answer": "RECOMMENDED: EXCISION BIOPSY with 2 mm margin â€” offers best opportunity for correct pathologic diagnosis. INCOMPLETE BIOPSIES (punch, incision, curette, shave) are problematic because: (1) May contribute to significant pathologic MISDIAGNOSIS rate (both false-positives and false-negatives). (2) Unrepresentative sampling of HETEROGENEOUS tumor risks incorrect diagnosis. (3) Insufficient tissue for adequate assessment of pathologic criteria. (4) Shave biopsy TRANSECTING the base precludes accurate BRESLOW THICKNESS measurement â€” patient may not be offered appropriate SLNB. Rate of incomplete excision with shave biopsies: up to 97%. EXCEPTIONS: incisional biopsy acceptable when excision not feasible (e.g., large facial lentigo maligna â€” broad superficial shave appropriate when dermal invasion suspicion is low). KEY: false-negative rate significantly reduced by writing the SUSPECTED DIAGNOSIS on the pathology request form. All melanocytic tumors should be assessed by an expert DERMATOPATHOLOGIST.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is lentigo maligna? How does it differ from lentigo maligna melanoma? What is its risk of progression?", "answer": "LENTIGO MALIGNA (LM): melanoma IN SITU occurring in the presence of significant chronic sun damage to the skin; historically called 'Hutchinson's melanotic freckle'. An IN SITU lesion (abnormal melanocytes confined to epidermis). Risk of progression to INVASIVE melanoma (LMM) estimated up to 3.5% PER YEAR, resulting in mean time to progression of 28 years. LENTIGO MALIGNA MELANOMA (LMM): progression of LM to dermal INVASION â€” a different entity than LM. LMM lesions are often POORLY CIRCUMSCRIBED both clinically and histologically; may be amelanotic or slightly pigmented; can extend well beyond visible lesion. Typically on chronically sun-exposed sites (face, forearms). Majority have NEITHER BRAF NOR NRAS mutations. Clinical significance of MIS in general: (1) signifies 5-10-fold elevated risk of developing FURTHER primary melanomas (lifelong surveillance needed), (2) without complete excision, INVASIVE component cannot be completely excluded.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the congenital melanocytic nevus (CMN): classification, melanoma risk, and management.", "answer": "Classification by projected adult size: SMALL (<1.5 cm), MEDIUM (1.5-20 cm), GIANT (>20 cm). Prevalence: ~1% of population (vast majority small); giant = ~1/20,000 live births. Appearance: irregular pigmentation with hyperpigmented papules, sometimes hair; often deep and larger than acquired nevi. MELANOMA RISK: small CMN = very low; giant CMN = ~2% overall; highest risk (8%) in giant CMNs >60 cm projected adult size or multiple CMNs without single large lesion; highest risk (12%) if also abnormal brain MRI screening in first year of life. KEY POINTS: (1) Surgical excision of giant CMN does NOT completely remove melanoma risk â€” melanoma can develop at OTHER sites including LEPTOMENINGEAL. (2) Superficial removal techniques (e.g., dermabrasion) have NO EFFECT on final color of lesion â€” final color determined by normal skin color in process of spontaneous lightening. Management: giant nevi removed by serial excision, skin grafting, local flaps, or combination.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is the WHO 2018 classification of melanoma? How does it differ from the traditional classification?", "answer": "WHO 2018 classification defines 9 subtypes by their DISTINCT EVOLUTIONARY PATHWAYS, grouped into three categories: GROUP A (associated with cumulative solar damage/CSD): Pathway I: SSM (low CSD); Pathway II: LMM (high CSD); Pathway III: Desmoplastic melanoma (high CSD). GROUP B (NOT associated with CSD): Pathway IV: Spitz melanomas; Pathway V: Acral melanomas; Pathway VI: Mucosal melanomas; Pathway VII: Melanomas arising in congenital nevi; Pathway VIII: Melanomas arising in blue nevi; Pathway IX: Uveal melanomas. GROUP C (can occur in most pathways): Nodular melanoma (NM) Â± CSD association. Key difference from traditional classification: organized by EVOLUTIONARY PATHWAY rather than morphology alone, recognizing that different subtypes have distinct molecular drivers (BRAF mutations in SSM, copy number variations in ALM, neither BRAF nor NRAS in LMM).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the route of melanoma metastasis, the definitions of satellites, microsatellites, and in-transit metastases.", "answer": "Melanoma metastasizes through LYMPHATIC channels in ~90% of cases; direct hematogenous dissemination is less common. All intralymphatic metastases portend similarly poor prognosis and are included in the N category (AJCC 8th Edition). MICROSATELLITES: tumor deposits in cutaneous/subcutaneous tissue in the initial excision biopsy or wide local excision specimen, discrete from the main primary mass, within the pathologic specimen (effectively within 2 cm). Must be TRULY separate (not just fibrosis/inflammation between them). Rates: 5-10% in intermediate-thickness melanoma. SATELLITES: clinically detected tumor deposits within 2 cm of primary. IN-TRANSIT METASTASES: tumor deposits beyond 2 cm from primary but PROXIMAL to regional lymph nodes. N staging: N1c = intralymphatic deposits WITHOUT nodal disease; N2c = intralymphatic + single positive node; N3c = intralymphatic + multiple positive nodes. Important: deposits in DEEP structures (e.g., muscle) = stage IV, not stage III.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the immune-related adverse events (irAEs) of checkpoint inhibitor immunotherapy? How do they differ from BRAF/MEK inhibitor toxicities?", "answer": "ICI irAEs: inflammatory AUTOIMMUNE toxicities in nearly any organ system. Premature treatment termination: <10% monotherapy, >30% combination therapy. Common irAEs: interstitial pneumonia, COLITIS, hypothyroidism, liver dysfunction, skin rash, vitiligo, hypophysitis, type 1 diabetes, renal dysfunction, myasthenia gravis, neuropathy, myositis, uveitis. Most irAEs are LOW-GRADE and respond rapidly to STEROIDS and immunosuppressants. EXCEPTION: most ENDOCRINOPATHIES are PERMANENT (hypopituitarism, hypothyroidism, hypoadrenalism, type I diabetes). No identified predictive factors â†’ rely on EARLY DETECTION and rapid intervention. BRAF/MEK TOXICITY (markedly different): pyrexia/chills, fatigue, diarrhea, hypertension, vomiting. Key distinction: toxicities generally RESOLVE RAPIDLY after discontinuation of treatment (unlike permanent endocrinopathies from ICI).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the Sappey's lines and how has lymphoscintigraphy changed our understanding of lymphatic drainage patterns?", "answer": "SAPPEY'S LINES: lymphatic drainage patterns mapped by Sappey in 1874 using mercury injection into skin. General principles: lesions >2 cm ABOVE a 'belt line' (drawn through umbilicus) drain to AXILLARY nodes; >2 cm BELOW drain to INGUINAL nodes. Lesions >2 cm lateral to midline drain IPSILATERALLY. Lesions within the central 4 cm vertical and horizontal bands could drain to EITHER or BOTH sides and either or both axillary/inguinal nodes. MODERN LYMPHOSCINTIGRAPHY: has demonstrated many VARIATIONS in lymphatic drainage â€” very few body sites have reliably predictable drainage. This is why preoperative lymphoscintigraphy is essential for SLNB rather than relying on Sappey's lines alone. Techniques: Tc99m with various tracers (antimony sulfide colloid, nanocolloid, tilmanocept preferred over sulfur colloid); SPECT/CT hybrid imaging provides precise 3D anatomical localization of sentinel nodes, especially helpful in HEAD/NECK and PELVIS.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the role and indications for adjuvant radiotherapy in melanoma.", "answer": "Adjuvant radiotherapy post-lymphadenectomy improves NODAL BASIN CONTROL in high-risk disease but confers NO OVERALL SURVIVAL benefit. Indications for consideration: (1) Multinodal disease â€” any parotid disease, â‰¥2 nodes in neck/axilla, â‰¥3 nodes in groin. (2) EXTRANODAL SPREAD. (3) Large involved node (â‰¥3 cm neck, â‰¥4 cm axilla/groin). (4) POSITIVE MARGIN. (5) Recurrent disease after previous surgery. (6) Desmoplastic melanoma with neurotropism where adequate surgical margins cannot be achieved. Limitations: lack of survival benefit must be balanced against morbidity of salvage lymphadenectomy, especially in the era of MORE EFFECTIVE SYSTEMIC THERAPY. Still has a role when ICI immunotherapy is unlikely to be tolerated or CONTRAINDICATED (e.g., autoimmune disease, solid organ transplantation). Note: melanoma is considered relatively RADIORESISTANT (broad shoulder on cell survival curve); overcome by HYPOFRACTIONATION (e.g., 6 Gy twice/week).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the current approach to neoadjuvant therapy in stage III melanoma. What are the key trial results?", "answer": "Emerging data suggest NEOADJUVANT (before surgery) therapy may have increased therapeutic efficacy OVER adjuvant (after surgery) therapy for clinically evident regional metastasis. Key regimens and results: (1) DABRAFENIB + TRAMETINIB neoadjuvant: pathologic complete response (pCR) in 49-58%; neoadjuvant arm showed dramatically better disease-free outcomes vs adjuvant-only arm. (2) NIVOLUMAB + IPILIMUMAB neoadjuvant: pCR rates 45-57%; 2-cycle regimen showing pathologic response in up to 80%. (3) PEMBROLIZUMAB neoadjuvant: pCR/major pathologic response in 29.6%; 63% DFS and 93% OS at 2 years. Clinical implications: (1) In patients with neoadjuvant therapy showing radiologic response, more SELECTIVE surgery with nerve/vessel preservation may be oncologically sound. (2) Final pathology after neoadjuvant often shows pigmented macrophages WITHOUT viable melanoma. (3) Duration of adjuvant treatment (anti-PD1 or dabrafenib/trametinib) arbitrarily set at 1 year â€” optimal duration still unclear.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Define 'biomaterial' per the NIH definition, and describe how the definition has broadened with tissue engineering.", "answer": "NIH definition: any substance (other than a drug) or combination of substances, synthetic or natural in origin, which can be used for any period of time, as a whole or part of a system which treats, augments, or replaces tissue, organ, or function of the body. Broadened definition: any material used in a medical device intended to interact with biological systems â€” this includes structures and combination devices that actively interact with the body. Biomaterials can be classified as SYNTHETIC (man-made) or BIOLOGICAL (produced by a biological system). General categories: metals, polymers, ceramics, glues, skin substitutes, and bioprosthetics.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "List the properties of an ideal implant as described by Cumberland and Scales.", "answer": "(1) Minimal foreign-body response, (2) Elastic or supple, (3) Can be tailored easily, (4) Good tissue incorporation, (5) Allows collagen ingrowth, (6) Promotes permanent tissue repair, (7) Good tensile strength, (8) Tolerates infected environment, (9) Minimal wound complications. These criteria were published ~60 years ago but remain the fundamental properties that all modern biomaterials attempt to achieve.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare stainless steel, cobalt-chromium, and titanium alloys for medical implant use: composition, advantages, disadvantages, and current applications.", "answer": "STAINLESS STEEL (316L): iron-chromium-nickel alloy with >=17% chromium, low carbon, high nickel. Advantages: high tensile strength, easily bent (useful for arch bars). Disadvantages: can leach metallic ions causing inflammatory reaction/pain, less desirable mechanical properties than alternatives. Current use: surgical wire, arch bars. COBALT-CHROMIUM (CoCrMo/Vitallium): ~60% cobalt, 25-30% chromium, 5-7% molybdenum. Advantages: corrosion resistant, strong. Disadvantage: significant CT scatter artifact. Largely replaced by titanium; still used in dental applications. TITANIUM: strongest, lightest, highest corrosion resistance, lowest inflammation. <0.5% iron â€” does NOT trigger metal detectors, minimal CT/MRI artifact. Less stress shielding (less stiffness = less localized osteopenia). Unique property: forms chemical bonds with mineralized bone (OSSEOINTEGRATION) without intervening fibrous tissue. Used for plates, screws, orbital mesh.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What is stress shielding, and why is titanium advantageous in this regard?", "answer": "Stress shielding: localized osteopenia secondary to a metal implant protecting bone from normal physiological loading. When an implant is stiffer than bone, it bears a disproportionate share of mechanical loads, causing the bone underneath to resorb due to lack of stimulus (Wolff's law). Titanium has LESS stiffness than other metal alloys (stainless steel, cobalt-chromium), resulting in less stress shielding and better preservation of underlying bone density.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What are the medical applications of gold and platinum in plastic surgery? What determines the choice between them for eyelid weights?", "answer": "GOLD: chemically inert but poor mechanical properties in pure form. For eyelid weights in lagophthalmos (e.g., facial nerve palsy): 24-carat gold (99.9% purity) is used to ensure chemical inertness. PLATINUM: also inert, used in patients with GOLD SENSITIVITY. Key advantage: platinum is DENSER than gold, so eyelid implants have a LOWER PROFILE and are less noticeable. Platinum is also used as a catalyst (platinum black) in silicone gel breast implant manufacturing. Cisplatin (platinum complex) is a chemotherapeutic agent with side effects including cumulative irreversible kidney damage and deafness.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Differentiate the silicone nomenclature: silicon, silica, silicate, siloxane, silicone, and poly-dimethylsiloxane (PDMS).", "answer": "SILICON (Si): most abundant element on earth; does not occur naturally in metallic state. SILICA (SiO2): sand, marble, or quartz. SILICATE (Na2SiO3): used as desiccant (e.g., in anesthesia machines). SILOXANE (R2SiO): monomer of silicon and oxygen â€” the basic repeating unit of silicone. SILICONE (|R2SiO|n): polymers of silicon and oxygen. POLY-DIMETHYLSILOXANE/PDMS (|(CH3)2SiO|n): the building block for most medical-grade silicone products including breast implants; silicon-oxygen backbone with two methyl side chains; one of the most inert biomaterials available.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "How do the mechanical properties of silicone change with molecular weight and cross-linking? Describe the hydrosilation reaction in breast implant manufacturing.", "answer": "Molecular weight effects: PDMS with <30 monomers = low-molecular-weight, viscosity similar to baby oil. >3000 monomers = high-molecular-weight, solid. Cross-linking: as polymer chains are cross-linked, ability to move independently decreases â€” liquid becomes gel becomes solid. HYDROSILATION REACTION: some methyl side chains (CH3) are replaced by VINYL side chains (CH=CH2), allowing silicone chains to cross-link with each other. This reaction is catalyzed by PLATINUM â€” residual platinum can be found in silicone gel breast implants. The silicone SHELL is fully polymerized silicone with amorphous (noncrystalline) silica filler added for strength. Cohesive gel implants: extensively cross-linked silicone that retains shape even if implant ruptures.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the FDA regulatory timeline for silicone gel breast implants: key dates, decisions, and the IOM findings.", "answer": "1962: silicone gel-filled breast implants first introduced in US. 1988: FDA relabeled as class III medical devices, called for safety/effectiveness data. 1992: FDA claimed 'inadequate information to demonstrate safety and efficacy'; placed MORATORIUM on silicone gel implants for cosmetic use (still allowed for reconstruction, congenital deformities, replacement of ruptured implants). 1999: IOM released comprehensive report 'Safety of Silicone Breast Implants' â€” found 'diseases such as connective tissue diseases, cancer, neurological diseases are NO MORE COMMON in women with implants than without.' 2006: FDA lifted ban; required 10-year study on current recipients PLUS additional 10-year study in 40,000 women; mandated patient brochures explaining risks. Key: over 35 well-conducted studies from many countries found no conclusive evidence silicone causes disease.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the ISO classification of breast implant surface texturing. What manufacturing processes create textured surfaces?", "answer": "ISO 14607:2018 classification by average roughness: SMOOTH (<10 Âµm), MICROTEXTURED (10-50 Âµm), MACROTEXTURED (>50 Âµm). Manufacturing processes: (1) SALT-LOSS: salt crystals applied onto silicone shell before curing, removed by rinsing afterward; creates coarse, granular texture (e.g., Allergan BIOCELL surface). (2) IMPRINT-STAMPING: generates finer, more homogenous surface texture (e.g., Mentor Siltex surface). Purported benefits: tissue ingrowth, improved adherence, reduced rotation, and decreased capsular contracture. Recent evidence challenges these: long-term studies show minimal difference in contracture rates between textured and smooth. Macrotextured devices (roughness >80 Âµm) linked to highest foreign body response and inflammation. Use of textured implants has dropped precipitously in the US.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the relationship between textured breast implants and BIA-ALCL: epidemiology, hypothesized mechanisms, and FDA actions.", "answer": "BIA-ALCL: CD30-positive, ALK-negative T-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. First sentinel case reported 1997. Only observed in patients with TEXTURED surface implants. Over 1,150 women worldwide diagnosed. FDA 2011: safety communication about 'very small but increased risk.' July 2019: FDA ordered CLASS I VOLUNTARY RECALL of all Allergan textured devices. Risk is HIGHER in macrotextured devices. Hypothesized mechanisms: (1) increased biofilm development, (2) shell shedding of particulates causing perpetual exhaustive phagocytosis and cytokine release by macrophages, (3) increased mechanical shear/friction stresses at implant-tissue interface causing overt inflammatory response. Macrotextured devices linked to chronic inflammation; animal studies confirm highest severity foreign body response with roughness >80 Âµm. Causal link not yet definitively established.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare PTFE (Teflon) and expanded PTFE (ePTFE/Gore-Tex): structure, properties, and medical applications. What are the limitations of ePTFE mesh?", "answer": "PTFE: carbon backbone with fluorine side chains; chemically very stable, cannot be cross-linked (making it flexible), nonadherent surface. ePTFE (Gore-Tex): created by Bob Gore (1969) by rapidly stretching heated PTFE rods â€” transforms solid PTFE into microporous structure that is more lightweight and pliable. Medical applications: vascular grafts, mesh for abdominal wall reconstruction, facial augmentation implants. ePTFE mesh limitations for hernia repair: (1) infection often requires EXPLANTATION (cannot be salvaged), (2) limited incorporation strength to surrounding fascial edge compared to macroporous meshes (polypropylene), (3) pore size 10-30 Âµm limits tissue ingrowth â€” this same property reduces repair site adhesions (advantage for visceral-facing surface).", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare polypropylene and polyethylene (Medpor) as biomaterials: structure, applications, advantages, and complications.", "answer": "POLYPROPYLENE: carbon backbone with hydrogen and methyl side chains. Applications: hernia repair mesh, sutures, pelvic organ prolapse repair. Advantages: rarely rejected, high ultimate tensile strength, strong fibrovascular incorporation. Complications: can erode through soft tissues over time; FDA warnings for pelvic organ prolapse mesh near vaginal wall due to erosion. Direct placement over viscera causes dense adhesions, fistula, and erosion. Reoperation challenging due to fibrotic scarring to intraperitoneal viscera. HIGH-DENSITY POROUS POLYETHYLENE (Medpor): carbon backbone with hydrogen side chains (ethylene). Applications: facial implants, orbital floor reconstruction (alone or with embedded titanium mesh). Advantages: porosity allows tissue and vascular ingrowth, can be carved/customized. Disadvantages: firm/stiff, difficult to place (tissue adheres readily), difficult to remove (due to ingrowth), poor CT visibility when used alone.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Describe the biodegradable polymers used in plastic surgery: chemistry, degradation mechanism, and clinical applications.", "answer": "Most are Î±-HYDROXY ACIDS: poly(lactic acid) (PLA), poly(glycolic acid) (PGA), and copolymer poly(lactic-co-glycolic acid) (PLGA). Degradation: HYDROLYSIS producing lactic or glycolic acid â€” common byproducts of normal human biochemical pathways. All breakdown products must be biocompatible. Key principle: increasing PLA concentration DECREASES degradation rate. Familiar example: Vicryl (polyglactin 910) = PGA/PLA copolymer suture. Applications: biodegradable meshes for abdominal wall reconstruction (Vicryl mesh for temporary abdominofascial closure in contaminated wounds â€” creates iatrogenic hernia for delayed repair), biodegradable plates/screws for craniofacial and hand applications. Examples: LactoSorb (82% PLA, 18% PGA), Resorb X (100% PDLLA). At implantation: strength equal to titanium plating; parameters tuned to preserve structural integrity for first 8 weeks for bony healing.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What are the properties of ceramics as biomaterials? Compare hydroxyapatite and tricalcium phosphate.", "answer": "Ceramics: crystalline structure of inorganic, nonmetallic molecules with HETEROPOLAR bonding (electrons bound to individual atoms, unlike metals' homopolar bonding with free-flowing electrons). Manufactured by SINTERING (fusion under high pressure and temperature). Advantages: decreased foreign body response, resist bacterial colonization, high compressive strength, tissue ingrowth into porous materials (100 Âµm pore size for bone, 30 Âµm for soft tissue). Disadvantage: BRITTLE â€” fracture easily under tensile, torsional, or bending loads. Main use: non-load-bearing bone augmentation/replacement (face and cranium). CALCIUM PHOSPHATES â€” most common ceramics in plastic surgery. Hydroxyapatite (Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2): slower resorption, available as cement paste (can be molded intraoperatively for cranioplasty). Tricalcium phosphate (Ca3(PO4)2): FASTER resorption and replacement by bone. Both: granules for injection or solid/porous blocks; laboratory evidence of osteoinduction and osteoconduction (not yet demonstrated clinically).", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare the three tissue adhesives used in plastic surgery: fibrin sealant, platelet gels (PRP), and cyanoacrylate â€” mechanisms, preparation, and applications.", "answer": "FIBRIN SEALANT: two components â€” fibrinogen + thrombin (from pooled human plasma) combined with factor XIII, calcium, antifibrinolytic, and bovine aprotinin. Requires refrigeration, 20 min prep, warming. Adhesive strength proportional to FIBRINOGEN concentration; polymerization rate controlled by THROMBIN concentration (lower thrombin when tissues need manipulation). Mist applicators produce thinnest/strongest layer. Applications: skin graft adherence, seroma treatment. PLATELET GELS (PRP): from 70 mL whole blood, centrifuged; platelet layer combined with bovine thrombin. Less expensive but LOWER fibrinogen concentration = weaker adhesive/hemostatic properties. Applications: brow lift, facelift, abdominoplasty, DIEP/TRAM donor sites. CYANOACRYLATE: polymerizes on exposure to MOISTURE. Butyl-cyanoacrylate (first gen): short chain, rapid breakdown, wound dehiscence, toxic breakdown products (formaldehyde, cyanoacetate). Octyl-cyanoacrylate: longer side chains, stronger, longer-lasting. Application: skin closure only (deep layers must be tension-free).", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "Describe the composition and mechanism of Integra: layers, indications, and the two-stage application process.", "answer": "Integra: BILAYER skin substitute. Lower 'dermal' layer: BOVINE COLLAGEN base with glycosaminoglycan CHONDROITIN-6-SULFATE. Upper layer: SILICONE sheet acting as temporary epidermis. Mechanism: as wound heals, dermal layer is replaced with patient's own cells (neodermis); neodermis attaches to underlying bed and VASCULARIZES over 10-14 days. TWO-STAGE process: Stage 1 â€” apply Integra to wound. Stage 2 â€” after vascularization (10-14 days), remove silicone layer and apply thin split-thickness skin graft onto neodermis. Indications: partial- or full-thickness burns, complex wounds, multiple types of ulcers, wounds where skin graft is nonadherent to the wound bed. Compared to Biobrane: higher wound infection rate but better wound-healing time than autograft, allograft, or xenograft.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "Compare Epicel, Dermagraft, and Apligraf: cell source, composition, indications, and key features.", "answer": "EPICEL (cultured epidermal autograft): patient's OWN keratinocytes grown on proliferation-arrested 3T3 MURINE FIBROBLAST feeder cells until 2-8 cell layers thick; attached to petrolatum gauze with stainless steel clips (~50 cm2). Indication: deep dermal or full-thickness burns >=30% TBSA. DERMAGRAFT: POLYGLACTIN (Vicryl) mesh seeded with NEONATAL FIBROBLASTS that produce collagen, GAGs, fibronectin, growth factors; mesh resorbs and is replaced by patient's tissue. Indications: chronic wounds, burn excision sites with STSG. Equivalent to allograft for infection, healing time, graft take. APLIGRAF (bilayered skin-equivalent): lower 'dermal' layer = type I bovine collagen + neonatal foreskin FIBROBLASTS; upper 'epidermal' layer = neonatal KERATINOCYTES. Must be applied FRESH â€” shelf life only 5 DAYS at room temperature. Indications: venous ulcers, diabetic foot ulcers, temporary covering over meshed expanded autograft for burns.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "What are the characteristics of an ideal skin substitute?", "answer": "Five characteristics: (1) Adhere to the wound bed RAPIDLY, (2) Recapitulate the physiologic and mechanical properties of normal skin, (3) Be INEXPENSIVE, (4) Avoid immune rejection by the host, (5) Be highly effective in accelerating tissue regeneration and wound repair. Engineering of cultured skin substitutes requires three components: (1) a CELL source, (2) a 'tissue differentiation-inducing' SUBSTANCE, and (3) a MATRIX. A variety of cells, mediators, and polymers have been tested in various combinations. The ideal skin substitute does not yet exist.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare human acellular dermal matrix (HADM/AlloDerm) and porcine acellular dermal matrix (PADM): processing, applications, and the key difference between cross-linked and non-cross-linked PADM.", "answer": "HADM (AlloDerm, Allomax, FlexHD): from donated allograft human dermis. Processing: epidermis and subcutaneous tissue removed, dermis processed with freeze-drying or chemical detergents to produce collagen structure of dermal matrix. Applications: implant-based breast reconstruction, abdominal wall, chest wall, pelvis reconstruction, lip augmentation. Micronized form (Cymetra) for laryngoplasty/soft tissue filler. PADM: more abundant, easier to harvest, but xenogeneic source requires additional processing. CROSS-LINKED PADM (CollaMend, Permacol): chemical cross-linking of collagen reduces immunogenicity and collagenase degradation, BUT alters ECM structure, inhibiting cellular infiltration, revascularization, and matrix remodeling â€” implant becomes ENCAPSULATED. NON-CROSS-LINKED PADM (Strattice): galactose-Î±(1,3)-galactose antigen (major cause of immune response) enzymatically removed; rapidly infiltrated with host cells and vessels, weaker adhesions, increased mechanical strength at early timepoints. Non-cross-linked may have early clinical advantages.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What is small intestinal submucosa (SIS)? Describe its source, processing, and applications.", "answer": "SIS (Biodesign/Surgisis, Cook Biotech): biomaterial from PIG SMALL INTESTINE. Processing: mucosal, serosal, and muscular layers removed, leaving the strong collagenous SUBMUCOSAL matrix (the layer providing mechanical strength to the intestine). The submucosa is biochemically rich and diverse in extracellular matrix components. First described as a vascular graft in 1989. Applications in humans: multiple types of hernia repair, dural repair, bladder reconstruction, stress urinary incontinence treatment (>20 applications total). Originally released as Surgisis (1989), renamed Biodesign (2008) reflecting significant improvements. Key advantages: naturally derived, infection-resistant, strong yet biocompatible extracellular matrix scaffold that allows tissue remodeling.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "Describe the use of amniotic membrane as a biomaterial: structure, properties, and clinical applications.", "answer": "Amnion: used as a biomaterial for over 100 years (first published use as skin graft 1910, first use in burns 1912). Structure: MONOLAYER of epithelial cells, THICK BASEMENT MEMBRANE, and AVASCULAR matrix. The epithelium manufactures multiple cytokines and growth factors. Properties: promotes epithelialization, antimicrobial, immunomodulatory, and analgesic â€” many properties preserved even after de-epithelialization and sterilization. Products: dehydrated/decellularized amniotic membrane (BioFix, AmnioFix) for wound coverage; products with chorion included (BioFix Plus, EpiFix); injectable placental connective tissue matrix (BioFix Flow); cryopreserved placental membrane containing native cells including epithelial cells, fibroblasts, and stem cells (Grafix â€” must be thawed before use). Dehydrated products: room temperature storage, 5-year shelf-life, no preparation needed, can be placed either side up.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Describe the foreign body response to biomedical implants: cellular sequence, consequences, and why it is the fundamental limitation of implant longevity.", "answer": "The foreign body response is a chronic inflammatory reaction at the biomaterial-tissue interface. Cellular sequence: (1) NEUTROPHILS and MACROPHAGES recruited to interface, (2) inflammatory cells recruit collagen-producing FIBROBLASTS, (3) excessive fibroblast proliferation causes ENCAPSULATION of foreign body by collagen-rich matrix. Consequences: reduced biomaterial-tissue integration, loss of implant function, contracture, and pain. Examples: breast implants â€” capsule initially positions implant, but excessive fibrosis leads to capsular contracture; continuous glucose monitors â€” foreign body response develops in 30-90 days leading to impaired sensor functionality and unreliable readings. This is the FUNDAMENTAL LIMITATION in improving implant function and longevity. Nearly ALL known implanted materials elicit a host response in vivo. Current mitigation strategies: anti-inflammatory/antifibrotic drugs (local and systemic), chemical modification of biomaterial surfaces, study of mechanical signaling effects on fibrotic response.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What are hybrid biosynthetic meshes? Name three commercially available products and their compositions.", "answer": "Hybrid biosynthetic meshes combine BIOLOGIC substrates with PERMANENT SYNTHETIC materials, aiming to provide: increased durability/support, mitigation of host response, and promotion of tissue ingrowth â€” addressing limitations of both purely synthetic and purely biologic meshes. Three commercially available products: (1) SYNECOR (Gore): polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) fibers combined with bioabsorbable copolymer scaffold of polyglycolic acid (PGA) and trimethylene carbonate (TMC). (2) ZENAPRO (Cook): polypropylene mesh sandwiched between layers of porcine small intestinal submucosa (SIS). (3) OVITEX (TELA Bio): ovine rumen reinforced with interwoven polypropylene. Preclinical evidence: reinforced biologic scaffolds support cellular adhesion, display biomimetic properties, and maintain native architecture over prolonged period. These are used primarily in abdominal wall reconstruction.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What pore sizes are optimal for tissue ingrowth into porous biomaterials? How does this differ between bone and soft tissue?", "answer": "Optimal pore sizes for tissue ingrowth: BONE requires approximately 100 Âµm pore size; SOFT TISSUE requires approximately 30 Âµm pore size. These specifications guide ceramic implant design and other porous biomaterials. For example, porous polyethylene (Medpor) implants allow tissue and vascular ingrowth through their porosity â€” this provides stability but makes removal difficult. Conversely, ePTFE mesh modulates pore size to 10-30 Âµm to LIMIT tissue ingrowth (desired for visceral-facing surfaces to reduce adhesions in hernia repair). The relationship between pore size and ingrowth is a fundamental design parameter: too small prevents integration, too large compromises structural integrity.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Define autologous, allogeneic, and xenogeneic transplantation. Give a clinical example of each in plastic surgery.", "answer": "AUTOLOGOUS: reconstruction using the patient's own tissue; no immune reaction. Example: DIEP flap breast reconstruction, skin grafts. ALLOGENEIC: transplantation between unrelated individuals of the SAME species; requires lifelong immunosuppression due to rejection risk. Example: face transplantation, hand transplantation, cadaver skin for burns. XENOGENEIC: from a DIFFERENT species; highest risk of acute rejection. Example: porcine heart valves, temporary coverage of burn wounds with pig skin. In plastic surgery terminology: 'flap' implies defined blood flow, 'graft' does not. In transplant terminology, 'graft/allograft' is used even for vascularized transplants (organs, VCA). Key historical milestone: Joseph E. Murray (plastic surgeon, Nobel Prize) performed first successful kidney transplant between identical twins in 1954.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What is vascularized composite allotransplantation (VCA)? List the nine UNOS/OPTN definition criteria for a VCA.", "answer": "VCA: transplantation of whole anatomical units (hands/arms, face) composed of multiple tissue types (skin, muscle, tendons, bone, vessels, lymphatics, nerves). VCA is LIFE-ENHANCING (not life-saving), making risk-benefit analysis critical. Nine UNOS criteria: (1) Must be VASCULARIZED requiring surgical connection of blood vessels, (2) must contain MULTIPLE tissue types, (3) must be recovered from a human donor as an ANATOMICAL UNIT, (4) must be transplanted as an anatomical unit, (5) cannot be PROCESSED, (6) must be used for LIKE-WITH-LIKE replacement, (7) cannot be combined with a device, (8) is susceptible to ISCHEMIA and cannot be cryopreserved, (9) is susceptible to REJECTION requiring immunosuppression. To date: >90 upper extremity transplants and >44 face transplants performed worldwide. VCA came under UNOS/OPTN oversight in 2014; defined as human ORGANS (not tissue).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the role of MHC class I and class II antigens in transplant immunology. What other antigen system is critical?", "answer": "MHC (Major Histocompatibility Complex): glycoprotein family encoded on CHROMOSOME 6 (224 genes, 3.6 megabase pairs) determining recipient-donor compatibility. Function: epitope for antigen binding and presentation â€” immune cells bind, recognize, and stimulate immune response. MHC CLASS I: expressed on nearly ALL NUCLEATED CELLS and platelets; presents antigens to CD8+ cytotoxic T lymphocytes. MHC CLASS II: expressed only on ANTIGEN-PRESENTING CELLS (macrophages, B lymphocytes, dendritic cells); presents antigens to CD4+ T-helper lymphocytes. ABO SURFACE ANTIGENS: also critical; expressed on blood cells AND vascular endothelial cells. Patients develop antibodies against ABO antigens they don't express. ABO mismatch can cause RAPID graft rejection. Crossmatching: donor lymphocytes incubated with recipient serum to exclude preformed donor-specific antibodies (prevents hyperacute rejection).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the three types of antigen-presenting cells (APCs) and their roles in transplant rejection.", "answer": "APCs present foreign antigens complexed with MHC molecules to T lymphocytes, driving adaptive immunity. (1) MACROPHAGES: circulate in blood or reside stationary in tissues (e.g., LANGERHANS CELLS in skin). Phagocytize antigens, break them down, present fragments on surface. Activate T lymphocytes through antigen presentation and cytokine secretion. (2) DENDRITIC CELLS: reside in interstitial space; necessary for activation of NAIVE T cells (critical first step). When activated, migrate to lymph nodes where they activate T lymphocytes. (3) B LYMPHOCYTES: internalize foreign antigens and present them to T-helper lymphocytes. Upon activation, T-helpers stimulate B lymphocyte differentiation into PLASMA CELLS that produce immunoglobulins. Five immunoglobulin classes: IgG, IgM, IgE, IgA, IgD. Immunoglobulins act by opsonization (marking for phagocytosis) and stimulating the COMPLEMENT pathway (membrane attack complex).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe T lymphocyte subtypes and their roles in transplant rejection.", "answer": "T lymphocytes originate from the THYMUS; each expresses a unique T cell receptor (TCR) for specific pattern recognition. Three subtypes: (1) T-HELPER (TH) LYMPHOCYTES: CD4+; assist other immune cells upon recognition of antigens presented by APCs. Secrete cytokines that regulate/boost immune response by activating other immune cells. (2) CYTOTOXIC T LYMPHOCYTES: CD8+; bind target antigens complexed with MHC CLASS I on nucleated cell surfaces. Kill target cells directly and attract macrophages. (3) REGULATORY T LYMPHOCYTES (Tregs): also CD4+; main role is SUPPRESSION of autoreactive T lymphocytes and regulation of immunological tolerance. In VCA rejection: skin contains TWICE as many effector T lymphocytes as peripheral blood. During active rejection in face transplants, the majority of lymphocytes in injured areas were DONOR-DERIVED CD8+ T lymphocytes (Boston group finding), meaning both recipient and donor immune cells contribute.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What is 'split tolerance' in VCA? Why is skin the most immunogenic component?", "answer": "Split tolerance: phenomenon where rejection episodes affect SKIN but NOT other allograft components (muscle, bone). Rejection of muscle rarely occurs without skin rejection. This is because skin is as much a part of the IMMUNE SYSTEM as lymph nodes and the spleen â€” it functions as a lymphoid organ. Key evidence: normal skin contains TWICE as many effector T lymphocytes compared to peripheral blood (Clark et al.). Implications: (1) skin is primary site of rejection in VCA (often the only tissue to react), (2) for face transplants, mucosal rejection can occur BEFORE skin rejection and may be more severe, (3) 80-100% of VCA patients experience acute rejection within first year (vs only 10% of kidney transplants), (4) 50% experience MULTIPLE rejection episodes. Advantage: direct observation of transplanted skin allows early detection. Environmental stimuli (trauma, irritation, UV radiation) can trigger rejection through DAMPs (damage-associated molecular pattern molecules).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the triple immunosuppression maintenance protocol for VCA: drugs, mechanisms, and side effects.", "answer": "Standard maintenance: CORTICOSTEROIDS + MYCOPHENOLATE MOFETIL (MMF) + TACROLIMUS (calcineurin inhibitor). CORTICOSTEROIDS: bind intracellular receptors causing expressional changes reducing pro-inflammatory cytokines. Side effects: glucose intolerance, osteoporosis, hypertension, osteonecrosis. MMF: inhibits inosine monophosphate (IMP)-dehydrogenase required for purine synthesis during RNA/DNA metabolism. Most cells can circumvent this pathway EXCEPT lymphocytes â€” therefore selectively inhibits lymphocyte proliferation. Side effects: bone marrow suppression, GI irritation. Initiation: 1000 mg pre-surgery, then 1000 mg bi-daily. TACROLIMUS: blocks calcineurin/NFAT (nuclear factor of activated T-cell) signaling pathway, causing T-cell arrest and preventing cytokine transcription. Most relevant side effect: NEPHROTOXICITY through vasoconstriction of prerenal arterioles. Trough levels: 10-15 ng/mL. Can be replaced by BELATACEPT (T-cell co-stimulation blocker) in severe renal dysfunction. Topical tacrolimus can treat lower-grade rejections.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe induction and rescue immunosuppression protocols in VCA.", "answer": "INDUCTION: aims to prevent early allograft rejection during perioperative phase. Most common agent: antithymocyte globulin (ATG) â€” polyclonal antibodies against human lymphocyte antigens. Preparation: immunizing pathogen-free RABBITS with human thymocytes/lymphocytes. Mechanism: binds T-lymphocyte surface antigens causing complement activation and cell lysis; also modulates cell surface/adhesion molecules. Dose: thymoglobulin 1.5 mg/kg daily for first 4-5 days postop. Side effects: leukopenia, thrombocytopenia, cytokine release syndrome (serum sickness â€” fever, rash). Additional induction: 500 mg methylprednisolone before allograft reperfusion. RESCUE (for acute rejection despite maintenance therapy): (1) Increase maintenance immunosuppression to therapeutic levels, (2) corticosteroid BOLUS therapy. If corticosteroid-resistant (7.5-19% of episodes): ATG or ALEMTUZUMAB. Can be supplemented with immunosuppressive topical ointments and mouth rinses.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the Banff 2007 classification for acute VCA rejection: grades, criteria, and limitations.", "answer": "Banff 2007: standardized histopathological grading system for VCA rejection evaluating perivascular/epidermal infiltration and epidermal injury. GRADES: Grade 1 â€” Mild perivascular and dermal infiltration WITHOUT epidermal affection. Grade 2 â€” Moderate perivascular inflammation WITH or WITHOUT epidermal involvement. Grade 3 â€” Severe inflammation and epidermal affection with epithelial apoptosis, dyskeratosis, and keratinolysis. Grade 4 â€” Epidermal NECROSIS. LIMITATIONS: (1) Susceptible to inter- and intra-rater differences based on pathologist expertise. (2) Vascular inflammation/allograft vasculopathy NOT included. (3) Originally developed for HAND transplant patients; facial skin contains larger neutrophilic lymphocytic infiltrates that resemble Grade 1, so many centers don't treat Grade 1 in face transplants. (4) Used for mucosal rejection though it's fundamentally different tissue. (5) Regular biopsies cause additional scarring. Sentinel flaps (donor-originated free flaps) showed good correlation (r=0.88) but lost monitoring potential over time.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Differentiate hyperacute, acute, and chronic rejection in VCA: timing, mechanism, and treatment.", "answer": "HYPERACUTE: occurs IMMEDIATELY after allograft reperfusion. Mechanism: preformed antibodies against donor or ABO antigens cause complement activation, endothelial cell injury, arterial/venous thrombosis. Prevention: immunologic screening for preformed antibodies and crossmatching. ACUTE: most common complication; ~80% of VCA patients within first year. Skin is primary site (often only tissue affected); mucosa may reject before skin in face transplants. Presentation: fever, maculopapular rash, edema, induration, loss of function. Histology: lymphatic infiltration (Banff classification) with vascular destruction. Predisposing factor: allograft ischemia time. Treatment: corticosteroid bolus; ATG for severe/steroid-resistant cases. CHRONIC: not fully defined; involves primarily skin and vascular system. Mechanism: likely antigen-mediated intimal damage. Presentation: cutaneous plaques, rashes, sclerosis, fibrosis, necrotic ulcers, premature aging. NO sufficient treatment available â€” prevention of acute rejection episodes is crucial (acute rejection likely contributes to chronic rejection development).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What are the major complications of lifelong immunosuppression after VCA?", "answer": "Three categories: (1) INFECTIONS: most common complication. Viral: CMV infection (risk factors: donor-recipient serology mismatch, degree of immunosuppression, ATG use; range from flu-like to severe organ disease), EBV causing post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder (uncontrolled B-cell proliferation â†’ aggressive lymphoma). Bacterial: early postop, affecting wound/bloodstream/respiratory/urinary tract; characterized by HIGH MULTIDRUG RESISTANCE. Fungal: Candida spp. or Aspergillus spp. (invasive candidiasis/aspergillosis). (2) MALIGNANCIES: up to 5-FOLD increased incidence; in SOT, ~50% develop neoplasia within 25 years (cancer is a leading cause of death). Most frequent: BCC and SCC of skin â€” requires regular dermatologic follow-up. (3) RENAL DYSFUNCTION: most common DRUG-related complication. Calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus) cause afferent arteriolar constriction and chronic structural changes (fibrosis, glomerulosclerosis). Management: reduce calcineurin inhibitor levels or switch to belatacept.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the surgical sequence for upper extremity transplantation. How does it compare to replantation?", "answer": "Sequence: BONE osteosynthesis â†’ EARLY REVASCULARIZATION (reduce ischemia time; one artery + â‰¥2 veins end-to-end) â†’ MUSCLE/TENDON repair â†’ DEFINITIVE REVASCULARIZATION (remaining artery + additional veins; â‰¥4 veins total from superficial and deep systems) â†’ NERVE repair (ulnar, radial, median + branches; epineural if fascicular repair impossible) â†’ PROPHYLACTIC CARPAL TUNNEL RELEASE â†’ skin/soft tissue closure. Key differences from replantation: VCA allows thorough preoperative planning; replantation is emergency. In replantation, bone shortening is needed for tension-free repair. In VCA, excess length of arteries/veins/nerves/tendons can be harvested. Critical ischemia time: 4-6 hours for muscle (travel time limit: 2 hours). Skin incisions: four-flap design preserving subcutaneous veins and perforators. Better outcomes with distal amputation levels (shorter nerve distance to intrinsic muscles, functioning forearm flexors/extensors allowing immediate tenorrhaphy).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Compare trunk versus branch-level facial nerve coaptation in face transplantation: advantages, disadvantages, and timeline for motor recovery.", "answer": "TRUNK-LEVEL coaptation: includes parotid gland in allograft (adds bulk to cheek area or requires superficial parotidectomy); limits access to individual facial nerve branches. Motor reinnervation begins within 5-6 months (longer distance to neuromuscular end plates). Higher risk of SYNKINESIA. BRANCH-LEVEL coaptation (medial to parotid): allows EXCLUSION of parotid gland (better cheek contour). Advantages: (1) reduces synkinesia, (2) allows better TARGETED reinnervation, (3) earlier motor reinnervation within 3-4 months (shorter distance to effector muscles). Mean restoration of facial motor function: ~60% within 2 years. SENSORY recovery: can occur as early as 3 months; usually 3-8 months. Includes near-total recovery of heat/cold discrimination and light-touch sensibility. Important: sensory recovery occurred during first year REGARDLESS of whether surgical sensory nerve coaptation was performed (trigeminal nerve branches). Recovery achieved through end-to-end coaptation; nerve grafts avoided as much as possible.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What functional outcomes are achieved after face transplantation?", "answer": "MOTOR recovery: begins 6-8 months post-transplant; ~60% restoration of facial motor function within 2 years. Smile restored (zygomaticus major) in all patients. SENSORY recovery: begins as early as 3 months; usually 3-8 months. Near-total recovery of heat/cold discrimination and light-touch. Occurs only during first year; independent of surgical nerve coaptation. BREATHING: nose breathing restored; patients with tracheostomy decannulated. SMELL: restored to pre-trauma levels by restoring nasal passage. EATING: significant mastication improvement within first year; previously necessary gastrostomies removed. SPEECH: intelligibility restored (80-97% at word/sentence level) within first year through restoration of labial function. SOCIAL REINTEGRATION: significant improvement in quality of life. Assessment methods: EMG (detects early re-myelinization but doesn't correlate with clinical improvement), facial expression recognition software (evaluates smile, frown, purse lips, open mouth, lift eyebrows, close eyes, wrinkle nose compared to healthy controls).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the VCA patient and donor selection process. What are the key matching criteria?", "answer": "PATIENT SELECTION (3-12 months): (1) Team leader assesses surgical indication and potential for form/function restoration. (2) Medical evaluation. (3) Psychiatric evaluation by TWO psychiatrists: one identifies disqualifying conditions, another serves as patient advocate assessing understanding, expectations, and compliance ability. Exclusions: active psychiatric issues, substance abuse. (4) Social work assessment: stable support network, financial resources. (5) Immunologic profiling: blood type, HLA, panel reactive antibody (%PRA) â€” high %PRA = low chance of negative crossmatch. (6) Infectious disease screening (hepatitis A/B/C, CMV, VZV, TB, syphilis, EBV, HIV). Team decision: consensus attempted; >50% in favor â†’ waitlist. Re-evaluation every 6 months. DONOR SELECTION: brain-dead donors (all US VCA to date). Matching: ABO compatibility, sex, age, skin color. Additional: limb size, tattoos, scars. Crossmatching performed to exclude preformed donor-specific antibodies. Next-of-kin: separate authorization required for VCA donation (per UNOS).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What are the critical ischemia time considerations in VCA? How is allograft preservation managed?", "answer": "Maximal tolerable ischemia time for MUSCLE tissue without irreversible damage: 4-6 HOURS (muscle is the most ischemia-sensitive component). Travel time limit: maximum 2 hours recommended. VCA procurement MUST be performed PRIOR to solid organ procurement (recovery frequently exceeds 6 hours). However, life-saving organ procurement takes PRIORITY if cardiopulmonary instability occurs. Allograft preservation: perfused with UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN SOLUTION, sterilely packed, stored on ICE SLURRY during transport. To reduce ischemia time: vascular anastomoses performed FIRST during allograft inset. Intraoperative perfusion assessment: INDOCYANINE GREEN (ICG) angiography. Future: extracorporeal (ex vivo) perfusion of allografts may extend tolerable ischemia time (already used in SOT), could reduce ischemia-reperfusion injury using antioxidant solutions. Post-procurement donor dignity: facial restorative mask placed by anaplastologist; limb prostheses of adequate skin tone provided.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What are the emerging VCA indications beyond face and upper extremity transplantation?", "answer": "UTERUS TRANSPLANTATION: first performed 2000; first successful live birth reported by BrÃ¤nnstrÃ¶m in 2014. Enables women with absolute uterine factor infertility or hysterectomy to undergo normal pregnancy (especially relevant where surrogacy is illegal). Major advantage: lifelong immunosuppression NOT needed because uterus can be REMOVED after pregnancy. PENILE TRANSPLANTATION: first performed in China 2005 (removed after 2 weeks due to recipient's wife's psychological concerns); subsequently performed in US and South Africa with promising functional results (erectile function, ejaculation, urination). VCA is still considered EXPERIMENTAL; biggest challenge is transition to standard of care. Current funding: governmental/institutional grants (not scalable). Acceptance by third-party payers (insurance) needed, which requires universally accepted treatment protocols and uniform outcome measures.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Compare the five noninvasive body contouring technologies: cryolipolysis, HIFEM, radiofrequency, ultrasound, and LLLT â€” in terms of mechanism and target tissue effect.", "answer": "CRYOLIPOLYSIS: cooling below physiologic but above freezing temperatures causes adipocyte APOPTOSIS (fat cells more susceptible to cold than skin/nerves/vessels). Inflammatory response removes injured cells (peaks day 14). No skin change. HIFEM (high-intensity focused electromagnetic field): supraphysiologic muscle contractions (20,000 pulses/30 min) cause MUSCULAR HYPERTROPHY; may decrease fat via lipolysis from free-fatty acid release. Only technology targeting muscle. RADIOFREQUENCY: energy waves cause tissue molecules to move/collide/change orientation producing HEAT. Variable impedance means different tissues affected differently. Adipocyte apoptosis + deep dermal collagen contraction/remodeling for skin tightening. ULTRASOUND: HFFU (high-frequency) uses heat for COAGULATIVE NECROSIS of adipocytes and collagen; LFFU (low-frequency) causes MECHANICAL DISRUPTION of adipocytes with less heat/discomfort. LLLT (low-level laser therapy): 635-680 nm wavelength; PHOTOCHEMICAL (not thermal); creates microscopic PORES in adipocyte membranes allowing lipid leakage without cell death; 80% of contents released at 4 min, 99% at 6 min.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "What is paradoxical adipose hyperplasia (PAH)? What technology causes it and how is it treated?", "answer": "PAH: a complication of CRYOLIPOLYSIS where treated areas paradoxically INCREASE in fat volume rather than decrease. Only 16 cases reported in published literature (systematic review). Hypothesized mechanism: some adipocytes may be 'naturally selected' to survive cold exposure and subsequently proliferate. Although rare, it is an important risk to communicate to patients. Treatment: the ONLY treatment is surgical lipectomy â€” either direct excision or liposuction. This phenomenon has generated significant concern in the lay press.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Describe the HIFEM (EMSCULPT) protocol: dosing, frequency, maintenance, and what unique finding has been reported regarding rectus diastasis.", "answer": "Protocol: 20,000 electromagnetic pulses during a 30-minute session, delivered supraphysiologically. Schedule: twice per week for 2 weeks (4 total sessions). Maintenance: one treatment every 3-6 months. Results: average waist circumference reduction of 3.29 cm after 4th treatment; increased abdominal muscle thickness of 1.6 mm in 21/22 patients. RECTUS DIASTASIS: significant narrowing in 20/22 subjects (1.8 mm narrower by MRI, P <0.001). This is the only noninvasive technology that can improve muscle tone and has NO surgical equivalent for muscle toning. FDA approved 2018 for abdomen and buttocks. Contraindications: pregnancy, metal implants, pacemakers, defibrillators, spinal cord stimulators. Side effects: transient muscle soreness. Better results in patients with LOWER BMI. Limitation: most early studies were industry-funded.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Compare high-frequency focused ultrasound (HFFU) and low-frequency focused ultrasound (LFFU) for body contouring: mechanism, tissue depth, pain, and efficacy.", "answer": "HFFU (e.g., Ultherapy): uses external transducer to transmit ultrasound energy generating HEAT causing COAGULATIVE NECROSIS of adipocytes and collagen. Can target specific tissue planes up to 8 mm depth: dermis (1.5 mm), deep dermis (3.0 mm), or SMAS/subdermal tissues (4.5 mm) by altering transducers. Painful (mean pain score 3.9/10 despite topical anesthesia); causes erythema and edema. Two-pass protocol targeting SMAS and superficial fascia showed improvement in facial/neck laxity in 8/10 patients. LFFU (e.g., UltraShape): uses sound for MECHANICAL DISRUPTION of adipocytes; produces LESS heat and LESS discomfort. Mean abdominal circumference decrease of 1.65 cm after 3 treatments. No adverse effects reported. Summary: HFFU has more discomfort and transient risks but more potential aesthetic benefit compared to LFFU.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Describe radiofrequency energy devices (RFED) for aesthetic body contouring: mechanism of action, tissue effects, and clinical results.", "answer": "Mechanism: RF energy causes tissue molecules to move, collide, or change orientation, producing and releasing HEAT. Key concept: VARIABLE IMPEDANCE â€” RF affects specific tissues differently. Two tissue effects: (1) Preferential adipocyte injury â†’ apoptosis â†’ subcutaneous volume reduction. (2) Heating deep dermis and collagen-based FIBROUS SEPTAE â†’ contraction, remodeling â†’ improved skin tightness/tone. Results: facial application showed clinical improvement in nasolabial/mesolabial folds in 28/30 patients; no improvement in patients >62 years. Abdominal use: average circumference decrease of 4.93 cm after 4 sessions, maintained at 4 years (4.42 cm reduction). Side effects: erythema (common), soreness requiring NSAIDs, dysesthesia (rare). No burns or long-term complications. Limitation: offers only MILD benefits; best suited for individuals with MILD cutaneous and subcutaneous excess. Multiple FDA-approved devices: ThermaCool, truSculpt, Venus Legacy, Vanquish, Velashape.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "How does LLLT differ from all other noninvasive body contouring modalities in terms of mechanism? What are its limitations?", "answer": "Key difference: LLLT acts through a PHOTOCHEMICAL pathway, not a THERMAL mechanism (unlike cryolipolysis, RF, and ultrasound). Uses 635-680 nm wavelength laser. Creates MICROSCOPIC PORES in adipocyte cell membranes allowing lipids to leak into interstitial space â€” no demonstrable temperature change, no macroscopic cell changes, no cell death/apoptosis. Efficacy: cumulative circumference reduction of 3.51 inches (waist/hips/thighs) in RCT; 70% satisfaction. LIMITATIONS: (1) Unlike liposuction or other devices that DESTROY adipocytes, LLLT does not kill cells â€” unclear how adipocytes react or rebound over time. (2) Effect of releasing triglycerides and adipocyte contents into interstitial space is unknown (unclear if reabsorbed into bloodstream). (3) Requires multiple sessions (6-8 treatments). Contraindications: pregnancy, scar or tattoo at treatment site. Safety: well tolerated with no documented adverse effects (photochemical, not thermal).", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "When should patients be counseled toward surgery versus noninvasive body contouring? What patient factor most limits noninvasive results?", "answer": "Surgery (liposuction/excisional procedures) remains GOLD STANDARD for loose skin and excess subcutaneous fat â€” results are more limited with noninvasive technologies. Direct to SURGERY when: significant skin laxity or adipose excess is present. Noninvasive options appropriate for: patients with early aging changes, mild skin/subcutaneous excess, those not ready for surgery, or who desire modest changes. HIFEM is unique as an adjunct even to surgery (no surgical equivalent for muscle toning). Key limiting factor: BMI â€” the lipolytic response is INVERSELY PROPORTIONAL to BMI; higher BMI patients have less appreciable/quantifiable results from noninvasive treatments. Additional patient education: multiple treatments are required; despite avoiding surgery costs, accumulated treatment costs may eliminate financial advantage; results are more modest than surgery. The minimally invasive procedural volume in the US has increased by nearly 300% over two decades vs 22% for cosmetic surgery.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Preoperative assessment and WPATH criteria", "question": "Describe the WPATH SOC8 criteria for gender-affirming surgery. How do requirements differ between facial surgery, mastectomy, gonadectomy, and genital surgery?", "answer": "SOC8 criteria COMMON TO ALL: (1) Letter from healthcare professional with competencies in TGD assessment â€” 1 letter required for ALL procedures (changed from SOC7 which required 2 letters for genital surgery). (2) Marked and sustained gender incongruence. (3) Capacity to consent. (4) Meets diagnostic criteria for gender incongruence where required. (5) Other causes of gender incongruence excluded. (6) Mental/physical conditions controlled. (7) Stable on gender-affirming hormones for at least 6 months (unless not desired or contraindicated). ADDITIONAL requirements by procedure: GONADECTOMY and GENITAL SURGERY: fertility counseling required. SOC7 vs SOC8 differences: SOC7 required 0 letters for facial surgery, 1 for breast augmentation/mastectomy, 2 for genital surgery. SOC7 also required 12 months continuous social transition for genital reconstruction.", "notes": "Gender-affirming surgery has its own topic in the topic list", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Hormone therapy considerations", "question": "List the common hormone therapies used in gender-affirming care and their main side effects. What are the perioperative hormone management considerations?", "answer": "ESTROGEN: main side effect is deep venous thrombosis (transdermal administration may lessen this risk). PROGESTERONE: increased cardiac and cancer risks. ANTI-ANDROGENS (e.g., spironolactone): potential effects on electrolytes. TESTOSTERONE: polycythemia and lipid alterations. Perioperative management: ESTROGEN â€” controversy exists. Some surgeons stop 2-4 weeks preoperatively, others reduce dose, others continue. Data suggesting continuation is safe are not robust enough for standardized protocols. TESTOSTERONE â€” generally accepted to continue perioperatively. For breast augmentation: patients should be on well-controlled exogenous estrogen for at least 12 months to allow maximal breast development before surgery. For facial feminization: estrogen effects on midface should be given 1-2 years before considering malar augmentation, as estrogen alone can feminize this region.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Chest masculinization (mastectomy)", "question": "Describe the Fischer grading scale for gender-affirming mastectomy. How does each grade guide the surgical approach?", "answer": "Fischer grading evaluates three components: skin laxity, degree of ptosis, and glandular tissue volume. GRADE 1: no laxity, NAC above IMF, minimal tissue. Approach: periareolar (small NAC) or circumareolar (moderate/large NAC). GRADE 2A: little to no laxity, NAC above IMF, moderate tissue. Approach: circumareolar, inferior pedicle, or double incision with free nipple graft (DIFNG). GRADE 2B: increased laxity, NAC at or below IMF, moderate tissue. Approach: inferior pedicle or DIFNG. GRADE 3: irrespective of laxity, NAC below IMF, significant tissue. Approach: DIFNG. GRADE 4: significant laxity, NAC below IMF, deflated breast. Approach: DIFNG. DIFNG is the most commonly performed procedure â€” most patients present with significant excess of both volume and skin (many develop ptosis/laxity from prolonged breast binding). DIFNG has consistently lower revision rates than other approaches.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Chest masculinization (mastectomy)", "question": "Describe the double incision with free nipple graft (DIFNG) technique: markings, NAC positioning, and common complications.", "answer": "Markings: gently curved incision mirroring the pectoralis major border; can extend laterally for axillary adiposity contouring. NAC position: lateral two-thirds of the clavicle, one fingerbreadth above planned incision along pectoralis border (~2 Ã— 3 cm oval FNG). Technique: FNG harvested full thickness and thinned; superior chest flap elevated just above breast capsule (can be thicker to approximate upper abdominal subcutaneous thickness); breast removed above pectoralis fascia; IMF released; closure in layers over drain; NAC site de-epithelialized and FNG secured with bolster. COMPLICATIONS: hematoma (5-12%, up to 5-10% requiring acute reoperation); seroma (2-5%); nipple necrosis (2-5%); NAC pigmentation changes; revision rates 10-40% (DIFNG lowest). Common revisions: scar revision, dog-ear excision, liposuction. KEY: this is NOT an oncologic resection â€” specimens must be screened by pathologist for occult cancer. Post-mastectomy: self-exam plus yearly clinical breast exam recommended.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Breast augmentation in transfeminine patients", "question": "What anatomical differences must be considered in transfeminine breast augmentation compared to cisgender augmentation?", "answer": "Key anatomical differences: (1) LIMITED SKIN EXPANSION from testosterone exposure. (2) Proportionally SHORTER nipple-to-IMF distance. (3) WIDER STERNUM with wider breast base width â€” often requires wider implants leading to larger volumes (BW <13: 300-500cc; BW 13-17: 400-600cc; BW >17: 500-700cc). (4) LATERALIZED NAC position â€” medial placement offers better cleavage but displaces NAC relative to implant. (5) More developed PECTORALIS MUSCLE â€” can cause animation deformity with subpectoral approach; 'pec test' assesses for marked pectoral hypertrophy. Pocket selection: subglandular if pinch test >1.5 cm, good estrogen skin softening, and excess sternal bone width; otherwise dual-plane subpectoral (90% of cases). IMF lowering: N-IMF should equal half of implant base width. Scarpa's fascia should be secured to chest wall when IMF is lowered to prevent malposition. Medium profile implant standard unless anatomy mandates otherwise. Previous silicone injections can impact candidacy.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "Compare the four phalloplasty donor sites: radial forearm, anterolateral thigh (ALT), SCIP/lower abdomen, and modified latissimus dorsi.", "answer": "RADIAL FOREARM: best vascularity (++++), BEST sensation (+++++), BEST pliability (+++++), moderate donor site morbidity (++), moderate hairlessness (++). Elevated with cephalic vein, radial artery, vena comitans; includes branches of lateral/medial/posterior antebrachial cutaneous nerves. Donor site: STSG or biologic matrix coverage; requires hand therapy. ANTEROLATERAL THIGH (ALT): good vascularity (++++), good sensation (++++), moderate pliability (+++), higher morbidity (+++), good hairlessness (+++). Includes LFCN; preoperative CT for perforator mapping; pinch test <1 cm for TWT suitability. SCIP/LOWER ABDOMEN: moderate vascularity (+++), limited sensation (++), moderate pliability (+++), BEST donor site morbidity (+++++), best hairlessness (++++). Can be closed primarily. MODIFIED LATISSIMUS DORSI: best vascularity (+++++), poorest sensation (+), limited pliability (++), best morbidity (+++++), good hairlessness (+++). Most common flaps: radial forearm and ALT. Most common design: tube-within-tube (TWT).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "Differentiate simple metoidioplasty, complete metoidioplasty, and phalloplasty: what each achieves and key counseling points.", "answer": "SIMPLE METOIDIOPLASTY: shaft lengthening + shaft skin creation WITHOUT urethral extension. Can be with or without vaginectomy/scrotoplasty. Creates small sensate phallus using local tissue based on embryologic origin (labia majora â†’ scrotum, labia minora â†’ shaft skin). Requires preoperative clitoral length â‰¥3 cm. Suspensory ligament and urethral plate released; ventral raw surface covered with buccal mucosal graft. Standing micturition sometimes possible; penetrative intercourse usually NOT possible. COMPLETE METOIDIOPLASTY: adds urethral lengthening + vaginectomy + scrotoplasty. Vaginectomy strongly encouraged if full-length urethra created (adds vascularized tissue layers over reconstruction). PHALLOPLASTY: creates adult-sized phallus capable of standing micturition and penetrative intercourse (with erectile implant). CRITICAL counseling: patients should NOT undergo standard metoidioplasty if they ultimately desire phalloplasty â€” the urethral diameter and potential complications can make conversion technically challenging.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "Compare single-stage phalloplasty, the Big Ben method, and metoidioplasty-first staging: components, advantages, and disadvantages.", "answer": "SINGLE-STAGE: shaft + shaft urethra + perineal urethra + vaginectomy + scrotoplasty in ONE surgery (glansplasty optional; implants always later). Advantage: fewer surgeries, less recovery/cost, higher patient volume. Disadvantage: flap complications can simultaneously impact urethral reconstruction. BIG BEN METHOD (St. Peter Andrology Institute, London): Stage 1 â€” shaft + shaft urethra + unilateral labia minora resection. Stage 2 â€” glansplasty + perineal urethra + scrotoplasty + vaginectomy. Advantages: separates flap-related from urologic complications; perineal urethra is SHORTER; urethral anastomosis closed as inverted Y (non-circumferential), potentially reducing stricture risk. METOIDIOPLASTY-FIRST: Stage 1 â€” metoidioplasty with urethral lengthening. Stage 2 â€” phalloplasty with clitoral burying. Advantage: urethra connected to clitoral glans (better erogenous stimulation); helpful for undecided patients. All approaches: erectile implants always placed at LATER stage. Overall complication rate ~50% regardless of method.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Vaginoplasty", "question": "Describe the penile inversion vaginoplasty (PIV) technique: key surgical steps, neoclitoral creation, and canal depth.", "answer": "Lithotomy position; hip/knee flexion <90Â° (prevent neuropraxia/compartment syndrome). Key steps: (1) Posterior perineal flap raised (pedicled posteriorly), 2 fingerbreadths above anus. (2) Scrotal skin graft harvested (12-15 cm Ã— ~5 cm), thinned, tubularized. (3) Bilateral orchiectomies. (4) Penis degloved above Buck's fascia preserving dorsal neurovascular bundle. (5) Canal dissection above rectum/below urethra/prostate in Denonvillier's fascia plane to peritoneal reflection (~15 cm depth). (6) Rectal integrity tested (dilute povidone-iodine enema). (7) NEOCLITORIS: W-shaped design (2 cm wide) at proximal dorsal corona, raised with deep erectile tissue, pedicle dissected in subtunical plane, coned and inset at adductor longus tendon line. (8) Urethra separated from corpora spongiosum, split ventrally, spatulated open for vulvar cleft. (9) Penile skin + scrotal graft sewn (non-circular suture line to prevent contracture), inverted into canal. (10) Labia majora contoured and closed.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Vaginoplasty", "question": "What are the common complications after penile inversion vaginoplasty? What is the most important postoperative requirement?", "answer": "COMPLICATIONS: Hematoma (up to 10%, some requiring operative drainage). Urinary retention requiring catheter replacement. Rectovaginal fistula (RVF): most serious surgical complication (1-3%); managed with colorectal surgery, usually requires temporary diverting ostomy. Surgical site complications: up to 70% â€” wound dehiscence (labia majora/introitus), hypergranulation tissue in vaginal canal, partial or complete neovaginal STENOSIS. For intestinal vaginoplasty: mucorrhea, diversion colitis, bowel anastomotic leaks. MOST IMPORTANT postoperative requirement: VAGINAL DILATATION â€” typically 20 minutes twice daily; must be CONSISTENT or stenosis will invariably occur. Postop protocol: Foley catheter and vaginal packing/stenting for 5-6 days; antibiotics while bolster in place; speculum exam confirming neovaginal integrity before starting dilations and vaginal rinses. CONTRAINDICATIONS to vaginal vault creation: previous prostatectomy, prostatic radiation, IBD (higher RVF risk).", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Facial feminization surgery", "question": "Describe the testosterone-driven skeletal changes in the upper face and the surgical techniques for forehead feminization.", "answer": "Testosterone effects on upper face: (1) Increased muscle strength â†’ facial skull grows more angular. (2) FRONTAL BOSSING from enlarged frontal sinuses with decreased nasofrontal angle. (3) Lower-set eyebrows with less lateral arching and more acute angulation between eyelid crease and brows. (4) Increased AP dimension of supraorbital rim (more shadows, decreased perceived eyelid-brow distance). (5) Thickened skull cortices. (6) More acute forehead slope. (7) Masculine hair pattern (testosterone â†’ DHT conversion). FOREHEAD FEMINIZATION via hairline or bicoronal incision: (1) Frontal bone contoured for more convex shape; often requires ANTERIOR TABLE OSTEOTOMY (setback) to reduce AP dimension, with subsequent osteosynthesis. (2) Orbital aperture opened with burring/lateral orbital osteotomy for more oval shape with sharpened supraorbital edges. (3) Brow elevation with bony fixation and soft-tissue draping. (4) Hairline advancement (if pretrichial incision); galeal scoring incisions posteriorly. (5) Simultaneous hair transplantation possible. Complication: bone resorption of anterior table, mucoceles.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Facial feminization surgery", "question": "What are the key surgical considerations for feminization of the middle and lower thirds of the face?", "answer": "MIDDLE THIRD: Rhinoplasty â€” reductive approach especially at nasal dorsum; infracturing osteotomies (prevent open roof); decrease length/projection, increase tip rotation; cephalic trim of lower lateral cartilages; crural strut grafts for inferior rotation. Upper lip lift: resect 4-6 mm subnasal skin (decreases upper lip length, adds volume via vermilion eversion; avoid if gummy smile). Malar augmentation: fillers, fat grafting, or implants (allow 1-2 years of estrogen effect first); zygomatic osteotomies for width reduction. LOWER THIRD: Masculine features include increased vertical height, wider bigonial width with flare/hypertrophy, square menton. Jaw contouring: intraoral triple incision with mental nerve protection; chin reduction (vertical and/or horizontal); sliding genioplasty; gonial angle width reduction (avoid over-resection). Critical: inferior alveolar nerve limits body resection. Soft-tissue resuspension essential (internal sutures + compressive garment). LARYNX: laryngochondroplasty â€” resection limited inferiorly by vocal cord insertions (located by CT or intraoperative needle). Patients must be warned of iatrogenic jowling requiring secondary skin tightening.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "What are the urethral creation options in phalloplasty, and why is vaginectomy strongly recommended with urethral lengthening?", "answer": "Two parts of urethra needed: PERINEAL URETHRA (pars fixa) and SHAFT URETHRA (pars pendulans). Shaft urethra options: (1) TUBE-WITHIN-TUBE (TWT): urethra created as part of primary flap (2-4 cm longer than shaft), most common design. (2) COMPOSITE PHALLOPLASTY: separate flap for urethra. (3) PRELAMINATION: graft placed within donor site before phallic creation (largely abandoned due to high complication rates). (4) SPLIT SHAFT AND GRAFT: phallus split vertically, graft secured, then tubularized at third surgery. Graft materials: uterine, vaginal, or buccal mucosa, or skin. Perineal urethra: created from vulvar tissue (urethral plate, medial labia minora, anterior vaginal flap, natal urethral meatus). VAGINECTOMY STRONGLY RECOMMENDED because: (1) adds multiple VASCULARIZED TISSUE LAYERS over urethral reconstruction, (2) vaginal canal abuts native urethra â€” retaining it risks long-segment urethral strictures. Vaginal preservation is considered a CONTRAINDICATION to urethral lengthening by most surgeons. Hair removal on urethral segments is ESSENTIAL before surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Reconstructive ladder vs reconstructive elevator", "question": "What is the difference between the reconstructive ladder and the reconstructive elevator?", "answer": "The reconstructive ladder is an old paradigm that advocates a linear, stepwise approach starting with the simplest technique and progressing to more complex ones only when simpler options fail. The reconstructive elevator (Gottlieb & Krieger, 1994) is a newer paradigm that encourages selection of the most definitive reconstruction method first, even if it is more complex, rather than exhausting simpler options sequentially.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Replace like with like", "question": "A patient requires upper eyelid skin reconstruction after tumor excision. What is the ideal donor site and why? What are the backup options?", "answer": "The ideal donor site is full-thickness skin from the opposite upper eyelid because it matches in thickness, color, pliability, and elasticity, and donor site morbidity is low when harvesting relatively excess eyelid skin. Backup options include postauricular skin or supraclavicular skin, selected because they are the next most similar tissue substitutes.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Patient optimization", "question": "What are the key modifiable patient risk factors that should be addressed prior to plastic surgery, and what is the recommended smoking cessation protocol for body contouring?", "answer": "Modifiable risk factors include: smoking, uncontrolled diabetes, obesity, infection, steroid use, certain homeopathic medications, and malnutrition. Social factors (postoperative support system) must also be assessed. For body contouring, smoking is an absolute contraindication; cessation for at least 4 weeks with confirmation by urine cotinine test is required before scheduling surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Form and function", "question": "How does reconstruction after pelvic exenteration for advanced colorectal cancer illustrate the principle of preserving form and function? What flap is commonly used?", "answer": "The oblique rectus abdominis myocutaneous (ORAM) flap is commonly used. Goals include: recreating normal anatomy, obliterating pelvic dead space, and supplying additional vascularity to a previously irradiated field. The ORAM flap has long reach, large soft tissue bulk, reliable blood supply, and a skin paddle that can resurface vaginal defects and perianal skin deficits — addressing both form and function.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "When to choose each modality", "question": "A child has a 5 cm x 4 cm full-thickness plantar foot burn with healthy granulation tissue and no exposed bone or tendon. What is the best reconstructive option and why?", "answer": "Full-thickness skin graft from the lower abdomen is the best option. On the weight-bearing surface of the foot, a full-thickness skin graft is more durable than a split-thickness skin graft. Secondary healing would result in excessive scarring and potential toe contractures. A free ALT flap is reserved for more complex wounds with exposed critical structures.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "How comorbidities change the plan", "question": "How does arterial insufficiency change the reconstructive plan for a chronic lower extremity wound?", "answer": "The patient should be referred to a vascular surgeon for revascularization prior to surgical wound treatment. Surgery may need to be postponed to optimize blood flow. A delay procedure may also be performed (partially raising the flap and waiting 1-2 weeks before definitive elevation) to allow choke vessels to physiologically dilate, increasing flap reliability.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Timing of reconstruction", "question": "What is the role of tissue expansion in scalp reconstruction for a defect comprising approximately 40% of hair-bearing scalp with no exposed calvarium?", "answer": "A staged approach is best: first close the wound with a split-thickness skin graft (since the base has healthy granulation tissue and galea). Once healed, tissue expanders are placed to gradually grow the remaining hair-bearing scalp. After sufficient expansion, the expanders are removed, the skin graft is excised, and the expanded hair-bearing scalp is used to resurface the area. Defects up to ~50% of hair-bearing scalp can be reconstructed this way.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Functional priorities", "question": "Why is a reverse radial forearm flap or free flap preferred over dermal substitutes and skin grafting for dorsal hand reconstruction with exposed extensor tendons?", "answer": "Although dermal substitutes and skin grafting may close the wound, they do not provide sufficiently durable soft tissue coverage over gliding tendons, which would result in unacceptable hand stiffness. A reverse radial forearm flap or free flap (e.g., free gracilis muscle flap) provides the necessary durable coverage to preserve tendon gliding and hand function.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis/inflammation/proliferation/remodeling", "question": "What are the four phases of wound healing, their approximate timelines, and their key cellular/molecular events?", "answer": "1) Hemostasis (immediate): Coagulation cascade activation, platelet aggregation, fibrin scaffold formation; platelets release PDGF, TGF-beta, VEGF from alpha-granules. 2) Inflammation (~48 hours): Neutrophils phagocytose debris, monocytes differentiate into macrophages; macrophages release TNF-alpha and IL-1 via integrin receptors on ECM. 3) Proliferation (~48 hours to 10 days): Keratinocyte migration/epithelialization, fibroblast collagen production, angiogenesis (HIF-1 → VEGF/SDF-1), granulation tissue formation, wound contraction by myofibroblasts. 4) Remodeling (~2 weeks to years): Type III collagen replaced by type I collagen via MMPs; wound reaches ~80% of normal skin tensile strength.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What collagen transition occurs during the remodeling phase, what enzymes mediate it, and what is the maximum tensile strength a scar achieves?", "answer": "During remodeling, type III collagen is converted to predominantly type I collagen by matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs), produced by fibroblasts and other cell types. The mature scar achieves approximately 80% of normal unwounded skin tensile strength. Mature scar formation occurs between 6 and 18 months after wounding. Cutaneous scar tissue contains the same ECM macromolecules as normal tissue but in different ratios, and typically lacks hair follicles and fat.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Angiogenesis and epithelialization", "question": "What is the primary molecular stimulus of angiogenesis during wound healing, and what growth factors drive epithelialization?", "answer": "The hypoxic wound environment increases expression of hypoxia-inducible factor 1 (HIF-1), which is the primary stimulus of angiogenesis. HIF-1 activates target genes including VEGF and SDF-1 to induce neovascularization. Epithelialization is driven by the epidermal growth factor family: epidermal growth factor (EGF), heparin-binding EGF (HB-EGF), and TGF-alpha, which stimulate keratinocyte migration and proliferation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing", "question": "How does radiation therapy adversely affect wound healing at the cellular level?", "answer": "Radiation produces acute effects: damage to the basement membrane and increased vascular permeability causing edema, which reduces neovascularization. During the inflammatory phase, excess expression of several growth factors leads to tissue fibrosis. Late effects include fibroblast injury leading to fibrosis and contraction. Ionizing radiation disrupts the complex pathways of wound healing at multiple phases.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing", "question": "What are the effects of malnutrition on wound healing, and what specific deficiencies are important?", "answer": "Malnutrition prolongs the inflammatory phase by reducing fibroblast proliferation and collagen formation. It also increases infection risk by altering immune cell function (reduced phagocytosis, decreased complement levels). Key deficiencies include: micronutrients (copper, zinc, magnesium — essential for wound healing chemical processes), and macronutrients (protein, amino acids, carbohydrates, fats). Reduced protein intake is associated with increased wound infection and decreased wound strength. Lipid deficiencies also alter wound healing.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Differences in healing by tissue type", "question": "How do diabetic foot ulcers differ pathophysiologically from venous ulcers in terms of wound healing?", "answer": "Diabetic foot ulcers: Chronic inflammation with elevated IL-1, IL-6, TNF-alpha; hyperglycemia leads to advanced glycation end-products (AGEs) that decrease ECM solubility, cause cell apoptosis, and disrupt angiogenesis/migration/proliferation; glucose induces MMP overexpression; peripheral neuropathy and peripheral arterial disease also contribute. Venous ulcers: Caused by valvular incompetence leading to venous hypertension; elevated venous pressures alter shear stress and mechanical forces; endothelial cells detect changes via ICAM-1 and mechanosensitive channels, triggering an inflammatory cascade; capillary leakage of fibrin decreases collagen production.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Acute vs chronic wound", "question": "How is a chronic wound defined, and what are the four major categories of chronic wounds?", "answer": "A chronic wound is defined as a loss of continuity of skin secondary to injury that persists for longer than 6 weeks. The four major categories are: (1) venous ulcers, (2) arterial ulcers, (3) diabetic foot ulcers, and (4) pressure ulcers/injuries. All share common features: excessive/persistent inflammatory phase, impaired cell proliferation, abnormal cell migration, microbial colonization, presence of biofilms, and inability to complete all four phases of healing within the normal timeframe.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Clean/contaminated/dirty classification", "question": "What is the NPUAP pressure injury staging system?", "answer": "Stage 1: Nonblanchable erythema of intact skin. Stage 2: Partial-thickness skin loss with exposed dermis. Stage 3: Full-thickness skin loss. Stage 4: Full-thickness skin and tissue loss (e.g., probing to bone). These stages guide clinical decision-making for wound management and reconstruction planning.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Vascularity", "question": "What are the classic locations for arterial vs venous ulcers, and what underlying pathology differentiates them?", "answer": "Venous ulcers: Located in the gaiter area on the medial aspect between the knee and ankle; caused by venous insufficiency with valvular incompetence leading to increased venous pressure. Arterial ulcers: Located over bony prominences including toes, heels, and ankles; caused by arterial insufficiency from narrowing of the arterial lumen (most commonly atherosclerosis). Other arterial causes include embolism, diabetes, vasculitis, pyoderma gangrenosum, sickle cell disease, and thalassemia.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Culture interpretation", "question": "Why are superficial wound cultures unreliable for chronic wounds, and what culture method is preferred?", "answer": "Superficial cultures do not represent the diverse populations of bacteria in the biofilm of chronic wounds. Deep wound cultures are preferred because they better reflect the actual organisms causing infection. Antibiotics should be targeted to specific organisms identified from deep cultures and should have high tissue bioavailability. Systemic antibiotics are indicated for infected chronic wounds but NOT for wounds merely colonized with bacteria.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Viable vs nonviable tissue", "question": "What role do biofilms play in chronic wound pathology, and how do they impair healing?", "answer": "Biofilms are adherent three-dimensional populations of microbes organized on extracellular polymers. They impair healing by: producing toxins and damaging enzymes, promoting complex chronic inflammatory pathways, releasing proteases that impede growth factors and wound healing proteins, and generating exudate that affects cell proliferation. Biofilm-infected wounds are resistant to antimicrobials and the immune system. Management includes debridement (often serial, as recolonization is common), NPWT, appropriate dressings, and systemic antibiotics.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "Sharp/surgical debridement", "question": "Why is adequate debridement critical before definitive reconstruction, and when might complete debridement not be possible?", "answer": "Debridement removes barriers to tissue growth including infection, biofilm, and senescent cells. Failure of reconstruction is often attributed to inadequate debridement. Complete debridement may not be possible when: (1) exposed orthopedic hardware cannot be removed due to fracture instability — debridement reduces microbial burden and deep cultures guide antimicrobial therapy, with suppressive antibiotics until hardware removal; (2) extensive osteomyelitis in pressure ulcers — complete bone resection is not feasible, so aggressive bursa excision is performed with suppressive antibiotics guided by intraoperative bone cultures.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "Mechanical/enzymatic/autolytic/biologic debridement", "question": "What are the different modes of debridement for chronic wounds?", "answer": "1) Surgical/sharp debridement: Operative excision of necrotic tissue, the most definitive method. 2) Mechanical debridement: Physical removal of debris (e.g., wet-to-dry dressings). 3) Enzymatic debridement: Use of topical enzymatic agents to dissolve necrotic tissue. 4) Autolytic debridement: Using the body's own enzymes under occlusive or moisture-retentive dressings to liquefy necrotic tissue. Debridement reduces biofilm burden, but recolonization is common, so sequential debridements are often required for successful healing.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "NPWT indications/contraindications", "question": "What is the mechanism of action of negative-pressure wound therapy (NPWT), and what evidence supports its use?", "answer": "NPWT uses an open-pore polyurethane sponge placed over the wound connected to suction. It works through mechanical forces: inducing microdeformations at the wound surface, drawing wound edges together, ensuring wound drainage, aiding granulation tissue development, and expediting wound contraction. Mechanical forces (mechanotransduction) stimulate cell proliferation and migration. RCT data show improved ulcer healing and reduced second amputations. Observational data with adjunctive topical dressings demonstrate decreased biofilm load.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "Dressing types (Xeroform/silver/hydrocolloid/hydrogel/alginate/foam)", "question": "What is the role of antiseptic dressings (silver, chlorhexidine, iodine) and topical antimicrobials in wound management?", "answer": "Antiseptic dressings containing chlorhexidine, silver, or iodine and topical antimicrobials (e.g., fusidic acid) have been developed with limited success overall. Several studies concluded that antiseptic dressings are not significantly better than saline gauze alone for chronic wounds. Topical antimicrobials have promoted bacterial resistance. However, there are special situations where they are proven beneficial: particularly in burn injuries (especially second-degree burns) to treat infection and prevent sepsis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "Dressing types (Xeroform/silver/hydrocolloid/hydrogel/alginate/foam)", "question": "What is Integra, and what is the evidence for its use in wound healing?", "answer": "Integra is a bilayer matrix composed of bovine collagen and glycosaminoglycan derived from shark skin, lyophilized to form a highly porous scaffold. It acts as a platform for cell migration and angiogenesis. It has been used with considerable success in burns, and clinical trial data support its use in healing chronic wounds, specifically decreasing time to wound closure in diabetic foot ulcers. It can be used over nonvascularized structures, with secondary skin grafting performed after vascular ingrowth.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What are the key clinical and histological differences between hypertrophic scars and keloids?", "answer": "Keloids: Extend beyond the margins of the original wound, rarely regress, frequently result from minor trauma, have familial predisposition, and have elevated TGF-beta. Hypertrophic scars: Remain confined to the limits of the original wound, are raised/erythematous/pruritic, can partially or totally regress spontaneously, result from trauma/incision/burns/prolonged healing, have increased epidermal/dermal thickness, random orientation of collagen fibrils, decreased collagen content, lack of epithelial ridges, elevated TGF-beta, and increased mast cells.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection/silicone/pressure/laser/radiation", "question": "What is the protocol for corticosteroid injection therapy in keloid and hypertrophic scar management?", "answer": "Triamcinolone injection is widely used as initial treatment. Dosage ranges from 2.5 to 40 mg, either solo or mixed with xylocaine + epinephrine (to decrease pain and steroid dispersion). For hypertrophic scars, injections can be repeated at 4-6 week intervals until desired effect or side effects are observed. For keloids, steroid pretreatment followed by surgical excision plus postoperative injections produces cure rates up to 80%. Side effects include skin atrophy, hypopigmentation, and pain with injection.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection/silicone/pressure/laser/radiation", "question": "What is the evidence and protocol for radiation therapy in keloid treatment?", "answer": "Keloid excision followed by radiation therapy within 24-48 hours (single or multiple doses) achieves cure rates of 67-98% depending on anatomic area. Radiation monotherapy is NOT effective. The mechanism involves damaging keloid fibroblasts, affecting collagen production and structure. Concerns: potential for radiation-induced carcinogenesis, especially in pediatric patients and areas prone to radiation-induced carcinoma (thyroid, breast). Adequate shielding and careful patient selection are recommended. Side effects include hyperpigmentation, hypopigmentation, and transient erythema.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Z-plasty/W-plasty/geometric broken-line closure", "question": "What theoretical lengthening does a standard Z-plasty with 60-degree angles achieve, and what are the indications for Z-plasty vs W-plasty?", "answer": "A standard Z-plasty with equal-length sides and 60-degree angles provides approximately 75% lengthening along the central limb. Increasing the angle or central limb length provides proportionally greater lengthening. Z-plasty indications: Realigning tissue in functional deficits such as joint contractures; functional reorientation and scar lengthening to improve range of motion. Multiple in-series Z-plasties can be used for longitudinal gain. Adequate lateral skin laxity is needed. W-plasty indication: Breaking up the scar outline to camouflage appearance by reducing light reflection and noticeability.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Scar revision principles", "question": "What are the principles of scar prevention through incision planning and surgical technique?", "answer": "Prevention includes: meticulous wound closure technique, minimizing tension, adequate debridement of nonviable tissue, removing foreign bodies, approximating layers, filling dead space, preventing hematoma/seroma/infection, and timely suture removal. Adequate undermining with deep dermal suturing creates wound edge eversion to reduce tension and minimize scar width. Incision placement: scars in natural creases, at junctions between contours, and at edges of hair-bearing skin for camouflage. Working within relaxed skin tension lines (described by Borges, Kraissl, and Langer) reduces tension and produces less widened scars.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection/silicone/pressure/laser/radiation", "question": "What is the recommended silicone gel protocol for scar management, and what is its mechanism of action?", "answer": "Silicone gel dressing should be worn 12-24 hours per day for 2-3 months at the onset of visible scar abnormality. The mechanism of action is occlusion and epithelial hydration (NOT temperature increase or chemical absorption of silicone). It likely influences the collagen remodeling phase of wound healing. Silicone gel has been shown to benefit hypertrophic scars, keloids, and surgical incisions, with better evidence for treatment than prevention.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection/silicone/pressure/laser/radiation", "question": "What is the role of pulsed dye laser (PDL) and CO2 laser in hypertrophic scar treatment?", "answer": "Pulsed dye laser (585/595-nm wavelength): Treats scar pruritus and erythema; works by destruction of scar microvasculature via photothermolysis and possibly collagen modulation by reducing TGF-beta expression; response rates ~70%; earlier treatment (< 1 year, while still erythematous) yields better outcomes than treating mature scars. CO2 laser: Ablative, causing tissue vaporization via selective absorption by water in tissues; indicated for scar texture treatment. Best results for hypertrophic burn scarring.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Contractures", "question": "When is flap closure indicated for scar contracture, and what types of flaps can be used?", "answer": "Flap closure after scar excision is indicated for severe contractures, especially across major joints (knee, elbow, axilla). The more severe the contracture, the more likely flap closure is needed. Flap types include: cutaneous, myocutaneous, and fasciocutaneous flaps — local, random, pedicled, perforator, or free tissue transfer. Requirements for adequate results are: maximal scar release, dead space filling, and tension-free closure. Flaps relieve tension, fill dead space, and improve both aesthetics and function.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Timing of revision", "question": "When should scar revision be performed, and what factors guide the choice of modality?", "answer": "Mature scar formation occurs between 6-18 months after wounding. Hypertrophic scars treated with pulsed dye laser earlier (< 1 year, while still erythematous) respond better than mature scars. Pressure garments are recommended prophylactically in burn injury after extensive skin grafting or if spontaneous healing requires > 10-14 days. Factors guiding modality choice include: scar type (keloid vs hypertrophic), extent, size, orientation, location, etiology, symptomatology, and patient preferences. There is no single optimal therapy for all situations — individualized treatment combining modalities is advised.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection/silicone/pressure/laser/radiation", "question": "What is the role of pressure therapy in burn and keloid scar management?", "answer": "Pressure garments are commonly used after burn injury to control hypertrophic scarring. They are recommended prophylactically after extensive skin grafting or when spontaneous wound healing requires > 10-14 days. The target pressure is 15-25 mm Hg, though optimal pressure has not been definitively established. The mechanism likely involves influencing collagen synthesis and remodeling. For ear lobe keloids, compression earrings after complete surgical excision achieve effectiveness up to 80%. Limitations include poor patient compliance due to discomfort, appearance, and heat generation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Random-pattern vs axial-pattern flaps", "question": "What is the key difference between a random-pattern flap and an axial-pattern flap?", "answer": "A random-pattern flap has no known named artery at its core and relies on the random subdermal plexus for perfusion. An axial-pattern flap has a known or named artery coursing along its longitudinal axis. Axial flaps can be designed with a longer length-to-width ratio and may carry a random extension distally.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Length-to-width ratios", "question": "What is the maximum safe length-to-width ratio for a random-pattern flap, and why can axial-pattern flaps exceed this?", "answer": "Random-pattern flaps must generally be limited to a 3:1 length-to-width ratio to remain viable at the tip. Axial-pattern flaps can exceed this ratio because they have a named artery coursing along their longitudinal axis, providing more reliable perfusion to the distal end. Axial flaps may also carry a random extension beyond the named vessel territory, but that extension follows the same 3:1 limitation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Advancement/rotation/transposition/interpolation", "question": "What are the four basic types of local flap movement, and how do they differ?", "answer": "1) Advancement - flap moves directly forward into the defect (e.g., V-Y, bipedicled, keystone). 2) Rotation - flap pivots around a point to swing into the defect in a curvilinear fashion. 3) Transposition - flap moves laterally over intervening normal tissue to reach the defect (e.g., Z-plasty, rhomboid, bilobed). 4) Interpolation - flap is moved into a nearby but non-adjacent defect, with the pedicle passing over or under intervening tissue, typically requiring a second stage for pedicle division.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Rhomboid/bilobed/V-Y/keystone/nasolabial/forehead flap", "question": "Describe the keystone flap design, its blood supply, and how it is closed.", "answer": "The keystone flap (described by Behan) is a perforator island flap shaped like two opposing V-Y flaps (keystone arch shape) designed parallel and adjacent to the defect. It is at least as wide as the defect and extends beyond each end. It is based on one or more smaller perforators. Dissection extends through skin, subcutaneous tissue, and fascia to mobilize the flap for advancement. Closure borrows tissue from all directions, with each end repaired as a V-Y advancement.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and contracture release", "question": "What is a propeller flap, and what is the most common complication associated with it?", "answer": "A propeller flap (first described by Hyakusoku et al. in 1991) is a local perforator flap based on a single large perforating vascular pedicle close to the defect that is rotated up to 180 degrees. The main perforator serves as the pivot point and is identified with a handheld Doppler. The most common complication is venous congestion, usually due to impaired venous outflow through thin, fragile comitant veins that kink when the flap and pedicle are twisted 180 degrees. This is more likely with a bulky pedicle. The solution is to fully dissect the pedicle and free it from surrounding soft tissue and fascia.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Flap delay", "question": "What is the delay phenomenon, and what physiologic changes does it induce?", "answer": "Flap delay involves a preliminary surgical stage to partially raise the flap and divide a portion of its blood supply, delivering a sublethal ischemic insult. This stimulates: 1) vessel dilation (particularly dilation of choke vessels), 2) ischemic preconditioning, 3) neovascularization, and 4) axialization of blood flow. These changes condition the flap tissues to lower oxygen levels in anticipation of full flap transfer at a second stage, allowing survival of a larger surface area on a given pedicle.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Venous congestion vs arterial insufficiency", "question": "How do you distinguish venous congestion from arterial insufficiency in a flap, and what is the initial management of each?", "answer": "Arterial insufficiency: flap is pale/white, cool, lacks capillary refill. Usually recognized early and may be due to poor flap design, pedicle kinking, or anastomotic thrombosis. Requires urgent revision of the anastomosis or pedicle. Venous congestion: flap appears dark/purple, swollen, with rapid/brisk capillary refill. Onset is more insidious. Initial management includes: 1) release insetting sutures causing tension or kinking, 2) serial needle pricks to reduce venous burden, 3) deepithelialization with periodic heparin application, 4) medicinal leeches (Hirudo medicinalis), 5) cannulation of a vein with angiocatheter for periodic drainage.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Random-pattern vs axial-pattern flaps", "question": "What is a reverse-flow flap? Give a clinical example.", "answer": "A reverse-flow flap is one in which the native direction of blood flow through the main pedicle is reversed at inset. The classic example is the reverse radial forearm flap: the radial artery is transected proximally, and the flap relies on reverse blood flow in the radial artery across the palmar arch for perfusion. This allows coverage of dorsal hand defects while maintaining hand perfusion through the ulnar artery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Rhomboid/bilobed/V-Y/keystone/nasolabial/forehead flap", "question": "What is the advantage of a V-Y advancement flap for local reconstruction?", "answer": "The V-Y advancement flap causes minimal distortion to surrounding tissues and replaces like tissue with like. It advances tissue directly into the defect without rotation or transposition, minimizing tension on adjacent structures. For example, a V-Y flap on the temple can provide a well-vascularized flap without altering brow position. The donor site is closed in a Y-pattern as the trailing edge of the V is advanced forward.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and contracture release", "question": "A transposition flap (such as a rhomboid flap) closes a defect by what mechanism?", "answer": "A transposition flap moves laterally over intervening normal tissue to reach and close the defect. In a rhomboid (Limberg) flap, the transposed flap closes the primary defect while distributing tension along the planes of the donor site. The donor site is closed primarily by recruiting tissue from the surrounding area. This effectively redirects wound closure tension away from the primary defect.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Angiosome/perforasome concepts", "question": "Define angiosome and perforasome. How are adjacent angiosomes connected?", "answer": "An angiosome (Taylor and Palmer, 1987) is a 3D body of tissue supplied by a source (segmental or distributing) artery and its accompanying vein(s) spanning between skin and bone. Each can be subdivided into an arteriosome and venosome. A perforasome (Saint-Cyr et al.) is the 3D territory of tissue supplied by a single perforator vessel. Adjacent angiosomes are connected by: 1) true small anastomotic bidirectional arterioles/venules, and 2) reduced-caliber choke (retiform) anastomotic vessels. Adjacent perforasomes are connected by direct (fascial) and indirect (subdermal) linking vessels.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Mathes-Nahai muscle flap classification", "question": "Describe the Mathes and Nahai classification of muscle flaps (Types I-V) with examples of each.", "answer": "Type I: One dominant vascular pedicle (e.g., gastrocnemius, rectus femoris, tensor fascia lata). Type II: One dominant pedicle and minor pedicle(s) (e.g., gracilis, soleus, temporalis, trapezius, platysma, vastus lateralis, peroneus longus/brevis). Type III: Two dominant pedicles (e.g., rectus abdominis, gluteus maximus, semimembranosus). Type IV: Multiple segmental vascular pedicles (e.g., tibialis anterior, sartorius). Type V: One dominant pedicle and secondary segmental pedicles (e.g., pectoralis major, latissimus dorsi).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Choke vessels", "question": "What are choke vessels, and what happens to them during the delay phenomenon?", "answer": "Choke vessels are reduced-caliber anastomotic vessels that connect adjacent angiosomes. Under normal conditions, they serve as regulated connections with limited flow between territories. During the delay phenomenon (when part of a flap's blood supply is divided in a preliminary surgical stage), choke vessels dilate and can convert to true anastomoses by approximately 7 days. This allows capture of an adjacent vascular territory, extending the functional angiosome and permitting survival of a larger flap area on a single source vessel.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Delay phenomenon", "question": "How does tissue expansion affect a flap's vascularity and tissue characteristics?", "answer": "Tissue expansion produces several important changes: 1) The vascular trees within flaps enlarge following expansion, with pronounced neovascularization in the papillary dermis and capsular layers. 2) The mechanical force of stretching tissues enhances tissue neovascularity. 3) There is thinning of all tissue layers except the epidermis. 4) Expanded flaps allow for greater reach and coverage, can minimize donor site defects, and the accompanying thinning can be an additional bonus in reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Random vs axial flap", "question": "What is the Cormack and Lamberty classification of fasciocutaneous flaps?", "answer": "Type A: Pedicled fasciocutaneous flap dependent on multiple fasciocutaneous perforators at the base, oriented along the long axis (e.g., lateral arm flap). Type B: Pedicled or free flap depending on a single sizeable, consistent fasciocutaneous perforator feeding a plexus at the deep fascia level (e.g., parascapular flap). Type C: Blood supply dependent on fascial plexus supplied by multiple small perforators along its length from a deep artery passing through fascial septum between muscles (e.g., radial forearm flap). Type D: Fascial septum taken in continuity with adjacent muscle and bone sharing the same artery (e.g., free fibula flap).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Venous congestion vs arterial insufficiency", "question": "What is a supercharged flap? When is supercharging used?", "answer": "A supercharged flap is one in which the arterial inflow or venous outflow is augmented by using microsurgical techniques to perform a second anastomosis, providing additional inflow or outflow capability. It is used when the primary pedicle alone provides insufficient perfusion or drainage for the flap territory. A common example is anastomosing the superficial inferior epigastric vein (SIEV) during DIEP flap breast reconstruction to augment venous drainage when the flap appears congested despite a patent primary venous anastomosis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Gastrocnemius/soleus/reverse sural/ALT/gracilis/latissimus flaps", "question": "What is a chimeric (compound) flap, and give an example based on the subscapular system?", "answer": "A chimeric flap contains more than one tissue type linked together via a common regional source vessel, with tissue components that can be independently maneuvered while remaining attached. An example is the subscapular system chimeric flap, which can include: latissimus dorsi muscle, parascapular fasciocutaneous flap, scapular bone, and serratus anterior muscle -- all based on branches of the subscapular vascular system. This allows complex 3D defect reconstruction with multiple tissue types from a single donor site.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Free flap recipient vessels", "question": "What are the key considerations when evaluating recipient vessels for free tissue transfer?", "answer": "1) Proximity: recipient vessels should be close (deep or adjacent) to the wound. 2) Quality: vessels should be assessed for injury on preoperative angiogram or intraoperative inspection; use vessels outside the zone of injury for better outcomes. 3) Caliber: should approximate the flap vessels; if significant size mismatch exists, end-to-side anastomosis is an option. 4) Pedicle length: slight slack allows tension-free anastomosis in a comfortable orientation for the surgeon. 5) If no adequate vessels exist near the defect, consider vein grafts or AV loops. 6) In extremities, flow-through flaps should be considered if distal perfusion would be compromised.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Gastrocnemius/soleus/reverse sural/ALT/gracilis/latissimus flaps", "question": "Describe the ALT (anterolateral thigh) flap: its blood supply, perforator anatomy landmarks, and advantages.", "answer": "Blood supply: descending branch of the lateral circumflex femoral artery. Landmarks: draw a line from ASIS to superolateral patella border (overlying the septum between vastus lateralis and rectus femoris). Perforators are expected at the midpoint (or between 1/3 and 2/3 of this line), usually within a 3 cm radius, spaced about 5 cm apart. Perforators typically course through the vastus lateralis. Advantages: versatile (skin, fascia, muscle can be included), long pedicle, large skin paddle possible, donor site often primarily closable (less visible scar, hidden by clothing), and the flap can be harvested as a sensate flap.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Indications", "question": "What are the indications for free tissue transfer in reconstruction?", "answer": "Free flaps are used to close wounds and restore form and function in patients with traumatic, oncologic, or congenital defects. Specific indications include: 1) defects too large for local/regional flap coverage, 2) inadequate local tissue quality (radiation, scarring), 3) need for specialized tissue (bone, functional muscle, thin fasciocutaneous tissue), 4) complex 3D defects requiring tissue bulk, 5) lower extremity trauma with exposed bone/hardware, and 6) head and neck reconstruction after ablative surgery. With flap failure rates less than 2%, free tissue transfer is now performed with confidence.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Recipient vessel selection", "question": "What preoperative evaluation is important for recipient vessel selection in free tissue transfer?", "answer": "Preoperative angiography (traditional or image-based) may be required, especially when physical exam findings are abnormal or diseased/injured vessels are suspected. Ideal recipient vessels should be: 1) in close proximity to the defect, 2) outside the zone of injury in trauma cases (increases limb salvage rates), 3) of adequate caliber to match flap vessels, 4) of sufficient quality (not irradiated, atherosclerotic, or damaged). If planned vessels are inadequate, alternatives include vein grafts, AV loops, or selecting different recipient vessels. In extremities, assess need for flow-through flaps to maintain distal perfusion.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Arterial vs venous anastomosis", "question": "What is the order for removing clamps after completing arterial and venous free flap anastomoses?", "answer": "After completing both arterial and venous anastomoses: 1) Remove venous clamps FIRST to restore outflow. 2) Remove the DISTAL arterial clamp next and check backflow. Repair any leaks at this point. 3) Remove the PROXIMAL arterial clamp LAST. This sequence ensures that venous outflow is established before arterial inflow is restored, preventing acute venous congestion of the flap.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "End-to-end vs end-to-side", "question": "What are the indications for end-to-side versus end-to-end anastomosis in microsurgery?", "answer": "End-to-end anastomosis is appropriate for most arterial and venous anastomoses. End-to-side anastomosis may be necessary when: 1) limb reconstruction requires maintenance of distal perfusion through the recipient vessel, 2) significant size mismatch exists between donor and recipient vessels, or 3) the recipient vessel cannot be sacrificed. There is no difference in patency rate between end-to-end and end-to-side techniques. However, end-to-side anastomoses are technically more difficult, evidenced by longer mean ischemia times.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Coupler basics", "question": "How does an anastomotic coupler device work, and what are its indications and limitations?", "answer": "Anastomotic couplers simplify and expedite end-to-end venous anastomoses with patency rates equivalent to hand-sewn anastomoses. Technique: vessel ends are passed through polyethylene rings, everted, and secured on pins. The device approximates the rings, and interdigitating pins hold the vessel ends together, creating an automated anastomosis stented open by a soft plastic ring. Indications: primarily for venous anastomoses; can also be used on soft-walled arteries over 1 mm diameter. Size mismatch can be managed by differential pin placement. Limitation: should NOT be used on irradiated vessels.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Ischemia time", "question": "What are the ischemia tolerances for different tissue types during free flap transfer?", "answer": "Skin and subcutaneous tissue: viable for approximately 24 hours of ischemia. Muscle: irreversible microcirculation damage at approximately 6 hours without blood flow. Connective tissue (bone, cartilage): very low metabolic requirements, can withstand prolonged periods of hypoxia. Cooling prolongs ischemia tolerance for all tissue types. The no-reflow phenomenon can occur with prolonged ischemia: brisk initial inflow after anastomosis is followed by a sharp flow rate decline, triggering intravascular thrombosis despite technically excellent anastomosis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring", "question": "Describe the postoperative monitoring protocol for free flaps and the clinical signs of arterial vs venous compromise.", "answer": "Monitoring protocol: flap checks by experienced observer at least every 1 hour for first 48 hours, then every 2 hours until POD 5, then every 4 hours until discharge. Clinical evaluation includes color, capillary refill, turgor, and temperature. Arterial insufficiency: flap is cool, pale, and lacks capillary refill. Venous thrombosis: rapid capillary refill, swelling, and purple/dark discoloration. Adjuncts: handheld Doppler (perforator locations marked intraoperatively), implantable Doppler probes for buried flaps, surface temperature, pulse oximetry, near-infrared spectroscopy, IV fluorescein angiography. Note: Doppler signals may persist for several hours despite venous thrombosis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Arterial vs venous thrombosis", "question": "When is thrombosis most likely to occur after free flap surgery, and what is the overall salvage rate?", "answer": "Thrombosis is most common within 24 hours of surgery. Early failure is often related to anastomotic imperfections or pedicle positioning. The critical period for thrombus formation is the first 3 to 5 days, correlating with platelet dissipation and pseudointima formation. Approximately 50% of ailing free flaps can be salvaged overall. The success rate of salvage is inversely related to the time interval from onset of ischemia to restoration of blood flow, emphasizing the need for prompt recognition and timely intervention.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap salvage", "question": "Describe the take-back procedure for a compromised free flap.", "answer": "1) Inspect flap and patient for easily correctable issues (positioning, constrictive dressings, external compression). 2) Release inset sutures if pedicle compression suspected. 3) If clinical suspicion for thrombosis, proceed immediately to OR. 4) Elevate flap, inspect anastomosis. 5) Administer IV heparin (5000 units). 6) Take down anastomosis and perform mechanical thrombectomy with Fogarty catheter to remove entire thrombus. 7) Trim both donor and recipient vessels back to pristine intima. 8) Redo anastomosis (vein grafts if needed for tension-free repair). 9) Consider local thrombolytic infusion (tPA, streptokinase, urokinase) within the flap while isolated from systemic circulation. 10) If no recipient inflow, choose different recipient site.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Anticoagulation", "question": "What is the evidence regarding antithrombotic use in microsurgery, and what are the risks of dextran?", "answer": "The routine use of antithrombotics remains controversial. Multiple studies show postoperative antithrombotic use offers no protection from microvascular thrombosis and may increase complication rates. Despite this, 84% of surveyed surgeons use at least one antithrombotic. Specific agents: Heparin increases antithrombin-3 activity; aspirin irreversibly inactivates COX, blocking thromboxane A2; dextran decreases RBC aggregation. Dextran specifically has NO effect on flap survival but carries a 3.9- to 7.2-fold increase in systemic complications including renal failure, pulmonary edema, and congestive heart failure. Aspirin and heparin remain commonly used.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Donor-site morbidity", "question": "What patient factors affect free flap outcomes, and which is a proven risk factor for flap failure?", "answer": "Obesity is a proven risk factor: free flaps in obese patients are twice as likely to fail, with increased risks of seroma, delayed wound healing, and mastectomy flap necrosis. Age alone is NOT a contraindication (safe in children and elderly). Diabetes: animal models show poor intimal healing, but clinical studies show no difference in flap failure rate; strict glycemic control reduces surgical complications. Smoking: does NOT reduce anastomotic patency but affects wound healing, skin graft take, infection risk, flap necrosis, hernia formation, and hospital stay. Patients should quit smoking at least 4 weeks before surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Common free flaps (DIEP, MS-TRAM, fibula, radial forearm, ALT, scapular, latissimus, gracilis, PAP/TUG)", "question": "Compare the DIEP flap and TRAM flap for breast reconstruction in terms of blood supply and donor site morbidity.", "answer": "Both use lower abdominal skin/fat supplied by the deep inferior epigastric system. TRAM (transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous): harvests the rectus muscle with the overlying skin paddle; can be pedicled (on superior epigastric) or free (on deep inferior epigastric). Greater donor morbidity: abdominal weakness, bulge, and hernia are specific complications. DIEP (deep inferior epigastric perforator): harvests skin and fat on perforators from the deep inferior epigastric vessels WITHOUT sacrificing rectus muscle or fascia. Anterior rectus fascia can often be closed primarily (some reinforce with mesh). Decreased donor morbidity while maintaining equivalent flap vascularity. The more reliable blood supply is the deep inferior epigastric system entering the inferior muscle.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Common free flaps (DIEP, MS-TRAM, fibula, radial forearm, ALT, scapular, latissimus, gracilis, PAP/TUG)", "question": "When are leeches indicated in microsurgery, and what prophylactic antibiotic is needed?", "answer": "Leeches (Hirudo medicinalis) are indicated for flaps with venous congestion DESPITE a patent venous anastomosis -- i.e., good inflow but limited drainage. They should NOT replace reexploration of the venous anastomosis if patency is in question. Leeches are applied directly to the flap, consume several mL of blood per feeding, and fall off at satiety. They also inject hirudin (an anticoagulant) which promotes continued bleeding after detachment. Prophylaxis against Aeromonas hydrophila is necessary because this organism routinely inhabits the digestive tract of leeches.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG", "question": "Compare split-thickness (STSG) and full-thickness (FTSG) skin grafts in terms of composition, contraction, durability, and metabolic demand.", "answer": "STSG: contains epidermis and partial dermis (0.005-0.030 inches; thin/medium/thick). Less primary contraction (10-20% area loss), MORE secondary contraction (myofibroblast-mediated), more fragile after healing, more pigment changes, lower metabolic demand, higher chance of complete graft take. FTSG: contains epidermis and entire dermis. MORE primary contraction (~40% area loss due to dermal elastin recoil), LESS secondary contraction, more durable/less fragile once healed, higher metabolic demand on wound bed, slightly lower chance of complete survival. FTSGs are favored over joints where mobility is needed. FTSGs generally do not lose hair follicles or sweat glands.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Sheet vs meshed grafts", "question": "What is the purpose of meshing a skin graft, and how does it compare to pie-crusting?", "answer": "Meshing uses a hand-driven roller instrument to create uniform slits throughout the graft. Purposes: 1) allows drainage of fluid (prevents hematoma/seroma accumulation under graft), 2) permits expansion of the graft to cover a larger surface area (up to 1:9 expansion for meshed STSG, vs 1:5 for FTSG). Pie-crusting uses a scalpel to create multiple small fenestrations for similar fluid drainage purposes but without significant expansion capability. Sheet (unmeshed) grafts provide superior cosmetic results but are more susceptible to fluid collection underneath. Both techniques help avoid fluid buildup that interferes with revascularization and graft take.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take (imbibition/inosculation/revascularization)", "question": "Describe the three classic phases of skin graft take and the timeline for each.", "answer": "1) Imbibition (0-48 hours): Plasma leaks from wound bed capillaries into the interface; fibrinogen converts to fibrin (adhering graft to bed). Graft becomes edematous, gaining up to 40% of weight. Metabolism becomes anaerobic, pH falls to 6.8, ATP drops 70%, glucose drops 80%. 2) Inosculation (48-72 hours): Historically described as wound bed vessels connecting with graft vessels at the interface; now understood as early angiogenic ingrowth from wound bed into graft. Capillary-sized vessels (10-11 um) grow through fibrin interface. 3) Revascularization (>96 hours): Continued angiogenesis with vessel ingrowth using preexisting graft vasculature as conduits. Full revascularization by day 10. Peak vessel density at graft interface occurs at day 7.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Causes of graft loss", "question": "What are the common causes of skin graft failure?", "answer": "1) Hematoma - fluid collection lifts graft from bed, preventing revascularization. 2) Seroma - same mechanism as hematoma. 3) Infection - bacterial loads >10^5 organisms/gram of tissue predict graft failure (Robson and Krizek). 4) Shear forces - disrupt fibrin adhesion and fragile new vascular connections. 5) Poorly vascularized wound bed - exposed bone/tendon without periosteum/paratenon cannot support graft take. 6) Medical comorbidities - diabetes (grafts take ~2 weeks longer), peripheral vascular disease, radiation history. 7) Inherent graft properties - thicker grafts have greater metabolic demands and require more vessel ingrowth distance.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Donor sites", "question": "What are the common donor sites for STSG and FTSG, and what determines donor site selection?", "answer": "STSG donors: lateral thigh (most common - ease of harvest/dressing), buttocks (less visible scarring), scalp (minimal morbidity, no visible scar after hair regrows, but requires shaving). FTSG donors: inguinal creases, postauricular region, supraclavicular area. Selection factors: color match (especially important for head/neck - grafts above clavicles preferred), size of graft needed, donor site morbidity (STSG heals by secondary intention; FTSG requires primary closure, limiting graft size), visibility of donor scar, and patient preference.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Bolster dressings", "question": "What are the options for skin graft fixation and bolster dressing, and when is the initial dressing removed?", "answer": "1) Tie-over bolster: xeroform sheet filled with mineral oil-soaked cotton balls, common for smaller grafts. 2) Negative-pressure wound therapy (VAC): increasingly popular for larger grafts, mobile areas, or difficult-to-bolster locations (hand, axilla); allows patient mobility but requires carrying the device. 3) Spray fibrin sealants (Evicel, Artiss): secure graft edges and increase adherence; offer immediate mobility and minimal dressings but are costly and work best on thin STSGs. The initial dressing is typically removed at approximately 1 week, once graft adherence is more secure and revascularization has begun. Local wound care continues until graft maturity at 3-4 weeks.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Grafts over tendon/bone/cartilage/hardware", "question": "Can skin grafts be placed directly over exposed bone, tendon, or hardware? What is required for graft take?", "answer": "Skin grafts require a vascularized wound bed for successful take. Exposed bone without periosteum, tendon without paratenon, and exposed hardware are NOT appropriate for direct skin grafting because they lack the vascular bed needed for graft revascularization. These wounds need to be optimized with well-vascularized tissue (flap coverage or granulation tissue). However, if viable paratenon or periosteum is present, grafting may succeed. Dermal substitutes like Integra, especially combined with negative-pressure wound therapy, can generate granulation tissue even over bone, tendon, and hardware, potentially creating a graftable surface as a bridging therapy.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Dermal substitutes and biologic matrices", "question": "Describe Integra dermal regeneration template: its composition, healing phases, and clinical application.", "answer": "Composition: bilaminar membrane with (1) a porous coprecipitate of bovine tendon type I collagen and shark glycosaminoglycan (chondroitin-6-sulfate) and (2) a temporary silicone epidermal substitute. The silicone prevents moisture loss and granulation tissue on the surface. Chondroitin-6-sulfate provides elasticity, controls biodegradation rate, and maintains open pore structure for cell migration. Healing phases: 1) Imbibition - matrix fills with wound fluid, fibrin fosters adherence. 2) Fibroblast migration - myofibroblasts start migrating by day 7, producing collagen by week 3. 3) Neovascularization - new blood vessels in deep matrix by day 12, reaching surface by day 28. 4) Remodeling/maturation. A thin STSG may be applied once vascularized (typically ~4 weeks; accelerated to 1 week with negative-pressure therapy).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG", "question": "Why are full-thickness skin grafts preferred for wounds overlying joint surfaces?", "answer": "Full-thickness grafts undergo LESS secondary contraction (the myofibroblast-mediated contraction during graft healing) compared to split-thickness grafts, because the thicker dermal component inhibits wound contraction. This is critical over joints because secondary contraction can cause significant limitations in stretch and mobility, leading to joint contracture and limited range of motion. Additionally, once wound contraction is complete, full-thickness grafts are able to grow with the surrounding tissue, whereas split-thickness grafts remain fixed. Full-thickness grafts are also more durable and less susceptible to subsequent trauma.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take (imbibition/inosculation/revascularization)", "question": "What is the current understanding of the mechanism of skin graft revascularization?", "answer": "The current model (supported by in vivo mouse models by Lindenblatt et al.) shows that angiogenesis is the primary mechanism: 1) Wound bed capillaries widen (10.6 to 15.9 um) with early bud formation starting at 24 hours. 2) New capillary vessels grow from wound bed through the fibrin interface into the graft. 3) Preexisting graft vasculature acts as conduits for ingrowth, not just passive channels -- graft vessels show a temporary angiogenic response (days 3-8) with buds containing endothelial cells and pericytes that serve as docking points. 4) Matrix metalloproteinases MT1-MMP and MMP-2 facilitate vascular connections. 5) By day 10, peripheral graft vessels are ~100% replaced by host vessels; central vessels are 50-60% replaced. The traditional concept of direct end-to-end inosculation is no longer considered valid.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Pectoralis major", "question": "Describe the pectoralis major flap: its blood supply classification, origins, and primary clinical uses.", "answer": "Blood supply: Mathes and Nahai Type V (one dominant pedicle + secondary segmental pedicles). Dominant: thoracoacromial artery. Segmental: perforators of the internal thoracic, intercostal, and lateral thoracic arteries. The muscle has two portions: clavicular (origin: clavicle, insertion: humerus) and sternocostal (origin: sternum and costal cartilages 1-6, insertion: external oblique aponeurosis). Primary uses: 1) Sternal wound reconstruction (workhorse since 1968) -- unilateral or bilateral advancement, or turnover flap on medial intercostal perforators. 2) Head and neck reconstruction -- rotated on thoracoacromial pedicle with skin paddle; a fast, reliable salvage option. Can include 5th rib for mandible reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Latissimus dorsi", "question": "Describe the latissimus dorsi flap: blood supply, muscle characteristics, and key surgical considerations.", "answer": "Blood supply: Mathes and Nahai Type V. Dominant pedicle: thoracodorsal artery (terminal branch of subscapular artery off axillary artery). Segmental: medial posterior thoracic intercostal and lumbar perforators. Muscle: broad, fan-shaped; origin from posterior iliac crest and lower 6 vertebrae; inserts into humerus forming posterior axillary fold. Versatility: pedicled for head/neck and anterior trunk defects; free transfer anywhere. Long vascular pedicle, large surface area, ease of harvest. Key considerations: 1) Thoracodorsal nerve should be divided to prevent unsightly flap motion. 2) Previous axillary dissection may interrupt pedicle -- can rely on serratus branch. 3) Donor site prone to seroma; use drains/quilting sutures. 4) For breast reconstruction, often needs implant for volume. 5) Shoulder function may be impaired but ADLs usually preserved.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Rectus abdominis/VRAM", "question": "What is the difference between a VRAM and TRAM flap, and what is the most common complication of rectus-based flaps?", "answer": "Both are based on the rectus abdominis muscle (Mathes and Nahai Type III -- two dominant pedicles: deep inferior epigastric and superior epigastric). VRAM (vertical rectus abdominis myocutaneous): skin island oriented vertically, commonly used for pelvic/perineal reconstruction. TRAM (transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous): skin island oriented transversely, the workhorse for breast reconstruction. Both can be pedicled (superiorly based on superior epigastric) or free (on deep inferior epigastric -- the more reliable blood supply). The most specific complications are abdominal weakness, bulge, and hernia from fascial/muscle harvest. Fascia may need reconstruction with mesh or biologic matrix.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Gracilis", "question": "Describe the gracilis flap, its blood supply, and its main clinical applications.", "answer": "Blood supply: Mathes and Nahai Type II (one dominant pedicle + minor pedicles). Dominant pedicle: medial femoral circumflex vessels (branch of profunda femoris), entering approximately 10 cm distal to the ischium. The gracilis is located 2-3 cm posterior to the palpable adductor longus in frog-leg position. Applications: 1) Muscle alone for perineal defects. 2) With obturator nerve branch for functional muscle transfer (facial reanimation). 3) With overlying skin as TUG (transverse upper gracilis) or DUG (diagonal upper gracilis) for breast reconstruction. The PAP (profunda artery perforator) flap is a nearby alternative using profunda femoris perforators without the gracilis muscle. Donor site considerations: avoid damaging greater saphenous vein; resuspend fascia to prevent labial distortion.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Gastrocnemius/soleus", "question": "What Mathes and Nahai type are the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles, and what region of the leg does each cover?", "answer": "Gastrocnemius: Mathes and Nahai Type I (one dominant vascular pedicle -- sural arteries from the popliteal artery). Most commonly used for coverage of proximal third and middle third tibial defects. The medial head is larger and more commonly used than the lateral head. Soleus: Mathes and Nahai Type II (one dominant pedicle + minor pedicles). Used for coverage of middle third tibial defects. The proximal portion is most reliable. Both muscles conform well to irregular wound beds and are workhorses for soft tissue coverage of the proximal and middle leg with exposed bone or hardware.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Radial forearm", "question": "Describe the radial forearm flap, its versatility, and key preoperative requirements.", "answer": "The radial forearm is a fasciocutaneous flap providing thin, pliable tissue with robust, reliable vascularity. Blood supply: radial artery sending multiple septocutaneous perforators between brachioradialis and flexor carpi radialis (Cormack and Lamberty Type C). Venous drainage: superficial system (cephalic vein) and deep system (venae comitantes of radial artery -- more reliably drains flap tissue). Versatile uses: intraoral, penile/urethral, extremity reconstruction; can be used as sensate flap, reversed (retrograde), flow-through, adipofascial, with partial radius bone, or with palmaris longus tendon for functional reconstruction. Key preoperative requirement: Allen test must confirm complete palmar arch communication between ulnar and radial arteries. Donor site limitation: often requires skin graft for closure; visible donor scar.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Groin flap", "question": "What are the groin and SCIA (superficial circumflex iliac artery) flaps, and what nearby flaps should be known in this region?", "answer": "The groin flap is based on the superficial circumflex iliac artery (SCIA) system. It provides skin and subcutaneous tissue from the inguinal/groin region. Historically used as a pedicled flap for hand reconstruction (cross-groin flap requiring a second stage for pedicle division). It can also be used as a free flap. Nearby flaps in this region include: 1) Rubens flap (based on the deep circumflex iliac artery -- DCIA), which can include iliac crest bone, and 2) SIEA (superficial inferior epigastric artery) flap for lower abdominal tissue transfer, though reliability of the SIEA vessels is less assured.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Temporalis", "question": "What is the Mathes and Nahai classification of the temporalis muscle, and what are its clinical applications?", "answer": "The temporalis muscle is Mathes and Nahai Type II (one dominant pedicle + minor pedicles). It is supplied by the deep temporal arteries (branches of the internal maxillary artery). Clinical applications include: 1) regional coverage of cranial and orbital defects, 2) facial reanimation (temporalis tendon transfer for smile reconstruction), and 3) reconstruction of maxillary and orbital floor defects. Its proximity to the face makes it a valuable regional flap for head reconstruction, though its bulk is limited compared to larger muscle flaps.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Regional and pedicled flaps", "subtopic": "Cross-finger/thenar flaps", "question": "What are cross-finger and thenar flaps, and when are they indicated?", "answer": "Cross-finger and thenar flaps are local/regional flaps used for soft tissue coverage of digital defects, particularly fingertip injuries with exposed bone or tendon. Cross-finger flap: skin and subcutaneous tissue from the dorsum of an adjacent finger is raised and transposed to cover a volar or dorsal defect on the injured finger. Requires a second stage (typically 2-3 weeks later) for pedicle division. Thenar flap: skin from the thenar eminence is used to cover fingertip defects; the injured finger is flexed and sutured to the thenar donor site, with pedicle division at a second stage. Both are indicated when local tissue is insufficient for primary repair and provide durable, well-vascularized coverage for small digital wounds.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "What are the Sunderland classifications of peripheral nerve injury, and which degrees require surgical intervention?", "answer": "Sunderland classifies nerve injuries into 5 degrees (plus a 6th by Mackinnon/Dellon). 1st degree (neurapraxia): demyelination only, full spontaneous recovery in 6-8 weeks. 2nd degree: axon disrupted but endoneurium intact, full recovery at 1-3 mm/day. 3rd degree: endoneurium disrupted but perineurium intact, partial recovery. 4th degree: only epineurium intact, no spontaneous recovery - surgery required. 5th degree (neurotmesis): complete transection of all layers - surgery required. 6th degree: mixed injury pattern with variable recovery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "What is the rate of axonal regeneration, and what is the clinical significance of the Tinel sign in tracking nerve recovery?", "answer": "Axonal regeneration proceeds at approximately 1-3 mm per day (slightly more than 1 inch per month). A positive Tinel sign is elicited by tapping along the course of a peripheral nerve, producing an electric shock or pins-and-needles sensation at the site of regenerating axons. Distal migration of the Tinel sign over weeks demonstrates ongoing regeneration. Muscle fibers undergo irreversible loss of neuromuscular junctions if not reinnervated within 1-2 years, whereas sensory end organs can be reinnervated years later.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "When is nerve autograft preferred over conduit or allograft for nerve gap reconstruction, and what are the common donor nerves?", "answer": "Autologous nerve graft is the gold standard for motor nerve defects or any nerve gap >3 cm. Conduits and decellularized allografts are acceptable only for sensory nerve defects <3 cm in small-diameter nerves (or <0.5 cm in large-diameter nerves). Common autograft donors: sural nerve (30-40 cm per leg), medial antebrachial cutaneous nerve (up to 20 cm), and lateral antebrachial cutaneous nerve (up to 8 cm). Grafts should be 10-20% longer than the defect to account for fibrosis-related shortening and placed in reversed orientation to prevent axon loss down side branches.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "What is the Oberlin transfer, and when are nerve transfers preferred over grafting?", "answer": "The Oberlin transfer involves transferring the flexor carpi ulnaris fascicle of the ulnar nerve to the biceps branch of the musculocutaneous nerve to restore elbow flexion after brachial plexus injury. Nerve transfers are preferred for proximal injuries where the distance to target muscles is too great for timely reinnervation (risk of irreversible motor end plate loss within 1-2 years). Ideal donor nerves have a high quantity of motor axons, proximity to the target muscle, and synergy of muscle function.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "What are the key principles of primary nerve repair, and within what timeframe should it ideally be performed?", "answer": "Primary tensionless repair should be performed within 2-3 days of a clean laceration. Key principles: (1) tension-free coaptation (excessive tension causes endoneurial blood supply compromise, necrosis, and fibrosis); (2) proper fascicular alignment using epineurial vascular landmarks; (3) direct stimulation of distal motor fascicles can aid alignment if done within 72 hours (after which neurotransmitters deplete); (4) epineurial repair with 9-0 or 10-0 microsutures; (5) fewest number of sutures to decrease iatrogenic harm; (6) fascicles should be 'kissing' not bulging.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "What EMG/NCS findings distinguish different degrees of nerve injury, and when do fibrillations and positive sharp waves (PSWs) appear?", "answer": "1st degree (neurapraxia): decreased conduction velocity and increased latency on NCS, normal EMG. 2nd-3rd degree: fibrillations and PSWs appear on EMG (PSWs as early as 3 weeks, fibrillations around 6 weeks post-injury), with MUPs reappearing around 12 weeks via collateral sprouting. 4th-5th degree: fibrillations and PSWs present but no MUPs due to complete axonal discontinuity. Small/absent CMAP amplitudes indicate axon loss. If no recovery signs on EMG/NCS by 3-6 months, surgical exploration is indicated.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Peripheral nerve injuries: nerve repair principles, nerve gaps, conduits, grafting, sensory/motor recovery grading", "question": "In crush or avulsion nerve injuries where the zone of injury is unclear, what is the recommended management strategy?", "answer": "When the zone of injury is unclear (crush/avulsion), the nerve should NOT be repaired acutely. Instead: (1) debride devitalized tissue; (2) tack the two nerve ends to surrounding structures to prevent retraction; (3) allow at least 3 weeks for demarcation of the injury zone. At re-exploration, excise the proximal neuroma in bread-loaf fashion until a healthy fascicular pattern is seen; similarly debride the distal stump. The resultant defect is then repaired primarily (if possible) or reconstructed with nerve graft.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine/bupivacaine/epinephrine", "question": "What are the maximum doses of lidocaine with and without epinephrine, and how does tumescent technique alter safe dosing?", "answer": "Lidocaine: 300 mg without epinephrine, 500 mg with epinephrine. Bupivacaine: 175 mg without epinephrine, 225 mg with epinephrine. In tumescent technique (highly dilute lidocaine with epinephrine 1:500,000-1:100,000 in saline/LR), doses up to 35 mg/kg lidocaine are routinely and safely administered for liposuction of the trunk/extremities. However, the manufacturer-recommended maximum remains 7 mg/kg. Peak serum lidocaine levels may occur 10-14 hours post-injection in tumescent cases, and only ~20% of infiltrated local anesthetic is removed with lipoaspirate.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "LAST recognition", "question": "What are the signs and treatment of local anesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST)?", "answer": "CNS toxicity (lower dose threshold): light-headedness, tinnitus, tremors, lip/tongue numbness, restlessness, seizures, apnea, loss of consciousness. CVS toxicity (higher dose, more dangerous): hypotension, tachycardia/bradycardia, arrhythmias, cardiac arrest. Bupivacaine is particularly dangerous due to myocardial affinity and long half-life. Treatment: (1) Airway control with 100% FiO2; (2) hyperventilation to alter seizure threshold; (3) diazepam 0.1 mg/kg or thiopental 2 mg/kg for seizures; (4) IV fluids and vasopressors for hypotension; (5) Intralipid 20% lipid emulsion bolus of 1.5 mL/kg followed by continuous infusion (acts as 'lipid sink').", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Digital/field/ring blocks", "question": "How is a complete hand block performed at the wrist level, and what are the key anatomic landmarks?", "answer": "Complete hand anesthesia requires blocking three nerves at the wrist: (1) Median nerve: inject on the ulnar side of the palmaris longus tendon at the proximal wrist crease (5-10 cc into carpal tunnel); (2) Ulnar nerve: inject deep to the flexor carpi ulnaris tendon, proximal to the hook of hamate, advancing needle ulnar-to-radial (1-3 cc, aspirate to avoid ulnar artery injection); (3) Superficial radial nerve: diffusely infiltrate the dorsoradial aspect of the wrist from the ulnar styloid dorsally to mid-dorsal wrist (3-10 cc). Digital blocks are performed by infiltrating each digital nerve at the volar-lateral surface of the proximal phalanx.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "WALANT principles", "question": "Is epinephrine safe for use in digital anesthesia, and what is the reversal agent if ischemia is prolonged?", "answer": "Yes, epinephrine is now considered safe for digital anesthesia. Multiple large studies (including the Dalhousie Project with 3,110 consecutive cases) have demonstrated the safety and efficacy of epinephrine in the fingers and hand. Benefits include improved visualization and reduced need for painful tourniquet use. If concern for prolonged digital ischemia persists, phentolamine can be used as a reversal agent. However, this is usually unnecessary; simple observation and elevation of the extremity are typically sufficient, as perfusion returns as the epinephrine wears off.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine/bupivacaine/epinephrine", "question": "How are local anesthetics classified by chemical structure, and how does this affect metabolism and allergenicity?", "answer": "Local anesthetics are classified as esters or amides based on their chemical linkage. Esters (procaine, chloroprocaine, tetracaine, cocaine) are metabolized by plasma pseudocholinesterase. Amides (lidocaine, mepivacaine, prilocaine, bupivacaine, etidocaine) are metabolized in the liver. True allergic reactions are exceedingly rare; most 'allergies' are reactions to preservatives such as para-aminobenzoic acid (PABA). When true allergy occurs, esters are more commonly implicated than amides. The mechanism of action is inhibition of sodium channels via passive diffusion, which explains poor efficacy in inflamed (acidic) tissue.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia", "question": "What is the TAP block, and what are its clinical applications in plastic surgery?", "answer": "The transversus abdominis plane (TAP) block anesthetizes the intercostal nerves in the lateral abdominal wall by infiltrating local anesthetic in the plane between the internal oblique muscle and the transversus abdominis muscle under ultrasound guidance. Applications include abdominoplasty, hernia repair, and DIEP flap harvest. TAP block has been shown to improve postoperative pain control and augment early mobilization. This is important because DVT risk is theoretically increased in abdominal procedures due to pain-limited mobility and increased inferior vena cava pressure.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic consult mindset", "subtopic": "Body dysmorphic disorder", "question": "What is body dysmorphic disorder (BDD), what is its prevalence in cosmetic surgery patients, and why is surgery contraindicated?", "answer": "BDD is an obsessive-compulsive related disorder (DSM-5) with four diagnostic criteria: (1) preoccupation with perceived flaws that appear minimal/normal to others; (2) preoccupation hinders functioning (social, professional); (3) repetitive behaviors (mirror checking, manipulation of feature); (4) no better-suited diagnosis. Prevalence: 1.9% in general population but 6-33% in cosmetic surgery patients (higher in rhinoplasty). Surgeons underestimate prevalence (9.7% screened positive but only 4.0% raised suspicion). Surgery is contraindicated because the complaint is psychiatric, not physical; surgery provides no benefit and may exacerbate the condition, leading to dissatisfaction, litigation, or even violence.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic consult mindset", "subtopic": "Expectations management", "question": "What framework should a plastic surgeon use to evaluate patient suitability for aesthetic surgery?", "answer": "Three key variables must be assessed: (1) the presenting complaint (e.g., dorsal hump, scar); (2) the patient's attitude toward the feature (level of concern, impact on quality of life, source of concern - self-motivated vs. external pressure); (3) amount of motivation for surgery. These are evaluated against the surgeon's objective assessment and skill set. 'Satisfaction = result / expectation' - expectations must be clearly defined. The SIMON acronym (Single, Immature, Male, Overly expectant, Narcissistic) identifies high-risk patients, especially in rhinoplasty. Red flags include secondary gain motivations, controlling significant others, and desire to comply with social trends against personal preferences.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic consult mindset", "subtopic": "Patient selection", "question": "What are the warning signs of borderline personality disorder (BPD) in aesthetic surgery patients, and how should these patients be managed?", "answer": "BPD prevalence is up to 9% in the plastic surgery population. Warning signs: female gender, age early 20s-30s, history of psychiatric disorders (especially depression), adverse childhood events, multiple procedures with doctor shopping, self-harm behavior (cutting, burning), tattoos and multiple piercings, dissatisfaction/anger toward previous surgeons, splitting phenomenon toward surgeon or staff, and concern with multiple body parts that shifts over time. Surgery is contraindicated due to extremely poor satisfaction rates. Management: empathetic approach, steer toward mental health care rather than outright refusal; avoid direct confrontation which leads to an angry patient who moves to the next practice.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic consult mindset", "subtopic": "Informed consent", "question": "What are the key principles of informed consent and complication disclosure in aesthetic surgery?", "answer": "Informed consent requires: (1) face-to-face discussion with the patient; (2) review of all risks, benefits, and alternatives (including non-surgical and not undergoing the procedure); (3) ample time for questions; (4) the consenting physician must be able to perform the procedure. Early education about potential complications decreases postoperative dissatisfaction if adverse events occur. Lack of informed consent is a frequent cause of legal action after claims for poor outcomes. After complications, frequent postoperative visits, time spent face-to-face, and honest efforts to rectify the situation can salvage patient expectations. A minor needs only one parent's signature for consent to be valid.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic consult mindset", "subtopic": "Revision surgery ethics", "question": "How should a surgeon manage an adverse outcome or dissatisfied patient in aesthetic surgery, particularly one with unrecognized psychiatric comorbidity?", "answer": "The cornerstone of managing adverse outcomes is empathetic care: frequent postoperative visits, face-to-face time, and honest efforts to rectify the situation. This approach can salvage patient expectations and even yield positive reviews despite complications. For patients with personality disorders or unrealistic expectations discovered postoperatively, treat the underlying psychiatric issue - involve a mental health professional sooner rather than later. Thorough documentation is critical for defense against litigation. The majority of malpractice cases are won by the physician, but proactive documentation and informed consent practices are essential.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What is the Caprini score, and what are the key DVT prophylaxis measures in plastic surgery?", "answer": "The 2005 Caprini risk-assessment model is a validated tool for VTE risk stratification in plastic and reconstructive surgery patients. It guides appropriate mechanical and chemical prophylaxis decisions. Key DVT prophylaxis measures: (1) Intermittent pneumatic compression devices must be on and functioning at least 30 minutes prior to induction of anesthesia; (2) Early ambulation - the single best preventative measure - encouraged on the evening of surgery if safe; (3) Chemical prophylaxis based on Caprini score. Increased operative time is linked to higher thrombotic event rates.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Antibiotic timing", "question": "What are the guidelines for preoperative antibiotic prophylaxis in plastic surgery, including timing, dosing, and redosing?", "answer": "Cefazolin is the first-line agent: 2 g (3 g if >120 kg), given 30-60 minutes before skin incision, half-life 2 hours. Clindamycin (900 mg, 60 min before, t1/2 3 hours) for true cephalosporin allergy. Vancomycin (15 mg/kg, given 2 hours before, t1/2 6 hours) reserved for MRSA-colonized patients. Redosing: every 2 half-lives or for blood loss >1500 mL. No data justify prophylactic antibiotics beyond 24 hours. Chlorhexidine-alcohol is preferred over povidone-iodine for skin antisepsis. Shaving the site the day before surgery increases SSI risk; shave at least 2 days preoperatively or use clippers.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Time-out/site marking", "question": "What is the Joint Commission Universal Protocol, and what key patient safety measures are mandated perioperatively?", "answer": "The Joint Commission Universal Protocol is a nationally mandated process requiring proper time-out before any surgical procedure. The team must verify: correct patient, correct site, and correct side (laterality). Additional safety measures include: (1) day-of-surgery pregnancy test in women of childbearing age; (2) communication between surgeon, anesthesia, and nursing staff; (3) proper patient positioning (knees flexed 15 degrees, shoulders abducted no more than 90 degrees, eyes protected when prone); (4) normothermia maintenance (hypothermia defined as <36 degrees C is an independent risk factor for bleeding and wound complications); (5) prewarming with forced warm air for at least 15 minutes.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Tourniquet safety", "question": "What modifiable risk factors should be optimized before elective plastic surgery, and what is the recommended nicotine-free period?", "answer": "Key modifiable risk factors: (1) Nicotine use: at least 4 weeks nicotine-free before surgery (including vaping, dip, cessation products); urine cotinine test can verify compliance. (2) BMI: optimize preoperatively; BMI >35 kg/m2 increases complication risk for chest/trunk procedures. (3) Diabetes: HbA1c >6.5% is associated with increased postoperative complications. (4) MRSA: high-risk patients should be screened and undergo decolonization (5 days nasal mupirocin + chlorhexidine baths). (5) Nutrition status. The surgeon should not proceed until modifiable factors are optimized.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Pressure injury prevention", "question": "What are the key principles of intraoperative patient positioning, temperature management, and fluid balance in plastic surgery?", "answer": "Positioning: pad bony prominences to prevent pressure nerve injury; knees gently flexed 15 degrees; shoulders abducted no more than 90 degrees; protect eyes when prone; coordinate intraoperative position changes carefully. Temperature: hypothermia (<36 degrees C) increases bleeding and wound complications; prewarm with forced warm air for at least 15 minutes; maintain ambient room temperature at least 21 degrees C; use warm IV/irrigation fluids. Fluid balance: balanced fluid management is optimal; target urine output 30-50 mL/h if Foley present; remove Foley within 48 hours.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Blood loss estimation", "question": "What are the transfusion thresholds and cardiac risk assessment guidelines relevant to plastic surgery patients?", "answer": "Transfusion: indicated for all patients with hemoglobin <7 g/dL; above this threshold, consider for symptomatic anemia or cardiac history patients. Preoperative anemia (WHO/CDC: <13 g/dL male, <12 g/dL female) increases morbidity/mortality; most common cause is iron deficiency. Cardiac: plastic surgery is generally low-risk (<1% major adverse cardiac event). No preoperative cardiac testing needed for patients undergoing low-risk surgery or those who can perform >4 METs (light housework, climbing one flight of stairs). After drug-eluting stent with STEMI, minimum 1 year of DAPT before elective surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Levels of evidence", "question": "What are the major study designs in clinical research, and how do they rank in the hierarchy of evidence?", "answer": "From highest to lowest evidence: (1) Randomized controlled trials (RCTs) - gold standard; randomization balances measured and unmeasured confounders, enabling causal inference. (2) Cohort studies - prospective or retrospective; can establish incidence and temporal relationships. (3) Case-control studies - good for rare outcomes; match cases to controls and compare exposures (can only calculate odds ratios, not relative risk). (4) Cross-sectional studies - single snapshot in time; determine prevalence but cannot establish sequence of events. A meta-analysis of level 3 evidence papers cannot exceed level 3 evidence regardless of how well the meta-analysis is performed.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Basic biostatistics", "question": "What is the difference between Type I and Type II errors, and how do alpha, beta, and power relate to study design?", "answer": "Type I error (alpha error): incorrectly rejecting the null hypothesis (false positive), saying a difference exists when it does not. Alpha is conventionally set at 0.05 (5%). Type II error (beta error): incorrectly accepting the null hypothesis (false negative), missing a true difference. Beta is conventionally set at 0.20. Power = 1 - beta (typically 0.80 or 80%) = probability of correctly detecting a true effect. Increasing sample size increases power. Four pieces needed for power calculation: event rate, smallest clinically important difference, power (usually 80%), and significance level (usually 0.05). Statistical significance does not equal clinical significance.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Basic biostatistics", "question": "When should each of the following statistical tests be used: t-test, ANOVA, chi-square, and Fisher's exact test?", "answer": "t-test: compares means of two groups; requires normally distributed (parametric) data. Independent t-test for two unrelated groups; paired t-test for same group at different times. ANOVA: compares means of three or more groups (extension of t-test); if significant, does not specify which groups differ - requires post hoc testing (Tukey, Dunnett). Chi-square: compares proportions of categorical/dichotomous data between groups. Fisher's exact test: like chi-square but used when sample size is small (often <30). Nonparametric equivalents: Mann-Whitney U (for independent t-test), Wilcoxon signed-rank (for paired t-test), Kruskal-Wallis (for ANOVA).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Basic biostatistics", "question": "What is the difference between sensitivity, specificity, positive predictive value, and negative predictive value?", "answer": "Using a 2x2 table (A=true positive, B=false positive, C=false negative, D=true negative): Sensitivity = A/(A+C) - ability to detect disease (true positive rate). Specificity = D/(D+B) - ability to identify true negatives. Positive predictive value (PPV) = A/(A+B) - probability that a positive test is truly positive. Negative predictive value (NPV) = D/(D+C) - probability that a negative test is truly negative. PPV and NPV are sensitive to disease prevalence: if disease is very rare, even a positive test is more likely to be a false positive.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Basic biostatistics", "question": "What are confounders, mediators, and moderators in research study design?", "answer": "Confounder: a variable independently associated with both the main exposure (predictor) AND the outcome, but NOT part of the causal pathway; it must be present before the outcome. It creates a spurious association. Can be controlled by randomization, stratification, or adjusted analysis. Mediator: a variable that is directly part of the causal pathway between predictor and outcome (e.g., smoking causes vasoconstriction causing poor wound healing - vasoconstriction is the mediator). Moderator (interaction term): changes the magnitude or direction of the effect the predictor has on the outcome (e.g., anticoagulation lessens the effect of smoking on wound healing). No empiric test distinguishes mediators from confounders.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Basic biostatistics", "question": "What is the difference between odds ratio, relative risk, absolute risk reduction, and number needed to treat?", "answer": "Relative risk (RR): compares incidence of disease between exposed and unexposed groups; used in prospective studies (cohort, RCTs) that follow patients over time. Odds ratio (OR): compares prevalence (odds of disease in exposed vs. unexposed); used in case-control studies and cross-sectional studies. Absolute risk reduction (ARR): quantifies how much risk decreases if the exposure is eliminated (control event rate minus experimental event rate). Number needed to treat (NNT) = 1/ARR: the number of patients who must be treated to prevent one adverse outcome. OR approximates RR when disease is rare.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "How to read a PRS article", "question": "What are the key differences between a priori and post hoc analyses, and what precautions apply to each?", "answer": "A priori analyses are planned before data collection and are considered the purest form of analysis; they minimize bias, determine sample size and power, and prevent inappropriate statistical fishing. Post hoc analyses are performed after data collection on findings not part of the original plan; they are hypothesis-generating only, NOT proof of a hypothesis. Post hoc findings must be clearly labeled in methods/results/discussion. Negative results from a well-powered a priori analysis are still important and publishable. Dangers of post hoc analysis include alpha error inflation and data dredging. The Bonferroni correction can reduce combined alpha value when multiple comparisons are made.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Evidence and research", "subtopic": "Quality improvement", "question": "What is intention-to-treat (ITT) analysis, and why is it the recommended standard per CONSORT guidelines?", "answer": "Intention-to-treat (ITT) analysis includes ALL originally enrolled participants in the final analysis, even those who did not complete the study or provide all outcome measurements. Missing data are estimated using imputation from observed values. ITT is recommended as standard practice per CONSORT guidelines because it: (1) eliminates potential post hoc or selection bias; (2) preserves the benefits of randomization; (3) reflects real-world conditions where patients may not comply. The trade-off is that ITT may dilute the intervention's true effect. Alternatives include per-protocol and as-treated analyses, but these introduce selection bias.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the NCCN recommended surgical margins for melanoma based on Breslow depth?", "answer": "Melanoma in situ (Tis): 0.5 cm margin. T1 (<=1.0 mm): 1.0 cm margin. T2 (1.0-2.0 mm): 1.0-2.0 cm margin. T3 (2.0-4.0 mm): 2.0 cm margin. T4 (>4.0 mm): 2.0 cm margin. Excision should include skin and subcutaneous fat down to but NOT including the fascia. Breslow depth is measured from the granular layer of the epidermis to the greatest depth of invasion using an ocular micrometer. It is the single best prognostic factor for tumor outcome and guides margin recommendations.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "SLNB", "question": "What are the indications for sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) in melanoma?", "answer": "SLNB is indicated for: (1) Stage I/II melanoma with Breslow depth 1.0-4.0 mm; (2) Thinner melanomas (0.76-1.0 mm) with high-risk features: ulceration, lymphovascular invasion, significant vertical growth phase, increased mitotic rate; (3) Tumors >4.0 mm with clinically negative nodes also benefit. SLNB is NOT indicated for melanoma <0.8 mm without ulceration or for patients with clinically palpable nodes (who should proceed directly to complete therapeutic lymph node dissection). Node status is the MOST important prognostic factor in melanoma staging. Stage IV melanoma has only 10-15% five-year survival.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "BCC", "question": "What are the subtypes and key features of basal cell carcinoma, and when is Mohs surgery indicated?", "answer": "BCC is the most common skin cancer in Caucasians, arising from pluripotent epidermal stem cells. It is locally aggressive with virtually no metastatic potential (no role for lymph node sampling). Two main categories: Circumscribed (nodular is most common, ~50% of all BCC, pink/red pearly papule) and Diffuse (superficial, micronodular, infiltrating, morpheaform). Morpheaform is the most aggressive - firm depressed plaque resembling a scar with invasion beyond visible edges. Mohs indications: high-failure-rate areas (periorbital, periauricular, nose), poorly defined borders, recurrent tumors, aggressive histologic subtypes (morpheaform, micronodular, basosquamous, infiltrating), perineural invasion, and areas needing tissue preservation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "SCC", "question": "What are the high-risk features of squamous cell carcinoma, and how does it differ from BCC in clinical behavior?", "answer": "Unlike BCC, SCC has metastatic potential requiring lymph node assessment. High-risk features: poorly defined borders, diameter >20 mm in Area L or >10 mm in Area M, recurrent tumors, arising in scars/RT sites/chronic inflammation, immunosuppression, poorly differentiated/undifferentiated histology, thickness >2 mm or Clark IV/V, perineural/lymphatic/vascular invasion, and desmoplastic or acantholytic subtypes. More aggressive sites include ear, lips, and mucosal surfaces. Palpable nodes require FNA biopsy. Actinic keratosis is a precursor with 0.06% per year transformation risk. SCC in situ (Bowen disease) presents as a scaly elevated plaque. Keratoacanthomas are considered SCC variants.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the five histological growth patterns of melanoma, and which carries the worst prognosis at diagnosis?", "answer": "1. Superficial spreading (most common): prolonged radial growth, occurs in sun-exposed areas. 2. Nodular (2nd most common, worst prognosis at diagnosis): dome-shaped dark lesion, early vertical growth, often on trunk/head/neck, typically more advanced at diagnosis. 3. Lentigo maligna: large tan lesions with convoluted patterns, low malignancy potential, more common in women on head/face/neck. 4. Acral-lentiginous (rarest in Caucasians but >30% in dark-skinned individuals): palms, soles, subungual - Hutchinson sign (longitudinal pigmented nail band). 5. Amelanotic (2-8% of invasive cases): lacks pigment, difficult to identify clinically, diagnosed later. Desmoplastic melanoma is aggressive locally but less likely to metastasize.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Merkel cell carcinoma", "question": "What are the key features, presentation, and management of Merkel cell carcinoma?", "answer": "Merkel cell carcinoma is a rare, aggressive neuroendocrine skin cancer affecting older (>50) fair-skinned individuals in sun-exposed areas. Presentation: solitary erythematous nodular lesion, most commonly on head and neck. It is aggressive like melanoma with 25-30% of patients having positive lymph nodes at initial presentation. Local recurrence rate is 40-45%. Staging depends on node involvement with SLNB indicated. Treatment: primary surgical excision with wide margins or Mohs micrographic surgery. Radiation therapy can be used as adjuvant therapy. Like melanoma, node status is critical for prognosis and staging.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins", "question": "What is Mohs micrographic surgery, and what are its primary indications for both BCC and SCC?", "answer": "Mohs uses serial saucer-like layers of tissue removal with intraoperative frozen section analysis of 100% of the surgical margin, creating a map for the surgeon to mark areas of residual tumor for further excision. This achieves highest cure rates while maximally preserving normal tissue. Indications: (1) Areas with high treatment failure rates (periorbital, periauricular, nose, paranasal); (2) Poorly delineated clinical borders or tumors in scar tissue; (3) Aggressive BCC subtypes (morpheaform, micronodular, basosquamous, infiltrating); (4) Aggressive SCC (Breslow >2 mm, poorly differentiated, perineural invasion); (5) Recurrent BCC/SCC; (6) Critical structures like eyelids; (7) DFSP and microcystic adnexal carcinoma.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Breslow depth", "question": "What is the ABCDE mnemonic for melanoma assessment, and how do Breslow depth and ulceration affect staging and prognosis?", "answer": "ABCDE: Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Color variation, Diameter >6 mm, Enlarging/Evolving. Breslow depth (measured from the granular layer to the deepest point of invasion using ocular micrometer) is the best prognostic indicator and directly determines T-stage: T1 <=1.0 mm, T2 1.0-2.0 mm, T3 2.0-4.0 mm, T4 >4.0 mm. Within each T category, ulceration and mitotic rate are modifiers indicating worse prognosis (mitotic rate is an independent predictor of survival). Specimens must be processed with standard stains (NOT frozen section) to prevent distortion and allow accurate Breslow measurement. Node status remains the single most important prognostic factor overall.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Burn depth (superficial/partial/full)", "question": "How do you differentiate superficial partial-thickness from deep partial-thickness burns on clinical examination?", "answer": "Superficial partial-thickness burns present with blisters that, when unroofed, reveal a pink, moist, edematous, painful, blanching base. Deep partial-thickness burns are whiter, have varying degrees of sensation and edema, and often do not demonstrate blanching or capillary refill. Superficial partial-thickness burns limited to the upper dermis often heal without grafting, whereas deep partial-thickness burns involving dermal appendages may require excision and autografting.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "TBSA estimation (Rule of 9s, Lund-Browder)", "question": "What are the common methods for estimating TBSA, and what special consideration applies to pediatric patients?", "answer": "The Lund-Browder chart is the oldest and historically most accurate method. The Rule of Nines is the most frequently used due to simplicity. The palmar method uses the patient's own palm as approximately 1% TBSA. Children have disproportionately larger heads relative to their legs, so a pediatric-specific chart (Lund-Browder) should be used. Obese patients have a relatively larger proportion of skin on their trunks.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Parkland formula", "question": "What is the Parkland formula, and how does the ABA consensus formula differ? What is the standard endpoint for titrating resuscitation?", "answer": "The Parkland formula is 4 mL x weight (kg) x %TBSA, with half given in the first 8 hours and the remainder over the next 16 hours using lactated Ringer solution. The ABA consensus formula is 2 mL x weight (kg) x %TBSA for adults. The standard endpoint is urine output of 0.5-1.0 mL/kg/hr and mean arterial pressure >65 mmHg. Urine output is the gold standard surrogate for end-organ perfusion. For pediatric patients, glucose (dextrose) should be added to prevent hypoglycemia.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Burn-center transfer indications", "question": "List the American Burn Association criteria for referral to a burn center.", "answer": "ABA burn center referral criteria include: (1) Partial-thickness burns >10% TBSA; (2) Burns involving face, hands, feet, genitalia, perineum, or major joints; (3) Third-degree burns in any age group; (4) Electrical burns including lightning; (5) Chemical burns; (6) Inhalation injury; (7) Burns with preexisting medical disorders complicating management; (8) Burns with concomitant trauma where burn poses greatest risk; (9) Burned children in hospitals without qualified pediatric personnel; (10) Burns requiring special social, emotional, or rehabilitative intervention.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Airway/inhalation injury", "question": "Describe the differences between supraglottic and subglottic inhalation injury, including diagnosis and treatment timelines.", "answer": "Supraglottic (upper airway) injury results from breathing hot air, causing epithelial edema and potential airway obstruction. Treatment is early endotracheal intubation with supportive ventilation; edema usually resolves in 48-72 hours (assessed by cuff leak or endoscopy). Subglottic injury results from inhaling toxic combustion products causing chemical pneumonitis similar to ARDS. Diagnosis is confirmed by bronchoscopy (findings may not be immediately evident on chest X-ray). Treatment is supportive mechanical ventilation, usually resolving over 5-10 days. High-flow percussive ventilation with inhaled heparin and acetylcysteine is a useful adjunct.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "CO and cyanide toxicity", "question": "How is carbon monoxide poisoning diagnosed and treated in burn patients?", "answer": "CO poisoning should be suspected with any inhalation injury. CO competes with oxygen at the hemoglobin binding site and is NOT detectable by pulse oximetry. Diagnosis is made by measuring carboxyhemoglobin (COHb) level at presentation. Treatment is 100% oxygen via nonrebreather mask or endotracheal tube, which reduces the half-life of CO from 4 hours to 40-60 minutes. After CO treatment, low FiO2 should be attempted to prevent oxidative damage to the pulmonary parenchyma.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Escharotomy vs fasciotomy", "question": "When is escharotomy indicated versus fasciotomy in a burn patient? What structures are at risk during escharotomy?", "answer": "Escharotomy is indicated for circumferential full-thickness burns causing compromised distal extremity perfusion or limited chest expansion/hypoventilation. Fasciotomy is indicated if neurovascular exam does not improve after adequate escharotomy, if muscle bulging is seen through fascia, or if compartment pressures are elevated (common in electrical injuries or large-volume resuscitation). During escharotomy, structures at risk include: the radial artery at the wrist, the ulnar nerve at the medial epicondyle, and the common peroneal nerve at the fibular neck. Incisions follow mid-axial lines except over the hand where they continue over the dorsal hand.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Topical antimicrobials", "question": "What is the standard topical antimicrobial approach for burn wounds, and when are silver-releasing dressings preferred?", "answer": "Topical antimicrobials are the standard of care for all burn wounds lacking an epidermal barrier, as the thermal injury destroys normal skin flora. Daily silver sulfadiazine with gauze is always reasonable, especially for evolving wounds or when daily debridement of eschar/necrotic tissue is needed. Silver-releasing dressings have sustained activity for up to 7 days and are preferred for more stable wounds, as they limit multiple painful debridements. They are especially suitable for superficial partial-thickness wounds managed as outpatient, particularly pediatric scald burns. Systemic antibiotics have no role in uninfected burns.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Split-thickness grafting", "question": "When should burn wounds be excised and grafted? What are the advantages of sheet grafts versus meshed grafts?", "answer": "Burns that will not heal within 3 weeks should be excised and autografted. Early excision generally refers to within 7-10 days; ultra-early excision within 72 hours may yield better results. Sheet (unmeshed) grafts provide the best long-term functional and aesthetic outcomes and should be standard for face, hands, feet, and most pediatric burns. Meshed grafts cover larger areas but have a reticulated appearance and more contracture. Sheet grafts require meticulous postop care; seromas/hematomas can be drained with an 18-gauge needle. Grafts are typically harvested at 10-12 thousandths of an inch; thinner for pediatric/geriatric patients.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Pediatric burns", "question": "What are the key differences in managing pediatric burn patients compared to adults?", "answer": "Key differences include: (1) Resuscitation fluids require added dextrose to prevent hypoglycemia; (2) TBSA estimation must account for larger head-to-leg ratio using pediatric-specific charts (Lund-Browder); (3) Skin grafts should be harvested thinner due to thinner reticular dermis; (4) Sheet grafts should be standard for most pediatric burns; (5) Silver-releasing dressings are especially suitable for outpatient management of superficial partial-thickness scald burns; (6) Burns >10% TBSA in children warrant ICU admission; (7) Abuse must be ruled out during initial evaluation; (8) Oxandrolone should be used cautiously in children <4 years of age.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Z-plasty", "question": "What are the theoretical gains in length for Z-plasty at various limb angles, and what is the classic configuration?", "answer": "Z-plasty gains based on limb angle: 30 degrees = 25% gain; 45 degrees = 50% gain; 60 degrees = 75% gain; 75 degrees = 100% gain; 90 degrees = 120% gain. The classic Z-plasty uses 60-degree angles with three equal limbs for a theoretical 75% lengthening. This balances the desired increase in length by using available lateral skin laxity. Z-plasty can lengthen a scar, redirect a scar, flatten a raised or depressed scar, and recreate a webspace.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar management", "question": "What are the key strategies to optimize burn scars and treat hypertrophic scarring, including the role of laser therapy?", "answer": "Steps to optimize burn scars: (1) Wound closure of burns unlikely to heal in 3 weeks; (2) Sun avoidance for first 6 months; (3) Compression garments for up to 1 year; (4) Keeping the scar moist. Treatment modalities include surgical manipulation (tension relief), intralesional corticosteroids, cryotherapy, and laser therapy. The 585 nm pulsed dye laser (PDL) treats erythematous scars (2-6 treatments). Fractional CO2 laser (10,600 nm) targets water, creating columns of tissue destruction that stimulate collagen production in adjacent tissue. For erythematous and hypertrophic scars, combined PDL + CO2 laser is used. Tension is a key pathologic factor that must be addressed.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Neck/axilla/elbow/hand/groin/knee contractures", "question": "What is the algorithm for neck contracture repair based on severity?", "answer": "Scar band: Z-plasty (large Z-plasties can be used in the neck due to robust blood supply). Moderate contracture: release plus thick STSG or FTSG (large FTSG can be harvested from abdomen using abdominoplasty technique). Severe contracture: release and supraclavicular flap (can be pre-expanded) or free fasciocutaneous flap. The neck should be the first facial region addressed in reconstruction because tension here can cause disfigurement/discoloration of the entire face. The release should be aggressive, extending the entirety of the neck with fish tails at the ends. Free tissue options include ALT, groin flap (thin, based on SCIA), and scapular/parascapular flaps.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Hand burn splinting", "question": "What is the proper splinting position for the upper extremity after a burn injury, and what is the algorithm for hand contracture repair?", "answer": "Upper extremity splinting: shoulder abducted at 90 degrees, elbow extended at 180 degrees, wrist slightly extended, and hand in intrinsic plus position. Hand contracture repair algorithm: Webspace contractures = five-flap jumping man Z-plasty; MCP and PIP contractures = Z-plasty; Nail bed and DIP contractures = release and FTSG. For severe small finger PIP contractures with joint involvement, a Digit Widget external fixator can be used for slow distraction. K-wires can maintain digits in intrinsic plus position to prevent deforming contractures.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Contracture release", "question": "Why should burn scars generally NOT be excised during contracture release? What is the concept of scar rejuvenation?", "answer": "A contracture implies a lack of skin; scar excision only increases the amount of skin replacement needed. The concept of scar rejuvenation aims to improve the scar environment without actual excision. Despite not removing tissue, a large defect is often created once tension is released. This defect is then treated by adding new tissue (FTSG or thick STSG) or using tissue rearrangements (Z-plasty, V-Y advancement). Scar excision may only be considered for hypertrophic facial scarring when the subunit concept is indicated, and even then, CO2 laser resurfacing should be considered as an alternative.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "What are the principles and applications of tissue expansion in burn reconstruction?", "answer": "Tissue expansion is valuable when a large contiguous piece of skin is needed as a graft or flap. It works through mechanical creep (immediate increase in surface area) and biologic creep (cellular changes over time including epidermal thickening, dermal thinning, cellular hypertrophy, collagen realignment). Expanded skin has greater vascularity (delay phenomenon), increasing flap reliability. Up to 50% of the scalp can be reconstructed with expansion. The expanded skin must cover both the width of the expander and the eventual defect. Complications include infection, implant exposure, and flap ischemia. It is particularly useful for the cheek (replacing with similar sensate, hair-bearing tissue) and scalp (hair-bearing reconstruction).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Laser resurfacing", "question": "What are the main chromophores in the skin, and how does the concept of selective photothermolysis guide laser selection?", "answer": "The main chromophores are hemoglobin (oxy- and deoxyhemoglobin), melanin, water, and tattoo pigment. Selective photothermolysis means choosing a wavelength absorbed by the target chromophore and a pulse width shorter than the thermal relaxation time (TRT) of the target, allowing precise destruction while sparing surrounding tissue. Key principle: pulse width should not exceed TRT to avoid collateral injury and loss of selectivity. Laser wavelength and penetration depth are directly proportional until water becomes the primary chromophore (>1100 nm), after which penetration decreases. For higher Fitzpatrick skin types, longer wavelengths minimize melanin-related collateral injury.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Laser resurfacing", "question": "What is fractional photothermolysis, and how does it differ from fully ablative laser therapy?", "answer": "Fractional photothermolysis (introduced 2004) creates discrete columns of thermal injury (microscopic treatment zones) within the epidermis and dermis, varying from a few to several hundred micrometers in diameter, penetrating up to 4 mm. Intervening untreated skin acts as a reservoir of epidermal stem cells, enabling shorter healing times with reduced side effects compared to fully ablative therapy. Fully ablative (nonfractional) lasers remove successive layers of tissue, providing greater skin contraction and fibroplasia but with higher risk of scarring, dyspigmentation, prolonged erythema, and infection. Fractional approaches require serial treatments to match fully ablative results. Ablative fractional laser (AFL) combined with PDL is the cornerstone of burn/trauma scar treatment.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Laser resurfacing", "question": "What is the treatment of choice for capillary vascular malformations (port wine stains), and what is the optimal treatment strategy?", "answer": "The 595 nm pulsed dye laser (PDL) is the gold standard treatment for port wine stains (PWSs), targeting oxyhemoglobin as its chromophore. The treatment endpoint is durable purpura. Start with short pulse width (0.45 ms) to eliminate fine vessels, then increase pulse width at subsequent sessions (1.5, 3 ms) to target larger vessels. Epidermal cooling (DCD) is essential. For violaceous/deoxyhemoglobin-rich areas, the 755 nm alexandrite laser can be added. Initiating treatment early (infancy) is critical to minimize scatter from dermal collagen and acquired melanin. One million patients in the US are affected; without treatment, 65% become hypertrophic.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Laser resurfacing", "question": "What laser settings and approach are used for treating erythematous hypertrophic scars?", "answer": "The combined use of 595 nm PDL and fractional 10,600 nm CO2 laser is the cornerstone for hypertrophic scar treatment. PDL settings: pulse width 0.45-1.5 ms, 7 mm spot size, fluence titrated upward from 5.0 J/cm2 to the endpoint of transient purpura. PDL excels at decreasing erythema and pruritus and can be performed every 4 weeks. CO2 AFL settings: 15-40 mJ, 5-10% density, 150-200 Hz, repeated every 3 months. Topical triamcinolone (10 mg/mL) is applied after CO2 treatment, and intralesional triamcinolone (20 mg/mL) can be injected. AFL creates columns repopulated with collagen resembling nonwounded skin up to 4 mm deep.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Cleft lip anatomy", "question": "What is the embryologic basis of cleft lip, and what structures fail to fuse?", "answer": "Cleft lip results from failure of fusion of the medial nasal prominence and the maxillary prominence during weeks 4-7 of gestation. The medial nasal prominence gives rise to the nasal tip, columella, philtrum, and premaxilla. The lateral nasal prominence becomes the nasal ala. The maxillary prominences form the lateral lip elements. The upper lip is a composite: philtrum from fused medial nasal prominences and lateral lip from maxillary prominences. Left unilateral clefts are most common (6:3:1 ratio of left:right:bilateral) because the left palatine process achieves horizontal position after the right.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Cleft palate anatomy", "question": "Describe the Veau classification of cleft palate and how it relates to embryologic anatomy.", "answer": "Veau classification: Class I = cleft of soft palate only; Class II = cleft of hard and soft palate up to the incisive foramen; Class III = cleft of soft and hard palate extending unilaterally through the alveolus; Class IV = cleft of soft and hard palate extending bilaterally through the alveolus. The incisive foramen divides the primary palate (anterior, from intermaxillary segment including 4 incisors) from the secondary palate (posterior, from lateral palatine shelves). Palatine shelves initially grow obliquely downward beside the tongue, then assume horizontal orientation (right before left) and fuse anterior to posterior: hard palate complete by week 10, soft palate by week 12.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Timing of repair", "question": "What is the timeline for cleft lip and palate surgical interventions from birth through adulthood?", "answer": "Newborn: feeding assessment, hearing screening, counseling, genetics referral. 0-3 months: presurgical molding (NAM, lip taping). 3 months: primary cleft lip repair +/- primary tip rhinoplasty. 9-12 months: primary cleft palate repair + myringotomy tubes. 12-36 months: speech screening/evaluation for VPI. 3-5 years: secondary speech surgery if needed (Furlow conversion, pharyngeal flap, sphincter pharyngoplasty). School-age: lip/nasal revisions. 7-9 years: alveolar bone grafting (timed to permanent canine eruption). Adolescence: orthodontics, definitive rhinoplasty. Skeletal maturity (~16F/18M): orthognathic surgery (LeFort I advancement).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "NAM concept", "question": "What is nasoalveolar molding (NAM) and what are its goals and limitations?", "answer": "NAM uses serial application of a custom intraoral appliance with nasal extensions to: align alveolar segments, support alar domes, lengthen the columella, and improve nasal tip projection and symmetry. It is initiated in the first weeks of life, taking advantage of the plasticity of developing facial tissue. Studies demonstrate improvement in preoperative nasal and alveolar arch forms, though longevity on longitudinal follow-up remains uncertain. Limitations include frequent visits, need for expertise in fabrication/modification, and resource-intensive nature. Up to 40% of patients treated with gingivoperiosteoplasty (often done with NAM) still require secondary bone grafting.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "VPI", "question": "What are the subtypes of velopharyngeal dysfunction (VPD) and how does the treatment differ for each?", "answer": "VPD has three subtypes: (1) Velopharyngeal insufficiency (VPI) - insufficient palatal length despite normal elevation; this is an anatomic problem requiring surgical intervention (will NOT improve with speech therapy). (2) Velopharyngeal incompetence - aberrant palatal motion despite adequate length; may improve with speech therapy, rarely requires surgery. (3) Velopharyngeal mislearning - abnormal speech patterns despite normally functioning palate; treated with speech therapy alone. Surgical options for VPI include: Furlow conversion, posterior pharyngeal fat grafting (for gaps <2 cm2), posterior pharyngeal flap (large gaps, preserved lateral wall motion), and dynamic sphincter pharyngoplasty (using palatopharyngeus muscle).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Alveolar bone grafting", "question": "When should secondary alveolar bone grafting be performed, and what are the key details?", "answer": "Secondary bone grafting is performed just prior to eruption of the permanent maxillary canine into the cleft margin, typically at age 8-9 years (timing dictated by periapical radiographs showing canine eruption, not age alone). Cancellous bone is harvested from the iliac crest to close the anterior oral-nasal fistula, augment the piriform rim, and restore maxillary arch continuity. Success rates approach 80-90%. Donor site morbidity includes scarring, infection, hematoma, meralgia paresthetica, and iatrogenic fracture. Novel alternatives include demineralized bone matrix with cancellous allograft and rhBMP-2.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Pierre Robin sequence", "question": "What defines Pierre Robin sequence, and how does it differ from a syndrome? What is the management approach?", "answer": "Pierre Robin is a sequence (not a syndrome) - a single event leads to a sequential chain of anomalies: micrognathia leads to decreased oral cavity volume causing glossoptosis (posterior/superior tongue positioning), which physically impedes descent and fusion of lateral palatal shelves, resulting in a characteristic wide U-shaped cleft palate, plus airway obstruction and feeding difficulties. A syndrome, by contrast, is a group of anomalies from a single underlying abnormality (e.g., gene mutation). Management: supplemental oxygen and prone positioning may stabilize the airway; severe cases may require temporary intubation, tongue-lip adhesion, or mandibular distraction osteogenesis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Speech outcomes", "question": "What is the Furlow double-opposing Z-plasty technique, and why is it considered a major contribution to cleft palate repair?", "answer": "The Furlow technique uses reversed Z-plasties based on the cleft midline to simultaneously reposition the levator muscles and lengthen the palate. Each Z-plasty has a posteriorly based musculomucosal flap and an anteriorly based mucosal flap. The transposition reorients the levator veli palatini to its normal transverse position, recreating the velopharyngeal sling for dynamic palatal elevation. It provides palatal lengthening through the Z-plasty effect (gaining length at the expense of width). Recent retrospective studies show improved speech outcomes compared with other techniques. It is versatile as both a primary repair and a secondary revision for persistent VPI. Its main drawback is tension transversely across the closure, making it challenging for wide clefts.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Congenital nevi", "question": "What is the classification of congenital melanocytic nevi by size, and what is the malignant potential of each?", "answer": "Small nevi: <1.5 cm (most common, 1:100 births) - lifetime melanoma risk <1%. Medium nevi: 1.5-20 cm (1:1000 births) - lifetime melanoma risk <1%. Giant nevi: >20 cm (1:20,000 births) - lifetime melanoma risk 5-10%, often with satellite nevi. Nevi >50 cm are very rare (1:500,000). A large facial/scalp nevus may be classified as giant even if <20 cm. Giant nevi can be associated with neurocutaneous melanosis (melanotic tissue in skin and meninges), which carries a poor prognosis. Screening MRI can be done at 4-6 months for large nevi.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Congenital nevi", "question": "What are the ABCDEs of suspicious nevi, and what is the most important feature?", "answer": "A = Asymmetry; B = Border irregularity; C = Color variegation; D = Diameter >6 mm (about the size of a pencil eraser - probably the least important feature); E = Evolution (the MOST important feature - a nevus that is changing). Additional concerning signs include crusting, bleeding, and itching. A full-thickness biopsy (not shave biopsy) is indicated for suspicious lesions to include all skin layers and subcutaneous tissue, as tumor thickness (Breslow classification) is the most important prognostic indicator for melanoma. Patients with dysplastic nevus syndrome (many dysplastic nevi + 2 or more first-degree relatives with melanoma) may have near 100% lifetime melanoma risk.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Congenital nevi", "question": "What are sebaceous nevi (nevus sebaceous of Jadassohn) and what is their clinical significance?", "answer": "Sebaceous nevi are congenital lesions with a fleshy, tan, cobblestone appearance, most commonly on the scalp and face. They contain prominent sebaceous glands and are non-hair-bearing on the scalp. During puberty, they become oily and crusty due to hormonal stimulation. They carry a 10-15% risk of basal cell carcinoma (NOT squamous cell carcinoma) in adulthood. Treatment of choice for scalp lesions is surgical excision. For facial lesions, conservative observation, tangential shave excision, or CO2 laser may be chosen to avoid scarring, with parental understanding of the BCC risk. Pathologic margin evaluation can be difficult.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Infantile hemangioma vs vascular malformation", "question": "What are the key distinguishing features between infantile hemangiomas and vascular malformations?", "answer": "Infantile hemangiomas: NOT present at birth (appear ~2 weeks postnatally), female predominance (3:1), more common in Caucasians, go through proliferative (0-12 months), involution (12 months-10 years), and regression phases. GLUT-1 positive on biopsy. Most common tumor of infancy. Vascular malformations: ALWAYS present at birth (may not be clinically evident), equal gender distribution, grow proportionately with the child, do NOT involute, often enlarge at puberty due to hormonal changes. GLUT-1 negative. Classified as slow-flow (capillary, venous, lymphatic) or fast-flow (any lesion with arterial component).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "ISSVA classification", "question": "How does the ISSVA classify vascular anomalies, and what are the associated syndromes?", "answer": "ISSVA (1996, updated 2014) divides vascular anomalies into vascular tumors and vascular malformations. Malformations are classified by flow: slow-flow (capillary, venous, lymphatic) and fast-flow (arterial component/AVM). Hemangioma-associated syndromes: PHACES (posterior fossa anomalies, hemangiomas, arterial/cardiac/eye anomalies, sternal cleft), Kasabach-Merritt (thrombocytopenia + hemangiomas). Capillary malformation syndromes: Sturge-Weber (V1/V2 capillary malformation, leptomeningeal involvement, seizures), Klippel-Trenaunay (capillary + lymphatic malformations, limb hypertrophy). AVM syndromes: Parkes Weber (capillary malformation + AVM + limb hypertrophy), Osler-Weber-Rendu (telangiectasias, epistaxis, visceral AVMs).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Propranolol", "question": "What is the role of propranolol in treating infantile hemangiomas, and what precautions are needed?", "answer": "Propranolol (beta blocker) is administered at 2 mg/kg/day and is most effective when initiated during the proliferative phase (0-12 months). It may work by decreasing VEGF expression, triggering apoptosis of capillary endothelial cells, and inducing vasoconstriction. At many institutions, patients are admitted for observation during the first dose to monitor for hypoglycemia and hypotension. Patients must pass a thorough cardiopulmonary evaluation before initiation. Topical timolol 0.5% is also effective for superficial lesions. Beta blockers have come into favor alongside systemic corticosteroids (2-3 mg/kg/d prednisone) as first-line pharmacologic treatment. Approximately 85-88% of lesions stabilize with treatment.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Lymphatic/venous/AV malformations", "question": "How do the treatment approaches differ for lymphatic, venous, and arteriovenous malformations?", "answer": "Lymphatic malformations (slow-flow): Observation for asymptomatic lesions with compression garments. Macrocystic lesions treated with sclerotherapy (doxycycline, ethanol, sodium tetradecyl sulfate). Microcystic lesions treated with surgical excision (direct excision or liposuction). Venous malformations (slow-flow): Similar approach - observation, compression wraps, sclerotherapy, excision for debulking. Low-dose aspirin for pain from microthrombi. Characteristic swelling in dependent position and phleboliths on MRI. Arteriovenous malformations (fast-flow): 4 stages (quiescent, expansion, destruction, cardiac failure). Observation possible, but early intervention considered to prevent progression. Preoperative embolization recommended before surgical resection to decrease blood loss. These lesions do NOT involute.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Sclerotherapy/embolization/surgery", "question": "What are the four stages of AVM progression, and what is the role of embolization?", "answer": "Stage 1 (Quiescence): AVM may or may not be clinically evident; shunting seen on ultrasound imaging. Stage 2 (Expansion): manifests as thrill or bruit on physical exam. Stage 3 (Destruction): episodes of bleeding, pain, and local tissue damage. Stage 4 (Decompensation): cardiac failure and continued tissue destruction. Preoperative embolization or ligation is critical before surgical resection to decrease the significant blood loss associated with AVMs due to arteriovenous shunting. AVMs are present at birth, grow with the child, and never involute. MRI shows soft tissue thickening with flow voids on T1, variable signal increase with flow voids on T2.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What is Virchow's law regarding craniosynostosis, and what skull shape results from premature sagittal suture fusion?", "answer": "Virchow's law states that closure of a cranial suture results in compensatory growth parallel to the fused suture with arrest of growth perpendicular to the suture. Premature sagittal suture fusion produces scaphocephaly: an elongated skull with bitemporal/biparietal narrowing, frontal bossing, and occipital bulleting. Sagittal synostosis is the most common form of craniosynostosis, with a male predominance.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "How do you differentiate positional posterior plagiocephaly from lambdoid craniosynostosis on physical examination?", "answer": "Key differences: (1) Head shape: parallelogram in positional plagiocephaly vs. trapezoid in lambdoid synostosis. (2) Ipsilateral ear position from above: anteriorly displaced in positional vs. posteriorly displaced in lambdoid. (3) Ipsilateral mastoid bulge: absent in positional, present in lambdoid (nearly pathognomonic). (4) Ipsilateral forehead: anteriorly displaced in positional vs. retruded in lambdoid. (5) Frontal bossing: ipsilateral in positional vs. contralateral in lambdoid. (6) Onset: after birth in positional vs. at birth in lambdoid. Lambdoid synostosis is extremely rare.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What are the characteristic features of unicoronal craniosynostosis, and which genetic mutations are most associated with coronal synostosis?", "answer": "Unicoronal craniosynostosis features: ipsilateral forehead/supraorbital rim retrusion and brow elevation, contralateral forehead bossing, harlequin orbital deformity on AP radiograph (from greater wing of sphenoid involvement), nasal radix deviation toward the affected side, and chin point deviation toward the unaffected side. It has a female predominance. Coronal synostosis has the highest familial transmission rate (8-14%) and is most reliably linked to testable genetic mutations: FGFR3 (Muenke syndrome) and TWIST1 (Saethre-Chotzen syndrome).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What is trigonocephaly, and what is the optimal timing and technique for its surgical correction?", "answer": "Trigonocephaly results from premature metopic suture fusion and features a keel-shaped forehead, hypotelorism, bitemporal narrowing, and a palpable midline ridge. The metopic suture normally closes before 8 months of age, so the decision to intervene is based on severity of the deformity, not simply suture closure. The most widely accepted treatment is bilateral fronto-orbital advancement (FOA), typically performed between 8-11 months. The bandeau is split in the midline and widened with an interpositional bone graft; lateral orbits are bent inward to correct bitemporal narrowing.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What is the incidence of elevated intracranial pressure (ICP) in craniosynostosis, and what is the treatment for a symptomatic intraoperative venous air embolism during craniosynostosis surgery?", "answer": "Renier et al. found approximately 14% of patients with single suture and 47% with multisuture craniosynostosis experience elevated ICP. Treatment for symptomatic venous air embolism: (1) place a wet sponge over the operative field, (2) position patient in left lateral decubitus and Trendelenburg position. This discourages continued air entry and positions the right ventricular outflow tract inferior to the right ventricular cavity. Venous air emboli are common during craniosynostosis surgery (up to 82%) but few are symptomatic.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What is the Whitaker classification for outcomes in craniosynostosis surgery, and what factor most predicts a Whitaker I result?", "answer": "Whitaker classification: Class I - no additional procedure needed (excellent). Class II - minor soft tissue or bone contouring needed (adequate). Class III - major osteotomies required, but less than original surgery (poor). Class IV - major craniofacial procedure needed, essentially reproducing the original operation (unsatisfactory). Overcorrection of the deformity is the most important factor in obtaining a Whitaker I result, to account for continued growth of the child. Surgery before 1 year of age is desirable to harness rapid brain growth.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Syndromic craniosynostosis (Crouzon/Apert/Pfeiffer)", "question": "Compare the key features of Crouzon and Apert syndromes, including genetics, head shape, limb findings, and intelligence.", "answer": "Both are FGFR2 mutations with autosomal dominant inheritance. Crouzon (1:60,000): brachycephaly, midface hypoplasia, shallow orbits, exophthalmos, parrot-beaked nose, class III malocclusion. Normal extremities, normal intelligence. Apert (1:64,000-1:80,000): similar craniofacial features plus symmetric complex syndactyly of hands (index, long, ring fingers) and feet (pathognomonic), severe acne in adolescence, and increased incidence of intellectual disability. Most Apert cases are sporadic (point mutations in exon 7 of FGFR2 at amino acids 252 or 253). Overall phenotype in Apert is more severe.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Syndromic craniosynostosis (Crouzon/Apert/Pfeiffer)", "question": "Describe the three types of Pfeiffer syndrome and their associated findings and prognosis.", "answer": "All Pfeiffer types feature craniosynostosis with broad thumbs and great toes and partial soft tissue syndactyly. Mutations in FGFR1 or FGFR2. Type 1 (classic): autosomal dominant, brachycephaly or turribrachycephaly, normal intelligence, good prognosis. Type 2: Kleeblattschadel (cloverleaf skull), severe exophthalmos, brachydactyly, elbow ankylosis, profound disability, sporadic, mortality in infancy/childhood. Type 3: same as type 2 without cloverleaf skull, elbow ankylosis present, profound disability, sporadic, mortality in infancy/childhood. Estimated prevalence 1:100,000.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Syndromic craniosynostosis (Crouzon/Apert/Pfeiffer)", "question": "What is Saethre-Chotzen syndrome and what distinguishes Muenke syndrome from other syndromic craniosynostoses?", "answer": "Saethre-Chotzen (1:25,000-1:50,000, most common syndromic craniosynostosis): TWIST1 gene mutation, AD inheritance, variable expression. Features: coronal synostosis, low frontal hairline, eyelid ptosis, facial asymmetry, short stature, simple syndactyly, brachydactyly, clinodactyly, radioulnar synostosis. Usually normal intelligence. Muenke (1:130,000): FGFR3 Pro250Arg point mutation, AD. Features: uni/bicoronal synostosis, mild facial findings, negative canthal vector, ptosis. Key distinguishing features: sensorineural hearing loss (very common) and thimble-like middle phalanges on radiography (nearly pathognomonic). Carpal and calcaneal-tarsal fusions on imaging.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Syndromic craniosynostosis (Crouzon/Apert/Pfeiffer)", "question": "What are the advantages of posterior fossa distraction over fronto-orbital advancement (FOA) as an initial treatment in syndromic craniosynostosis, and what is the typical distraction protocol?", "answer": "Advantages of posterior fossa distraction: (1) greater increase in intracranial volume than FOA, (2) less invasive with minimal dural dissection, (3) less blood loss, (4) preserves growth potential of bone, (5) slow soft tissue stretching permits more volume gain than single-stage advancement. Protocol: latency period of up to 5 days, then distraction at 1 mm/day (usually 0.5 mm twice daily). Consolidation period is twice the activation period. Many high-volume centers now perform posterior fossa expansion at 3-6 months, followed by FOA around age 1 year. Disadvantage: requires second surgery for distractor removal.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Syndromic craniosynostosis (Crouzon/Apert/Pfeiffer)", "question": "Compare Le Fort III and monobloc advancement procedures in syndromic craniosynostosis, including advantages and complication profiles.", "answer": "Le Fort III moves the midface separately from the frontal bar; monobloc moves them as a unit. Le Fort III advantages: (1) favorable complication profile since extracranial approach reduces CSF leak and meningitis risk, (2) allows differential advancement of forehead and midface, (3) timing of each surgery can be optimized independently. Monobloc advantages: corrects exorbitism, midface and forehead retrusion simultaneously, small increase in intracranial volume. Monobloc distraction reduced serious complications from 50% to 0% and overall complications from 67% to 8% compared to acute advancement. Facial bipartition can be combined with monobloc (not Le Fort III) to address hypertelorism and midface width. Midface surgery typically performed age 5-8 years.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniofacial microsomia", "question": "What is craniofacial microsomia (CFM), what is the OMENS+ classification, and what is the modified Pruzansky classification for mandibular hypoplasia?", "answer": "CFM is the second most common congenital craniofacial anomaly after cleft lip/palate (incidence ~1:3000-5600). It involves first and second branchial arch structures. OMENS+ classifies: Orbit, Mandible, Ear, Nerve, Soft tissue (each rated 0-3), plus extracraniofacial abnormalities. Modified Pruzansky (Kaban): Type I - small but morphologically normal mandible, functional TMJ. Type IIa - abnormal ramus/condyle morphology but functional TMJ in near-normal position. Type IIb - hypoplastic/malformed ramus/condyle displaced toward midline, nonfunctional TMJ. Type III - absent ramus with no TMJ. Treatment hinges on TMJ functional status.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniofacial microsomia", "question": "What is the treatment approach for craniofacial microsomia based on the modified Pruzansky classification, and what workup is recommended?", "answer": "Type I/IIa: expand existing bone via distraction osteogenesis or sagittal split osteotomy. Type IIb with adequate bone stock: may be distracted to create a pseudo-TMJ. Type IIb (insufficient bone)/III: costochondral graft to reconstruct ramus, TMJ, and zygomatic arch (age ~4+). Recommended workup: auditory testing, echocardiogram, renal ultrasound, cervical spine X-rays (for vertebral anomalies causing instability), cephalograms/CT. In CFM, the mandibular foramen is shifted superiorly (one-third down from sigmoid notch vs. halfway in normals), and the inferior alveolar nerve is closer to the buccal cortex. Right side affected more often (60%), male predominance (65%).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Orthognathic surgery basics", "question": "Describe the Angle classification of malocclusion and the key cephalometric measurements (SNA, SNB) used in orthognathic surgery planning.", "answer": "Angle classification is based on the relationship of the mesiobuccal cusp of the maxillary first molar to the buccal groove of the mandibular first molar. Class I: cusp aligns with groove (normal molar relationship). Class II: maxillary cusp is mesial to groove (retrognathic appearance, mandible posterior). Class III: maxillary cusp is distal to groove (prognathic appearance, mandible anterior). SNA angle (normal 80-84 degrees): maxillary position relative to cranial base. SNB angle (normal 78-80 degrees): mandibular position relative to cranial base. Low SNA = posterior maxilla; high SNB = anterior mandible. Normal overjet is 2-4 mm.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Le Fort osteotomies", "question": "Describe the Le Fort I osteotomy technique and the impact of skeletal movements on soft tissue aesthetics in orthognathic surgery.", "answer": "Le Fort I allows multivector maxillary movement (AP, craniocaudal, rotational in all planes). Technique: upper gingivobuccal sulcus incision, subperiosteal dissection preserving infraorbital nerve, osteotomies through medial/lateral buttresses and anterior maxillary wall with reciprocating saw, nasal septum release from vomer, pterygomaxillary osteotomies, then downfracture. Fixed with L-shaped plates at medial and lateral buttresses. Key aesthetic principle: movements expanding the skeleton (advancement) smooth rhytids and provide youthful appearance; movements contracting the skeleton (impaction, setback) can create deeper creases and aging appearance. Alar base widening is a concern with maxillary advancement. Up to 25% of cleft lip/palate patients require orthognathic surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Orthognathic surgery basics", "question": "What is the sagittal split osteotomy (SSO) technique, and what are the key considerations for osseous genioplasty?", "answer": "SSO: most common mandibular osteotomy. Incision in gingivobuccal sulcus at first molar extending along anterior ramus. Medial ramus osteotomy above the lingula (to protect inferior alveolar nerve), carried across anterior ramus along external oblique line to first molar, then vertical cut to inferior border. Sagittal split completed with osteotomes. Creates proximal segment (buccal plate, ramus, condyle, coronoid) and distal segment (tooth-bearing body/symphysis). Condyles must be properly seated during fixation. Genioplasty: the inferior alveolar nerve drops 5-6 mm below the mental foramen before exiting bone - osteotomy must account for this. Mentalis cuff must be preserved to prevent witch's chin deformity. VRO is limited for advancement but suited for mandibular setback.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Tessier clefts", "question": "Describe the Tessier classification of craniofacial clefts, including the numbering system and common cleft combinations.", "answer": "The Tessier classification centers around the orbits. Facial clefts: numbered 0-7 (caudal to orbit). Cranial clefts: numbered 8-14 (cephalad to orbit). When cranial and facial clefts occur together, their numbers often sum to 14 (e.g., 0+14, 1+13, 2+12, 3+11). Soft tissue contours follow underlying bony abnormalities. The No. 7 cleft (lateral commissure to preauricular region) is the most common craniofacial cleft, associated with hemifacial microsomia and Goldenhar syndrome. Treacher Collins syndrome involves No. 6, 7, and 8 clefts. Hypertelorism is a physical finding, not a syndrome. Bony findings are more consistent and reliable for diagnosis than soft tissue findings.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Hypertelorism", "question": "How is orbital hypertelorism classified and surgically corrected?", "answer": "Hypertelorism is defined by increased bony interdacryon distance (distance between anterior lacrimal crests), distinct from telecanthus (widened intercanthal distance with normal bony orbits). Adult classification: 1st degree 30-34 mm, 2nd degree 34-40 mm, 3rd degree >40 mm. In children, defined relative to age-normed values. Surgical correction: box osteotomy (repositions orbits and zygomas, preserves midfacial/occlusal relationships) or facial bipartition (ideal when hypertelorism coexists with maxillary hypoplasia, narrow maxillary arch, and malocclusion - removes central bone wedge from crista galli to alveolus). Goal: interdacryon distance <17 mm. Surgery delayed until orbital maturity (6-9 years). Craniofrontonasal dysplasia (X-linked EFNB1 gene) is a unique inherited form of hypertelorism.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Microtia and ear reconstruction", "question": "Describe the embryology of the external ear, the Nagata classification of microtia, and the timing/technique of autogenous ear reconstruction.", "answer": "Embryology: auricle develops from six hillocks around the first branchial groove. Hillocks 1-3 (first/mandibular arch): tragus, root of helix, superior helix. Hillocks 4-6 (second/hyoid arch): antihelix, antitragus, lobule. Nagata classification: Anotia (absent tissue), Lobule type (vestige with lobule, no concha/meatus/tragus), Concha type (vestige with lobule, concha, meatus, tragus), Small concha type, Atypical. Brent technique: 4-stage reconstruction starting at age 6. Nagata technique: 2-stage using ipsilateral ribs 6-9, starting at age 10 (chest circumference >60 cm). Nagata harvests cartilage without perichondrium to reduce donor site deformity. Normal auricle: 55-65 mm height, width ~50-55% of height, tilts posteriorly 15-20 degrees, located one ear length posterior to lateral orbital rim.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Microtia and ear reconstruction", "question": "What are the three major options for microtia reconstruction, and what are the key complications of autogenous ear reconstruction?", "answer": "Three options: (1) Autogenous rib cartilage (Brent 4-stage at age 6, or Nagata 2-stage at age 10) - most reliable, lowest complications. (2) Porous polyethylene (Medpor) framework with TPF flap coverage - can be done earlier, but risk of long-term exposure/extrusion (initially 42%, reduced with TPF flap). (3) Osseointegrated prosthesis - alternative for poor surgical candidates, requires remakes every 2-5 years. Key complications: most common is construct not resembling normal auricle; chest wall deformity (most common late complication, ~2/3 of cases); skin flap necrosis; hematoma (rare 0.3% but devastating - requires immediate drainage); infection (<0.5%); framework extrusion (more common with synthetic); cartilage resorption. Ear molding is effective if started <3 months (ideally <1 month) for non-hypoplastic deformities.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "VPI", "question": "What are the three subtypes of velopharyngeal dysfunction (VPD), and what are the five closure patterns described by Croft et al.?", "answer": "Three subtypes: (1) Velopharyngeal insufficiency (VPI) - structural defect causing inadequate closure (e.g., short velum after cleft repair, submucous cleft). (2) Velopharyngeal incompetence - neurologic/neuromuscular dysfunction (e.g., 22q11.2 deletion, stroke). (3) Velopharyngeal mislearning - learned disarticulation, treated with speech therapy. VPD occurs in 20-30% of cleft palate patients postoperatively. Five closure patterns (Croft): (1) Coronal - most common in normals, posterior velum movement with less lateral wall contribution. (2) Sagittal - predominantly medial lateral wall movement. (3) Circular - good velum and lateral wall motion. (4) Circular with Passavant ridge. (5) Bowtie - velum and posterior wall movement, poor lateral wall motion.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Furlow palatoplasty", "question": "Describe the surgical algorithm for treating VPI, including the indications for sphincter pharyngoplasty versus pharyngeal flap versus Furlow palatoplasty.", "answer": "Algorithm based on gap size, closure pattern, and lateral wall motion: (1) Furlow palatoplasty: double opposing Z-plasty, lengthens palate, repositions levator muscle. Best for small gaps, submucous cleft, or repaired cleft with anterior levator insertion. Up to 30% failure rate but lower OSA risk. (2) Pharyngeal flap: myomucosal flap from posterior pharyngeal wall inset into velum, creates midline obstruction converting one large port into two lateral ports. Best for sagittal or circular closure pattern with good lateral wall motion. Ideally inserted at C1 level. (3) Sphincter pharyngoplasty: 90-degree transposition of palatopharyngeus muscles from posterior tonsillar pillars to posterior pharyngeal wall. Best for large posterior gap with coronal/circular/bowtie pattern and poor lateral wall motion. Failure rates: pharyngeal flap 20%, sphincter pharyngoplasty 16%.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "VPI", "question": "What are the key anatomy considerations for velopharyngeal function, and what special considerations apply to patients with 22q11.2 deletion syndrome and VPI?", "answer": "Key anatomy: Levator veli palatini (LVP) is the most important muscle - normally a horizontal sling in the middle 40% of velum, innervated by pharyngeal plexus (CN IX, X). In cleft palate, LVP is abnormally oriented anteroposteriorly. Submucous cleft triad: bifid uvula, notched hard palate, zona pellucida (diastasis of LVP). Tensor veli palatini is the only muscle innervated by CN V (not pharyngeal plexus). 22q11.2 deletion (velocardiofacial/DiGeorge/Shprintzen syndrome): most common syndrome associated with cleft palate and VPI. Features: cardiac defects (Tetralogy of Fallot), hypocalcemia, learning disabilities, submucous cleft. Critical: medialized internal carotid arteries are frequent - imaging MUST be obtained before pharyngeal flap surgery. Intellectual disability may impair relearning after functional repair, favoring pharyngeal flap or sphincter pharyngoplasty.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What are the key facts about fibrous dysplasia of the craniofacial skeleton, including genetics, radiographic findings, and treatment approach?", "answer": "Fibrous dysplasia is the most common craniofacial tumor encountered by plastic surgeons. Caused by somatic activating mutations in GNAS gene. May be monostotic (skull involved in 27%) or polyostotic (skull involved up to 50%). Most commonly affects frontal bone, sphenoid, and maxilla. CT shows ground-glass pattern (56%), homogeneously dense (23%), or cystic (21%). McCune-Albright syndrome: polyostotic fibrous dysplasia + precocious puberty + cafe au lait spots. Malignant transformation in 3.2% (usually osteosarcoma). Treatment: Chen zones - total excision for Zone 1 (fronto-orbital/zygomatic/upper maxillary), conservative contouring for Zones 2-4. Optic nerve decompression only when vision loss begins (too risky with normal vision). Radiotherapy is contraindicated.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What are the key features of Pierre Robin sequence (PRS) and Treacher Collins syndrome (TCS), and how are they managed?", "answer": "PRS: triad of micrognathia, glossoptosis, upper airway obstruction. Cleft palate is associated but not required (U-shaped). May be isolated, PRS-plus (Stickler, 22q deletion), or syndromic (TCS, Nager). Treatment: mild - prone positioning; moderate/severe - mandibular distraction (preferred to avoid tracheostomy); glossopexy is temporary. Cleft palate repair delayed to 18+ months. TCS: autosomal dominant (TCOF1 gene, chromosome 5), 60% de novo mutations. Bilateral Tessier 6, 7, 8 clefts. Features: zygomatic/mandibular hypoplasia, antimongoloid palpebral fissures, lower lid colobomas, microtia, conductive hearing loss, class III malocclusion. Treatment timeline: infancy (airway, cleft repair), mid-childhood ages 6-9 (ear reconstruction, malar/orbital bone grafting at 8-12 years), skeletal maturity (orthognathic surgery).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Cleft and craniofacial", "subtopic": "Craniosynostosis (sagittal/coronal/metopic/lambdoid)", "question": "What is the key distraction osteogenesis protocol for craniofacial applications, including the three phases and standard rate?", "answer": "Three phases: (1) Latency period: 5-7 days (may be shortened or eliminated in infants) for initial callus formation. (2) Activation period: distraction at standard rate of 1 mm/day (usually 0.5 mm twice daily). Higher rates possible in infants. Too fast = poor regenerate; too slow = premature consolidation. (3) Consolidation period: typically 6-8 weeks (shorter in infants at ~6 weeks) for bony regenerate to solidify. The process creates new bone without cartilaginous intermediate and expands the soft tissue envelope. Key cellular factors: TGF-B1 peaks during activation, inducing collagen/ECM deposition. VEGF and FGF drive neovascularization. First applied to craniofacial skeleton by McCarthy et al. Ilizarov established efficacy in long bones.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "Le Fort I/II/III", "question": "Describe the Le Fort fracture classification system and the principles of reduction.", "answer": "Le Fort I: horizontal fracture parallel to occlusal plane, from piriform aperture through pterygomaxillary junction. Separates the tooth-bearing maxilla. Le Fort II: pyramidal pattern from pterygomaxillary junction through zygomaticomaxillary buttress and orbital floor obliquely to nasofrontal junction. Le Fort III: craniofacial disjunction - horizontal fracture through upper midface from zygomatic arch through pterygomaxillary junction, lateral orbital rim, orbital roof, to nasofrontal junction. All types involve ipsilateral pterygoid plate disruption. Key principles: (1) restoration of normal occlusion is the primary goal, (2) facial width/height/projection restored by plating involved facial buttresses, (3) Le Fort I treated via upper buccal sulcus; Le Fort II/III benefit from coronal approach, (4) Rowe disimpaction forceps for reduction. Fracture patterns often differ on each side (hemi-Le Fort).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "Orbital floor fractures", "question": "What are the indications for orbital floor fracture repair, and what is the significance of the 'white-eyed blowout' fracture in children?", "answer": "Indications: (1) diplopia (primary indication), (2) entrapment of extraocular muscles (surgical emergency), (3) enophthalmos >2 mm, (4) fractures >1-2 cm2 (more likely to cause persistent diplopia). In children, greenstick 'white-eyed blowout' fractures allow inferior rectus to prolapse into maxillary sinus with periosteal recoil snapping bone back - this muscular entrapment is a surgical emergency. The muscle becomes ischemic and if not released within 6-8 hours, fibrosis and permanent diplopia result. Early enophthalmos in acute setting reliably indicates need for correction (swelling usually masks enophthalmos). The optic nerve is 32-42 mm posterior to the infraorbital rim. Zygomaticosphenoid buttress is most important for verifying accurate ZMC realignment. ZMC must be reduced before orbital floor repair.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "NOE fractures", "question": "Describe the classification and management of nasoorbitoethmoidal (NOE) fractures.", "answer": "NOE classification (based on central fragment to which medial canthal tendon attaches): Type I: single central fragment, stable. Fixed with miniplates at frontomaxillary, zygomaticomaxillary, and medial maxillary buttresses. Type II: comminuted, but tendon still attached to a fragment large enough for miniplate/microplate fixation. Type III: tendon detached from bone, extensive bony loss/comminution - requires transcanthal wiring (3-0 stainless steel wire passed posterior and superior to medial canthal attachment through to contralateral medial orbital wall). Medial canthi should be no more than 25 mm apart; vertical asymmetry of 2 mm is noticeable. NOE fractures are prone to late deformity because the central midface lacks sagittal buttresses. Subperiosteal edema must be managed with padded metal bolster splinting.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "Mandible fractures (condyle/angle/body/symphysis)", "question": "What are the biomechanical principles of mandible fracture fixation, and which fracture location has the highest complication rate?", "answer": "Biomechanics: muscles of mastication displace posterior segment superiorly; suprahyoid muscles pull anterior segment inferiorly. Body/angle experience tension along upper border and compression along inferior border. Two fixation types: (1) Rigid/load-bearing (e.g., reconstructive plate at inferior border) - primary bone healing, useful for atrophic bone, bony defects, smokers. (2) Functionally stable/load-sharing (e.g., Champy plate along oblique ridge, miniplates) - secondary bone healing with callus. Locking plates preferred due to curved mandible. Angle fractures have the highest complication rate, especially with impacted third molars. 50-67% of mandible fractures occur at multiple sites (ring structure concept). Condylar fractures (25-35% of mandibular fractures) are often treated closed with MMF for 2-3 weeks. Restoration of normal occlusion is the primary objective.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "Frontal sinus fractures", "question": "What is the management algorithm for frontal sinus fractures?", "answer": "Management depends on anterior vs. posterior table involvement, displacement, and nasofrontal outflow tract (NFOT) status. Nondisplaced anterior table without NFOT obstruction: observation. Displaced anterior table without NFOT obstruction: ORIF with low-profile miniplates. With NFOT obstruction (any table, any displacement): must obliterate or cranialize the sinus. Posterior table fractures: nondisplaced without CSF leak - observation; displaced with CSF leak risk - obliteration (less severe) or cranialization (more displaced/comminuted). Cranialization: remove posterior table, curet mucosa, burr inner anterior table, occlude NFOT with bone graft - brain fills former sinus space. Complications: mucoceles (from residual basilar mucosa in diploic veins of Breschet), abscess, meningitis. Frontal bone is strongest facial bone; fractures indicate high-energy mechanisms with frequent intracranial injury.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "Panfacial trauma", "question": "What are the principles of sequencing panfacial fracture repair, and what happens to facial dimensions with panfacial fractures?", "answer": "Panfacial fractures cause the face to assume a spherical shape: loss of vertical height, reduced AP projection, increased width. Sequencing principle: build from known (stable, non-fractured bone) to unknown (fractured segments). Three strategies: (1) Bottom-up: restore mandibular stability first, then MMF, then reduce midface from this reference. Most common approach. (2) Top-down: start from noninjured cranial base/zygomaticofrontal suture. (3) Inside-out. Critical rules: ZMC must be reduced before orbital floor (ZMC reduction may change floor fracture orientation); restore occlusion with MMF as a reference point; primary bone grafting may be needed for comminuted/devitalized bone. Over 45% of facial fracture patients have concomitant intracranial injury; ~10% have cervical spine injuries.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "Nasal fractures", "question": "What is the technique for closed nasal reduction and what is the significance of septal hematoma?", "answer": "Technique: inject local anesthetic along dorsum (infratrochlear nerves), around infraorbital nerve, and along columella/nasal floor. Insert vasoconstrictor-soaked pledgets for 10 minutes. Measure distance from naris to displaced bone externally to prevent intracranial injury. Insert Boies elevator intranasally and apply manual pressure while palpating externally. Reduce septum with Asch forceps to median position. Apply transseptal mattress sutures or packing, then external thermoplastic splint (protect skin with tape from exothermic curing). Septal hematoma is a surgical emergency: blood between perichondrium and cartilage deprives cartilage of blood supply, causing necrosis and saddle nose deformity. Treatment: aspirate with 18-gauge needle or lance with 11-blade, then pack nose. Nasal bones are the most commonly fractured facial bones (>55% of facial fractures).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Layered closure by region", "question": "What are the key principles of facial laceration repair, and what suture choices and timing are recommended?", "answer": "Principles: (1) Minimal debridement - rich vascularity allows partially compromised tissue to survive. (2) Copious saline irrigation to prevent infection. (3) Meticulously debride gravel/glass/debris using loupe magnification. (4) Close in layers, minimize buried dissolvable sutures in contaminated fields. (5) Place key sutures first at landmarks where minor discrepancies are most notable (eyebrow margin, vermilion border). Suture choices: 6-0 nylon/polypropylene for high-profile facial areas, 5-0 for concealed areas; 6-0 plain or fast gut for children (no removal needed). Remove permanent sutures within 5-7 days to prevent track marks (epithelial migration along sutures occurs after 7-10 days). Scars should be placed in relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Facial nerve injury", "question": "How do you evaluate and manage facial nerve injuries in the setting of facial lacerations?", "answer": "Assessment must be completed BEFORE local anesthetic injection. Pitanguy line (0.5 cm inferior to tragus to 1.5 cm superior to lateral eyebrow) marks frontal branch course - highest risk zone. Buccal branch injuries are most common with large midcheek lacerations and often associated with parotid duct injury. Marginal mandibular nerve (little redundancy) - at risk crossing inferior border of mid-mandibular body. Zygomatic and buccal branch injuries medial to lateral canthus rarely cause deficits due to distal arborization. If injury suspected: explore wound, tag cut ends, stimulate distal end (possible up to 72 hours post-injury; after that, acetylcholine depletion prevents stimulation). Loss of lower lip depression can be marginal mandibular OR cervical branch - distinguish by asking patient to evert lower lip (preserved mentalis function = cervical branch injury).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Parotid duct injury", "question": "How is a parotid duct (Stenson duct) injury diagnosed and managed?", "answer": "The parotid duct travels horizontally through the cheek in close proximity to the buccal branch of the facial nerve, opening intraorally on the buccal side of the second maxillary molar. No immediate signs exist - injury often noted days later when saliva drains from the laceration. Diagnosis: cannulate the intraoral orifice with a pediatric IV catheter and inject methylene blue or saline - look for extravasation in the wound. Repair: over a small-caliber pediatric feeding tube left as a stent for 14 days. Place subcutaneous drain for 1 week and facial compression wrap for 48 hours to prevent sialocele. High index of suspicion needed with any deep cheek laceration, especially if buccal branch of facial nerve is also injured.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Ear lacerations/auricular hematoma", "question": "How should auricular lacerations and hematomas be managed to prevent complications?", "answer": "Lacerations: minimal debridement due to limited cartilage vascularity. Cartilage and skin can usually be reapproximated in a single layer (firm skin-cartilage adherence). Use 5-0 polypropylene in adults, 5-0 fast-absorbing gut in children. Hematoma: ballotable fluid between perichondrium and cartilage must be promptly drained to prevent necrosis, fibrosis, and cauliflower ear. After repair or drainage: bolster dressing for 5-7 days using petroleum-impregnated gauze rolls on both sides of ear, secured with mattress sutures. Antibiotic prophylaxis for 7-10 days (typically ciprofloxacin) for penetrating auricular injuries to prevent chondritis. Cauliflower ear results from an undrained hematoma that undergoes cartilaginous transformation; once established, surgical correction is needed.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Canalicular injury", "question": "When should you suspect canalicular injury in facial lacerations, and how is it managed?", "answer": "Suspect canalicular injury with any laceration near the medial canthus of the upper or lower eyelid. The superior and inferior canaliculi drain tears from the puncta to the lacrimal sac and then through the nasolacrimal duct. Ophthalmology consultation is warranted. The canaliculi should be probed acutely to determine if injury is present. Treatment involves suture repair and stenting. Untreated canalicular injury leads to chronic epiphora (excessive tearing). This injury is easily missed if not specifically evaluated during the initial examination.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "ZMC fractures", "question": "How are zygomaticomaxillary complex (ZMC) fractures evaluated and treated?", "answer": "The zygoma is a tetrapod structure stabilized at four sutures: zygomaticofrontal, zygomaticotemporal, zygomaticomaxillary buttress, and zygomaticosphenoid. Fractures typically displace the zygoma inferiorly, laterally, and posteriorly (widening and flattening the face). The zygomaticosphenoid buttress is the most important landmark for verifying accurate realignment. Trismus can occur from impingement on the coronoid process. Approach: transconjunctival and upper buccal sulcus incisions, with lateral canthotomy if needed. Reduction via elevator/bone hook through buccal sulcus or Carroll-Girard bone screw percutaneously. Stabilize with titanium miniplates at the buttresses. Associated orbital floor fractures are addressed after ZMC reduction. Isolated arch fractures: Gillies approach (temporal incision, elevator under arch) or Keen approach (upper buccal sulcus).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial fractures", "subtopic": "CT interpretation", "question": "What are the key features to evaluate on a facial CT scan for trauma, and what constitutes superior orbital fissure syndrome versus orbital apex syndrome?", "answer": "CT evaluation: thin-slice (1 mm or finer), examine in all planes. Evaluate: orbital floor/wall integrity (coronal and sagittal cuts), fracture dimensions, extraocular muscle position on soft tissue windows, frontal sinus anterior and posterior tables, nasofrontal outflow tract, pterygoid plates (disruption indicates Le Fort pattern), mandibular continuity, condylar position. Superior orbital fissure (SOF) syndrome: ptosis (CN III), proptosis, ophthalmoplegia (CN III, IV, VI), pupillary dilation (parasympathetic CN III), loss of forehead/corneal sensation (V1). Orbital apex syndrome: all SOF findings PLUS blindness (optic nerve CN II involvement). Treatment is primarily medical (high-dose corticosteroids); may resolve spontaneously as edema subsides. Red desaturation is one of the earliest signs of optic nerve injury/visual loss.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Common flaps (fibula/radial forearm/ALT/scapula/pectoralis major/latissimus)", "question": "What are the two most important risk factors for upper aerodigestive tract squamous cell carcinoma, and what is the combined effect on cancer risk?", "answer": "Tobacco and alcohol are the two most important risk factors. A meta-analysis found a relative risk of 3.4 for oral cavity and 6.8 for oropharynx SCC in current tobacco smokers. Tobacco and concomitant alcohol consumption synergistically increase the risk 10- to 15-fold. Over 95% of upper aerodigestive tract tumors are squamous cell carcinomas.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Oral cavity defects", "question": "What is the role of HPV in oropharyngeal cancer, and how does HPV-positive oropharyngeal cancer differ from HPV-negative disease?", "answer": "HPV (most commonly HPV-16) accounts for 73% of oropharyngeal SCCs (225% increase between 1988-2004). HPV-positive patients tend to be younger, healthier, and have better prognosis with limited/no smoking history. p16 immunohistochemistry is used as a surrogate marker. The AJCC 8th edition created a separate staging algorithm for HPV-associated oropharyngeal cancer due to markedly different prognosis. As a general rule, nodal metastases reduce survival by 50%, except in HPV-associated oropharyngeal cancer.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Oral cavity defects", "question": "What are the three types of cervical lymphadenectomy (neck dissection) and what structures are removed in each?", "answer": "1) Radical neck dissection (RND): en bloc removal of lymph nodes levels I-V plus sternocleidomastoid muscle (SCM), internal jugular vein (IJV), and spinal accessory nerve (SAN). 2) Modified radical neck dissection (MRND): removal of all lymph node groups as in RND but with preservation of one or more nonlymphatic structures (SCM, IJV, SAN). Sparing all three is called a functional neck dissection. 3) Selective neck dissection (SND): lymphadenectomy preserving one or more lymph node groups routinely removed in RND/MRND. For oral cavity cancers, SND (I-III) or (I-IV) is commonly performed.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Oral cavity defects", "question": "When is segmental mandibulectomy indicated versus marginal mandibulectomy in oral cavity cancer?", "answer": "Marginal mandibulectomy (single cortex) may be performed when bone invasion is limited to the periosteum or there is minimal cortical involvement. Segmental (full-thickness) mandibular resection is required when there is medullary invasion. Preoperative imaging (CT) determines the extent of bony involvement. Intraoperatively, the periosteum may be stripped to inspect underlying bone. Immediate reconstruction of the mandible with an osteocutaneous free flap is usually indicated after segmental mandibulectomy.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Common flaps (fibula/radial forearm/ALT/scapula/pectoralis major/latissimus)", "question": "What is the 80/80/50/80 rule regarding salivary gland tumors, and what is the most common salivary gland malignancy?", "answer": "About 80% of salivary gland tumors occur in the parotid gland. About 80% of parotid gland tumors are benign. About 50% of submandibular gland tumors are malignant. About 80% of minor salivary gland tumors are malignant. Only 1% occur in sublingual glands. Mucoepidermoid carcinoma (MEC) is the most common salivary gland malignancy (~35% of salivary cancers). Pleomorphic adenoma (benign mixed tumor) is the most common overall salivary gland tumor.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Common flaps (fibula/radial forearm/ALT/scapula/pectoralis major/latissimus)", "question": "What are the characteristics of adenoid cystic carcinoma (ACC) of the salivary glands including histologic subtypes and survival patterns?", "answer": "ACC is the second most common salivary gland malignancy after MEC. It has a propensity for perineural invasion. Three histologic subtypes: cribriform (classic Swiss cheese appearance), tubular (glandular architecture), and solid/basaloid (sheets of cells). ACC shows slow but relentless progression: 5-year survival up to 90%, but 15-year survival <70% and 20-year survival only 28%. Risk for regional spread is low (5-20%), but distant recurrence occurs even 10-15 years after treatment. Most common metastatic sites: lungs, bone, and brain.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Scalp/calvarial reconstruction", "question": "What are the layers of the scalp, and what are the key techniques for reducing tension during primary closure of scalp defects?", "answer": "The scalp is among the thickest skin (3-8 mm) with the fibrous galea aponeurotica limiting pliability. Primary closure is typically limited to defects ≤3 cm. Tension-reducing techniques: 1) Orient closure perpendicular to relaxed skin tension lines (sagittal on scalp, transverse on forehead). 2) Wide undermining in the subgaleal layer circumferentially. 3) Galeal scoring: incisions parallel to the leading flap edge, spaced ≥1 cm apart, dividing only the galea. Each galeal incision increases scalp length by 1.67 mm. Scores deeper than the galea will disrupt the random pattern blood supply.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Scalp/calvarial reconstruction", "question": "What are the recipient vessel options for microsurgical scalp reconstruction, and what technical considerations apply to the superficial temporal vessels?", "answer": "The superficial temporal (ST) vessels are the first-line recipient option with a 96% flap success rate. The anastomosis should be performed at the level of the tragal notch where vessels emerge from the parotid (greatest diameter, least tortuosity). The artery is more superficial and posterior; the vein is deeper and more anterior. The vein is notoriously thin-walled and prone to twisting. If ST vessels are unavailable, neck vessels (facial, lingual, superior thyroid) can be used but almost always require vein grafts due to distance. Patients should not wear eyeglasses postoperatively to avoid pedicle compression.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Scalp/calvarial reconstruction", "question": "What are the alloplastic materials used for calvarial reconstruction, and when is reconstruction recommended?", "answer": "Calvarial reconstruction is recommended for any full-thickness defect >6 cm². Materials include: 1) Titanium mesh - strong, low infection risk, but imaging artifact. 2) Polymethyl methacrylate - easily moldable but cures by exothermic reaction that can damage tissue. 3) Porous polyethylene - pores encourage tissue ingrowth mitigating infection; best for small defects. 4) Calcium phosphate cement - weak, high late infection risk. 5) PEEK (polyetheretherketone) - strong, radiolucent, can be customized via CAD/CAM. PEEK is preferred when postoperative imaging surveillance for recurrence is needed. The type of alloplastic material was not an independent risk factor for complications on multivariate analysis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Maxillectomy reconstruction", "question": "What determines whether a prosthetic obturator versus a flap is appropriate for maxillectomy defects?", "answer": "Palatoalveolar defects that spare both canine teeth can generally be successfully treated with an obturator due to favorable root morphology of the canine and generous arch length for prosthetic retention. Obturators are inappropriate when: defects include skull base, orbital floor, orbital contents, or facial skin resection; the defect extends mesial to the ipsilateral canine tooth (greater cantilever forces). Bilateral palatomaxillectomy defects require bony reconstruction (typically fibula, 14-16 cm length) as obturators lack support and soft tissue flaps lack rigidity. Osseointegrated implants in irradiated bone flaps carry high risk of infection and osteoradionecrosis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Maxillectomy reconstruction", "question": "How is the fibula free flap configured for bilateral palatomaxillectomy reconstruction, and what is the role of virtual surgical planning?", "answer": "The fibula is shaped like the Greek letter omega (Ω) in the transverse plane. Lateral portions replace the anterior maxillary sinus wall and malar eminence. The middle portion restores anterior projection and alveolus. The fibula width replaces midfacial height. Soleus or flexor hallucis longus muscle fills the maxillary sinus. The skin paddle reconstructs the palatal defect. CAD/CAM systems use preoperative CT scans of the facial skeleton and CT angiogram of the lower extremity to preplan osteotomy locations/angles based on perforator anatomy. 3D-printed cutting guides are produced for both fibula and maxilla, and custom-milled titanium plates can be created. Dental implants are placed 3-6 months after reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects", "question": "What are the Irish classification regions of skull base tumors, and how does the location dictate the reconstructive approach?", "answer": "Region I (anterior skull base): Tumors from orbits, nose, sinuses, cribriform plate. Small defects: pericranial flap. Larger: free flap (ALT/RAM). Region II (lateral skull base): Tumors from infratemporal/pterygopalatine fossae extending to middle cranial fossa. Includes nasopharyngeal carcinoma, parotid tumors. Typically requires bulky myocutaneous free flap (ALT/RAM) with de-epithelialized skin paddle for volume. Region III (posterior skull base): Tumors from ear, parotid, temporal bone. Requires bulky flaps; muscle obliterates middle ear and seals mastoid air cells. Prosthetic rehabilitation is the mainstay for auricular reconstruction after resection.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "Describe the lamellar anatomy of the eyelid and the key measurements of the tarsal plates and palpebral fissure.", "answer": "The eyelid is divided into anterior lamella (skin and orbicularis oculi muscle) and posterior lamella (tarsus and conjunctiva). The superior tarsal plate is 10-12 mm in height centrally (crescentic shape); the inferior tarsal plate is ~4 mm centrally (rectangular). Each tarsus is ~30 mm long and 1 mm thick maximum, containing 25-40 meibomian glands. The palpebral fissure measures 28-30 mm long and ~9 mm high. The upper lid crease is 8-9 mm above the margin in men, 9-11 mm in women (lower in Asians). The lateral canthus sits 2 mm higher than the medial canthus in Caucasians, 3 mm in Asians.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "How are full-thickness upper eyelid defects managed based on size, and what is the rule about lamellae blood supply?", "answer": "Defects ≤25% (up to 1/3 in elderly): primary closure. Wedge resection with apex pointing AWAY from lid margin to create pentagon avoids notching. 25-75%: modified Hughes tarsoconjunctival flap with skin graft, or composite graft with myocutaneous advancement flap. At least one lamella MUST have intact blood supply. 4 mm of tarsus is needed to maintain lid margin stability. >75%: mucosalized tarsal graft with overlying myocutaneous orbicularis oculi flap, often combined with hinged periosteal flaps. The most common late complication after upper eyelid reconstruction is exposure keratopathy (20%).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Ptosis concepts", "question": "How is ptosis severity classified and what surgical procedure is selected based on levator function?", "answer": "Ptosis severity: mild (1-2 mm), moderate (2-3 mm), severe (≥4 mm). Levator function: good (≥8 mm), fair (5-7 mm), poor (≤4 mm). Normal excursion is >12 mm. Surgical selection: 1) Müller muscle-conjunctiva resection: mild ptosis (2-3 mm) with good levator excursion and positive phenylephrine test. 2) Levator advancement: mild to moderate ptosis with fair to good levator function (≥5 mm); success rate 76-85%. 3) Frontalis sling: poor levator excursion (≤4 mm), common in congenital ptosis. Materials include silicone, autologous fascia lata, palmaris longus. Double rhomboid design most common. Lid lag is the most frequent complication (90% of fascia lata slings).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "What is the snap-back test grading system for lower eyelid laxity, and what procedures address each grade?", "answer": "Grade 0: immediate return (normal). Grade I: 2-3 second delay. Grade II: 4-5 second delay. Grade III: >5 seconds, returns with blinking. Grade IV: frank ectropion, no return. Management: Mild laxity (firm snap back): tarsal tuck canthopexy - tarsus sutured to periosteum inside lateral orbital rim with 4-0 PDS. Moderate to significant laxity (abnormal snap back): lateral tarsal strip canthoplasty - lateral canthotomy, inferior cantholysis, strip creation, tarsus secured to Whitnall tubercle with 4-0 polypropylene. Success rate 87%. Canthopexy tightens without severing the tendon; canthoplasty detaches and repositions the tendon (more powerful but greater risk of rounding).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Ptosis concepts", "question": "What is the Marcus Gunn jaw-winking phenomenon and how does it affect surgical planning for ptosis?", "answer": "Marcus Gunn jaw-winking accounts for 2-13% of congenital ptosis. Patients demonstrate variable ptosis at rest and winking associated with jaw movement, sucking, or swallowing. It results from aberrant connections between motor branches of CN V (trigeminal) and the superior division of CN III (oculomotor). Surgical approach depends on which component (ptosis vs. winking) causes greater cosmetic defect. Shortening the levator aponeurosis improves ptosis but may increase wink excursion. Severing the levator tendon reduces winking but requires a frontalis sling, creating other significant asymmetries.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Reconstruction by aesthetic subunit", "question": "What is the nasal subunit principle and how many subunits compose the nose?", "answer": "The nose has 9 esthetic subunits (described by Burget and Menick): dorsum, tip, columella, and the paired sidewalls, alae, and soft triangles. According to the subunit principle, if >50% of a given subunit is involved in a defect, the entire subunit should be excised before reconstruction. This places scars at subunit borders (areas of shadow/concavity) rather than in the middle of a subunit (area of convexity/high visibility), minimizing the patchlike appearance. However, this principle should be used as a guide rather than an absolute rule and individualized for each patient.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Nose/eyelid/lip/ear/scalp reconstruction", "question": "What is the bilobed flap and what are the key design principles for nasal tip reconstruction?", "answer": "The bilobed flap is the workhorse for defects of the thick, stiff skin of the distal third of the nose, up to 1.5 cm. Design: First lobe replaces the defect 1:1; second lobe is ~50% of defect width and oriented vertically in the more lax upper nose. The Zitelli modification decreases rotation to 90-100° (from traditional 180°), improving viability. The flap base should be positioned laterally for tip defects and medially for alar defects. Flaps should not extend onto cheek or lower lid skin. Elevated with muscle superficial to periosteum/perichondrium with wide undermining. Dog-ear excision is planned between the defect and pivot point. Postoperative distortion and pincushioning are common.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Nose/eyelid/lip/ear/scalp reconstruction", "question": "What is the paramedian forehead flap, and how is the three-stage approach performed for nasal reconstruction?", "answer": "The forehead flap is the workhorse for complex nasal reconstruction, based on the supratrochlear pedicle. Stage 1: Define defect using subunit principle, transfer template to forehead, elevate flap in loose areolar plane above periosteum (with frontalis muscle). Pedicle narrowed to 1.2-1.5 cm at base. Flap rotated 180° and inset. Donor site partially closed, superior portion heals by secondary intention. Stage 2 (≥3 weeks later): Flap re-elevated at 2-3 mm thickness off nasal bed, excess fat/frontalis sculpted, cartilage grafts placed, flap re-inset. Stage 3 (another ≥3 weeks): Pedicle division, proximal pedicle debulked, medial brow skin unfurled and inset as inverted V pennant. For lining defects, additional distal tissue can be folded under the flap.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Reconstruction by aesthetic subunit", "question": "What are the reconstructive options for nasal defects based on location (upper, middle, and lower thirds)?", "answer": "Upper/middle third (thin, compliant skin): Primary closure for defects <5-6 mm. Full-thickness skin grafts for sidewall defects (privileged area for grafting due to thin skin and rigid bony support). Dorsal nasal, glabellar, Rieger, and miter flaps use glabellar/dorsal tissue excess, supplied by angular artery. V-Y flaps from nasal sidewall for vertically oriented defects. Lower third (thick, sebaceous, immobile skin): Bilobed flaps for defects ≤1.5 cm on tip/ala. Nasolabial flaps (superiorly or inferiorly based) for sidewall and ala defects, one or two stages. Forehead flap for defects >1.5 cm, composite defects, or those involving multiple subunits.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Nose/eyelid/lip/ear/scalp reconstruction", "question": "What are the key principles of lip laceration repair and the critical importance of the vermilion border (white roll)?", "answer": "The white roll is a pale ridge at the vermilion-cutaneous junction formed by pars marginalis fibers of orbicularis oris. Step-offs as small as 1 mm are noticeable at conversational distances. Key principles: 1) Mark the white roll with parallel marks BEFORE infiltrating local anesthetic to prevent distortion. 2) Use regional nerve blocks (infraorbital, mental) rather than direct infiltration. 3) Incisions/scars should cross the white roll at 90° angles. 4) Layered closure: approximate mucosa, orbicularis oris muscle, then skin. 5) Wound edge eversion is critical to prevent notching. The normal intercommissural distance is 5-6 cm at rest.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Lip lacerations", "question": "What are the reconstructive options for intermediate-sized (1/3 to 2/3) full-thickness lip defects?", "answer": "Lip-switch flaps are the best method: Abbe flap: Two-staged lip-switch procedure using full-thickness tissue from the opposite lip based on the labial artery. Rotated 180° on its pedicle, divided at 3 weeks. Flap height matches defect; width is HALF the defect width. For upper lip central defects, excise entire central subunit and interpolate Abbe from lower lip. Never use the central upper lip as donor (philtral columns are irreplaceable). Estlander flap: For lateral lower lip defects involving the commissure. Full-thickness medially based triangular flap from upper lip; width = half defect width. Creates a rounded commissure requiring secondary commissuroplasty. Karapandzic flap: Musculocutaneous rotation advancement preserving neurovascular bundles. For central defects up to 80%. Maintains oral competence and sensation. Risk: microstomia and commissure blunting.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial lacerations", "subtopic": "Vermilion border alignment", "question": "How is a total or near-total lower lip defect reconstructed, and what is the role of the radial forearm free flap?", "answer": "Defects >80% are difficult with regional tissue alone. Webster modification of Bernard-Burow technique: bilateral cheek advancement with triangular skin excisions near nasolabial folds and paramental flaps. Drawbacks: incomplete sensation recovery, vermilion color mismatch, poor oral competence. Radial forearm free flap with palmaris longus tendon: Most commonly used free flap for total/near-total lower lip defects. Provides thin, pliable, hairless skin with reasonable color match. Palmaris longus tendon attached to modiolus or anchored to malar eminence acts as a sling for oral competence. Can be made sensate by coaptating lateral antebrachial cutaneous nerve to mental or inferior alveolar nerve. Free gracilis muscle flap with reinnervation is another option for dynamic reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Nose/eyelid/lip/ear/scalp reconstruction", "question": "What are the key considerations for cheek reconstruction and what flap is most appropriate for large medial cheek defects near the eyelid?", "answer": "Cheek reconstruction principles: 1) Place scars at cheek margins or within relaxed skin tension lines. 2) Scars immediately adjacent (1 mm away, parallel) to nasolabial or preauricular creases - not within them, as they obliterate these landmarks. 3) Release retaining ligaments (zygomatic/McGregor patch, mandibular ligaments) for flap mobilization. For medium-large defects near the eyelid: Cervicofacial rotation-advancement flap transfers loose preauricular/neck skin. Anchoring to zygoma reduces tension on lower eyelid, minimizing ectropion risk. V-Y advancement flaps provide excellent outcomes for lid-cheek junction defects with less undermining and improved ectropion rates compared to Mustarde-type flaps. Deep plane elevation (skin, subcutaneous tissue, SMAS, platysma) improves vascularity but increases facial nerve injury risk.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Aging face anatomy", "question": "What is Bell palsy and how does it differ from other causes of facial paralysis? What is the expected recovery?", "answer": "Bell palsy is the most common diagnosis for facial paralysis in adults. It is an acquired, idiopathic palsy of sudden onset and a diagnosis of exclusion. The underlying etiology is likely latent herpes simplex virus. Treatment: corticosteroids (most effective within 24 hours of onset) and antivirals. Approximately 75% experience full resolution. Recovery typically begins within 3 weeks, though some take 3-6 months. Bell palsy is less likely with: bilateral palsy, insidious onset, or waxing/waning symptoms. In children, infectious, traumatic, and iatrogenic causes occur more frequently than Bell palsy. Mobius syndrome (bilateral CN VI and VII palsy with possible Poland syndrome and talipes equinovarus) is the most common congenital cause of bilateral facial paralysis (~1 in 50,000).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Aging face anatomy", "question": "What are the dynamic surgical options for facial paralysis, and when is each indicated?", "answer": "Options depend on nerve/muscle viability: 1) Nerve repair: When proximal and distal stumps are available. Primary repair if no tension; interpositional grafting (sural nerve) if gap exists. Ideally within 72 hours (for intraoperative stimulation of distal stumps). 2) Nerve transfer: When distal stumps/muscle are viable but no proximal stump. Cross-facial nerve graft (CFNG) is the only option providing emotional smile control (within 6-12 months of injury). Nerve to masseter: reliable, single-stage, greater excursion but only volitional control. 3) Free functional muscle transfer (FFMT): When viable muscle is absent (>24 months denervation causes irreversible atrophy). Gracilis is most commonly used. Standard for children. CFNG requires two stages (12 months apart); masseter nerve is single-stage. 4) Local muscle transfer: Temporalis (Labbé technique) or masseter for patients not suitable for FFMT.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Aging face anatomy", "question": "What is Zuker's point and Pitanguy's line, and what is their clinical significance in facial nerve surgery?", "answer": "Zuker's point: The midpoint of a line from the root of the helix to the oral commissure. The branch of the zygomaticobuccal nerve innervating the zygomaticus major (critical for smile) is found within 2.3 mm of this point. Used to identify donor branches for cross-facial nerve grafting and defines a danger zone for facial procedures. Pitanguy's line: Extends from 0.5 cm inferior to the tragus to 1.5 cm superior to the lateral extent of the eyebrow. Approximates the course of the temporal branch of the facial nerve. The temporal branches cross the zygomatic arch within the innominate fascia, then course on the undersurface of the superficial temporal fascia. To avoid injury, dissection should be deep to the superficial layer of the deep temporal fascia.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Mandibular reconstruction", "question": "What are the advantages of the free fibula flap for mandibular reconstruction, and what are the key technical considerations?", "answer": "The free fibula (Hidalgo, 1989) is the standard for vascularized mandible reconstruction. Advantages: Up to 26 cm length; based on peroneal artery with robust periosteal circulation allowing multiple osteotomies; each segment must maintain ≥2 cm length. Can be harvested with perforator-based skin paddle (up to 5 cm wide) for intraoral closure. Supports osseointegrated dental implants. Can reconstruct any mandibular segment including condyle. Up to 100% flap survival reported. Key considerations: Preserve 6 cm of proximal and distal bone for joint integrity. Can be double-barreled/stacked for height. Virtual surgical planning (VSP) with 3D-printed osteotomy guides and custom-milled plates significantly reduce operative time and improve accuracy. Nonvascularized bone grafts should NEVER be placed in irradiated fields.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Mandibular reconstruction", "question": "When are nonvascularized bone grafts appropriate for mandibular reconstruction, and what is the preferred donor site?", "answer": "Nonvascularized bone grafts are appropriate for: noncritical defects (generally <6 cm), patients without prior radiation and who will not receive postoperative radiation, benign tumors or localized malignancies with nonaggressive features, and when there is a healthy well-vascularized soft tissue bed. The iliac crest (both anterior and posterior) is the most common and ideal donor site, providing corticocancellous grafts with inherent structural support. Key principles: Rigid fixation is essential. Extraoral approach recommended to avoid salivary contamination. Delayed grafting after soft tissue healing improves outcomes. Main failure factors: bony resorption, infection, and defect length. Alternative donors include rib, fibula (nonvascularized), tibia, and split calvarial grafts.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Osteoradionecrosis", "question": "What are the pathophysiology and treatment principles for osteoradionecrosis of the mandible?", "answer": "Osteoradionecrosis occurs due to radiation-induced localized hypovascularity, hypocellularity, and hypoxia causing mandibular bone death. The extent is often not obvious on imaging and frequently involves soft tissue. When pathologic fracture or extensive segmental disease is present: 1) Aggressive/radical resection of involved mandible extending ≥1 cm beyond lesion edges to ensure healthy bone margins. 2) Reconstruction with vascularized bone (fibula flap) - nonvascularized grafts are wholly unsuitable as the irradiated tissue bed will not permit healing. 3) Often requires a second soft tissue free flap in addition to vascularized bone. 4) VSP is essential for planning accurate resection and reconstruction. 5) Load-bearing reconstruction plates for fixation. Antibiotics alone or simple ORIF will not address the underlying radiation-damaged tissue.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Mandibular reconstruction", "question": "What is the 'jaw-in-a-day' procedure and what role does virtual surgical planning (VSP) play?", "answer": "The jaw-in-a-day procedure combines vascularized fibula flap reconstruction with simultaneous osseointegrated implant-based dental prosthetic restoration in a single operation. VSP creates 3D reconstructions from CT imaging to plan osteotomies, implant placement, and prefabricated prosthetic dentition before surgery. 3D-printed patient-specific osteotomy guides ensure precise bone cuts at both mandible and fibula. Custom-milled reconstruction plates are pre-contoured to the patient's anatomy. Benefits: patient awakens with fully functional jaw; eliminates the gap between reconstruction and dental rehabilitation. VSP cases are more complex (more osteotomies) but 163 minutes faster on average. VSP should be considered for essentially all but simplest mandible reconstruction cases.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Pharyngoesophageal reconstruction", "question": "What are the flap options for circumferential pharyngoesophageal defects after total laryngopharyngectomy, and how does the ALT compare to the jejunum?", "answer": "The ALT flap has supplanted the jejunum as the optimal donor. ALT advantages: Can be used for circumferential or partial defects; sutured into a 9.4 cm wide tube; can include second skin island for tracheostomal resurfacing; ischemia tolerance >4 hours (vs. 60 min for jejunum); primary donor closure. Functional outcomes: ALT achieves speech fluency 80-100% vs. 50-75% jejunum; TEP speech use 60-100% vs. 25%; return to oral diet 91% vs. 73%; tube feeding dependence 9% vs. 27%. Jejunum is preferred in morbidly obese patients where tubular fasciocutaneous flap is prohibitive. Key technical detail: Cricopharyngeus myotomy with V-shaped flap inset at distal anastomosis helps prevent stricture. Posterior orientation of longitudinal suture line over prevertebral fascia prevents direct salivary leakage into neck.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Pharyngoesophageal reconstruction", "question": "What recipient vessels are available in a vessel-depleted neck after surgery and radiation for head and neck cancer?", "answer": "In a virgin neck: facial artery and common facial vein are primary. Secondary: lingual artery, superior thyroid artery, middle thyroid vein, internal jugular vein branches. In a vessel-depleted (irradiated/reoperative) neck: The transverse cervical artery is the key salvage vessel - available in >92% of patients, located in level Vb (supraclavicular fossa, posterolateral to SCM base), typically spared during neck dissections and radiation fields. The external jugular vein near its subclavian confluence provides reliable outflow resistant to compression. Additional options: end-to-side to external carotid; contralateral neck vessels (often need vein graft); internal mammary vessels (last resort, with vein grafts); mobilized cephalic vein.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Oral cavity defects", "question": "How do reconstructive goals differ between hemiglossectomy and total glossectomy, and what flaps are optimal for each?", "answer": "Hemiglossectomy (≤50% tongue): Goal is to preserve function of the remaining tongue. Requires a thin, pliable flap that folds easily to create ventral/dorsal surfaces and lingual sulcus. Flap width 6-8 cm. Best options: radial forearm, ulnar artery perforator (better cosmetic donor site), ALT/PAP in thin patients. Over 90% resume oral diet; speech scores of 4-5 achievable. Total glossectomy: Goal is to provide bulk for neotongue-palate contact for speech/swallow and to prevent aspiration. Requires a thick/bulky flap. ALT with vastus lateralis muscle is versatile. Flap must contact palate with mouth closed. Hyoid resuspension to mentum (~4.5-5 cm) is mandatory. Outcomes are much less favorable: >50% need tube feed supplementation long-term; speech intelligibility usually 2-3 at best.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Pharyngoesophageal reconstruction", "question": "What is the supercharged jejunal flap and when is it indicated for total esophageal reconstruction?", "answer": "The supercharged jejunum flap is a long-segment jejunal flap for total esophagectomy reconstruction. Indications: absence of stomach, radiated stomach, combined total laryngopharyngectomy and total esophagectomy where the stomach cannot reach. Technique: The first mesenteric arcade is preserved. The second arcade is dissected to its SMA origin and divided for later microsurgical supercharging. The third arcade is usually divided for length. The fourth arcade serves as the pedicle. Bowel is divided 30-40 cm from the ligament of Treitz and passed through the posterior mediastinum or retrosternal space. Manubriectomy with medial clavicular head and first rib resection expose recipient vessels (internal mammary preferred, transverse cervical second choice). Results (n=51): 94% flap success, 90% regular diet, 80% off tube feeding, 10% stricture rate.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Skin care basics", "question": "What is the Fitzpatrick skin type classification, and which types are at highest risk for postinflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) after resurfacing?", "answer": "Fitzpatrick classification divides skin into 6 types based on sun reactivity: Type I (always burns, never tans, extremely fair) through Type VI (never burns, always tans, markedly dark brown/black). Higher Fitzpatrick types (IV-VI) are at greatest risk for PIH after resurfacing procedures. PIH is an acquired hypermelanosis following cutaneous inflammation or injury. Regardless of ethnic background, patients with a history of freckles, melasma, or previous PIH are at increased risk.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Skin care basics", "question": "What is the role of tretinoin in skin preconditioning before chemical resurfacing, and what are its cellular-level effects?", "answer": "Tretinoin (vitamin A derivative) is used for 6-12 weeks prior to chemical resurfacing (8-12 weeks in darker individuals) at 0.05%-0.1% concentration combined with 4% hydroquinone. Cellular effects include: increased epithelial cell turnover, decreased stratum corneum thickness, decreased adherence of epithelial cells within dermal appendages, and suppressed melanocyte activity. Benefits include ensuring even depth of treatment penetration and faster post-procedure healing. It is the only therapy proven to repair photodamage with benefits persisting even after discontinuation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Skin care basics", "question": "What are the three chromophores targeted in selective photothermolysis, and what does complete photorejuvenation require?", "answer": "The three chromophores are: (1) water - targeted for treatment of fine lines and rhytids, (2) melanin - targeted for pigmented lesions, and (3) hemoglobin (oxyhemoglobin) - targeted for vascular lesions. Complete photorejuvenation requires targeting all three chromophores. No single laser or wavelength meets all of these objectives on its own. Selective photothermolysis uses a wavelength preferentially absorbed by the desired chromophore, delivered for a duration equal to or less than the thermal relaxation time of the target structures.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Laser resurfacing", "question": "Compare CO2 laser (10,600 nm) and Er:YAG laser (2940 nm) for skin resurfacing in terms of chromophore affinity, clinical endpoints, and healing.", "answer": "Er:YAG has 12-15 times higher affinity for water than CO2 laser, allowing more precise delivery with less collateral damage but significantly reduced collagen contraction. CO2 clinical endpoint: chamois (pale yellow) color at papillary dermis; waterlogged cotton thread appearance at reticular dermis. Er:YAG clinical endpoint: punctate bleeding (just past DEJ). In a split-face study, CO2 showed 63% improvement with 7.7 days crusting vs Er:YAG 48% improvement with 3.4 days crusting. CO2 remains the most effective modality for wrinkle removal but causes prolonged erythema (6+ months) and permanent hypopigmentation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Chemical peels", "question": "Describe the clinical depth signs (frost endpoints) for TCA peels and the differences between superficial, medium, and deep chemical peels.", "answer": "TCA peel depth endpoints: (1) Partial-depth epithelial: light white frost with stable epidermis; (2) Full-thickness epithelial: light white frost with epidermal sliding; (3) Papillary dermis: white frost with pink beneath; (4) Reticular dermis: opaque white frost. Superficial peels include alpha-hydroxy acids (glycolic acid, up to 30-50%), beta-hydroxy acids (salicylic acid, up to 30%), and Jessner solution. Medium-depth peels use TCA, often preceded by Jessner solution for more uniform penetration. Deep peels use phenol/croton oil (Baker-Gordon formula), with Hetter demonstrating croton oil as the active ingredient. Deep peels carry the highest risk of scarring and hypopigmentation and require cardiac monitoring.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Chemical peels", "question": "What complications are associated with chemical peels, and what is the recommended pretreatment for isotretinoin patients?", "answer": "TCA peel complications: PIH (especially darker skin), herpes outbreak (prophylactic antivirals required). Pretreatment with isotretinoin may increase risk of hypertrophic scarring because it interferes with re-epithelialization and keratinocyte adherence along dermal adnexal structures. Isotretinoin should be stopped 6-12 months prior to any elective cosmetic laser or chemical resurfacing procedure. Phenol/croton oil peel complications: hypopigmentation (decreased melanocytes), PIH from neomelanocyte sun sensitivity, rare wound infections (yeast, staph, strep), and risk of cardiac arrhythmia requiring cardiac monitoring.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Laser resurfacing", "question": "What is fractionated photothermolysis and how does it differ from traditional ablative laser resurfacing?", "answer": "Fractionated photothermolysis (available since 2003) delivers thousands of microscopic ablative injuries (microthermal treatment zones) surrounded by islands of untreated skin, keeping the stratum corneum largely intact. This preserves dermal appendages for more efficient healing and maintains the skin's barrier function. Unlike traditional full-field ablative lasers that uniformly destroy the epidermis/papillary dermis, fractionated lasers allow more aggressive treatment depth with a better safety profile and can be safely used on darker-skinned patients. However, results are less dramatic than non-fractionated ablative devices, with only 30% improvement in periorbital rhytids in one study (improving to 54% after four treatments).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fillers", "question": "What are the key biophysical properties of hyaluronic acid (HA) fillers, and which property is most directly related to duration of effect?", "answer": "Key HA filler properties: (1) Cross-linking - greater degree correlates with longer duration of effect (most important for longevity); (2) Viscosity - ability of gel to resist shear forces, affected by HA particle size and molecular weight; higher viscosity decreases spread but decreases ease of injection; (3) Elastic modulus (G') - ability to resist deformation, determined by bond strength; higher G' provides greater tissue lift but firmer feel. HAs are chemically identical in all species (no allergy testing needed), derived from bacterial fermentation of Streptococcus equi. First FDA-approved HA: Restylane (2003). Duration: 6-12 months depending on formulation and site.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fillers", "question": "What is the mechanism and management of filler-related vascular compromise and blindness?", "answer": "Vascular compromise occurs from vessel compression or intravascular injection of filler. The glabellar region and nasal dorsum are high-risk areas for blindness due to anatomic communication between terminal branches of the angular artery and ophthalmic artery (supratrochlear, supraorbital, dorsal nasal arteries). Accidental injection into the dorsal nasal artery under pressure can push filler retrograde into the ophthalmic artery, occluding the central retinal artery. Management of HA-related vascular compromise: immediate hyaluronidase injection at injection site and along affected vessels (mainstay), warm compresses, massage, topical nitroglycerin paste. Adjuncts: intraarterial hyaluronidase, hyperbaric oxygen, prostaglandin E1.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fillers", "question": "What is the Tyndall effect, and how are superficially placed HA fillers and CaHA nodules managed differently?", "answer": "The Tyndall effect is a bluish discoloration caused by light scattering through superficially placed HA filler particles. Management: massage to redistribute filler; if inadequate, inject hyaluronidase (enzyme that metabolizes HA); if persistent, incision and drainage with 18-gauge needle or no. 11 blade. CaHA placed too superficially appears as white nodules. CaHA is suspended in a cellulose gel, and when placed superficially or in mobile regions (lips), it migrates and coalesces into nodules. Management: massage, incision/drainage, direct excision, or observation for resorption. Intralesional corticosteroids are NOT effective for acute CaHA nodules (unlike PLLA nodules, which respond to intralesional steroids ± imiquimod or 5-FU).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fillers", "question": "Which injectable filler products require allergy skin testing prior to use, and why?", "answer": "Bovine collagen (Zyderm/Zyplast) requires double skin testing: 0.1 mL injected into the antecubital area, then 30 days later a separate body area. A positive test is a local wheal-and-flare reaction within 48-72 hours; <5% of patients test positive. Polymethylmethacrylate (PMMA/Bellafill) also requires skin testing because the preparation contains bovine collagen. Products NOT requiring skin testing: HA fillers (chemically identical in all species), human collagen (Cosmoderm/Cosmoplast), porcine collagen (Evolence/Fibrel - treated to remove allergenic telopeptides), PLLA (Sculptra), and CaHA (Radiesse).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Neuromodulators", "question": "What is the mechanism of action of botulinum toxin, and what are the three SNARE protein targets?", "answer": "Botulinum toxin is a 150 kDa zinc metalloprotease from Clostridium botulinum. Mechanism involves 5 steps: (1) binding to cholinergic nerve terminals using acetylcholine, (2) endocytosis via ATPase proton pump, (3) translocation of light chain across vesicle membrane, (4) release and activation of light chain in cytosol, (5) cleavage of SNARE proteins. The three SNARE protein targets are: VAMP/synaptobrevin, SNAP-25, and syntaxin. BoNT-A (Botox, Dysport, Xeomin) cleaves SNAP-25; BoNT-B (Myobloc) cleaves VAMP. Once SNARE proteins are cleaved, acetylcholine vesicles cannot fuse with the membrane, blocking neuromuscular signal transmission. Effect lasts 3-4 months as SNARE proteins are replaced.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Neuromodulators", "question": "What are the FDA-approved aesthetic indications for botulinum toxin, recommended doses, and most common adverse effects for each area?", "answer": "FDA-approved aesthetic areas: (1) Glabellar lines - 20 units Botox total (4 units x 5 sites: 2 in each corrugator, 1 in procerus). Most common adverse effect: eyelid ptosis (~3%). (2) Lateral canthal lines (crow's feet) - 24 units total (4 units x 3 sites per side). Most common: eyelid edema and bruising (~1%). (3) Forehead lines - treated with 40 units total (combined with glabellar). Most common: headache (9%), brow ptosis (2%), eyelid ptosis (2%). Onset: 2-3 days, increasing over first week; duration 3-4 months. To prevent eyelid ptosis from glabellar injections, avoid injection near levator palpebrae superioris and make lateral injections at least 1 cm above supraorbital ridge.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Neuromodulators", "question": "Compare the four commercially available botulinum toxin preparations (Botox, Dysport, Xeomin, Myobloc) regarding molecular weight, formulation, and storage.", "answer": "Botox (onabotulinumtoxinA): 900 kDa, vacuum-dried powder, 2-8°C storage, 2-3 year shelf life, cleaves SNAP-25. Dysport (abobotulinumtoxinA): 500-900 kDa, lyophilized powder, 2-8°C, 2-year shelf life, cleaves SNAP-25, contains lactose. Xeomin (incobotulinumtoxinA): 150 kDa (smallest, contains ONLY the active neurotoxin with NO complexing proteins), lyophilized powder, room temperature storage, 3-4 year shelf life (most stable), cleaves SNAP-25. Myobloc (rimabotulinumtoxinB): 700 kDa, sterile solution (only liquid formulation), 2-8°C, 2-year shelf life, cleaves VAMP (not SNAP-25), no aesthetic FDA approval. Doses are NOT interchangeable between products.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Neuromodulators", "question": "What are the non-cosmetic applications of botulinum toxin in plastic surgery, including the PREEMPT trial dosing protocol for chronic migraines?", "answer": "Non-cosmetic applications: (1) Chronic migraines (>=15 headache days/month, lasting >=4 hours): 155 units total across 7 head/neck sites - corrugators (5U each), procerus (5U), frontalis (5U each), temporalis (5U each), occipitalis (15U each), cervical paraspinals (10U each), trapezius (15U each). PREEMPT trials showed -8.4 headache days/month (vs -6.6 placebo). (2) Axillary hyperhidrosis: 200 units per axilla, effect lasts ~7 months. (3) Raynaud phenomenon: 50-100 units into palm targeting neurovascular bundles. (4) Hypertrophic scars: reduces wound tension during healing. Absolute contraindications: hypersensitivity to formulation components and active infection at injection site.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fat grafting", "question": "What is the Coleman technique for fat grafting, and what are the key factors affecting fat graft viability and survival?", "answer": "The Coleman technique involves syringe aspiration of fat followed by centrifugation to separate adipocytes from other lipoaspirate constituents. Fat graft survival varies from 50-70% (never 100%), so repeat procedures are often needed. Key factors: (1) Patient age - younger patients have superior fat viability; (2) Obesity paradoxically compromises fat viability despite abundant donor sites; (3) Injection technique is critical - slow, controlled pressure minimizes shear stress on adipocytes; fat should always be injected while withdrawing the cannula, never while advancing; (4) Time from harvest to injection is crucial - quicker is better; (5) No donor site has been proven significantly superior to others in comprehensive studies. Lidocaine effects are mitigated by the washing/processing step.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fat grafting", "question": "What is the most dreaded complication of facial fat grafting, and how is it prevented?", "answer": "The most dreaded complication is blindness from fat embolism to the ophthalmic or central retinal artery. This occurs when fat graft is injected under excessive pressure or while advancing (rather than withdrawing) the cannula, causing fat to enter the arterial system. Prevention: (1) Always inject fat while withdrawing the cannula, never while advancing; (2) Avoid excessive injection pressure; (3) Use small aliquots. Other complications include fat necrosis (remaining injected fat can form oil cysts or palpable masses rather than being reabsorbed), which is particularly worrisome in breast reconstruction as it may mimic malignancy and require biopsy. There is NO evidence that fat grafting increases breast cancer recurrence.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fat grafting", "question": "What is the difference between microfat and nanofat, and what are their respective clinical applications?", "answer": "Microfat (coined by Tonnard): fat harvested in small particle sizes using tumescent infiltration and small gauge harvesting cannulas (2.0-2.4 mm); injection cannulas 0.7-1.2 mm. Used for facial volume restoration and volumization. Contains viable adipocytes. Nanofat: derived from emulsification of microfat; contains NO viable fat cells but preserves adipose stromal cells (stem cells). Should NOT be used for volume enhancement. Used as an adjuvant for skin quality improvement, credited with restorative skin effects. Fat graft survival rates are still uncertain (40-80%), so overcorrection is necessary for lasting results. Preparation methods (decanting, straining, washing, centrifugation) appear equally effective.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Brow lift", "question": "Describe the anatomy of the brow musculature, its innervation, and why brow aging differs from midface aging.", "answer": "Brow musculature follows agonist-antagonist configuration: Elevator (frontalis) raises the brow; Depressors (corrugators, procerus, orbicularis oculi) pull brow inferiorly. Motor innervation: temporal branch of facial nerve (the only motor nerve at risk during brow lift). Sensory innervation: supraorbital nerve (exits midpupillary line, dominant brow sensation) and supratrochlear nerve (runs in the substance of the corrugator muscle, ~8-12 mm medial to supraorbital nerve). Unlike midface/neck aging where skin laxity and fat volume loss dominate, brow aging is primarily driven by muscle activity and imbalance over time. This explains why brow rejuvenation focuses on rebalancing muscle equilibrium rather than excising excess skin.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Brow lift", "question": "What is compensated brow ptosis, why is it important to identify before blepharoplasty, and how is it diagnosed?", "answer": "Compensated brow ptosis is a condition where the frontalis muscle chronically contracts to compensate for a ptotic brow, maintaining brow height at baseline. Clinical clue: significant horizontal forehead rhytids at rest (indicating chronic frontalis contraction). Diagnosis: have the patient close their eyes - if frontalis relaxes and brow drops, compensated brow ptosis is confirmed. Importance: performing isolated upper blepharoplasty without addressing brow ptosis removes the compensatory stimulus (hanging lid skin) that drives frontalis contraction. This can cause frontalis relaxation, worsening brow ptosis, exacerbating glabellar furrows, and unmasking eyebrow malposition. Conversely, isolated brow lifting can unmask unrecognized upper eyelid ptosis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Brow lift", "question": "Compare the open coronal, endoscopic, and lateral temporal subcutaneous approaches to brow lifting.", "answer": "Open coronal: wide exposure, comprehensive muscle treatment, effective for all pathology; disadvantages include long incision, potential alopecia, scalp paresthesias. Modified to anterior hairline approach for patients with wide foreheads (>5-6 cm from hairline to brow). Endoscopic: 3 small incisions, subgaleal dissection with endoscopic visualization, reduced scar burden, decreased scalp paresthesias, less postoperative edema. Limitations: less effective for lateral ptosis and crow's feet, difficult in high hairline/acutely sloped forehead patients, fixation concerns. Lateral temporal subcutaneous: authors' preferred technique, elliptical excision (4-5 cm long, 2-2.5 cm wide), subcutaneous dissection only (avoids motor nerve injury), reliable for lateral brow ptosis. Can combine with medial subgaleal brow lift for low medial brow. Over 400 patients with only 1 requiring relapse correction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "Describe the upper eyelid anatomy including fat compartments, lid crease measurements, and the key retractors.", "answer": "Upper lid has 2 fat compartments: central and medial (nasal), separated by the superior oblique muscle. The medial fat pad is lighter in color and sits near the supratrochlear nerve/vessels. Laterally, the lacrimal gland sits in a shallow fossa of the frontal bone (Sommering ligaments attach it). Key retractors: levator palpebrae superioris (CN III) and Muller muscle (sympathetic innervation). The levator sends anterior fiber projections into skin/orbicularis above the tarsal plate, defining the lid crease. Lid crease: 6-8 mm above lid margin in men, 8-10 mm in women. Upper tarsus height: 8-10 mm. Lateral canthus is 2 mm higher than medial canthus. Normal upper lid margin covers superior 1-2 mm of cornea.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "What is the most feared complication of blepharoplasty, how does it present, and what is the immediate management?", "answer": "Retrobulbar (orbital) hematoma causing orbital compartment syndrome and vision loss. Presents with severe pain, pressure, decreased vision, proptosis, limitation of extraocular movements, and increased intraorbital pressure - usually within 24 hours postop. Prevention: careful tissue handling (avoid fat pad traction), meticulous hemostasis, blood pressure control, stop anticoagulants. Immediate management: (1) Open incision to evacuate hematoma, (2) Lateral canthotomy to relieve intraorbital pressure (this is the immediate next step), (3) High-dose IV steroids for vision loss. Operative drainage is a surgical emergency. Secondary measures include mannitol, beta-blockers, acetazolamide. Small hematomas without vision changes can be managed conservatively with elevation and ice.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "What are the lower eyelid laxity tests, their normal values, and when is lateral canthal tightening indicated?", "answer": "Snap-back test: distract lower lid inferiorly and release - normal lid snaps back instantaneously; delay of 2-5 seconds or need to blink indicates abnormal laxity. Distraction test: pull lower lid anteriorly from globe - >6 mm is abnormal (indicates poor lid tone; lower blepharoplasty alone will cause ectropion). Squint test: patient squeezes eyelids to assess orbicularis tone and fat location. When distraction test >6 mm, a lid-supporting procedure (canthopexy for mild laxity, canthoplasty or lateral tarsal strip for moderate-severe) must accompany blepharoplasty. Key difference: canthopexy tightens without dividing the canthus; canthoplasty divides the lateral canthal tendon before reinsertion.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Blepharoplasty", "question": "What extraocular muscles are most commonly injured during upper and lower blepharoplasty, and how does inferior oblique injury present?", "answer": "Superior oblique is most commonly injured during upper blepharoplasty; inferior oblique during lower blepharoplasty. Both can be injured during fat resection, transconjunctival dissection, or by traction. Inferior oblique injury presents with vertical diplopia in primary gaze that increases in adducted upgaze (the field of maximal inferior oblique elevation is in adduction). The inferior oblique's primary action is extorsion (external rotation), secondary is elevation, tertiary is abduction. It arises from the orbital surface of the maxilla lateral to the lacrimal sac and divides the medial and central fat pads of the lower lid. Diplopia is usually transient, managed conservatively. Persistent diplopia may require strabismus surgery or prism glasses.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Ptosis concepts", "question": "How is eyelid ptosis assessed, and what is the margin reflex distance (MRD1)?", "answer": "If the upper eyelid margin is more than 2 mm lower than the superior limbus, the patient may have eyelid ptosis, typically from dehiscence or stretching of the levator aponeurosis. MRD1 (margin reflex distance 1) is the measurement in millimeters from the corneal light reflex to the center of the upper eyelid margin with the patient in primary gaze. MRD1 of 2 mm or less = visually significant ptosis. Functional blepharoplasty criteria: MRD1 <=2 mm in primary gaze, superior visual field loss of >=12 degrees or >=24%, or downgaze ptosis impairing reading (MRD1 <=2 mm in downgaze). The Bell phenomenon should be tested (globe rolling upward when patient tries to close forcibly held eyes) - absence increases risk of corneal exposure post-surgery.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Aging face anatomy", "question": "Describe the retaining ligaments of the face, their relationship to the SMAS, and their significance in facelift surgery.", "answer": "Retaining ligaments (described by Furnas, 1989) are fibrous structures connecting bone to overlying facial skin, crossing all soft tissue layers. They separate facial fat compartments, are intimately related to facial nerve branches, and are structural components of facial support. Key ligaments include zygomatic, masseteric-cutaneous, mandibular, and platysma-cutaneous ligaments. Facial fat compartments are divided into superficial and deep relative to the SMAS. The SMAS (described by Mitz and Peyronie, 1976) is a superficial fascia investing the face and mimetic muscles, contiguous with the galea, temporoparietal fascia, parotid-masseteric fascia, and platysma. It is divided into fixed SMAS (firm, lateral, over parotid) and mobile SMAS (softer, medial). Mobilization of mobile SMAS to fixed SMAS is essential in any SMAS facelift.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "SMAS concept", "question": "Compare the dual-plane SMAS facelift techniques: high SMAS, lateral SMASectomy, SMAS plication, and MACS lift.", "answer": "All dual-plane approaches undermine skin and SMAS separately, allowing different vectors. (1) High SMAS: SMAS flap elevated at/above zygomatic arch with partial transection of zygomatic and masseteric ligaments; SMAS vector superolateral, skin vector posterolateral. (2) Lateral SMASectomy (Baker): diagonal strip of SMAS resected from malar eminence to mandibular angle parallel to nasolabial fold, with posterior SMAS plication. (3) SMAS plication: no flap elevation or resection; fixed and mobile SMAS plicated together with sutures, optionally with tissue stacking (Rohrich). (4) MACS lift (Tonnard): large purse-string suture loops suspend SMAS-platysma in cranial position. The deep plane (composite) approach differs by moving SMAS and skin as a single thick, well-vascularized unit - advantageous for smokers and diabetics.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facelift/neck lift basics", "question": "What is the most common complication of facelift, and what is the most commonly injured nerve? Include risk factors and management.", "answer": "Most common complication: hematoma (incidence 4-8% men, 1-3% women; expanding hematoma 1.8%). Male gender is an independent risk factor. Prevention: strict blood pressure control (SBP <150 mmHg intraoperatively), clonidine postop for SBP <140, quilting sutures (reduced hematoma to zero in published series). Management: minor hematoma (<30 cc) - bedside aspiration; expanding hematoma requires immediate surgical evacuation (risk of skin necrosis, airway obstruction, death). Most commonly injured nerve: great auricular nerve (C2,C3), located ~6.5 cm inferior to external auditory canal on SCM surface. Causes numbness of earlobe, concha, posterior auricle. Facial nerve injury is rare (<1%); marginal mandibular branch injury causes weakness of ipsilateral lower lip depressors (denervation of depressor anguli oris).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facelift/neck lift basics", "question": "Describe the platysma anatomy, the Cardoso de Castro classification of platysma decussation, and techniques for neck rejuvenation.", "answer": "The platysma is a paired superficial neck muscle originating from pectoralis major fascia, inserting into the mentum and inferior mandibular border, extending into the lower face connecting to depressor anguli oris and orbicularis oris. Cardoso de Castro classification of midline decussation: Type 1 (75%) - limited submental decussation; Type 2 (15%) - decussation from mandibular symphysis to thyroid cartilage; Type 3 (10%) - no decussation. Surgical techniques: (1) Liposuction for subcutaneous fat; (2) Anterior platysmaplasty (suturing medial borders from submental area to thyroid cartilage) with or without transverse platysma transection; (3) Subplatysmal procedures for deep fat, digastric muscles, submandibular glands (intracapsular resection safest to avoid neurovascular injury). Subcutaneous vs deep fat test: pinch submental fat while patient grimaces - if unchanged, fat is subcutaneous.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Rhinoplasty anatomy and analysis", "question": "What are the ideal nasolabial angle, nasofrontal angle, and tip projection measurements in rhinoplasty analysis?", "answer": "Nasolabial angle (between nostril long axis and vertical facial plane): 95-100° in women, 90-95° in men. Nasofrontal angle (intersection of dorsal plane and brow plane): 128-140° with ideal 134° for females, 130° for males. Columellar-lobular angle: ideally 30-45°. Tip projection: measured from alar-cheek junction to tip; should be ~0.67 times the radix-to-tip distance (Goode ratio). Alternative: 50-60% of a line from alar-cheek junction to tip should lie anterior to the upper lip line. Tip projection from alar base should equal alar base width. Alar base width should roughly equal intercanthal distance. Bony base width should be ~80% of intercanthal distance. Internal nasal valve angle (between septum and upper lateral cartilage): <15° may contribute to valvular insufficiency.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Rhinoplasty anatomy and analysis", "question": "What are spreader grafts, and when are they indicated in rhinoplasty?", "answer": "Spreader grafts are cartilage grafts placed between the dorsal septum and upper lateral cartilage to prophylactically maintain or widen the internal nasal valve angle, particularly when a narrow valve angle contributes to obstructive symptoms. They can also strengthen the dorsal septum and help straighten dorsal septal deviations. A positive Cottle test (manual lateral traction on cheek improves airflow) indicates internal nasal valve incompetence and supports spreader graft placement on the affected side. Grafts are typically fashioned from harvested septum but can use rib or auricular cartilage. Auto-spreader flaps are an alternative, created by scoring excess medial upper lateral cartilage and folding it on itself. An L-shaped strut of at least 1 cm of dorsal and caudal septum must always be preserved for structural support.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Rhinoplasty anatomy and analysis", "question": "Compare open vs closed rhinoplasty approaches and describe the basic osteotomy types.", "answer": "Open rhinoplasty: transcolumellar stair-step incision with marginal incisions; advantages include 3D binocular visualization, simultaneous teaching, more accurate assessment of anatomic variations. Disadvantages: wider dissection, more tip edema, columellar scar, longer operative/recovery time. Closed rhinoplasty: no external scar, limited undermining, less edema, faster recovery; disadvantages include limited visualization and more difficulty with complex tip work. Osteotomy types: (1) Medial oblique - curve-guarded osteotome at septum/nasal bone junction, carried obliquely 5-10 mm to protect keystone area; (2) Lateral low-to-low - narrows nasal base width; (3) Lateral low-to-high - closes open roof without narrowing base. The Webster triangle (bone along pyriform lip) is preserved to maintain alar cartilage anchor and nasal valve stability.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Rhinoplasty anatomy and analysis", "question": "What nasal skin thickness variations exist, and what is the significance of the nasal venous drainage?", "answer": "Nasal skin is thicker over the upper third (glabella/radix) and lower third (tip/ala) and thinner over the middle third (dorsum). The thinnest skin of the face is at the upper eyelid while the thickest overlies the nasal tip. This is clinically significant because thicker skin may mask underlying structural changes and graft contours, while thinner skin shows every irregularity. The nasal veins do NOT have valves, and the nasal venous system has direct communication to the cavernous sinus, making nasal infections potentially life-threatening (cavernous sinus thrombosis). Arterial supply: external nose from internal carotid (anterior ethmoid) and external carotid (facial/angular, superior labial/columellar). Sensory innervation: external branch of anterior ethmoid nerve supplies nasal skin from rhinion to tip.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Otoplasty", "question": "What is the optimal timing for ear molding in neonates, and what are the anatomical measurements for diagnosing a prominent ear?", "answer": "Ear molding should ideally be initiated between 1-3 weeks old (not before 1 week, to allow spontaneous correction) when circulating maternal estrogens facilitate cartilage manipulation. At 6 weeks, infant estrogens equal adult levels, making molding less effective. If mother is breast-feeding, molding may be attempted up to 8-10 weeks. After 12 weeks, molding is NOT effective. Prominent ear diagnosis: protrusion >18 mm at top of helix and >21 mm at midhelix from mastoid. Normal ear measurements: height 6.5 ± 1 cm, width 4.0 ± 0.5 cm, axis angled ~20° posterior from vertical, located one ear length (6-7 cm) posterior to lateral canthus. Top of helix at eyebrow level, lobule at base of columella. ~5% of population has prominent ears; 50% of anomalies are bilateral.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Otoplasty", "question": "Describe the Mustarde, Stenstrom, and Furnas techniques for otoplasty and their specific applications.", "answer": "Mustarde technique: scapha-concha mattress sutures (typically 3-4 using 4-0 Mersilene) to recreate the antihelical fold - used for setting back the superior third of the ear. Target: superior helix 15 ± 3 mm from mastoid. Preferred over scoring for greater control and predictability. Stenstrom technique: cartilage scoring (abrading anterior surface) to weaken cartilage and facilitate bending - used as adjunct in adults with very stiff cartilage. Risk of cartilage damage and contour abnormalities. Furnas technique: concha-mastoid sutures to set back the middle third of the ear. The author prefers conchal cartilage excision (2-7 mm width, ~2.0-2.5 cm length) over Furnas sutures because suturing hard cartilage to weak mastoid fascia has higher recurrence risk. Target: midhelix 18 ± 3 mm from mastoid. Measurements should differ by <2 mm between ears for symmetry.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Otoplasty", "question": "What are the common ear deformities (cryptotia, Stahl ear, constricted ear), and how are they managed?", "answer": "Cryptotia: superior helix buried beneath postauricular skin without a sulcus; impairs wearing eyeglasses. Treatment: one-stage V-Y advancement flap from scalp to recreate retroauricular sulcus. Stahl deformity: third crus of antihelix causing pointed helix. Treatment: anterior incision at helix-scapha junction, elevate skin, resect abnormal crus; excised crus can be grafted to reconstruct missing superior crus. Constricted (lop/cup) ear: spectrum from minor helical lidding to microtia variant, with (1) lidding of helix, (2) prominence, and/or (3) reduced size. Mild: simple excisions. Moderate: treat as prominent ear (scapha-concha sutures, concha-mastoid sutures). Severe: requires cartilage grafts and staged reconstruction similar to microtia. Most otoplasty procedures are best performed after age 3 (85% of ear growth complete) to facilitate procedure while memory/self-esteem have not yet formed.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facial implants", "question": "What are the two most commonly used alloplastic materials for facial skeletal augmentation, and how do they differ?", "answer": "Solid silicone: can be easily carved to desired shape/size, easily fixated with screws or sutures, lower reported infection rate compared to other materials. Generates a more robust fibrous capsule around the implant (smooth surface). Associated with more bone erosion/resorption of adjacent areas. Porous polyethylene (e.g., Medpor): allows tissue ingrowth due to porous surface, resulting in less robust capsule formation, less implant migration, and less adjacent bone erosion compared to smooth implants. Extended porous implants have limited flexibility and are often designed as two-piece for placement through smaller incisions. Subperiosteal placement is preferred for both as it provides a bloodless, safe dissection plane relative to neurovascular structures. Rigid screw fixation is recommended to minimize malposition and provide more accurate contour.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facial implants", "question": "What is the anatomy relevant to osseous genioplasty, and what are the key measurements for determining the need for chin augmentation?", "answer": "The mental nerve exits through the mental foramen between the first and second premolars. Horizontal osteotomy must be at least 5 mm caudal to the foramen (the nerve curves caudally as it approaches the foramen distally). Anterior muscles: mentalis, depressor angularis, depressor labii inferioris. Lingual muscles (maintain blood supply to mobilized segment): mylohyoid, geniohyoid, genioglossus. Assessment: Riedel's line connects projected points of upper and lower lip - chin (pogonion) should fall on this line. Lower third of face: stomion-to-menton should be twice subnasale-to-stomion distance. Upper lip projects 2 mm beyond lower lip; lower lip projects 2 mm beyond chin. When advancing chin, soft tissue-to-skeletal displacement ratio is 3:2. Labiomental groove should measure 4 mm (women) or 6 mm (men).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facial implants", "question": "What is the 'witch's chin' deformity, and what are the main complications of facial implant surgery and osseous genioplasty?", "answer": "Witch's chin deformity: soft-tissue ptosis of the chin caused by inadequate mentalis muscle reapproximation during wound closure after genioplasty or chin implant placement via intraoral approach. Corrected by soft tissue excision through submental elliptical incision. Lower lip retraction with increased incisor show can also result from improper mentalis repair. Facial implant complications: infection (2% acute rate), malposition/asymmetry (most common reason for reoperation, total rate 10%), bone resorption (more with solid than porous implants). If infected, implant removal is recommended with antibiotics; replacement at 12 months. Genioplasty complications: >50% have temporary neurosensory loss (usually neurapraxia resolving days-weeks), tooth devitalization (avoided by osteotomy >=30 mm caudal to mandibular canine occlusal edge), wound dehiscence (rare), hematoma.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facial analysis", "question": "What is the negative vector relationship in facial aesthetics, and why is it clinically significant?", "answer": "A negative vector describes a globe-orbital rim relationship where the most anterior projection of the globe lies anterior to the cheek mass/malar eminence (i.e., the infraorbital rim and malar eminence are deficient relative to the globe). This is associated with maxillary hypoplasia and is clinically significant because: (1) it predisposes patients to premature descent of lower eyelid and cheek soft tissues, contributing to early facial aging; (2) it carries significant risk of lower eyelid malposition (ectropion, retraction) after blepharoplasty. A positive vector exists when the cheek mass supported by the infraorbital rim lies anterior to the corneal surface. Augmentation of the infraorbital rim with alloplastic implants can reverse a negative vector, decreasing incidence of lower lid malposition after blepharoplasty.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Neuromodulators", "question": "What drug interactions and relative contraindications should be considered before botulinum toxin injection?", "answer": "Drug interactions that potentiate BoNT effects: aminoglycosides, penicillamine, quinine, and calcium channel blockers (all enhance neuromuscular blockade). Chloroquine and hydroxychloroquine may reduce BoNT effects. Absolute contraindications: (1) known hypersensitivity to any formulation ingredient, including lactose (Dysport) and albumin (all preparations), and (2) active infection at the injection site. Relative precautions: patients with cardiovascular disease or neuromuscular disorders (myasthenia gravis, Lambert-Eaton syndrome) should be monitored closely after treatment. Botulism-like symptoms (dry mouth, dysphagia, breathing difficulty) have been reported at high doses in non-aesthetic indications, particularly in patients with unrecognized myasthenia gravis. Doses are NOT interchangeable between BoNT products.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fat grafting", "question": "What are the indications and clinical applications of autologous fat grafting in plastic surgery?", "answer": "Fat grafting has broad applications across cosmetic and reconstructive surgery. Cosmetic: facial rejuvenation (lip/cheek augmentation, perioral rejuvenation), gluteal augmentation, calf augmentation, and penile enlargement. Reconstructive: breast reconstruction (most widely used reconstructive application), head and neck defect reconstruction, burn/scar treatment. For breast, studies demonstrate excellent volume retention and safety without increased cancer recurrence risk. The BRAVA negative-pressure system has been described to augment vascularization of the recipient bed before large-volume fat grafting, though it has not been widely adopted. Autologous fat advantages: abundant donor sites, low cost, natural biocompatible filler, and contouring benefit at the donor site. First recorded use: Gustav Neuber in 1893 for periorbital scar correction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Fat grafting", "question": "What are the donor site complications and the clinical presentation of lidocaine toxicity during fat harvesting procedures?", "answer": "Donor site complications include abdominal wall perforation (bowel/vascular injury) and compartment syndrome. If a patient has severe postoperative abdominal pain with guarding after abdominal fat harvesting, CT scan with contrast is the next step to evaluate for free air or active bleeding before exploration. For calf augmentation, compartment syndrome (pain, paresthesias, palpable pulses) requires emergent fasciotomies. Lidocaine toxicity from tumescent solution presents with disorientation, slurred speech, vertigo, and tinnitus. Treatment: immediate IV intralipid infusion to prevent progression to seizures and cardiac arrhythmias. The effects of lidocaine in tumescent solution on adipocyte viability are mitigated by the washing/processing step of fat preparation. Coleman technique remains the gold standard despite no proven superiority over newer commercial devices.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Brow lift", "question": "What are the surface landmarks for ideal brow position and how does brow aging differ between the medial and lateral brow?", "answer": "Ideal brow position: medial extent at the intersection of a vertical line drawn from the alar base and the supraorbital rim; lateral extent at an oblique line from the alar base through the lateral canthus. The brow should peak at the junction of the middle and lateral third (approximately at the lateral limbus), 0.5-1 cm above the supraorbital rim in women and at the rim height in men. Some modern fashion standards prefer the peak closer to the lateral canthus. Medial vs lateral aging: medially, the frontalis muscle is well developed and aging is driven primarily by muscle activity and depressor-elevator imbalance (corrugator/procerus vs frontalis). Laterally, the frontalis is attenuated and skin-to-periosteum attachments are weaker, making the lateral brow more susceptible to gravitational ptosis and skin laxity. This explains why lateral brow descent and hooding appear earliest and why lateral brow lift is a common isolated procedure.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Brow lift", "question": "What is the sentinel vein, and what are the key anatomical landmarks for avoiding nerve injury during endoscopic brow lift?", "answer": "The sentinel vein lies approximately 1.5 cm superior and lateral to the lateral canthus. It serves as an important landmark for the temporal branch of the facial nerve, which runs approximately 1 cm lateral and inferior to the sentinel vein, within the temporoparietal fascia. The temporal line of fusion at the temporal crest is also located near the sentinel vein. To avoid temporal branch injury: (1) adhere to the deep temporal fascia during dissection (nerve runs superficial in temporoparietal fascia), (2) remain more than 1.5 cm above the lateral orbital rim, (3) dissecting in the subcutaneous plane avoids any motor nerve risk. The endoscopic approach uses 3 incisions: one midline vertical (3 cm, subgaleal) and two lateral at the superior extent of the temporalis muscle (down to deep temporal fascia). The periosteal plane is entered sharply 2 cm proximal to the supraorbital rim. Fixation options include cortical tunnel sutures and anchoring devices (e.g., Endotine).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facelift/neck lift basics", "question": "What are the 'tell-tale' signs of a previous facelift, and what are the 'five Rs' of secondary rhytidectomy?", "answer": "Tell-tale signs of previous facelift: (1) 'Pixie ear' deformity -- tethering and forward rotation of the lobule base from excessive skin tension at closure; (2) 'Joker lines' -- unnatural creases from excessive lateral pull; (3) 'Lateral sweep' -- artificial lateral facial contour from improper SMAS/skin vectors (prevented by preserving platysma-cutaneous ligaments); (4) Postauricular banding; (5) Visible suturing points; (6) Noncorrection of facial deflation. The 'five Rs' for secondary rhytidectomy (Beale et al.): (1) Resect skin/scar, (2) Release abnormal vectors, (3) Refill by fat grafting, (4) Reshape with SMAS procedures, (5) Redrape skin. Secondary facelifts average approximately one decade after the primary procedure. Patients are older with thinner tissues, and ancillary procedures (skin resurfacing, fat grafting) are frequently added. Complications are similar to primary procedures.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Otoplasty", "question": "What are the complications of otoplasty, and what postoperative measures prevent recurrence of ear prominence?", "answer": "Complications: (1) Unfavorable cosmetic outcome (most common problem -- asymmetry, overcorrection, undercorrection); (2) Telephone deformity -- overcorrection of the middle third without addressing the superior and inferior thirds, creating a pinched middle appearance; (3) Suture extrusion or dehiscence of Mersilene mattress sutures causing recurrent prominence; (4) Hematoma; (5) Infection (uncommon); (6) Sharp, unnatural antihelical fold from sutures pulled too tight. Postoperative care: head wrap for 1 week, then soft headband worn at night for 6 weeks to prevent accidental anterior displacement that could disrupt antihelical sutures. By 6 weeks, scar tissue is strong enough to maintain ear shape. Key symmetry check: superior helix to mastoid distance should be 15 +/- 3 mm, midhelix to mastoid 18 +/- 3 mm, and measurements between ears should differ by no more than 2 mm.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Otoplasty", "question": "What is the most common ear anomaly at birth, and how are split earlobes and auricular keloids managed?", "answer": "Helical anomaly/constricted ear is the most common ear anomaly at birth (15% of newborns). About 50% of newborns have some auricular deformity; 33% persist at 1 month. Vaginal delivery and increased birth weight increase the risk (deformational forces). Accessory preauricular cartilage is the most common overall ear anomaly. Split earlobe (from earring pull-through): de-epithelialize the cleft edges and repair with absorbable sutures in a straight line closure; use a mattress suture at the cleft end for eversion to prevent notch from scar contraction. Repiercing along the scar is allowed at 3 months (camouflages scar but higher risk of re-pulling). Auricular keloids: first-line for small keloids is pressure (clip-on or pressure earring) worn nightly. Older children receive serial triamcinolone injections plus pressure. Large keloids require surgical resection followed by pressure earring at 2 weeks and monthly follow-up with possible corticosteroid injections for 6 months to prevent recurrence.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facial implants", "question": "Describe the approach to midface augmentation including malar, paranasal, and infraorbital rim implants and their specific indications.", "answer": "Malar augmentation: indicated for patients desiring fuller cheeks or those with true skeletal midface deficiency. Intraoral approach preferred (good exposure, no external scar); subperiosteal dissection over malar eminence onto zygomatic arch. Screw fixation minimizes malposition. Paranasal augmentation: corrects deficient midface projection (congenital, cleft-related, post-traumatic). Increases nasal base projection, opens nasolabial angle, and effaces nasolabial fold depth. Can simulate effect of LeFort I advancement. Placed via intraoral approach lateral to piriform aperture; avoid positioning over pyriform aperture (nasal airway compromise). Infraorbital rim augmentation: addresses the negative vector relationship (globe projection anterior to cheek mass/infraorbital rim). Reverses negative vector and decreases risk of lower eyelid malposition after blepharoplasty. Placed via subciliary, transconjunctival (with lateral canthotomy), or intraoral sulcus incisions. Malar soft tissue must be resuspended over the secured implant before closure.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial aesthetic", "subtopic": "Facial implants", "question": "What are the specific osteotomy patterns used in osseous genioplasty, and what dictates the choice of technique?", "answer": "Osteotomy patterns vary by deformity: (1) Standard horizontal advancement -- single horizontal osteotomy below mental foramina (>=5 mm caudal, >=4 mm with reciprocating saw), extended posteriorly to prevent visible step-offs; chin segment advanced and fixed with plates/screws. (2) Vertical shortening -- two parallel horizontal osteotomies with removal of the intervening bone segment; inferior cut always made first for ease of handling. (3) Vertical lengthening -- single osteotomy with interposition of bone substitute into the gap; gaps <5 mm need no interposition material. (4) Lateral shift -- segment repositioned laterally to correct lower face asymmetry. Key details: the canine tooth root is longest and most vulnerable (osteotomy >=30 mm caudal to mandibular canine occlusal edge); mentalis muscle reattachment with interrupted sutures is critical to prevent witch's chin and lower lip retraction. Alloplastic chin implants are limited to mild-moderate sagittal deficiency only; genioplasty offers correction in all planes.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast anatomy", "subtopic": "Blood supply (IMA, lateral thoracic, thoracoacromial, intercostals)", "question": "What are the primary blood supply sources to the breast parenchyma, and which intercostal perforators supply the superior, superomedial, and inferior pedicles used in reduction mammoplasty?", "answer": "Blood supply to the breast comes from perforating branches of the internal mammary artery (IMA), the lateral thoracic artery, thoracodorsal and thoracoacromial arteries, and multiple intercostal perforators. The superior pedicle relies on IMA perforators from the 2nd rib intercostal space. The superomedial pedicle is supplied by 2nd and 3rd intercostal perforators. The inferior pedicle is based on the 4th rib intercostal space.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast anatomy", "subtopic": "Innervation/NAC sensation", "question": "Which nerves provide the primary sensory innervation to the nipple-areolar complex (NAC), and what is the clinical significance of the 4th intercostal nerve?", "answer": "The lateral branches of the 4th, 5th, and 6th intercostal nerves supply the primary sensation to the NAC. The 4th intercostal nerve is considered the major contributor to NAC sensation. Both deep and superficial sensory nerve branches allow any full-thickness pedicle to supply sensibility to the NAC, provided there is careful dissection, limited undermining, and the muscle fascia remains intact.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast anatomy", "subtopic": "Aesthetic measurements", "question": "What are the key preoperative measurements for breast augmentation, and what is the minimum pinch thickness needed for subglandular implant placement?", "answer": "Key measurements include: base width (BW), sternal notch to nipple distance (SN-N), nipple to inframammary fold (N-IMF), NAC diameter, and internipple distance. A minimum of 2 cm of pinch thickness is required for subglandular or subfascial implant placement. Patients with less than 2 cm pinch thickness are better candidates for submuscular placement.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast anatomy", "subtopic": "Lymphatic drainage", "question": "Describe the lymphatic drainage pathways of the breast, including both superficial and deep systems.", "answer": "Lymphatic pathways parallel the venous drainage and include cutaneous, internal mammary, posterior intercostal, and axillary routes. The superficial lymphatic system drains the subareolar and subdermal regions to the axillary basin. The deep lymphatic system drains to axillary nodes and also connects to a perforating system draining to internal mammary nodes. Other draining node fields include interpectoral, infraclavicular, supraclavicular, and intercostal nodal basins.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast anatomy", "subtopic": "IMF", "question": "What anatomical structures form the inframammary fold (IMF), and what happens when these structures are inadequately released during tuberous breast correction?", "answer": "The IMF is formed by the fusion of deep and superficial fascia with the dermis (attachments from the superficial fascial system to the dermis). Inadequate ablation of the old IMF during tuberous breast correction results in a double-bubble deformity, because the superficial fascia and dermis attachments from the old fold persist. Full detachment of the superficial fascial system from the dermis is required for proper correction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Capsular contracture", "question": "Describe the Baker classification of capsular contracture and identify which implant type/plane combination carries the highest risk.", "answer": "Baker Classification: Grade I - soft, no pain; Grade II - palpable, minimal firmness, no pain; Grade III - easily palpable, moderate firmness, with pain; Grade IV - firm, distorted, painful. Smooth devices placed in the subglandular plane carry the highest risk of capsular contracture. Textured devices and submuscular placement both reduce contracture rates. Medical therapy with leukotriene inhibitors has shown some benefit. Recurrent contracture may require a neosubpectoral pocket or use of ADM.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "BIA-ALCL", "question": "How should a delayed seroma around a textured breast implant be evaluated for BIA-ALCL, and what are the expected immunohistochemical findings?", "answer": "A delayed seroma with a textured implant should raise suspicion for BIA-ALCL. The fluid should be aspirated by fine needle aspiration and tested for CD30 and ALK. BIA-ALCL fluid is CD30 positive and ALK negative. If diagnosed (CD30+/ALK−), a PET-CT scan of the chest is indicated. Treatment always requires complete capsulectomy. The case should be reported to the PROFILE Registry. Adjuvant chemotherapy or immunotherapy may be needed depending on staging. The incidence is approximately 1/30,000 with textured implants and may be greatest with macrotextured devices.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Implant pocket/plane/incision choices", "question": "What are the planes of breast implant placement and the three grades of dual-plane augmentation?", "answer": "Planes include: subglandular (below parenchyma, above pectoral fascia), subfascial (below pectoralis fascia, above muscle), submuscular/retropectoral (below pectoralis superiorly, below pectoralis fascia inferiorly as it interdigitates with rectus fascia), and dual-plane. Dual-plane grades: I - minimal inferior pectoralis release with limited implant-parenchyma contact inferiorly; II - moderate pectoralis release with more inferior parenchymal contact; III - greatest pectoralis release with maximum implant-parenchyma contact inferiorly. Incision options: IMF, periareolar, and transaxillary.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Regnault ptosis", "question": "How is breast ptosis classified relative to the inframammary fold, and how does the degree of ptosis affect the decision between augmentation alone versus mastopexy-augmentation?", "answer": "Ptosis is classified by the position of the gland and nipple relative to the IMF. Pseudoptosis: gland below fold but nipple above. Grade I: nipple at the fold. Grade II: nipple below the fold but above the lowest breast contour. Grade III: nipple at the lowest breast contour. Patients with visible breast skin below the NAC on frontal view (pseudoptosis or grade I-II) may be candidates for augmentation alone. Patients with grade III ptosis (no visible skin below NAC on frontal view) likely need mastopexy in addition to augmentation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Wise pattern vs vertical scar", "question": "Compare the SPAIR technique and the Hall-Findlay vertical mastopexy regarding pedicle blood supply, tissue management, and common complications.", "answer": "SPAIR technique: relies on the 4th intercostal perforator or inferior pedicle for NAC blood supply; preserves weight in the inferior breast which predisposes to bottoming out; periareolar closure can widen. Hall-Findlay technique: uses superomedial or medial pedicles based on 2nd and 3rd intercostal perforators; excises the inferior pole tissue, suturing medial/lateral pillars together for structural support; reduces gravitational pull on the NAC. Most common complications by technique: excess scarring (periareolar), suture spitting (SPAIR), persistent asymmetry (vertical), bottoming out (Wise pattern/inverted-T). Wise pattern revision rates up to 50% with periareolar approaches.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Symmastia/double bubble/waterfall", "question": "What is symmastia, what causes it, and how does implant plane affect the risk?", "answer": "Symmastia occurs when the implant migrates medially, causing the breasts to merge in the midline. It results from overdissection or attenuation of medial pocket boundaries. Symmastia is more likely with subglandular placement because the medial pectoralis muscle attachments are not present to prevent medial migration. It is less likely with submuscular placement because intact medial pectoralis muscle attachments prevent medial implant migration.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Reduction mammoplasty", "question": "What is the indication for the amputation/free nipple graft technique in breast reduction, and what are the expected breastfeeding outcomes across reduction techniques?", "answer": "The amputation/free nipple graft technique should be considered when the nipple-to-IMF distance exceeds 20 cm, as longer pedicle lengths raise concern for vascular compromise to the NAC. It is also appropriate for patients with scars crossing planned pedicles, prior reduction of unknown technique, radiation history, connective tissue disorders, or extensive smoking history. Breastfeeding outcomes: rates of successful breastfeeding range from <5% for amputation/free nipple graft (no preservation of subareolar parenchyma) to 75-100% for techniques with full preservation of subareolar parenchyma.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Gynecomastia", "question": "What is the Simon classification of gynecomastia, and what medications are the most common cause of gynecomastia in adult men?", "answer": "Simon Classification: Grade 1 - small breast enlargement, no skin excess; Grade 2a - moderate enlargement, no skin excess; Grade 2b - moderate enlargement, skin redundancy; Grade 3 - marked enlargement, skin redundancy. Medications and illicit drugs are the most common cause of gynecomastia in men. Common offenders include antiandrogens, spironolactone, cimetidine, digoxin, marijuana, anabolic steroids, alcohol, and opiates. Males with Klinefelter syndrome (XXY) have 60 times greater risk of breast cancer than the general male population.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Gynecomastia", "question": "What is the ideal nipple position in the male chest, and what are the key surgical principles in gynecomastia correction?", "answer": "Ideal male nipple position: sternal notch to nipple distance of 20 cm, internipple distance of 21 cm, average areolar diameter of 2.8 cm. The nipple should be placed inferior and lateral at the level of the inferior border of the pectoralis major muscle. Key surgical principles: intentionally disrupt the inframammary fold (feminizing landmark), leave at least 1.5 cm of gland below the NAC to prevent saucer-type deformity, contour lower pole to emphasize pectoralis muscle border. UAL is effective for disrupting dense glandular tissue and provides skin-tightening benefits.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Tuberous breast", "question": "What are the key features and classification of tuberous breast deformity, and what are the essential surgical steps for correction?", "answer": "Features: constricted skin envelope, deficient base diameter, elevated IMF, short nipple-to-IMF distance, areolar herniation (50% of cases), parenchymal hypoplasia, asymmetry. Grolleau classification: Type I - medial quadrant absent; Type II - both lower quadrants deficient; Type III - all quadrants deficient, constricted horizontally and vertically. Essential surgical steps: release constricted base with radial scoring to deep dermis, restore nipple-to-IMF distance, obliterate old IMF (prevent double-bubble), reduce herniated tissue, correct areolar hypertrophy, restore breast volume. Dual-plane III is usually performed. Simply placing an implant without these maneuvers is insufficient.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Congenital anomalies", "question": "What are the defining features of Poland syndrome, and what is the most commonly used method of breast reconstruction in affected females?", "answer": "Poland syndrome: hypoplasia or absence of the pectoralis major (key feature) with at least two minor criteria including breast hypoplasia/absence, nipple absence, axillary hair absence, absence of adjacent muscles, absent ribs/cartilage, subcutaneous tissue absence, axillary webbing, or ipsilateral hand anomalies. Incidence: 1 in 7,000-100,000, M:F ratio 2-3:1, 60-75% right-sided. The pedicled latissimus dorsi flap combined with a prosthetic device is the most common reconstruction. Leading etiologic theory: interruption of embryonic subclavian artery blood supply at 6 weeks of gestation. Associated conditions: renal anomalies, dextrocardia (5.6%), leukemia.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Mastectomy types (SSM/NSM/total/MRM)", "question": "What are the oncologic contraindications for nipple-sparing mastectomy (NSM), and what is the reported rate of partial/full nipple necrosis?", "answer": "Oncologic contraindications for NSM: tumor-to-nipple distance <2 cm, clinical involvement of the skin and/or nipple. NSM is performed with a frozen section from the posterior nipple margin to confirm no cancer invasion. If the frozen section is positive, the NSM is converted to a skin-sparing mastectomy (SSM). Partial or full nipple necrosis has been reported in 2-20% of NSMs. Overall survival, disease-free survival, and local recurrence rates are similar between NSM, SSM, and modified radical mastectomy.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "SLNB vs axillary dissection", "question": "According to the ACOSOG Z0011 trial, when is SLNB alone sufficient and when is a complete axillary lymph node dissection (ALND) required?", "answer": "The Z0011 trial (2011) showed that for clinical T1-T2 invasive breast cancer patients with clinically negative lymph nodes, SLNB with 1-2 positive sentinel nodes was not inferior to ALND for regional control. ALND is recommended when: (1) 3 or more metastatic sentinel lymph nodes are found on SLNB, (2) clinically positive nodes at diagnosis confirmed by FNA or core biopsy, or (3) no sentinel nodes are identified (mapping failure). ALND has a 16% risk of lymphedema at 5 years, compared to 5% with SLNB alone.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation/chemo implications", "question": "What are the NCCN indications for postmastectomy radiation therapy (PMRT), and how does radiation affect implant-based reconstruction outcomes?", "answer": "PMRT is indicated for: inflammatory breast cancer, T4 tumors, 4+ positive axillary nodes, local/regional recurrence. Strongly considered for: tumors >5 cm, 1-3 positive nodes, positive margins. May be considered for: close margins (<1 mm), high-risk features. Impact on implant reconstruction: odds ratio of 4.2 for any complication vs. no radiation; reconstructive failure rate ~20% (vs. 3% without radiation). Radiation of permanent implant is associated with higher capsular contracture and worse aesthetic outcomes. Patients receiving both chemo and radiation experience radiation-related complication profiles.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Immediate vs delayed recon", "question": "What are the advantages of immediate versus delayed prosthetic breast reconstruction, and what patient/oncologic factors favor each approach?", "answer": "Immediate advantages: preserves native skin envelope and breast borders, minimizes trips to OR, improved psychological/emotional outcomes. Delayed advantages: decreased risk of complications in setting of comorbidities or adjuvant radiation, decreased mastectomy skin flap necrosis. Immediate favored for: nonsmokers, nonobese, early-stage cancers. Delayed favored for: advanced-stage cancer requiring surveillance or adjuvant therapy, concern about mastectomy flap viability, patients with comorbidities. Overall implant loss rate: 14.4% single-stage vs. 8.7% two-stage reconstruction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Prepectoral vs subpectoral", "question": "Describe the standard technique for submuscular tissue expander placement with ADM and the role of ADM in implant-based reconstruction.", "answer": "Technique: identify lateral pectoralis border, develop submuscular plane superiorly and medially, release inferior pectoralis origins along IMF. ADM (8x16 cm) is anchored medially at muscle-chest wall junction, sutured to IMF fascial attachments inferiorly, and to chest wall laterally. Inferior pectoralis is sutured to superior ADM border. Expander placed under combined muscle (upper pole) and ADM (lower pole) coverage. ADM benefits: maintains implant position, defines IMF and lateral border, improves lower pole projection, reduces capsular contracture (0-4% vs. 10-30% expected), higher intraoperative fill volume. Potential drawbacks: higher rates of infection, seroma, and flap necrosis in some studies.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Autologous (DIEP/MS-TRAM/free TRAM/SIEA/PAP/TUG/latissimus)", "question": "What are the differences between DIEP, muscle-sparing TRAM, and free TRAM flaps regarding muscle harvest, fascial closure, and donor site morbidity?", "answer": "DIEP flap: perforators dissected intramuscularly without muscle harvest; primary fascial closure usually possible; minimal donor site morbidity. MS-TRAM: intervening muscle segment between medial and lateral row perforators is harvested; reduces need for intramuscular perforator dissection; some donor site morbidity. Free TRAM: complete transection of rectus muscle segment; wide fascial resection often requiring mesh; greatest donor site morbidity with increased risk of abdominal bulge/hernia. All are based on the deep inferior epigastric vessels (branches of external iliac). DIEP perforators are mostly within 10 cm of the umbilicus. The pedicled TRAM is based on the superior epigastric artery with a delay procedure (DIEA ligation 2-3 weeks before) to improve flow.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Autologous (DIEP/MS-TRAM/free TRAM/SIEA/PAP/TUG/latissimus)", "question": "What are the characteristics of the SIEA flap, PAP flap, and TUG flap as alternatives to abdominal-based breast reconstruction?", "answer": "SIEA flap: based on superficial inferior epigastric vessels (branches of femoral vessels), runs superficial to abdominal fascia so no fascial violation; usable vessels present in ~30% of patients; requires minimum 1.5 mm SIEA diameter at flap edge; unreliable perfusion across midline. TUG (transverse upper gracilis): based on medial circumflex femoral artery (branch of profunda femoris); mean weight 268 g; pedicle ~7 cm; best for small-moderate breasts; risk of labial spreading with closure. PAP (profunda artery perforator): posterior thigh tissue; average pedicle length 10.6 cm; perforators through adductor magnus ~5-6 cm below gluteal crease; mean weight 220 g (horizontal design) or 340-735 g (fleur-de-lis design).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Nipple recon/tattooing", "question": "What are the most common local flap techniques for nipple reconstruction, what is the expected long-term projection loss, and when is 3D tattooing the safest option?", "answer": "Common local flaps: skate flap, star flap, and C-V flap - all consist of two lateral flaps (form circumference) and a central flap (forms tip). Long-term projection loss is 40-70%, mostly in first 2 years. Surgeons should create a nipple at least 50% larger than desired. 3D tattooing is the safest option for patients with radiated implant-reconstructed breasts, as all flap/graft techniques require incisions in compromised, poorly vascularized tissue. Areolar tattooing is typically performed 6-8 weeks after nipple reconstruction. NAC reconstruction should be delayed 3-6 months after breast reconstruction to allow settling.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Lymphedema", "question": "What is the risk of lymphedema following ALND versus SLNB, and what other morbidities are associated with axillary surgery?", "answer": "ALND carries a 16% risk of lymphedema at 5 years. SLNB has a 5% risk of lymphedema at 5 years. In addition to lymphedema, axillary surgery can cause arm stiffness, pain, and paresthesia. Patients who undergo SLNB have improved arm volume, sensibility, and ROM compared to ALND patients. The NSABP-B04 and King's-Cambridge trials showed that treating the axilla decreased recurrence rate but did not improve survival in clinically node-negative patients.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Liposuction", "question": "What are the zones of adherence relevant to liposuction, and why must they be approached with caution?", "answer": "Zones of adherence are regions where subcutaneous tissues are securely adherent to the deep fascia. They include: gluteal crease, lateral gluteal depression, middle medial thigh, distal iliotibial tract, and distal posterior thigh. Liposuction in these areas should be avoided or performed with extreme caution because the risk of contour irregularities is very high. The subcutaneous fat has two layers: a superficial dense layer (adherent to dermis, most susceptible to contour irregularities) and a deep loose layer (safest to suction).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Tumescent technique", "question": "Compare the wetting solution techniques for liposuction including estimated blood loss, and what is the maximum safe lidocaine dose in tumescent liposuction?", "answer": "Dry: no infiltrate, 20-40% blood loss. Wet: 200-300 mL per area, 25% blood loss. Superwet: 1 mL infiltrate per 1 mL aspirate, ~1-4% blood loss. Tumescent: 2-3 mL infiltrate per 1 mL aspirate (to skin turgor), ~1% blood loss. Traditional maximum lidocaine dose is 7 mg/kg. In tumescent liposuction, doses up to 35 mg/kg have been reported as safe. Treatment for lidocaine toxicity (LAST): 20% lipid emulsion - bolus 1.5 mL/kg IV over 1 minute, then infusion at 0.25 mL/kg/min. LAST presents with perioral numbness, lightheadedness, progressing to seizures and cardiac arrest.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Post-bariatric", "question": "What preoperative criteria must massive weight loss (MWL) patients meet before body contouring surgery, and what are the most common nutritional deficiencies?", "answer": "Criteria: weight stable within 5 kg for at least 3 months; BMI ideally <30 kg/m2 (higher BMI increases complications); smoking cessation for 4+ weeks (verified by urine cotinine); adequate protein intake (75-100 g/day perioperatively). Up to 50% of post-bariatric patients have nutritional deficiencies. Most common: iron-deficiency anemia (~40%); also calcium (40-50%), vitamin D (20-40%), zinc (20-40%), folate (30-50%), vitamin B1/thiamine (20-30%), vitamin B12 (10-15%). Albumin <2.1 g/dL is predictive of increased mortality. VTE risk is ~3% overall, increasing to ~9% with BMI >35.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Gluteal fat grafting safety", "question": "What technique is used for gluteal augmentation via fat grafting during body contouring, and what safety considerations apply?", "answer": "Expansion vibration lipofilling (EVL) of the gluteal area is an extension of the SAFE (separation-aspiration-fat equalization) liposuction technique. It utilizes exploded liposuction tip cannulas and existing instrumentation. Close attention must be given to patient safety and avoiding critical structures when lipofilling to prevent fat embolism, which is the most feared complication. The most common cause of death following liposuction is VTE. For aspirates >5 L (large-volume liposuction), the procedure should be performed in a hospital setting with overnight monitoring and specific fluid replacement protocols.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Layers", "question": "What are the seven layers of the abdominal wall, and what are the three Huger zones of abdominal blood supply?", "answer": "Seven layers (superficial to deep): (1) skin, (2) superficial subcutaneous fat, (3) Scarpa fascia (superficial fascial system), (4) subscarpal/deep fat layer, (5) anterior rectus sheath, (6) muscle, (7) posterior rectus sheath. Four paired muscle groups: rectus abdominis, external oblique, internal oblique, transversus abdominis. Huger zones: Zone I (midabdomen) - supplied by deep superior and deep inferior epigastric arcades; Zone II (lower abdomen) - superficial and deep circumflex arteries; Zone III (lateral abdomen) - intercostal, subcostal, and lumbar arteries. After abdominoplasty, Zone I supply is lost; the flap is predominantly supplied by Zone III segmental perforators.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Progressive tension sutures", "question": "What is the role of progressive tension sutures in abdominoplasty, and how do they affect drain use and seroma rates?", "answer": "Progressive tension sutures minimize dead space and reduce tension at the closure line by advancing the abdominal skin flap and securing it to the underlying abdominal wall. Studies have shown that use of progressive tension sutures (or quilting sutures) can reduce seroma formation sufficiently that drains may be safely omitted without increased risk of seroma. These sutures, combined with meticulous hemostasis and compression garments, represent a multi-pronged approach to seroma prevention. The technique involves placing absorbable sutures from the deep surface of the flap to the underlying fascia.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Abdominoplasty", "question": "What nerve is most commonly injured during abdominoplasty, what syndrome does this cause, and what precautions can prevent this injury?", "answer": "The lateral femoral cutaneous nerve is the most commonly injured nerve during abdominoplasty, causing meralgia paresthetica - characterized by anterolateral thigh burning, tingling, and numbness. This nerve emerges approximately 2 cm (1 cm per some sources) medial to the anterior superior iliac spine (ASIS). To prevent injury, dissection in this area should be superficial, and at least some fat should be preserved overlying the musculofascia near the ASIS. Other at-risk nerves include the iliohypogastric (inguinal crease/gluteal numbness) and ilioinguinal (medial thigh/scrotum/labia numbness).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Seroma prevention", "question": "What is a diver's test in the context of abdominoplasty evaluation, and what does a positive result indicate?", "answer": "The diver's test is performed by having the patient flex at the waist from a standing position. A positive test shows a lower abdominal protuberance with flexion that is not present when erect, indicating myofascial laxity. This is most commonly a result of pregnancy causing separation of the rectus muscles (diastasis recti). Myofascial laxity is corrected with plication of the rectus muscles during abdominoplasty. Plication tightens the abdominal wall, but this is theorized to increase intra-abdominal pressure, which increases VTE risk. Abdominoplasty has the highest frequency of death due to PE among cosmetic procedures.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Abdominoplasty", "question": "What is the fleur-de-lis abdominoplasty, and when is it indicated?", "answer": "The fleur-de-lis abdominoplasty combines the standard low horizontal incision with excision of a vertical ellipse of abdominal tissue. It is best suited for patients with both horizontal AND vertical skin and tissue excess, which is commonly the case in massive weight loss patients. First described by Dellon, the major disadvantage is an additional vertical midline scar. Care must be taken to only undermine to the degree necessary for skin resection. Adjunctive liposuction to the lateral abdomen creates discontinuous undermining that increases flap excursion laterally without increasing vascular compromise risk.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Belt lipectomy", "question": "How does a belt lipectomy differ from a lower body lift (LBL), and what are the key goals of each procedure?", "answer": "Belt lipectomy: higher/more superior resection at the waistline level; emphasizes waist shape; directly excises central adiposity of flanks; suited for android (male) fat distribution; zones of adherence are disrupted with liposuction but not markedly; limited direct thigh correction. Lower body lift: more inferior resection pattern; enables more control of lateral thigh and buttock shape; suited for gynecoid (female) fat distribution with hip/thigh adiposity; more powerful direct lifting of lateral thighs; allows gluteal autoaugmentation with dermoglandular flaps. Belt lipectomy goals: eliminate ptotic panniculus, define waist, eliminate lower back rolls, elevate lateral thighs and mons pubis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Thigh lift", "question": "Why is a transverse-only thigh lift insufficient for massive weight loss patients, and what is the most feared complication of a medial thighplasty?", "answer": "Transverse-only thigh lifts can only treat the proximal third of the thigh deformity because the force of pull is not transmitted past the proximal third. MWL patients have circumferential excess along the entire thigh length, requiring a vertical medial thigh lift for adequate correction. Overly aggressive transverse resection attempting greater correction risks labial spreading. Thighplasty has the highest rate of recurrent skin laxity of all body contouring procedures - this is neither avoidable nor predictable preoperatively. The SFS of the thigh flap should be secured to Colles fascia to prevent labial distortion and scar migration.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Brachioplasty", "question": "What is the most commonly injured nerve during brachioplasty, and what anatomical considerations help prevent this injury?", "answer": "The medial antebrachial cutaneous (MABC) nerve is the most commonly injured sensory nerve during brachioplasty. It pierces the deep fascia an average of 14 cm proximal to the medial epicondyle and travels with the basilic vein in the superficial plane of the distal half to third of the upper arm. To prevent injury: leave at least 1 cm of fat on the deep brachial fascia, use liposuction for atraumatic dissection to preserve nerves and lymphatics, and avoid liposuction access incisions at the posteromedial elbow (risk to ulnar nerve). The most common reason for patient dissatisfaction/reoperation is unsightly scarring.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Seroma/contour deformity/fat embolism/wound breakdown", "question": "What is the most common postoperative complication of liposuction, and what technique helps prevent it?", "answer": "Contour irregularities are the most common postoperative complication of liposuction, occurring in up to 20% of patients. Prevention techniques include: use of small cannulas, multiple access incisions, and cross-tunneling/cross-hatching (creating intersecting parallel lines via multiple access sites). The SAFE technique (separation-aspiration-fat equalization) also helps minimize irregularities. Treatment of irregularities requires secondary fat equalization and fat grafting to oversuctioned regions. VTE is the most common cause of death following liposuction. Seroma is a common complication of abdominoplasty and belt lipectomy, reduced by progressive tension sutures, drains, and compression garments.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based", "question": "What are the risk factors for complications in prosthetic breast reconstruction, and what are the predictors of implant salvage failure in the setting of infection?", "answer": "Risk factors: smoking (OR 4 for early TE loss; more than doubles flap necrosis, infection, and reconstructive failure), obesity (BMI >30; 7x more likely to have reconstructive failure), diabetes (Hgb A1C >6.5%), large breasts/high mastectomy specimen weight, and radiation therapy. Infection rate is approximately 7.6% overall. Predictors of implant salvage failure: elevated WBC at admission and MRSA infection. Gram-positive organisms (Staphylococcus, Streptococcus, Propionibacteria) are the most common pathogens. Diffuse erythema, drain output character, fever, and MSSA growth are NOT predictive of salvage failure.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic breast", "subtopic": "Implant rupture", "question": "What is the FDA recommendation for screening of silent ruptures in silicone breast implants, and how do saline and silicone implant ruptures differ in presentation?", "answer": "FDA recommendation: MRI 3 years after placement, then every 2 years thereafter to identify silent ruptures. Saline rupture: easily identified by unilateral deflation and sudden breast asymmetry. Silicone rupture: may be silent - diagnosed on mammography or MRI; can be intracapsular or extracapsular. Fifth-generation cohesive gel implants differ from earlier generations due to increased cross-linking of silicone. Delayed capsular contracture can be due to a silent rupture. Regardless of type or manufacturer, implant rupture is inevitable. Silicone implants are considered 'off label' for women under 22 years per FDA.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Mastectomy types (SSM/NSM/total/MRM)", "question": "What is the lifetime risk of breast cancer, and what hereditary genes are associated with breast cancer susceptibility?", "answer": "Lifetime risk is approximately 12.4% (1 in 8 women). Hereditary breast cancer accounts for up to 20% of cases. Syndromic susceptibility genes: BRCA 1 and 2 (20-40% of hereditary cancers), TP53 (Li-Fraumeni), PTEN (Cowden syndrome), CDH1 (hereditary diffuse gastric cancer), STK11 (Peutz-Jeghers), mismatch repair genes (Lynch syndrome), NF1. Non-syndromic: PALB2, CHEK2, ATM. BRCA1: 55-65% breast cancer risk, 39% ovarian cancer risk by age 70. BRCA2: 45% breast cancer risk, 11-17% ovarian cancer risk. Both increase risk for fallopian tube, peritoneal, prostate, and pancreatic cancer.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Digital nerve/artery repair", "question": "Describe the vascular anatomy of the hand, including the superficial and deep palmar arches, and explain why ligation of a single digital artery rarely causes terminal ischemia.", "answer": "The ulnar artery's larger volar branch completes the superficial palmar arch, while its smaller dorsal branch completes the deep arch. The radial artery's larger dorsal branch passes through the anatomic snuffbox to the deep arch, with a small volar branch contributing to the superficial arch. Common digital arteries arise from the superficial arch; the princeps pollicis artery arises from the radial artery portion of the deep arch. Numerous redundant arterial interconnections exist within every hand, so disruption of one artery is unlikely to result in terminal ischemia. Nevertheless, arterial supply should always be examined before deciding to ligate rather than repair.", "notes": "Ch 67 - Upper Extremity Anatomy", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Digital nerve/artery repair", "question": "What is the clinical significance of the midlateral line of the finger, and how does it relate to the positioning of neurovascular structures?", "answer": "The midlateral line is defined by the junction of glabrous and nonglabrous skin, identifiable when the PIP and DIP joints are flexed. Incisions along this line minimize scar contractures of the joints. The digital neurovascular bundles and flexor tendon sheath lie volar to this line, while the bony phalanges are dorsal. This relationship is critical when placing percutaneous K-wires (place dorsal to midlateral line) and when planning surgical approaches to the digit.", "notes": "Ch 67 - Upper Extremity Anatomy", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Tissue handling", "subtopic": "Atraumatic handling", "question": "Why should the MP joints be splinted in flexion and the PIP joints in extension, and what anatomic features account for this difference?", "answer": "The MP joint metacarpal head is wider volarly, so flexion tightens the collateral ligaments and elongates the volar plate, maintaining joint mobility. Immobilizing the MP in extension allows the collateral ligaments to shorten, leading to contracture. The PIP joints have small volar checkrein ligaments from the proximal phalanx volar ridges to the volar plate that contribute to flexion contractures. Therefore, PIP joints should be splinted in full extension to prevent these contractures. This is the safe position (intrinsic plus): MPs flexed ~70-90 degrees, IPs in extension.", "notes": "Ch 67 - Upper Extremity Anatomy", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Tissue handling", "subtopic": "Blood supply", "question": "What is the significance of the A2 and A4 pulleys in flexor tendon surgery, and how does the pulley system prevent bowstringing?", "answer": "The flexor tendon sheath extends from the proximal edge of the A1 pulley to the DIP joint. Annular pulleys (A1-A5) are numbered proximal to distal with three compressible cruciate pulleys intervening from A2 to A5. These pulleys prevent bowstringing of the flexor tendons and allow for improved excursion/moment arcs at the corresponding joint levels. The A2 and A4 pulleys are the most critical biomechanically and must be preserved during flexor tendon surgery to maintain function. Loss of these pulleys results in bowstringing and loss of finger flexion efficiency.", "notes": "Ch 67 - Upper Extremity Anatomy", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Tissue handling", "subtopic": "Tension", "question": "What is the functional importance of the extrinsic versus intrinsic extensor mechanism at the PIP joint, and why do the PIP and DIP joints fail to extend without intrinsic muscle contraction?", "answer": "The extrinsic extensors primarily extend the MP joint via the sagittal bands, with some contribution to IP extension. At the PIP joint, the intrinsic muscles (interossei and lumbricals) join the extensor mechanism and contribute to the lateral bands, which pass volar to the MP joint axis (aiding MP flexion) but dorsal to the PIP joint axis. The intrinsic insertions function as the primary IP extensors. The PIP and DIP joints will not extend if the intrinsic muscles do not contract, because the extrinsic extensors alone cannot transmit adequate extension force past the proximal phalanx to the interphalangeal joints.", "notes": "Ch 67 - Upper Extremity Anatomy", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Sutures and needles", "subtopic": "Closure by location", "question": "Describe the principles of the ERAS (Enhanced Recovery After Surgery) approach to hand surgery, including the importance of surface anatomy knowledge for safe incision placement.", "answer": "ERAS principles in hand surgery emphasize understanding the relationship between surface landmarks and underlying anatomy to facilitate safe and efficient surgery. Key surface landmarks include: distal wrist crease at the midcarpal joint (proximal edge of transverse carpal ligament), distal palmar crease overlying metacarpal necks (5-8 mm proximal to MP joints), and the thenar crease corresponding to CMC motion. The misleadingly named MP crease actually overlies the midportion of the proximal phalanx. PIP and DIP creases overlie the actual joints and can be used to locate underlying flexor tendon pulleys. Incisions should respect these landmarks to minimize damage to underlying structures.", "notes": "Ch 67 - Upper Extremity Anatomy", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Flexor tenosynovitis (Kanavel signs)", "question": "What are the four Kanavel signs of flexor tenosynovitis, what is the most common pathogen, and what is the surgical management?", "answer": "The four Kanavel signs are: (1) fusiform (sausage-shaped) swelling of the digit, (2) digit held in a flexed position, (3) pain with passive extension, and (4) tenderness along the flexor tendon sheath extending into the palm. The most common pathogen is S. aureus. Surgical treatment involves two incisions: a palmar oblique incision over the A1 pulley and a midaxial/transverse incision at the distal P2 level. The A1 pulley is incised longitudinally, cultures are taken, and the sheath is irrigated with at least 1L of saline using a 14-18 gauge angiocatheter or pediatric feeding tube inserted proximally and draining distally. Retrospective studies show continuous postoperative irrigation has no better outcomes than intraoperative irrigation alone.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Paronychia/felon", "question": "Compare and contrast the presentation, pathogenesis, and treatment of paronychia and felon infections.", "answer": "Paronychia: Infection of skin around the nail fold, often from hangnails, manicure instruments, or nail biting. Presents with swelling, erythema, and pain around the nail plate. Most common pathogen is S. aureus. Early treatment: soaks, oral antibiotics (first-gen cephalosporin), elevation. If abscess forms: I&D with a #11 or #15 blade over the most prominent area, blunt dissection, and wick placement for 24 hours. Chronic paronychias are usually due to Candida albicans, treated with antifungals and marsupialization. Felon: Focal infection within the fingertip pulp, usually from a puncture wound. Extensive septae keep infection localized, causing abscess with throbbing pain often without visible external swelling until advanced. Same pathogen (S. aureus). I&D with longitudinal incision over most prominent point, avoiding neurovascular bundles. Blunt probing to break septae. Delayed treatment risks pulp necrosis, osteomyelitis, or extension into the flexor sheath.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Human/fight/animal bites", "question": "What is the appropriate workup and management of a fight bite (clenched fist injury), and why is the MCP joint violated in most cases?", "answer": "Fight bites result from tooth penetration through the joint capsule during a punch to the face, inoculating the sterile joint space with bacteria. The MCP joint is violated in 70% of cases. Patients typically present 2-3 days later with a benign-appearing scab over the dorsal MCP, pain with axial loading, and swelling. Management requires OR exploration: elliptical excision of the wound, examination of the extensor mechanism (which may have glided away from the skin wound), and full joint exploration. Because the extensor mechanism glides with ROM, punctures may not directly underlie the skin wound. If joint violation is found, capsulotomy, culture, irrigation with saline, and broad-spectrum antibiotics covering S. aureus and oral flora (Eikenella corrodens and Bacteroides sp.) are required. A gauze wick is placed, and the wound is loosely closed. Delay in treatment can result in extensive joint destruction and osteomyelitis.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Deep-space infections", "question": "Describe the horseshoe abscess and collar button abscess, including their anatomic pathways and treatment principles.", "answer": "Horseshoe abscess: A thenar space infection blocked from ulnar spread by the midpalmar septum instead travels proximally along FPL into the wrist Parona space, crosses to the small finger flexors, and spreads distally into the ulnar hand, circumventing the mid palm. Treated with extended carpal tunnel or curved longitudinal palmar incision. Collar button abscess: Originates in the volar webspace; the strong palmar aponeurosis blocks proximal spread, so infection spreads dorsally into the dorsal subcutaneous tissues, causing puckering, swelling, and abducted digit position. Requires both volar and dorsal incisions for complete drainage; transverse incisions in the webspace cause adduction contractures and should be avoided. All deep-space infections require formal I&D in the OR, cultures, gauze wicks, broad-spectrum IV antibiotics, and early hand therapy. Most common pathogens are S. aureus and group A Streptococcus.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Necrotizing infection", "question": "What are the clinical features and emergent management of necrotizing fasciitis of the hand?", "answer": "Necrotizing fasciitis is a life- and limb-threatening emergency. Patients present with rapidly ascending cellulitis, discoloration, blistering, crepitus, limited ROM, and pain out of proportion to exam. Inciting trauma is often minor. Type 1 involves multiple anaerobic and aerobic bacteria; Type 2 involves group A Streptococcus and Staphylococcus (MRSA isolated in up to 39% of cases). Immunocompromised patients, diabetics, elderly, and IV drug abusers are more susceptible. A classic intraoperative sign is cloudy 'dishwasher drainage' from fascial necrosis. Management: DO NOT delay treatment for imaging. Stat gram stain, broad-spectrum IV antibiotics, aggressive resuscitation, and emergent operative debridement are required. Amputation must be considered with advanced muscle necrosis and septic shock. ICU admission for hemodynamic monitoring. Return to OR for second look within 24-48 hours. Extensive soft tissue reconstruction is typically needed once infection clears.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Septic arthritis", "question": "How do you diagnose and manage septic arthritis of the wrist, and how do you differentiate it from gout or pseudogout?", "answer": "Septic arthritis presents with worsening wrist pain, severe pain with ROM and axial loading, swelling, warmth, and overlying cellulitis. Common pathogens: S. aureus, Streptococcus, H. influenzae (children), N. gonorrhoeae. Differentiation from gout/pseudogout: prior flares and patchy calcifications suggest autoimmune etiology; penetrating trauma, fever, erythema, and lymphangitis suggest infection. Wrist aspiration at the 3-4 interval (just distal and ulnar to Lister tubercle) confirms diagnosis; fluid sent for crystal analysis and culture. Normal fluid is clear/straw colored. Treatment: gonococcal may respond to IV antibiotics alone; all other bacteria warrant operative washout via dorsal longitudinal incision with ligament-sparing capsulotomy, culture, and 3L saline irrigation. Avoid pulse lavage (damages cartilage). Arthroscopic washout achieves similar results with less stiffness. Postop: wrist splint, elevation, IV antibiotics, low threshold for second look in 24-48 hours.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Fingertip amputations", "question": "What are the goals of fingertip reconstruction, and how does defect size guide the choice of closure method?", "answer": "Goals are to restore fingertip padding for tactile gnosis, preserve finger length, maintain an intact nail bed, and minimize downtime. Treatment algorithm: (1) Defects <1 cm2 with minimal bone/nail matrix exposure: heal by secondary intention (restores sensation and comparable functionality to skin grafts). (2) Defects 1-1.5 cm2 with volar oblique injury or tendon/bone exposure: surgical closure needed. (3) Defects with largest dimension <1 cm: local V-Y advancement flaps (best for transverse or dorsal oblique amputations with sufficient nail bed bony support; near-normal sensory recovery). (4) Larger or composite defects: homodigital, heterodigital, locoregional, or free tissue transfers. Cross-finger and thenar flaps require a two-stage procedure with 2-3 weeks of restraint. Microvascular toe pulp transfer is optimal for volar fingertip reconstruction due to glabrous skin similarity.", "notes": "Ch 69 - Fingertip/Nail Bed", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Nail-bed injuries", "question": "Describe the anatomy of the nail bed and the management principles for nail bed lacerations and avulsions.", "answer": "Nail anatomy includes: nail plate, paronychium (lateral soft tissue fold), eponychium (dorsal soft tissue creating the matte sheen), hyponychium (keratinous distal attachment to pulp skin), and the nail bed beneath the plate. The nail bed has two zones: germinal matrix (proximal to the lunula, responsible for nail growth) and sterile matrix (distal to the lunula). Management of lacerations: remove the nail plate under anesthesia/tourniquet, examine under magnification. If germinal matrix is involved, elevate the eponychial fold via bilateral incisions. Repair with 6-0 or 7-0 absorbable monofilament sutures. For stellate lacerations, conservatively debride but preserve small pieces of nail bed. For avulsions: if nail bed is recovered, suture it back; if partially avulsed, undermine and advance remaining nail bed; severe avulsions may require a nail bed graft from the big toe. After repair, reinsert the soaked nail plate (or silicone sheath) as a stent to prevent synechiae, secured with 5-0 nylon.", "notes": "Ch 69 - Fingertip/Nail Bed", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Fingertip amputations", "question": "What is the Moberg flap, when is it indicated for thumb reconstruction, and what are its advantages and limitations?", "answer": "The Moberg flap is a volar advancement flap used for thumb amputations distal to the interphalangeal joint, especially volar oblique thumb tip defects. It advances distally by 1.5-2 cm without causing flexion contracture. Advantages: excellent sensory restoration (bilateral neurovascular bundles are included), maintains contour, and provides a suitable fingerprint pattern for friction. Limitations: defects requiring >2 cm of advancement are not suitable because additional procedures are needed to prevent IP joint flexion contracture (e.g., division of the proximal skin bridge). Larger defects should be reconstructed with the first dorsal metacarpal artery (DMCA) flap, which provides more soft tissue and immediate sensation via a branch of the superficial radial nerve. If DMCA is not possible, an innervated heterodigital island flap from the long or ring finger is an alternative, though it requires more pedicle dissection and causes donor finger sensory loss.", "notes": "Ch 69 - Fingertip/Nail Bed", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Tuft fractures", "question": "When should a subungual hematoma be explored versus treated conservatively, and what is the significance of an associated distal phalanx fracture?", "answer": "Conservative treatment (warm compression and analgesics) is appropriate for asymptomatic patients or when the hematoma affects less than half the nail bed. If the hematoma affects more than half the nail bed, it is likely that the nail bed is lacerated and requires repair. In children, if the nail and perionychium are intact, no exploration or nail plate removal is needed; outcomes are similar regardless of treatment method. If X-ray shows a distal phalanx fracture associated with the subungual hematoma, the nail plate should be removed for thorough examination and any nail bed laceration should be repaired. A Seymour fracture (open physeal fracture in children with nail bed laceration) requires irrigation, debridement, nail bed repair, and fracture reduction.", "notes": "Ch 69 - Fingertip/Nail Bed", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Fingertip amputations", "question": "What is the reconstructive elevator concept, and how does it differ from the traditional reconstructive ladder in hand surgery?", "answer": "The traditional reconstructive ladder follows a stepwise approach increasing in complexity: primary closure, skin grafts, local flaps, regional flaps, distant flaps, and free flaps. The reconstructive elevator concept, more suitable for hand defects, allows the surgeon to select any procedure that will best achieve the desired functional and aesthetic outcomes, regardless of complexity level. For example, a surgeon may jump directly to a free flap if it provides the optimal result. Key principles: definitive wound closure should be planned expeditiously to achieve primary healing, minimize scar/contracture; wound bed preparation is mandatory before coverage; NPWT bridges the gap but prolonged use in the hand causes contracture and stiffness; exposed vital structures may require immediate flap coverage; and the ultimate goal is to replace like with like, restore function, and preserve sensibility and mobility.", "notes": "Ch 69 - Fingertip/Nail Bed", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Carpal tunnel", "question": "What is the anatomy, presentation, and diagnostic workup for carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS)?", "answer": "The carpal tunnel is a U-shaped canal formed by carpal bones and bridged anteriorly by the transverse carpal ligament (TCL). It contains 9 tendons and the median nerve. CTS is the most common compressive neuropathy (incidence ~2.3/100 person-years), much more common in women. Early symptoms: aching carpal tunnel pain, numbness/tingling in radial digit tips (thumb, index, long, radial half of ring), particularly at night. Numbness on the dorsal hand is inconsistent with CTS. Thenar atrophy is a late finding. Provocative tests: Phalen test, Tinel sign, Durkan test, scratch-collapse test. Diagnosis is predominantly clinical; electrodiagnostic studies add little to the surgical decision. Risk factors: obesity, diabetes, pregnancy, hypothyroidism, renal failure, amyloidosis, autoimmune disease. The recurrent motor branch can be subligamentous, intraligamentous, or extraligamentous.", "notes": "Ch 70 - Compression Neuropathies", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Carpal tunnel", "question": "Describe the operative treatment and expected outcomes for carpal tunnel syndrome, including management of recurrence.", "answer": "Operative treatment involves dividing the TCL and distal antebrachial fascia via a palmar incision. Internal neurolysis is not indicated in most cases. Results are gratifying regardless of technique (open vs. limited open vs. endoscopic), with long-term symptom relief in up to 91% of cases. Postoperative splinting is unnecessary. Complications include pillar pain (proximal palm aching), tendon subluxation over the hook of hamate, and injury to ulnar nerve or median nerve branches. For recurrence (rare): if initial relief followed by recurrence, suspect scarring; if minimal/no improvement, consider incomplete release, permanent intraneural damage, or other compression sites. Revision can be performed endoscopically or open with or without hypothenar fat grafting. Steroid injection can serve as a therapeutic test: if symptoms improve then recur, surgery will generally provide relief.", "notes": "Ch 70 - Compression Neuropathies", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Cubital tunnel", "question": "What is the presentation, diagnosis, and surgical management of cubital tunnel syndrome?", "answer": "Cubital tunnel syndrome is the second most common compressive neuropathy (incidence 21/100,000 person-years). Most common compression sites: Arcade of Struthers, intermuscular septum, Osborne ligament at medial epicondyle, and pronator/flexor fascia distal to elbow. Risk factors: male gender, heavy manual labor, tobacco use. Early symptoms: numbness/tingling along the ulnar aspect of the hand with proximal pain radiation. Altered sensation on both dorsal AND volar ulnar hand distinguishes elbow compression from wrist compression (wrist affects only volar). Late findings: ulnar clawing (MCP hyperextension with PIP/DIP flexion), hypothenar atrophy, positive Froment sign. Nonoperative: night splinting, PT, activity modification (50% efficacy for mild disease). Surgical options include simple decompression (open or endoscopic), anterior subcutaneous transposition, and submuscular transposition. No single technique has proven superior, with 77-86% positive outcomes at 1 year.", "notes": "Ch 70 - Compression Neuropathies", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Carpal tunnel", "question": "How does proximal median nerve entrapment (pronator syndrome) differ from carpal tunnel syndrome in presentation and diagnosis?", "answer": "Key differences: (1) Pain location: PMNE causes pain in the palm, wrist, and distal forearm exacerbated by sustained pronation; CTS causes pain at the carpal tunnel. (2) Thenar involvement: PMNE causes numbness in the thenar area (via palmar cutaneous branch, which exits 5 cm proximal to wrist); CTS spares the thenar eminence. (3) Motor weakness: PMNE causes weakness of FPL and FDP to index finger (AIN-innervated muscles); CTS may cause thenar weakness. (4) Thenar muscles maintain normal strength in PMNE. (5) Provocative test: PMNE symptoms provoked by firm palpation of median nerve near elbow and pronation against resistance (numbness <60 seconds is abnormal). (6) Electrodiagnostic studies are not helpful in PMNE but can be helpful in CTS. (7) PMNE is often misdiagnosed as CTS; diagnosis is often only considered after carpal tunnel release fails. Recovery of index/thumb flexion strength is generally rapid after surgical release.", "notes": "Ch 70 - Compression Neuropathies", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Nerve transfers", "question": "What are the key principles of nerve transfer, including donor nerve selection criteria and the 'donor distal, recipient proximal' mantra?", "answer": "Nerve transfers are indicated when the proximal nerve stump is unavailable (root avulsion, intracranial injury), the distance to target is prohibitive, there is a large zone of injury, prolonged time from injury, or segmental injuries. Donor nerve selection criteria: (1) functioning/intact donor, (2) redundant/expendable function, (3) synergistic movement preferred, (4) similar power, (5) proximity to target muscle, (6) modality matched (motor-to-motor, sensory-to-sensory). The mantra 'donor distal, recipient proximal' guides dissection: the donor nerve is dissected as far distally as possible to maximize length, and the recipient nerve is divided as proximally as reasonable. The coaptation must be tension-free and allow full ROM without tension. A minimum donor-to-recipient axon ratio of 0.7 is predictive of good function. Animal studies show that only 12-30% of native axon regeneration leads to motor function equivalent to preinjury.", "notes": "Ch 71 - Nerve Transfers", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Nerve transfers", "question": "Describe the Oberlin transfer and double fascicular transfer for restoration of elbow flexion. What are the donor and recipient nerves?", "answer": "The Oberlin transfer uses an FCU branch of the ulnar nerve transferred to the motor nerve to biceps, providing both elbow flexion and supination. It is one of the most commonly used and reliable nerve transfers. The double fascicular transfer (Mackinnon) combines the Oberlin transfer with transfer of a median nerve FDS/FCR branch to the brachialis nerve, reinnervating two elbow flexors. In a retrospective review, single vs. double transfer resulted in similar elbow flexion strength and DASH scores; the only significant difference was grip strength (double transfer: 63% of contralateral; single: 43%). Considering motor reeducation, the FCU fascicle (ulnar nerve) is preferred over FDS (median nerve) for biceps transfer because the biceps is a supinator and the median nerve controls pronation (antagonistic pairing), whereas FCU is more synergistic. Other donor options for complete plexus avulsions include thoracodorsal, medial pectoral, distal spinal accessory, or intercostal nerves.", "notes": "Ch 71 - Nerve Transfers", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Nerve transfers", "question": "What is a supercharge (reverse end-to-side) nerve transfer, and when is it particularly useful?", "answer": "In a supercharge (reverse ETS) transfer, the recipient nerve is left intact and the proximal end of the transected donor nerve is coapted to the side of the recipient nerve. This differs from classic ETS where the recipient nerve end is coapted to the side of an intact donor nerve. Supercharge transfers are particularly useful for: (1) Proximal ulnar nerve injuries: the AIN terminal branch to pronator quadratus is transferred to the side of the deep ulnar motor branch, allowing rapid intrinsic muscle reinnervation while sensory regeneration proceeds distally through the intact ulnar nerve. This is critical because high ulnar injuries have a poor prognosis for intrinsic recovery (regeneration time >18 months). (2) Partial nerve injuries where electrodiagnostic studies show severely reduced but still present axons in continuity. Results: 70% of patients achieved M3 or better intrinsic function with ulnar supercharge transfers. Animal models confirm augmented regeneration.", "notes": "Ch 71 - Nerve Transfers", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "TMR/RPNI", "question": "What is the concept of a babysitter nerve transfer, and what is the classic example described by Terzis for facial palsy?", "answer": "Babysitter nerve transfers are used to temporarily maintain recipient muscle motor endplates while awaiting regeneration over long distances. The classic example by Terzis (1984) for facial palsy: Stage 1: Cross-face nerve grafts are coapted to functional contralateral facial nerve branches (distal ends left free). On the injured side, 40% of the hypoglossal nerve is transferred to the critical nonfunctional facial nerve branches. Stage 2 (8-12 months later): Free ends of the cross-face grafts are connected to the distal stumps of the injured facial nerve, while the mini hypoglossal transfer is left intact. The hypoglossal transfer preserves facial mimetic muscle motor endplates while regeneration proceeds through the cross-facial grafts. Both sensory and motor nerves can maintain muscle mass. Muscles atrophy if not reinnervated within 12-18 months; babysitter procedures bridge this critical window.", "notes": "Ch 71 - Nerve Transfers", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Nerve transfers", "question": "What are the advantages of nerve transfers over nerve grafts, and what is the AIN-to-ulnar motor transfer used for?", "answer": "Advantages of nerve transfers over grafts: (1) closer to target, enabling faster recovery; (2) avoid re-entering the zone of injury; (3) avoid additional coaptation sites (grafts require two); (4) may provide stronger axonal input; (5) can be used when no proximal nerve stump is available; (6) avoid graft donor site morbidity. Disadvantages: require motor reeducation, may produce unwanted movements, movement may not be spontaneous. The AIN-to-ulnar motor transfer is one of the most commonly used transfers: the terminal AIN branch to pronator quadratus is transferred to the deep motor branch of the ulnar nerve for intrinsic muscle reinnervation. This is used for high ulnar nerve injuries where distance to the target intrinsic muscles is prohibitive for grafting. If PT is intact, there is no donor deficit. Grafting vs. transfer comparison for proximal ulnar injuries: 80% achieved M3+ with transfer vs. 22% with grafting.", "notes": "Ch 71 - Nerve Transfers", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Brachial plexus basics", "question": "Describe the anatomy of the brachial plexus from roots to terminal branches, including key clinical landmarks.", "answer": "The brachial plexus arises from C5-T1 spinal nerves. Roots exit between anterior and middle scalene muscles. Trunks: upper (C5-C6), middle (C7), lower (C8-T1), located between the scalene muscles. Each trunk splits into anterior and posterior divisions deep to the clavicle. Cords form deep to pectoralis minor near the coracoid process: lateral cord (anterior divisions of upper and middle trunks), posterior cord (all posterior divisions), and medial cord (anterior division of lower trunk). The axillary artery is sandwiched between the three cords. Terminal branches: axillary and radial nerves separate at the posterior cord deep to the lateral border of pectoralis minor. The musculocutaneous nerve is found between coracobrachialis and biceps brachialis. Median and ulnar nerves are found deep to brachial veins wrapping around the brachial artery. Common injury patterns: C5-T1 (50-70%), C5-C7 (20-35%), C5-C6 (15%), C8-T1 (10%). Young males represent >90% of adult brachial plexus trauma.", "notes": "Ch 72 - Brachial Plexus", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Brachial plexus basics", "question": "How do you differentiate preganglionic (root avulsion) from postganglionic brachial plexus injuries, and what clinical signs suggest root avulsion?", "answer": "Preganglionic injuries (root avulsions) tear rootlets from the spinal cord proximal to the dorsal root ganglion; postganglionic injuries are peripheral nerve ruptures distal to the DRG. Signs suggesting root avulsion: (1) Horner syndrome (miosis, ptosis, anhidrosis on the ipsilateral face) indicates disruption of sympathetic pathways near the lower plexus. (2) Deafferentation/phantom limb pain (severe, burning, lancinating causalgia). (3) Hemidiaphragmatic elevation on chest X-ray suggests upper plexus involvement (C3-C5 phrenic nerve). (4) Pseudomeningoceles on MRI/CT myelography where dura tears accompany avulsed roots. (5) On electrodiagnostic studies, intact sensory nerve action potentials (SNAPs) despite clinical sensory loss suggest preganglionic injury (the DRG and distal sensory nerve remain intact). Higher-energy mechanisms (high-speed MVCs, motorcycles) tend to produce preganglionic avulsions; lower-energy mechanisms (mopeds) tend to produce postganglionic ruptures.", "notes": "Ch 72 - Brachial Plexus", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Brachial plexus basics", "question": "What are the three categories of surgical management for brachial plexus injuries, and what determines the appropriate timing?", "answer": "Three categories: (1) Proximal exploration and reconstruction (3-5 months post-trauma): Supraclavicular neck incision to directly visualize injuries. Nerve ruptures require cable grafting (sural, saphenous, MABC, LABC nerves). Root avulsions managed with nerve transfers (CN XI, contralateral C7, intercostal, phrenic). (2) Distal (close-target) nerve transfers (3-9 months): Operate outside the zone of injury using intact nerves to reinnervate targets. Benefits: avoids fibrotic dissection, shorter regeneration distance extends the surgical window. Disadvantage: weakens intact function. (3) Biomechanical restorations (>9 months): Tendon transfers and functioning free muscle transplantation (gracilis FFMT) when motor endplate fibrosis has occurred (12-18 months). Used as a lifeboat when earlier interventions fail or for late presentations. Time from injury is the most critical factor: motor endplates undergo irreversible fibrosis at 12-18 months. Mixed-degree injuries may show spontaneous recovery over 3-6 months, hence the observation period.", "notes": "Ch 72 - Brachial Plexus", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Brachial plexus basics", "question": "Describe Mackinnon's classification of nerve injuries and explain the significance of the sixth-degree injury pattern in brachial plexus trauma.", "answer": "Mackinnon's classification extends the Sunderland system: First degree: demyelination only (neuropraxia), spontaneous recovery expected. Second degree: axonal injury with Wallerian degeneration but intact endoneurium; spontaneous recovery expected. Third degree: axonal injury plus endoneurial damage; variable recovery. Fourth degree: complete scar block preventing regeneration; requires surgery. Fifth degree: complete nerve transection (neurotmesis); requires repair. Sixth degree (Mackinnon's addition): MIXED pattern of injury, with different fascicles having different degrees of injury severity within the same nerve. This is the most common pattern in closed brachial plexus injuries. The clinical significance is that some fascicles may recover spontaneously (first through third degree) while others require surgical intervention (fourth and fifth degree). This is why a 3-6 month observation period is essential: it allows time to distinguish recovering from non-recovering elements, analogous to waiting for tissue demarcation in burn injuries.", "notes": "Ch 72 - Brachial Plexus", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tetraplegia", "question": "Explain the International Classification for Surgery of the Hand in Tetraplegia (ICSHT) and the reconstructive priorities for Groups 1-3.", "answer": "The ICSHT classifies patients by the number of muscles below the elbow with M4+ strength available for tendon transfer. Muscles are listed in order of expected recovery: Group 0 (C4+): No muscles below elbow available; no tendon transfer options. Group 1 (C5): Only BR available. Priorities: wrist extension (BR to ECRB), key pinch (FPL tenodesis with split FPL-to-EPL for IP joint stability). Groups 2-3 (C6): ECRL/ECRB available, providing tenodesis for rudimentary grasp/release. One-stage key pinch and release: BR transferred to FPL, EPL tenodesis (loop around 3rd extensor compartment), CMC arthrodesis for thumb stability. Approximately 2.2 kg of key pinch strength needed for ADLs. Only muscles with grade 4+ strength (active motion against gravity and resistance) are suitable for transfer. Tendon transfer results in decline of 1 point due to loss of efficiency. For Groups 1-3, pronosupination imbalance may require biceps rerouting (Zancolli) to convert biceps from supinator to pronator.", "notes": "Ch 73 - Tetraplegia", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tetraplegia", "question": "What are the reconstructive options for restoring grasp, pinch, and release in ICSHT Groups 4-5 tetraplegia patients?", "answer": "Groups 4-5 have additional muscles available: PT (Group 4) and FCR (Group 5). Reconstruction addresses two phases: Flexor phase (grasp): ECRL transferred to FDP tendons for finger flexion (chosen for greater excursion and strength). BR or PT transferred to FPL for thumb flexion and key pinch. Extensor phase (release): EDC tenodesis, anchoring digit extensors to the radius. Tension set in reverse cascade (index finger most flexed for finer pinch, MCP joints extended with wrist neutral) because ulnar digits are less likely to reach the thumb for key pinch. EPL tenodesis via loop around the 3rd extensor compartment retinaculum. Thumb stability: either opponensplasty (PT or BR to FDS ring finger, routed through a fascial loop to abductor pollicis brevis) or CMC arthrodesis in 20 degrees extension, 45 degrees abduction, slight pronation. For bilateral reconstruction, opponensplasty on one side and CMC arthrodesis on the contralateral side allows options for fine pinch vs. stronger grip.", "notes": "Ch 73 - Tetraplegia", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tetraplegia", "question": "What are the options for restoring elbow extension in tetraplegia, and what is the preferred technique for biceps to triceps transfer?", "answer": "Elbow extension is a top priority to facilitate transfers, reaching, and hand stability. Options for Groups 1-4 (C5-C6 injuries with poor triceps): (1) Biceps to triceps transfer: Preferred technique. Must confirm functional brachialis and supinator to preserve elbow flexion/supination after biceps transfer. Performed through a MEDIAL approach and routing (not posterolateral) to avoid injury or compression to the radial nerve. Tendon is tunneled subcutaneously and anchored to the olecranon and/or woven to the triceps tendon. Tensioned to accommodate 60-90 degrees of passive elbow flexion. (2) Posterior deltoid to triceps transfer: Requires an interposition graft (typically tensor fascia lata). Deltoid raised distally to proximally, protecting the axillary nerve. Disadvantage: potential for graft stretch with resultant loss of strength. Biceps to triceps is favored for earlier mobilization and avoidance of interposition graft stretch.", "notes": "Ch 73 - Tetraplegia", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tetraplegia", "question": "What are the prerequisites for surgical reconstruction in tetraplegia, and how are nerve transfers being applied as a future direction?", "answer": "Prerequisites: (1) Neurologic recovery has plateaued (typically 1 year post-injury). (2) Pain-free, supple joints with full passive ROM (shoulder, elbow, forearm, wrist, MCP, PIP). (3) Sufficient social support and motivation for postoperative rehabilitation. (4) Reasonable expectations. (5) Emotional adjustment to injury. (6) Optimized cognition and mental health (TBI and mood disorders are common). (7) Contracture prevention is essential: >50% of SCI patients develop contractures within 1 year (shoulder 43%, elbow/forearm 33%, wrist/hand 41%). Splint in functional position with digits extended, MCP in gentle flexion, forearm in pronation. Donor muscles must be M4+ strength, beyond the zone of injury. Future directions: Nerve transfers for SCI use nerves from above the level of injury as donors. Examples: axillary nerve branches to teres minor/posterior deltoid transferred to triceps branches of radial nerve for elbow extension. Musculocutaneous nerve branches to brachialis transferred to AIN for finger flexion (up to M4 strength achieved). Transfers may be time-dependent (recipient within zone of injury) or time-independent (recipient below zone).", "notes": "Ch 73 - Tetraplegia", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tetraplegia", "question": "Describe the Zancolli FDS lasso procedure and its role in intrinsic reconstruction for tetraplegia patients.", "answer": "Patients in ICSHT Groups 6-9 with intrinsic weakness develop a clawed hand posture: MCP hyperextension (loss of intrinsic MCP flexion) and PIP flexion (FDS spasticity), with an uncoordinated rolling phenomenon where DIP/PIP joints flex before the MCP joint during grasp. For the thumb, Froment sign occurs (FPL hyperflexion to compensate for weak adductor pollicis). The Zancolli FDS lasso procedure addresses this by creating MCP joint flexion force: the FDS is released distally and looped onto itself at the A1 pulley, creating a flexion force at the MCP joint with wrist extension, so that MCP joints flex first followed by IP joints for coordinated grasp. For patients with central slip deficiency (digits do not extend with wrist flexion), free tendon grafts are passed around the metacarpal neck volar to the intermetacarpal ligaments and attached to lateral bands or central slip during EDC tenodesis. Intrinsic reconstruction has been shown to greatly enhance hand function and quality of life.", "notes": "Ch 73 - Tetraplegia", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand infections", "subtopic": "Cellulitis vs abscess", "question": "How do you differentiate cellulitis from abscess in the hand, and what are the indications for hospitalization?", "answer": "Cellulitis: Most common hand infection. Presents with diffuse erythema, nonfocal swelling, generalized warmth, stiffness, lymphadenopathy, and edema. Patients rarely have one focal area of pain. There is no fluctuance. Common pathogens: Staph and Strep species. Surgery is NOT indicated for cellulitis; only local debridement if tissue necrosis or localized abscess at inoculation site. Abscess: Presents with fluctuance, focal swelling, focal pain, and possible purulent drainage. Requires incision and drainage. Indications for hospitalization: (1) ascending lymphangitis, (2) failed trial of oral antibiotics, (3) systemic symptoms (fever, altered mental status), (4) elevated WBC, (5) reasonable chance of needing operative intervention, (6) high risk of not following-up. Erythema should be outlined and dated in permanent marker to monitor progression. High-risk patients (diabetics, immunocompromised, IV drug users) should be monitored for septic shock and have a lower threshold for admission.", "notes": "Ch 68 - Hand Infections", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Sutures and needles", "subtopic": "Common sutures", "question": "What sutures are used for nail bed repair and flexor tendon sheath repair in hand surgery, and what are the principles of wound closure in different hand tissue layers?", "answer": "Nail bed repair: 6-0 or 7-0 absorbable monofilament sutures for precise approximation under magnification. The nail plate or silicone sheath is used as a stent secured with 5-0 nylon. Stellate lacerations require conservative debridement preserving all small pieces. After avulsion repair, the nail plate is soaked in betadine and reinserted into the nail fold to prevent synechiae. For flexor tendon sheath irrigation in tenosynovitis, incisions are loosely closed or left for secondary intention. Fight bite wounds: the capsule, extensor mechanism, and skin are loosely closed with a gauze wick. Deep-space infections: gauze wicks are placed for continued drainage; skin is loosely approximated. General principles: volar incisions should follow flexion creases or be designed as Bruner (zigzag) incisions; midlateral incisions minimize scar contractures; transverse webspace incisions should be avoided (cause adduction contractures). Hand splinting position: wrist extended 30 degrees, MCP flexed 90 degrees, digits extended.", "notes": "Ch 67-69 combined", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Metacarpal/phalangeal fractures", "question": "What is the typical fracture deformity pattern for metacarpal shaft fractures, proximal phalanx fractures, and middle phalanx fractures (proximal vs. distal to FDS insertion)?", "answer": "Metacarpal fractures: apex dorsal deformity (intrinsic muscles pull metacarpal head into flexion). Proximal phalanx fractures: apex volar deformity (intrinsics flex the base while extensor mechanism extends the distal shaft). Middle phalanx fractures proximal to FDS insertion: apex dorsal (central slip extends base, FDS flexes distal fragment). Middle phalanx fractures distal to FDS insertion: apex volar (FDS flexes shaft, extensor mechanism extends distal fragment).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Metacarpal/phalangeal fractures", "question": "What are the acceptable angulation limits for metacarpal neck and shaft fractures by digit?", "answer": "Metacarpal NECK: Index 10 degrees, Middle 20 degrees, Ring 30-40 degrees, Small 50-60 degrees. Metacarpal SHAFT: Index 10 degrees, Middle 20 degrees, Ring 30 degrees, Small 40 degrees. Greater angulation is tolerated in the ring and small fingers due to their more mobile CMC joints. The closed reduction maneuver for metacarpal neck fractures is the Jahss maneuver: MCP and PIP joints are fully flexed, volar force on metacarpal shaft, dorsal force on proximal phalanx.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Metacarpal/phalangeal fractures", "question": "How much metacarpal malrotation causes clinically significant digital overlap, and what are the indications for operative fixation of hand fractures?", "answer": "5 degrees of metacarpal rotation leads to 1.5 cm of digital overlap. Operative indications include: articular incongruity, digital malrotation, shortening or angulation beyond acceptable limits, multiple fractures, open fractures, and fractures with soft tissue injury or bone loss. All digits should point to the scaphoid without overlap on active ROM or wrist tenodesis testing. Stiffness is the most common complication after hand fracture management.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Bennett/Rolando fractures", "question": "Describe the Bennett fracture, its deforming forces, reduction maneuver, and how it differs from a Rolando fracture.", "answer": "Bennett fracture: oblique intra-articular fracture-dislocation of the thumb metacarpal base. The anterior oblique (beak) ligament maintains the small volar-ulnar fragment in place. The metacarpal subluxates proximally (APL pull), radially (EPB pull), and dorsally (adductor pollicis pull). Reduction: thumb axial traction, abduction, and pronation. Fixation typically with percutaneous K-wires. A Rolando fracture is similar but is comminuted with a Y- or T-shaped fracture pattern. Both are inherently unstable injuries requiring fixation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Metacarpal/phalangeal fractures", "question": "What is a Seymour fracture, and how should mallet fractures of the distal phalanx be managed?", "answer": "Seymour fracture: a physeal fracture of the distal phalanx in children that entraps a portion of the nail bed; treated with nail bed extraction, irrigation, and K-wire fixation urgently to prevent osteomyelitis. Mallet fractures (dorsal base of distal phalanx with extensor tendon avulsion): most managed with DIP joint splinting in full extension for 6 weeks. Dorsal block K-wire fixation is recommended when the fracture involves >1/3 of the articular surface or when there is volar subluxation of the distal fragment.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Distal radius fractures", "question": "What are the four key radiographic parameters of the distal radius, their normal values, and the criteria for acceptable reduction?", "answer": "Normal values: Radial height 10-13 mm, Radial inclination 21-25 degrees, Volar tilt average 11 degrees (range 2-20 degrees), Ulnar variance 0 +/- 2 mm. Acceptable reduction criteria: radial inclination >=15 degrees, loss of radial length <5 mm, volar tilt between 15 degrees dorsal and 20 degrees volar, articular step-off <=2 mm. Five factors predicting instability (Lafontaine): initial dorsal angulation >20 degrees, dorsal comminution, radiocarpal intra-articular involvement, associated ulnar fracture, and age >60 years. Three of five factors predict loss of reduction.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Distal radius fractures", "question": "What are the main fixation options for distal radius fractures, and what is the key anatomic landmark for volar locking plate placement?", "answer": "Options: closed reduction and casting, percutaneous pinning (transradial styloid or Kapandji intrafocal pinning), volar locking plate (VLP), dorsal plating, fragment-specific fixation, external fixation, and dorsal bridge (spanning) plating. The VLP must be placed proximal to the watershed line (transverse ridge between the pronator quadratus and volar extrinsic ligaments) to avoid flexor tendon irritation. VLP allows early mobilization, does not routinely require removal, and can support articular surface even with severe metaphyseal comminution. Dorsal plating has fallen out of favor due to extensor tendon irritation/rupture risk.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Scaphoid fractures", "question": "Why is the scaphoid prone to avascular necrosis and nonunion, and what is the standard operative fixation for scaphoid fractures?", "answer": "The scaphoid has a retrograde blood supply from branches of the radial artery, making the proximal pole particularly vulnerable to AVN and nonunion (blood supply enters distally). Acute scaphoid fractures may be radiographically occult; clinical suspicion with negative radiographs warrants immobilization and follow-up imaging or early advanced imaging (MRI/CT). Operative fixation is most commonly achieved with a cannulated headless compression screw. The approach (dorsal vs. volar) is guided by the fracture pattern. Scaphoid fractures presenting late are at higher risk for nonunion.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Flexor tendon zones and repair principles", "question": "Describe the five flexor tendon zones of injury and explain why Zone 2 is historically called 'no man's land.'", "answer": "Zone 1: distal to FDS insertion (only FDP involved). Zone 2: within flexor tendon sheath from A1 pulley to FDS insertion (both FDS and FDP at risk) - called 'no man's land' due to complex anatomy and high complication rate from adhesion formation. Zone 3: palm distal to carpal tunnel. Zone 4: within the carpal tunnel (uncommon injuries due to bony protection). Zone 5: proximal forearm to carpal tunnel. Zone 2 repairs are most challenging; Zones 3-5 have better prognosis with less adhesion formation.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Flexor tendon zones and repair principles", "question": "What are the key principles of flexor tendon repair regarding core sutures, epitendinous sutures, timing, and the quadriga effect?", "answer": "At least 4-strand core sutures with nonabsorbable 3-0 to 4-0 suture placed 1 cm from tendon ends. Epitendinous suture (6-0 nonabsorbable, 2 mm from cut edges, 2 mm deep) augments repair strength and smooths gliding surface. Gap <3 mm is critical for adequate healing. Repair should be performed within 7 days. After 6 weeks, primary repair is unlikely to succeed due to myostatic contracture. Shortening FDP >1 cm causes the quadriga effect (flexion lag in adjacent fingers because FDP tendons share a common muscle belly). Early protective motion (within 1 week) improves outcomes; at least 4-strand repair needed to withstand active motion protocols.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Mallet finger/boutonniere/jersey finger", "question": "What is the Leddy and Packer classification of Zone 1 flexor tendon avulsions (jersey finger), and how does management differ by type?", "answer": "Type I: FDP retracts into palm with vincular disruption; requires urgent repair within 2 weeks. Type II: FDP retracts to PIP joint level with partial vincular preservation; can be repaired within 6 weeks. Type III: large bony fragment prevents retraction proximal to A4 pulley; repaired with K-wire or screw. For delayed presentations beyond repair window, DIP arthrodesis can be considered if FDS function is intact. Two-stage tendon reconstruction is needed when scarring prevents tendon grafting. The lumbrical-plus finger (paradoxical IP extension with attempted flexion) can occur from tendon graft laxity; treatment is lumbrical release.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Extensor tendon zones and repair", "question": "How are extensor tendon injuries classified by zone, and what are the general principles of rehabilitation by zone?", "answer": "Kleinert-Verdan zones 1-8 (Doyle added zone 9): odd zones over joints, even zones between joints, starting at DIP (zone 1) progressing proximally. Zones 1-2: static splinting for 6 weeks then night splinting and ROM exercises. Zones 3-4: traditionally 3-4 weeks static splinting then controlled motion; early dynamic splinting shows promising results for zone 4+. Zones 5-7: early controlled motion protocols effective; dynamic splinting as effective as early active motion with less rupture risk. Zones 8-9: least risk of adhesions, static splinting 3-4 weeks. Each millimeter of extensor lengthening over proximal phalanx = 12 degrees PIP extension deficit; at DIP = 25 degrees lag per mm.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Mallet finger/boutonniere/jersey finger", "question": "What is a mallet finger injury, how is it classified (Doyle), and what is the standard treatment?", "answer": "Mallet finger: disruption of terminal extensor tendon from distal phalanx base causing DIP flexion posture. Doyle classification: Type I - closed, with/without small avulsion fracture (most common; treat with 6-8 weeks continuous DIP extension splinting). Type II - open laceration of terminal tendon (surgical repair with running suture + K-wire for 6 weeks). Type III - open with tendon/skin substance loss (primary repair or staged reconstruction). Type IVa - Seymour fracture in children. Type IVb - 20-50% articular fracture (conservative or operative). Type IVc - >50% articular fracture with volar subluxation (extension block pinning). Untreated mallet finger can lead to swan-neck deformity (PIP hyperextension).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Mallet finger/boutonniere/jersey finger", "question": "Describe the boutonniere deformity: its mechanism, clinical presentation, and why it may not be apparent acutely.", "answer": "Boutonniere deformity: PIP flexion + DIP hyperextension caused by zone 3 central slip disruption. Acutely, the intact lateral bands and triangular ligament maintain PIP extension, masking the injury. Over weeks, the triangular ligament stretches, lateral bands migrate volarly, becoming PIP flexors rather than extensors. Shortened lateral bands increase pull on terminal tendon causing DIP hyperextension. Acute closed injuries: treat with PIP extension splinting for 6 weeks allowing DIP motion. The Elson test (resisted PIP extension with PIP flexed 90 degrees) helps diagnose central slip injury. Chronic boutonniere requires surgical reconstruction if splinting fails.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Flexor tendon zones and repair principles", "question": "What are the critical flexor tendon pulleys, their locations, and their clinical significance?", "answer": "A2 and A4 pulleys are the most important: A2 originates from proximal phalanx periosteum, A4 from middle phalanx periosteum. They prevent bowstringing during flexion and maintain grip power. A1, A3, A5 pulleys arise from volar plates of MCP, PIP, and DIP joints respectively. A1 pulley is the site of trigger finger pathology. Cruciate pulleys (C1-C3) are between annular pulleys and accommodate joint flexion. The thumb has A1, oblique (most important in thumb), and A2 pulleys. During flexor tendon repair, A2 and A4 must be preserved; partial release of pulleys may be needed to decrease repair bulk.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Distal radius fractures", "question": "What associated injuries should be evaluated with distal radius fractures, and how is DRUJ instability managed?", "answer": "Associated injuries: median nerve dysfunction (acute carpal tunnel syndrome - if numbness persists after reduction, emergent carpal tunnel release indicated), ulnar styloid fractures (common but not independently predictive of outcomes), DRUJ instability (test in neutral/supination/pronation; compare to uninjured side), and intercarpal ligament injuries (scapholunate tears 16-40%, lunotriquetral tears 8.5-15%). DRUJ instability management: if large ulnar styloid fragment, fix it (K-wire/tension band/screw); if stable in supination, immobilize in supination 3 weeks then neutral 3 weeks; if unstable in supination, TFCC repair or DRUJ pinning is indicated.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Trigger finger", "question": "Describe the pathophysiology, presentation, and treatment algorithm for trigger finger.", "answer": "Pathophysiology: thickening of A1 pulley + nodule formation in flexor tendon from repetitive friction; histology shows fibrocartilage metaplasia and type 3 collagen upregulation (not inflammation). Lifetime risk: 2.6% general population, up to 10% in diabetics. Patients localize symptoms to PIP joint but pathology is at A1 pulley (MCP level). Treatment: splinting of MCP joint (66% success), corticosteroid injection (60-90% success; second injection increases success). Diabetics respond less well to injections. Percutaneous release: 95% success but higher digital nerve injury risk (especially thumb). Open release: 99% success under direct visualization. The thumb radial digital nerve is most at risk during release.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "De Quervain tenosynovitis", "question": "What is de Quervain disease, how is it diagnosed, and what is the most common cause of failed surgical release?", "answer": "De Quervain disease: stenosing tendiopathy of the first dorsal compartment (APL and EPB tendons). Most common in women (6:1 ratio), 5th-6th decade; associated with repetitive wrist motion, pregnancy, and lactation. Diagnosis: positive Finkelstein test (ulnar wrist deviation with thumb flexed into palm). Histology shows myxoid degeneration (not inflammation). Treatment: splinting + NSAIDs, corticosteroid injection (80% lasting relief), then surgical release if refractory. Most common cause of failed surgery: failure to identify and release a separate EPB subsheath (present in 44% of normal cadavers, 62% of de Quervain patients). Other surgical complications: radial sensory nerve injury (neuroma) and volar subluxation of tendons.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "De Quervain tenosynovitis", "question": "How does lateral epicondylitis differ histopathologically from a true inflammatory condition, and what is its natural history and treatment?", "answer": "Lateral epicondylitis (tennis elbow) involves the ECRB tendon origin at the lateral epicondyle. Histopathology shows mucoid/hyaline degeneration, fibrosis, calcifications, and fibrovascular proliferation - NOT inflammatory cells (no macrophages/neutrophils). It is tendinosis, not tenosynovitis. Natural history: self-limited, resolving in 12-18 months; up to 90% improve without intervention. Treatment: activity modification, counterforce bracing, physical therapy; corticosteroid injections may provide short-term relief (4-6 weeks) but no proven long-term benefit. Surgery reserved for failure of 6-12 months conservative treatment. Nirschl open ECRB debridement: 98% improvement, 85% return to work.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tendon transfers principles", "question": "What are the key principles of tendon transfer surgery, and what is Boyes's 3-5-7 rule?", "answer": "Principles: (1) Soft tissue equilibrium - all fractures healed, wounds closed, scars mature. (2) Supple joints - passive ROM must be maximized preoperatively (active ROM post-transfer never exceeds preop passive ROM). (3) Protective sensation should be restored first when possible. (4) One tendon, one function. (5) Straight line of pull (>40 degrees direction change causes significant force loss). (6) Donor must be expendable, of adequate strength, with good volitional control, and preferably synergistic. Transfer typically loses one MRC grade of strength. Boyes's 3-5-7 rule: wrist flexors/extensors excursion ~3 cm, digital extensors ~5 cm, digital flexors ~7 cm.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tendon transfers principles", "question": "What are the classic tendon transfer sets for radial nerve palsy, and what three functions must be restored?", "answer": "Functions to restore: (1) wrist extension (high palsy only), (2) MCP joint extension (IP extension maintained by intrinsics), (3) thumb extension and palmar abduction. Jones transfer: PT to ECRB (wrist extension), FCU to EDC (finger extension), PL to EPL (thumb extension). FCR/Brand/Starr transfer: PT to ECRB, FCR to EDC, PL to EPL - preferred by many because FCU is the only ulnar wrist motor and its sacrifice eliminates dart-thrower's motion. Boyes (superficialis) transfer: PT to ECRB+ECRL, FCR to APL+EPB, FDS-III to EDC, FDS-IV to EPL+EIP - uses FDS for better excursion but more complex. All sets produce good results; no proven superiority of one over another.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tendon transfers principles", "question": "What are the goals of tendon transfer in ulnar nerve palsy, and how does the Bouvier test guide surgical decision-making?", "answer": "Goals: (1) DIP joint flexion in ring/small fingers (high palsy only - side-to-side FDP tenodesis), (2) thumb adduction/key pinch (adductorplasty using ECRB or BR with free tendon graft through 3rd intermetacarpal space), (3) correct clawing/restore coordinated digital flexion. The Bouvier test: passively flex MCP joints and ask patient to extend IP joints. Positive Bouvier (can extend IPs) = simple/static claw: only MCP hyperextension needs correction (static procedures: Zancolli capsulodesis, osseous blocks, tendon grafts, or dynamic tenodesis). Negative Bouvier (cannot extend IPs) = complex/dynamic claw: attenuated central slip, transfer must provide both MCP flexion AND IP extension (modified Stiles-Bunnell FDS transfer to lateral bands). Froment sign (thumb IP flexion with pinch) indicates adductor pollicis weakness.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tendon transfers principles", "question": "What are the common opponensplasty options for low median nerve palsy, and which is used in high median nerve palsy?", "answer": "Low median nerve palsy opponensplasty options: (1) Camitz procedure (PL with palmar aponeurosis extension) - easiest, done with carpal tunnel release, but weak and provides palmar abduction rather than true opposition. (2) FDS ring opponensplasty (Royle-Thompson/Bunnell) - good strength and excursion, only usable if FDS innervation is intact (low palsy). (3) EIP opponensplasty (Zancolli/Burkhalter) - excellent vector when routed around ulnar wrist, usable in both high and low palsy. (4) Huber transfer (ADM) - mostly for children with hypoplastic thumbs, good cosmetic restoration of thenar bulk. In HIGH median nerve palsy, the EIP opponensplasty is most commonly used because FDS/PL/FCR are paralyzed. BR to FPL restores thumb IP flexion; ECRL to FDP or side-to-side FDP tenodesis restores index/long finger flexion.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Metacarpal/phalangeal fractures", "question": "Compare the advantages and disadvantages of the main hand fracture fixation techniques: K-wires, compression screws, plate and screws, and external fixation.", "answer": "K-wires: easily removed, low cost, limited soft tissue damage; but need additional immobilization, risk of pin tract infection/migration, no fracture site compression. A single K-wire does not provide rotational stability (need at least 2). Compression (lag) screws: rigid fixation, limited periosteal stripping; but technically demanding. Ideal when fracture length is at least 2x bone diameter. Plate and screws: rigid fixation allowing early motion; but requires extensive soft tissue dissection, risk of extensor adhesions (especially in phalanges), may need hardware removal. External fixation: rapid application, avoids fracture site, allows soft tissue reconstruction; but may not achieve anatomic reduction, pin site infection, rarely definitive.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Metacarpal/phalangeal fractures", "question": "How are phalangeal condylar fractures classified and treated?", "answer": "Classification: Type I - unicondylar, nondisplaced; Type II - unicondylar, displaced; Type III - bicondylar. Type I: may be managed nonoperatively with close radiographic follow-up to detect displacement. Type II (displaced): closed reduction with at least 2 K-wires or ORIF with screw fixation. Type III (bicondylar): ORIF through interval between central slip and lateral band with screw or K-wire fixation. Key surgical pearl: avoid stripping vascular supply from attached collateral ligaments during open repair. Phalangeal shaft fractures displaced >10-25 degrees sagittal or >10-15 degrees coronal require reduction and fixation. Screw diameter should be <1/3 of fracture length.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Distal radius fractures", "question": "Describe the three-column theory of the distal radius and the common fracture eponyms.", "answer": "Three-column theory: (1) Radial column (radial styloid + scaphoid fossa) - anchors radiocarpal stability, origin of volar radiocarpal ligaments. (2) Intermediate column (lunate fossa + sigmoid notch) - primary load-bearing surface, provides DRUJ congruity. (3) Ulnar column (distal ulna + TFCC) - shares carpal load, serves as stable pivot for rotating radius. Load distribution: neutral ulnar variance = 80% radiocarpal, 20% ulnocarpal. Eponyms: Colles fracture = dorsally displaced/angulated (dinner-fork deformity), Smith fracture = volarly displaced, Barton = intra-articular rim fracture (dorsal or volar), Chauffeur = radial styloid fracture.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Flexor tendon zones and repair principles", "question": "Describe the flexor tendon rehabilitation protocol after repair, including the dorsal blocking splint position and timeline for activity progression.", "answer": "Dorsal blocking splint: wrist flexion 20-30 degrees, MCP flexion 50-70 degrees, PIP and DIP in full extension. Therapy begins within 1 week under experienced hand therapist. At least 4-strand repair needed for active motion protocols; 3-5 mm of tendon excursion prevents adhesion formation in Zone 2. Active place-and-hold therapy improves finger active ROM compared to passive motion alone. Active ROM at 3-4 weeks. Dorsal splint discontinued at 6-8 weeks. Individual digit strengthening at 10 weeks. Return to normal activities at 4-6 months. For children/noncompliant patients: cast immobilization 4-6 weeks (wrist neutral, MCP 70 degrees flexion, IPs in extension).", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Flexor tendon zones and repair principles", "question": "When is single-stage versus two-stage flexor tendon reconstruction indicated, and what graft donor sites are available?", "answer": "Single-stage grafting: significant segmental tendon loss, late presentation outside primary repair window, or rupture after repair not amenable to re-repair. Requires intact pulley system and supple wound bed. Two-stage reconstruction: needed for extensive scarring, joint contractures unresponsive to therapy, and incompetent pulleys. Stage 1: silicone rod placement, pulley reconstruction, scar/contracture release (pseudosheath forms over 3 months). Stage 2: tendon graft replaces silicone rod. Graft donors: palmaris longus, plantaris, long toe extensors, EIP, EDM, toe flexors, or proximal FDS/FDP. TAM grading: excellent = 100% of 260 degrees, good >75%, fair 50-75%, poor <50%.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Extensor tendon zones and repair", "question": "Describe the anatomy of the six dorsal extensor compartments and the role of the sagittal bands and juncturae tendinae.", "answer": "Six dorsal compartments (radial to ulnar): 1st - APL + EPB; 2nd - ECRL + ECRB; 3rd - EPL (turns around Lister tubercle); 4th - EDC + EIP; 5th - EDM; 6th - ECU. The 1st compartment has a separate EPB subsheath in up to 34% (relevant to de Quervain release). EDM is doubled in 72% of cases. Sagittal bands encircle the MP joint, insert onto volar plates, and centralize the extensor tendon over the metacarpal head - providing MP extension without direct insertion onto the proximal phalanx. Juncturae tendinae connect finger extensor tendons on the dorsal hand, providing redundancy that can mask tendon injuries (no juncturae to the thumb). EIP lies ulnar to EDC at the MP joint.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Extensor tendon zones and repair", "question": "What is the swan-neck deformity after mallet finger, and what are the treatment options for chronic mallet injuries?", "answer": "Swan-neck deformity: DIP flexion + PIP hyperextension occurring after untreated mallet finger in patients with PIP volar plate laxity. Lateral bands migrate proximally and dorsally, pulling PIP into hyperextension. Assessment: block PIP hyperextension - if DIP extends actively, primary problem is PIP laxity (treat with figure-of-eight splinting, volar plate imbrication, or FDS tenodesis). If DIP cannot extend, problem is DIP extension deficit (treat with ORL reconstruction or Fowler tenotomy). Chronic mallet treatment options: (1) splinting if DIP still tender/inflamed, (2) tenodermodesis (skin + tendon imbrication), (3) Fowler/central slip tenotomy (wait 6-12 months for terminal tendon maturation), (4) spiral ORL reconstruction, (5) DIP arthrodesis.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Trigger finger", "question": "What is intersection syndrome, and how is it distinguished from de Quervain disease?", "answer": "Intersection syndrome involves the second dorsal compartment (ECRL and ECRB) where they cross beneath the first compartment muscles (APL and EPB), approximately 4-6 cm proximal to Lister tubercle on the dorsal-radial forearm. Presents with pain, swelling, erythema, and crepitus at the intersection point - more proximal than de Quervain disease (which is over the radial styloid). Distinguished from de Quervain by location: intersection syndrome is in the forearm, de Quervain is at the wrist. Treatment: NSAIDs, wrist splinting in 20 degrees extension for 2-3 weeks, corticosteroid injection for refractory cases. Surgical release of the second extensor compartment if conservative management fails.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Tendon transfers principles", "question": "What is the concept of synergy in tendon transfers, and what are the functional deficits and reconstruction goals in high versus low median nerve palsy?", "answer": "Synergy: donor muscles that are 'in phase' with the recipient's function are preferred (e.g., wrist flexors are synergistic with digital extension; wrist extensors with finger flexion). Exception: FDS has high independent cortical control and is easily retrained for any function. High median nerve palsy deficits: loss of forearm pronation (PT, pronator quadratus), all FDS function, index/long FDP, FPL, and thenar intrinsics. Goals: restore opposition (EIP opponensplasty), thumb IP flexion (BR to FPL), index/long finger flexion (ECRL to FDP or side-to-side FDP tenodesis to ulnar-innervated FDP). Low median nerve palsy deficit: loss of opposition only. Motor endplate degeneration is irreversible by 18 months; nerve transfers ideally within 6 months, tendon transfers can be done at any time.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Ligament injuries", "question": "What is the Eaton classification for volar plate injuries of the PIP joint, and how does each type present?", "answer": "Eaton Classification: Type I - hyperextension injury with avulsion of the volar plate from the middle phalanx without fracture; Type II - dorsal dislocation with a volar lip fracture involving less than 40% of the articular surface; Type III - fracture-dislocation with a volar lip fracture involving more than 40% of the articular surface, resulting in joint instability. Type I injuries are treated with extension-block splinting; Type II may be treated with extension-block splinting or surgery; Type III typically requires operative fixation such as hemihamate arthroplasty or dynamic external fixation.", "notes": "Chapter 80. The 'dorsal V sign' on lateral radiograph indicates dorsal subluxation of the PIP joint.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Ligament injuries", "question": "What is a Stener lesion, and why is it clinically significant in thumb UCL injuries?", "answer": "A Stener lesion occurs when the torn ulnar collateral ligament (UCL) of the thumb MCP joint displaces superficial to the adductor pollicis aponeurosis, preventing healing by interposing the aponeurosis between the ligament and its bony attachment. This occurs in approximately 80% of complete UCL tears. It is clinically significant because the displaced ligament cannot heal without surgical intervention, making operative repair mandatory. Diagnosis is suggested by greater than 30 degrees of valgus laxity or 15 degrees more than the contralateral thumb, and confirmed by MRI or ultrasound showing the displaced ligament.", "notes": "Chapter 80. Also known as 'Skier's thumb' (acute) or 'Gamekeeper's thumb' (chronic).", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Ligament injuries", "question": "What is Elson's test and what does it evaluate?", "answer": "Elson's test evaluates the integrity of the central slip of the extensor tendon mechanism, used to diagnose acute boutonniere deformity. The PIP joint is flexed 90 degrees over the edge of a table, and the patient is asked to extend against resistance. If the central slip is intact, the DIP joint will remain floppy (flexible). If the central slip is disrupted, the lateral bands compensate and the DIP joint becomes rigid with hyperextension during attempted PIP extension, indicating a positive test. Early diagnosis is critical because untreated central slip injuries lead to chronic boutonniere deformity with PIP flexion and DIP hyperextension.", "notes": "Chapter 80. Boutonniere deformity results from disruption of the central slip allowing the lateral bands to migrate volar to the PIP joint axis of rotation.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Ligament injuries", "question": "Describe the scapholunate ligament injury and its radiographic findings. What is DISI deformity?", "answer": "Scapholunate (SL) ligament injury is the most common carpal ligament injury. Radiographic findings include: (1) Terry Thomas sign - widened scapholunate gap >3mm on PA view, (2) Signet ring sign - scaphoid appears as a ring due to flexion on PA view, (3) Scapholunate angle >60 degrees on lateral view. DISI (Dorsal Intercalated Segment Instability) deformity occurs when the lunate extends dorsally without the restraint of the scaphoid, resulting in a scapholunate angle >60 degrees. The normal scapholunate angle is 30-60 degrees. Untreated SL injury progresses to SLAC (scapholunate advanced collapse) wrist arthritis through predictable stages.", "notes": "Chapter 81. Geissler arthroscopic grading: Grade I - hemorrhage/attenuation; Grade II - incongruence with step-off visible; Grade III - probe can be passed through gap; Grade IV - arthroscope can pass through SL interval from midcarpal space.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Ligament injuries", "question": "What are the four stages of Mayfield classification for perilunate dislocations?", "answer": "Mayfield classification describes progressive perilunar instability in four stages: Stage I - scapholunate dissociation (disruption of the SL ligament); Stage II - perilunate dislocation (capitate dislocates dorsally relative to the lunate); Stage III - lunotriquetral disruption (triquetrum separates from lunate); Stage IV - lunate dislocation (lunate dislocates volarly into the carpal tunnel, spilled teacup sign on lateral radiograph). This represents a progressive arc of injury around the lunate. Perilunate dislocations are frequently missed on initial presentation (up to 25% of cases). Trans-scaphoid perilunate dislocations are a variant involving a scaphoid waist fracture instead of SL ligament disruption.", "notes": "Chapter 81. The VISI (Volar Intercalated Segment Instability) deformity is associated with lunotriquetral ligament injury, where the lunate flexes volarly.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Ligament injuries", "question": "What is the Palmer classification for TFCC injuries?", "answer": "The Palmer classification divides TFCC (triangular fibrocartilage complex) injuries into traumatic (Type 1) and degenerative (Type 2). Type 1 (Traumatic): 1A - central perforation, 1B - ulnar avulsion (with or without distal ulna fracture), 1C - distal avulsion from carpal attachment, 1D - radial avulsion (with or without sigmoid notch fracture). Type 2 (Degenerative): 2A - TFCC wear, 2B - TFCC wear with lunate chondromalacia, 2C - TFCC perforation with lunate chondromalacia, 2D - TFCC perforation with lunate chondromalacia and lunotriquetral ligament perforation, 2E - 2D plus ulnocarpal arthritis. Type 1B is the most common traumatic type and most amenable to surgical repair.", "notes": "Chapter 81. The TFCC is the primary stabilizer of the distal radioulnar joint (DRUJ).", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Mutilating injuries", "question": "What are the warm and cold ischemia time limits for extremities and digits, and what is the 'ribbon sign'?", "answer": "Ischemia time limits: Extremities - 6 hours warm ischemia, 12 hours cold ischemia; Digits - 12 hours warm ischemia, 24 hours cold ischemia. Digits tolerate longer ischemia because they have minimal muscle mass. The 'ribbon sign' refers to the appearance of severely damaged arteries on angiography or direct visualization, where the vessel appears flattened like a ribbon due to intimal damage and thrombosis. This indicates severe vascular injury that may preclude replantation or successful revascularization. Cold preservation significantly extends the window for viable repair by reducing metabolic demands.", "notes": "Chapter 82. ATLS protocol should always be completed first before addressing extremity injuries. The 'spare parts' technique uses non-replantable tissue for wound coverage.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Mutilating injuries", "question": "What are the indications for fasciotomy in upper extremity mutilating injuries, and what nerve gaps can be bridged with conduits?", "answer": "Fasciotomy is indicated when compartment pressures exceed 30 mmHg or when clinical signs of compartment syndrome develop (pain out of proportion, pain with passive stretch, paresthesia, paralysis, and pulselessness). In the forearm, all three compartments (volar, dorsal, and mobile wad) should be released. Indications also include after prolonged ischemia and revascularization, crush injuries, and high-energy trauma. Regarding nerve repair, nerve conduits (synthetic or biologic) can bridge gaps of less than 3 cm. For gaps greater than 3 cm, autologous nerve grafting is required. Skeletal muscle can tolerate approximately 4 hours of ischemia before irreversible damage occurs.", "notes": "Chapter 82. Vascular shunting can be used as a temporizing measure while other injuries are stabilized.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Replantation indications and contraindications", "question": "What are the absolute and relative indications for digital replantation?", "answer": "Absolute indications: (1) Thumb amputation, (2) Multiple digit amputations, (3) Transmetacarpal amputations, (4) Wrist and forearm level amputations, (5) Any amputation in children, (6) Individual digits amputated distal to the FDS insertion. Relative indications include single digit amputations proximal to FDS insertion (zone II), ring avulsion injuries (Urbaniak Class II-III), and amputations in the elderly with carefully considered functional needs. Contraindications include: severe crush or avulsion mechanism, prolonged warm ischemia beyond time limits, multiple-level injuries in a single digit, severe comorbidities precluding lengthy surgery, and self-inflicted injuries with underlying psychiatric conditions.", "notes": "Chapter 83. The 'red line sign' indicates extent of intimal damage along the vessel, and the 'ribbon sign' indicates severely damaged arteries.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Replantation indications and contraindications", "question": "What is the Urbaniak classification for ring avulsion injuries, and what prophylactic antibiotic is given when leeches are used?", "answer": "Urbaniak Classification for ring avulsion injuries: Class I - circulation adequate, no skeletal injury; Class II - circulation inadequate (requiring vascular repair), no skeletal injury; Class III - complete degloving or complete amputation; Class IV (Kay modification) - complete amputation with fracture or joint injury. Class I is treated conservatively. Class II requires revascularization. Class III requires replantation versus revision amputation based on mechanism and patient factors. When leeches are used postoperatively to manage venous congestion, prophylactic fluoroquinolone antibiotics (e.g., ciprofloxacin) must be given to prevent infection with Aeromonas hydrophila, a gram-negative bacterium found in leech saliva.", "notes": "Chapter 83. Chen's criteria are used to assess outcomes of replantation: Grade I (excellent) - return to work with good function; Grade II (good) - return to work with some loss; Grade III (fair) - return to daily activities; Grade IV (poor) - essentially nonfunctional.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Thumb reconstruction", "question": "What percentage of hand function does the thumb represent, and what are the main options for thumb reconstruction?", "answer": "The thumb represents approximately 40% of overall hand function. Minimum functional length is at the level of the IP joint. Reconstruction options depend on the level of loss: (1) Moberg flap - volar advancement flap providing 1.5-2 cm of coverage for distal defects; (2) First dorsal metacarpal artery (FDMA/kite) flap - for dorsal defects; (3) Littler flap (neurovascular island flap) - for volar pulp defects with sensory restoration; (4) Toe-to-thumb transfer - great toe, wraparound, trimmed great toe, or second toe transfer for more proximal amputations; (5) Pollicization - transfer of an adjacent finger to the thumb position when the CMC joint is absent or destroyed. The choice depends on level of amputation, tissue quality, and patient factors.", "notes": "Chapter 84. Blauth classification for thumb hypoplasia grades I-V: Types IIIB-V require pollicization because the CMC joint is inadequate or absent.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Thumb reconstruction", "question": "What is the Blauth classification for congenital thumb hypoplasia, and at what level does management change from reconstruction to pollicization?", "answer": "Blauth Classification: Type I - minor generalized hypoplasia (small thumb, all structures present); Type II - intrinsic muscle weakness with first web space narrowing, UCL instability; Type IIIA - extrinsic tendon abnormalities plus Type II features, stable CMC joint; Type IIIB - extrinsic tendon abnormalities plus Type II features, unstable CMC joint; Type IV - floating thumb (pouce flottant), attached by a skin bridge; Type V - complete absence of thumb. The critical transition point is between Types IIIA and IIIB. Types I through IIIA have a stable CMC joint and can be reconstructed with opponensplasty, UCL reconstruction, and first web deepening. Types IIIB through V have an absent or unstable CMC joint and are best treated with pollicization of the index finger.", "notes": "Chapter 84. Pollicization typically uses the index finger, which is shortened, rotated, and repositioned to function as a thumb.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Dupuytren disease", "question": "Describe the components of the spiral cord in Dupuytren disease and explain why the neurovascular bundle is at risk during surgery.", "answer": "The spiral cord is formed by four diseased structures: (1) the pretendinous band (becomes the pretendinous cord), (2) the spiral band, (3) the lateral digital sheet, and (4) Grayson's ligament. As these structures contract, the spiral cord displaces the neurovascular bundle in three directions: proximally, centrally (toward midline), and superficially. This displacement puts the digital nerve and artery directly in the path of surgical dissection, making them extremely vulnerable to injury during fasciectomy. The neurovascular bundle may be displaced to a position immediately beneath the skin, rather than in its normal deep and lateral position. Surgeons must identify and protect the neurovascular bundle before excising diseased cord.", "notes": "Chapter 85. Dupuytren disease shows increased type III collagen. The MCP joint is most commonly affected, followed by the PIP joint.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Dupuytren disease", "question": "What defines Dupuytren diathesis, and what are the treatment options for Dupuytren disease?", "answer": "Dupuytren diathesis refers to an aggressive form of the disease characterized by: (1) male sex, (2) bilateral involvement, (3) positive family history, (4) Garrod pads (knuckle pads), (5) onset before age 50, and (6) ectopic disease (Peyronie disease, Ledderhose disease). Treatment options include: (1) Needle aponeurotomy (percutaneous fasciotomy) - office-based, high recurrence rate; (2) Collagenase Clostridium histolyticum (CCH) injection - enzymatic dissolution of cord, followed by manipulation; (3) Limited (partial) fasciectomy - most common surgical treatment; (4) McCash technique - open palm technique leaving transverse palmar wounds open to heal by secondary intention; (5) Dermofasciectomy with firebreak skin grafts - for recurrent disease, replacing involved skin with full-thickness graft; (6) Proximal interphalangeal joint arthrodesis or amputation for severe recurrent PIP contractures.", "notes": "Chapter 85. PALF (percutaneous aponeurotomy with lipofilling) is a newer technique combining needle aponeurotomy with fat grafting.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Soft-tissue tumors", "subtopic": "Hand tumors", "question": "What are the most common benign and malignant tumors of the hand, and what are the key biopsy principles?", "answer": "Most common benign tumors: Ganglion cysts are the most common overall hand tumor (70% arise from the dorsal wrist scapholunate interval). Giant cell tumor of tendon sheath (GCTTS/pigmented villonodular synovitis) is the second most common. Enchondroma is the most common primary bone tumor of the hand, occurring most frequently in the proximal phalanges followed by metacarpals. Most common malignant tumors: Soft tissue sarcomas in the hand are often less than 5 cm. Squamous cell carcinoma is the most common malignant skin tumor. Epidermal inclusion cysts can mimic malignancy. Key biopsy principles: Biopsy incisions should be oriented longitudinally, planned along future definitive excision lines, performed at the most superficial/accessible portion of the tumor, and avoid contamination of uninvolved compartments.", "notes": "Chapter 86. Epidermal inclusion cysts result from implantation of epidermal cells into the dermis after trauma and may be confused with malignancy.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Vascular disorders of the hand", "question": "How is primary Raynaud phenomenon differentiated from secondary, and what is the first-line medical treatment?", "answer": "Primary Raynaud phenomenon: Onset typically before age 30, symmetric bilateral involvement, no tissue necrosis or ulceration, negative serologic workup (ANA, ESR), no underlying cause identified. Secondary Raynaud phenomenon: Onset typically after age 30, often asymmetric, may cause digital ulceration and tissue loss, associated with underlying conditions (scleroderma, lupus, rheumatoid arthritis, hypothyroidism, thoracic outlet syndrome, vibration injury). Diagnostic criteria include episodic digital pallor or cyanosis provoked by cold or stress, with at least two color changes in the triphasic response (white/blue/red). First-line medical treatment is calcium channel blockers (nifedipine). For refractory cases, surgical options include periarterial sympathectomy (adventitial stripping). Botulinum toxin injection has also shown benefit.", "notes": "Chapter 87. Hypothenar hammer syndrome presents with a 'corkscrew sign' on angiography from ulnar artery thrombosis. Buerger disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) has only one effective treatment: smoking cessation.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Burn reconstruction", "subtopic": "Burned hand reconstruction", "question": "What are the 5 R's framework for burned hand management, and what is the intrinsic plus splinting position?", "answer": "The 5 R's of burned hand management: (1) Resuscitation - fluid management; (2) Rest - proper splinting in intrinsic-plus position; (3) Rehabilitation - early ROM exercises; (4) Reconstruction - surgical interventions as needed; (5) Reintegration - return to function. The intrinsic-plus (safe) splinting position is: wrist in 20-30 degrees extension, MCP joints in 70-90 degrees flexion, IP joints in full extension, and thumb in abduction and opposition. This position maintains the collateral ligaments at maximum length, preventing contracture formation. Escharotomy is indicated for circumferential full-thickness burns compromising perfusion; fasciotomy is needed when compartment pressures are elevated.", "notes": "Chapter 88. Sheet grafts at 14/1000th inch are preferred for hand burns. Z-plasty at 45 degrees provides 50% theoretical/30% actual length gain.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hand trauma", "subtopic": "Compartment syndrome of the hand/forearm", "question": "What are the critical pressure thresholds and time limits for compartment syndrome of the upper extremity?", "answer": "Critical pressure thresholds: Absolute pressure >30 mmHg, or compartment pressure within 20-30 mmHg of the diastolic blood pressure (delta-P). The forearm has 3 compartments (volar/flexor, dorsal/extensor, and mobile wad). The hand has 10+ compartments (thenar, hypothenar, adductor pollicis, 4 dorsal interosseous, 3 volar interosseous, carpal tunnel). Time sensitivity: Skeletal muscle tolerates approximately 4 hours of ischemia before irreversible damage. Nerves can be affected after as little as 1 hour. The 5 P's of compartment syndrome are: Pain (out of proportion and with passive stretch - earliest and most reliable sign), Paresthesia, Paralysis, Pallor, and Pulselessness (late finding). Volkmann's ischemic contracture is the devastating sequela of missed forearm compartment syndrome.", "notes": "Chapter 89. Stryker monitor system is commonly used for compartment pressure measurement. Pulselessness is a very late finding - absence does not rule out compartment syndrome.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Congenital hand conditions", "question": "What is the ASSH/IFSSH classification for congenital hand anomalies, and what is the most common type of polydactyly?", "answer": "The ASSH/IFSSH 7-category classification: (1) Failure of formation (longitudinal or transverse arrest), (2) Failure of differentiation (syndactyly, symphalangism), (3) Duplication (polydactyly), (4) Overgrowth (macrodactyly), (5) Undergrowth (thumb hypoplasia), (6) Constriction band syndrome, (7) Generalized skeletal anomalies. Postaxial polydactyly (ulnar/small finger side) is the most common type overall, occurring in 1:143 African Americans (autosomal dominant with variable penetrance) versus 1:1,339 Caucasians. For thumb duplication (preaxial polydactyly), the Flatt/Wassel classification is used, with Type IV (duplication at the proximal phalanx level) being the most common at 43% of cases.", "notes": "Chapter 90. Syndactyly types: Simple (skin only) vs Complex (bony fusion), Complete (to fingertip) vs Incomplete (partial). Apert syndrome has 3 hand types with complex syndactyly.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Congenital hand conditions", "question": "What are the three types of hand involvement in Apert syndrome, and how is constriction ring syndrome classified?", "answer": "Apert syndrome hand types: Type 1 (Spade hand) - simple complete syndactyly of digits 2-4 with free border digits (thumb and small finger), mildest form; Type 2 (Mitten/Spoon hand) - complex syndactyly of digits 2-5 with thumb free or minimally involved; Type 3 (Rosebud hand) - complex syndactyly of all five digits including thumb, most severe form. All types feature symphalangism (stiff joints) and complex bony fusions. Constriction ring syndrome (amniotic band syndrome) is classified by severity: mild constriction rings, rings with distal lymphedema or deformity, rings with acrosyndactyly (fusion of distal digits with proximal sinuses), and intrauterine amputation. Treatment involves Z-plasty release of constriction bands and syndactyly release for acrosyndactyly.", "notes": "Chapter 90. Radial longitudinal deficiency (radial club hand) is associated with Holt-Oram syndrome (cardiac defects), VACTERL association, Fanconi anemia, and thrombocytopenia-absent radius (TAR) syndrome.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Upper limb amputation and prosthetics", "question": "What are TMR and RPNI techniques, and what is the most common level of upper extremity amputation?", "answer": "TMR (Targeted Muscle Reinnervation) involves transferring residual peripheral nerves from the amputated limb to nearby denervated motor muscles. The transferred nerves reinnervate these target muscles, which then produce EMG signals that can be detected by myoelectric prosthesis sensors, allowing more intuitive prosthetic control. RPNI (Regenerative Peripheral Nerve Interface) involves implanting the severed nerve end into a small autologous muscle graft. The nerve reinnervates the graft, creating a biological amplifier for bioelectric signals and reducing neuroma formation. The most common level of upper extremity amputation is transradial (below-elbow). Prosthesis rejection rates exceed 30%. Body-powered prostheses use harness and cable systems, while myoelectric prostheses use EMG signals for motorized components.", "notes": "Chapter 91. Targeted sensory reinnervation can provide sensory feedback from the prosthesis. Marquardt angulation osteotomy creates a bony prominence for better prosthesis suspension in transhumeral amputees.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Rheumatoid hand", "question": "What is Vaughan-Jackson syndrome and how does it differ from the Mannerfelt lesion?", "answer": "Vaughan-Jackson syndrome is the progressive rupture of extensor tendons at the wrist in rheumatoid arthritis, occurring in an ulnar-to-radial sequence: EDM (extensor digiti minimi) ruptures first, followed by EDC to ring, long, and index fingers. The ruptures occur over the distal ulna (caput ulnae) due to attritional wear from bony prominences and synovitis. Mannerfelt lesion is an isolated rupture of the FPL (flexor pollicis longus) tendon caused by attrition over a volar osteophyte on the scaphoid bone (or scaphoid-trapezium joint). Treatment for Vaughan-Jackson syndrome involves extensor tendon reconstruction with tendon transfers (EIP to EDM, side-to-side transfers) combined with Darrach procedure or Sauve-Kapandji for the distal ulna. Mannerfelt lesion is treated with FPL reconstruction using tendon graft or transfer.", "notes": "Chapter 92. ACR/EULAR diagnostic criteria for rheumatoid arthritis: score of 6 or greater out of 10. Swan-neck deformity = PIP hyperextension + DIP flexion. Boutonniere deformity = PIP flexion + DIP hyperextension.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Osteoarthritis of the hand and wrist", "question": "What is the Eaton classification for thumb CMC (basal joint) arthritis, and what is the most common surgical treatment in the US?", "answer": "Eaton Classification: Stage I - normal joint space or slight widening due to synovitis, articular contour normal; Stage II - slight joint space narrowing, osteophytes <2mm, slight subluxation of metacarpal; Stage III - significant joint space narrowing, osteophytes >2mm, subluxation >1/3 of articular surface, sclerosis and cyst formation; Stage IV - pantrapezial arthritis involving both the CMC and scaphotrapezial (ST) joints. The most common surgical treatment in the US is trapeziectomy with ligament reconstruction and tendon interposition (LRTI). Stage I: splinting, NSAIDs, corticosteroid injection; Stage II-III: trapeziectomy + LRTI or simple trapeziectomy; Stage IV: trapeziectomy + LRTI (must address pantrapezial disease). Dorsal ligaments are the key stabilizers of the thumb CMC joint.", "notes": "Chapter 93. SLAC wrist stages: I - radial styloid-scaphoid, II - radioscaphoid, III - capitolunate. PRC (proximal row carpectomy) and four-corner fusion have equivalent outcomes, but PRC is contraindicated in patients under 40 years old.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Elective hand", "subtopic": "Osteoarthritis of the hand and wrist", "question": "What are the recommended fusion angles for DIP and PIP joints, and what are the stages of SLAC wrist?", "answer": "Recommended fusion angles: DIP joints should be fused at 10-20 degrees of flexion; PIP joints should be fused at approximately 40 degrees of flexion (the index finger at slightly less flexion and the small finger at slightly more). SLAC (Scapholunate Advanced Collapse) wrist stages: Stage I - arthritis between the radial styloid and scaphoid; Stage II - radioscaphoid arthritis (entire scaphoid fossa); Stage III - capitolunate arthritis (midcarpal joint); The radiolunate joint is characteristically preserved in SLAC wrist. SNAC (Scaphoid Nonunion Advanced Collapse) follows a similar but slightly different pattern, with initial changes at the radial styloid-scaphoid junction. Treatment for Stage I-II: scaphoid excision and four-corner fusion. Stage III: same, or proximal row carpectomy. Total wrist arthrodesis is reserved for pancarpal arthritis.", "notes": "Chapter 93. PRC is contraindicated in patients with capitate head arthritis or age under 40 years due to concerns about cartilage wear.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest surgery", "subtopic": "Chest wall reconstruction", "question": "What are the indications for skeletal chest wall reconstruction, and what is the workhorse flap for sternal reconstruction?", "answer": "Skeletal chest wall reconstruction is indicated for anterior or lateral chest wall defects involving three or more adjacent ribs or defects 5 cm or greater in width. Posterior defects can tolerate larger resections without skeletal reconstruction due to the stabilizing forces of the scapula and thoracic vertebrae. Previously irradiated chest walls may also tolerate larger defects because radiation-related fibrosis decreases compliance and paradoxical motion. The pectoralis major muscle flap is the workhorse flap for sternal and anterior chest wall reconstruction. It can be advanced medially as a uni- or bilateral advancement flap (based on thoracoacromial vessels) to cover the superior two-thirds of the sternum. A turnover pectoralis flap (based on internal mammary perforators) is useful for dead space or inferior third defects, but is contraindicated if the IMA was used for coronary bypass.", "notes": "Chapter 94. Bioprosthetic mesh should be used in patients at high risk for complications (radiation history, contaminated fields). Second-line options include the superiorly-based rectus abdominis or omentum flap.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest surgery", "subtopic": "Chest wall reconstruction", "question": "What is the Pairolero and Arnold classification of sternal wound infections, and how is each type managed?", "answer": "Type 1: Occurs within first few postoperative days, characterized by faint erythema and serosanguinous drainage. Actually a misnomer - these are typically sterile mechanical failures of wire closure, not true infections. Treatment: conservative debridement and irrigation; titanium plating for symptomatic sternal nonunion. Type 2: Occurs within first few weeks, with frankly purulent drainage and significant cellulitis. True infection requiring operative debridement and muscle flap reconstruction. Type 3: Chronic infection due to osteomyelitis, costochondritis, or retained foreign body. Requires aggressive debridement and flap reconstruction. Both Type 2 and 3 require: removal of all hardware and wires, aggressive debridement until uniform bleeding, culture-directed antibiotics, and reconstruction with well-vascularized tissue. Negative pressure therapy can temporize wounds between debridement and definitive closure.", "notes": "Chapter 94. Mediastinitis occurs in 0.25%-5% of cardiac surgery patients. Risk factors: diabetes, COPD, smoking, obesity, immunosuppression, off-midline sternotomy.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest surgery", "subtopic": "Posterior trunk reconstruction", "question": "What is the workhorse flap for midline posterior trunk wounds, and why should spinal hardware be maintained during infection?", "answer": "The paraspinous muscle advancement flap is the workhorse flap for midline posterior trunk defects and is an adequate option at any spinal level (cervical, thoracic, lumbar). The paraspinous muscles (spinalis, longissimus, iliocostalis) are Mathes and Nahai Type 4 flaps perfused by segmental perforating vessels. They are imbricated into the midline defect using a Lembert suture technique. Unlike extremity hardware in infected wounds, spinal instrumentation should be maintained at all costs in cases of acute wound infection. Hardware maintains spinal stability, protects the spinal cord, and actually stabilizes the wound by eliminating micromotion and shearing of fragile traumatized soft tissues. Hardware that is well-fixed promotes healing. Chronic infections (>6 months) may require hardware removal and replacement if vertebral osteomyelitis is present.", "notes": "Chapter 94. Other flap options: trapezius (cervical/upper thoracic), latissimus dorsi (thoracic), reverse latissimus (lower thoracic/lumbar), gluteal (lumbosacral). The paraspinous muscles terminate at L5, so they are not appropriate for sacral reconstruction.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Hernia repair and component separation", "question": "What are the advancement distances achievable with Ramirez component separation, and how does mesh affect hernia recurrence?", "answer": "Ramirez component separation achieves unilateral advancement of: 5 cm in the epigastric region, 10 cm at the umbilicus, and 3 cm in the suprapubic region. Bilateral release therefore yields 10 cm, 20 cm, and 6 cm respectively. The technique involves release of the external oblique aponeurosis 2 cm lateral to the rectus sheath, from the costal margin to the inguinal ligament, with development of the avascular plane between external and internal oblique muscles. Additionally, the posterior rectus sheath is released from the rectus to achieve full advancement. Regarding mesh, hernia repair with mesh reduces the 10-year recurrence rate from approximately 63% (without mesh) to 32% (with mesh) - approximately a 50% reduction in recurrence. Even with mesh, over 20% of ventral hernia repairs recur, usually at the mesh-suture-tissue interface.", "notes": "Chapter 95. Optimal fascial closure: small bites of 5mm every 5mm with slowly absorbable monofilament suture, achieving a suture-to-wound length ratio >4:1.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Abdominal wall", "subtopic": "Hernia repair and component separation", "question": "What are the four anatomic positions for mesh placement in abdominal wall reconstruction, and what are the mesh selection considerations?", "answer": "Four positions for mesh placement: (1) Onlay - anterior to the anterior rectus sheath; (2) Retrorectus - between the recti and posterior rectus sheath; (3) Preperitoneal - posterior to the posterior rectus sheath but anterior to the peritoneum; (4) Intraperitoneal - within the abdomen (requires antiadhesive coating). Mesh selection considerations: Lightweight meshes have been associated with tearing and recurrence, so moderate-to-heavyweight meshes are preferred. Synthetic mesh (polypropylene, polyester) is used in clean cases. Bioprosthetic mesh is recommended for contaminated or clean-contaminated fields per the Ventral Hernia Working Group. Degradable/biologic meshes should not be used for bridging repairs (high recurrence). Mesh should overlap fascia by 3-5 cm in all directions. Intraperitoneal mesh requires antiadhesive coating to prevent bowel erosion, adhesions, and fistula.", "notes": "Chapter 95. Prophylactic onlay mesh at time of laparotomy in high-risk patients is an emerging field shown to reduce hernia occurrence in recent RCTs.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Trauma and orthoplastic reconstruction", "subtopic": "Lower extremity trauma management", "question": "What is the Gustilo-Anderson classification for open tibial fractures, and what did the Godina study show about timing of reconstruction?", "answer": "Gustilo-Anderson Classification: Grade I - wound <1 cm; Grade II - wound >1 cm without extensive soft tissue damage; Grade IIIA - extensive soft tissue injury with adequate coverage possible; Grade IIIB - extensive soft tissue injury with bone exposure, periosteal stripping, and massive contamination, often needs soft tissue coverage; Grade IIIC - any open fracture with arterial injury requiring vascular repair. Godina's landmark study on timing of free flap coverage showed: Early reconstruction (<72 hours): 1% flap failure, 2% infection rate; Delayed (72h to 3 months): 12% failure, 18% infection; Late (>3 months): 10% failure, 6% infection. Early reconstruction had shorter hospitalizations, fewer anesthetics, and faster bone healing, establishing the paradigm for early microsurgical coverage of open fractures.", "notes": "Chapter 96. Plastic surgeons are most commonly needed for Gustilo IIIB and IIIC injuries. The orthoplastic 'fix and flap' approach guides treatment.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Lower extremity reconstruction by thirds", "question": "Describe the 'rule of thirds' for lower extremity reconstruction and the key flap choices for each region.", "answer": "Rule of thirds for leg reconstruction: Proximal third (knee and upper leg): Gastrocnemius muscle flap is the classic option, typically used as muscle-only with skin graft. The medial head is preferred over lateral to avoid peroneal nerve injury. Secondary options include proximally based soleus, bipedicled tibialis anterior. Middle third: Soleus flap is the classic option. Other local options include gastrocnemius, flexor digitorum longus, extensor digitorum longus. Large defects may require free flap. Distal third: Free flap is the classic and preferred option due to minimal local tissue. Small defects may be covered with flexor hallucis longus, flexor digitorum longus, or tibialis anterior. The reverse sural artery flap is an alternative but has high complication rates. Important principles: fasciocutaneous flaps are equivalent to muscle flaps for fracture healing and infection prevention; anastomosis should always be outside the zone of injury.", "notes": "Chapter 96. Reverse soleus is indicated for distal third but is less ideal than free flap due to higher necrosis risk.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Bone flaps and vascularized bone transfer", "question": "What are the indications for vascularized bone grafts versus conventional bone grafts, and what is the Masquelet technique?", "answer": "Conventional (nonvascularized) bone grafts are indicated for defects <6 cm, placed 6 weeks after soft tissue coverage, and heal by creeping substitution. Vascularized bone grafts (free flaps) are indicated for defects >6 cm and offer primary bone healing with maintained osteocyte viability. The free fibula is the most commonly used, providing long segments with a reliable peroneal artery pedicle and the ability to hypertrophy. The Masquelet (induced membrane) technique is a two-stage procedure: Stage 1 - an antibiotic-impregnated cement spacer is placed in the bone defect, inducing a pseudosynovial membrane over 4-12 weeks; Stage 2 - the spacer is removed and cancellous bone graft (usually from iliac crest) is placed within the membrane. The membrane prevents fibrous ingrowth, maintains space, provides vascularization and growth factors, resulting in 90% union rate.", "notes": "Chapter 96. The medial femoral condyle free flap provides vascularized periosteum and cancellous bone, ideal for smaller nonunions (gaps <4 cm). Free fibula was first described by Taylor in 1975.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hidradenitis and inflammatory disease", "subtopic": "Hidradenitis suppurativa pathophysiology and treatment", "question": "What is the current understanding of hidradenitis suppurativa pathophysiology, and what is the only FDA-approved biologic for its treatment?", "answer": "Hidradenitis suppurativa (HS) is now understood to be a disease of the terminal hair follicle (infundibulum), NOT a primary disorder of apocrine glands as historically believed. Pathophysiology: Perifollicular lymphocytic infiltration causes inflammation, leading to hyperkeratosis of the infundibular epithelium. This creates a keratin plug causing cyst formation in the follicular bulb. The cyst eventually ruptures, releasing keratin debris and bacteria into the dermis, triggering an acute neutrophilic inflammatory response that progresses to a granulomatous stage with foreign body giant cells. Sinus tracts form between ruptured follicles and skin surface. The term 'acne inversa' more accurately describes this condition. Adalimumab (anti-TNF-alpha) is the only FDA-approved biologic for HS treatment. Surgical wide excision is the only definitive treatment for chronic scars and sinus tracts. Chronic HS can lead to squamous cell carcinoma (Marjolin ulcer).", "notes": "Chapter 97. Incidence ~1%, 3:1 female predominance, presents in 2nd-3rd decade. Associated with obesity, diabetes, metabolic syndrome, and nicotine use. Hurley Scale and modified Sartorius Scale are used for staging.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hidradenitis and inflammatory disease", "subtopic": "Perineal reconstruction", "question": "What is the Cordeiro classification for acquired vaginal defects, and what flap is recommended for Type IB posterior wall defects?", "answer": "Cordeiro classification: Type I - partial, noncircumferential vaginal defects: Type IA (anterior/lateral wall, associated with bladder cancer or primary vaginal malignancy) and Type IB (posterior wall, associated with advanced colorectal cancer and abdominoperineal resection). Type II - circumferential defects: Type IIA (upper one-third to two-thirds, associated with uterine or cervical cancers) and Type IIB (total vaginectomies, associated with pelvic exenterations). For Type IB posterior wall defects, the vertical rectus abdominis myocutaneous (VRAM) flap is the most common reconstruction. It provides well-vascularized tissue for dead space obliteration, pelvic floor support, and vaginal wall reconstruction. For Type IIA, a tubed VRAM or tubed V-DIEP can reconstruct the vaginal canal. For Type IIB total vaginectomy, bilateral gracilis myocutaneous flaps provide adequate tissue for complete vaginal reconstruction and dead space obliteration.", "notes": "Chapter 97. The Singapore flap (pudendal thigh flap) is based on the posterior labial artery and posterior cutaneous nerve of the thigh, useful for vulvar and partial vaginal reconstruction. For total vaginal reconstruction, inner diameter of ~4 cm is desired.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Hidradenitis and inflammatory disease", "subtopic": "Fournier gangrene management", "question": "What are the key principles of Fournier gangrene management, and what is the most common comorbidity?", "answer": "Fournier gangrene is necrotizing soft tissue infection of the perineum involving skin, subcutaneous tissue, fascia, and muscle, with mortality rates of 10-40%. The most common comorbidity is diabetes mellitus. Male predominance. Management principles: (1) Prompt surgical debridement of all infected, ischemic, and necrotic tissues is the mainstay; second-look operations are often necessary. (2) Broad-spectrum IV antibiotics covering gram-positive, gram-negative, and anaerobic bacteria, adjusted by culture sensitivities. Common organisms: polymicrobial including E. coli, S. aureus, Streptococcus species, Enterobacter, Pseudomonas, Bacteroides, and Clostridia. (3) Resuscitation. (4) Orchiectomy only if the testicle itself is nonviable. (5) Testicles can be placed in subcutaneous thigh pockets temporarily but this is poorly tolerated long-term and may decrease fertility. (6) Negative pressure wound therapy after adequate debridement. (7) Scrotal reconstruction with split-thickness skin grafts or thigh flaps after granulation.", "notes": "Chapter 97. Other risk factors: recent perineal surgery, malignancy, alcoholism, morbid obesity, immunocompromise.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Lymphedema diagnosis and treatment", "question": "What are the ISL staging criteria for lymphedema, and what are the two main physiologic surgical treatments?", "answer": "International Society of Lymphology (ISL) staging: Stage 0 - subclinical, impaired lymph transport but no visible swelling; Stage I - spontaneously reversible, early lymph accumulation, pitting may be present, improved with elevation; Stage II - not spontaneously reversible, fat hypertrophy and tissue fibrosis, pitting present but not improved with elevation; Stage III - lymphostatic elephantiasis, nonpitting wooden edema, hyperkeratotic and verrucous skin changes. The two main physiologic surgical procedures are: (1) Lymphovenous anastomosis (LVA) - bypass of patent lymphatic channels to subdermal venules, best for early-stage disease (stages I-II) with residual patent lymphatics on ICG lymphography. Minimally invasive supermicrosurgery technique. (2) Vascularized lymph node transfer (VLNT) - transfer of lymph node-containing tissue from donor site to affected limb, works by either reconstituting lymphatic channels or acting as a pump to absorb interstitial fluid. Donor sites include groin, submental, supraclavicular, and lateral thoracic regions.", "notes": "Chapter 98. A 2 cm or greater increase in limb circumference defines lymphedema. CDT (complete decongestive therapy) is first-line treatment. BCRL incidence: 5-7% after sentinel node biopsy, ~20% after axillary dissection, 25-40% after dissection + radiation.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Lymphedema diagnosis and treatment", "question": "What is the most common cause of secondary lymphedema worldwide versus in developed countries, and what are the modifiable risk factors?", "answer": "Worldwide: Infection with Wuchereria bancrofti (filarial nematode) causing lymphatic filariasis is the most common cause, affecting 120-250 million people predominantly in low-income countries. In developed countries: Surgical tissue trauma, particularly from lymph node dissection, is the most common cause. Breast cancer-related lymphedema (BCRL) represents the greatest burden in the US due to high breast cancer incidence. Modifiable risk factors: (1) Obesity/overweight (BMI >25) - the best-recognized modifiable risk factor with robust evidence that weight loss ameliorates symptoms; (2) Infections (cellulitis) - increases lymphedema risk; (3) Radiation - causes lymphatic channel fibrosis. Notably discredited risk factors include: venipuncture in the affected arm, blood pressure monitoring, and resistance exercise. Exercise is actually beneficial for lymphedema patients, providing strength and function improvements without increasing risk.", "notes": "Chapter 98. Up to 77% of BCRL develops within 3 years of surgery, then risk is ~1% per year. Lymphoscintigraphy is the standard diagnostic test. ICG lymphography shows real-time lymphatic flow patterns.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Pressure injuries", "question": "What is the NPUAP pressure injury staging system, and what is the 'tip of the iceberg' concept?", "answer": "NPUAP Staging: Stage 1 - nonblanching erythema of intact skin; Stage 2 - partial-thickness loss of dermis; Stage 3 - full-thickness loss with subcutaneous tissue visible but no exposed muscle or bone; Stage 4 - full-thickness loss with exposed bone, tendon, or muscle; Unstageable - full-thickness loss of unknown depth obscured by eschar or slough; Deep tissue pressure injury - purple/maroon intact skin or blood-filled blister of unknown depth. The 'tip of the iceberg' concept explains that pressure injuries start deep at the bone-muscle interface and progress outward. The most severe tissue destruction is adjacent to the bone, while the skin surface may show only minimal changes. This occurs because when external pressure exceeds capillary bed pressure (32 mmHg), ischemic damage begins in the muscle overlying the bony prominence first, then progresses to superficial soft tissues, and lastly affects the skin. This means surface appearance significantly underestimates the true extent of injury.", "notes": "Chapter 99. Pressure injuries are 'never events' per CMS since 2008 - hospitals are not reimbursed for hospital-acquired pressure injuries. Relieving pressure for 5 minutes every 2 hours allows adequate perfusion.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Pressure injuries", "question": "What are the flap options for sacral, ischial, and trochanteric pressure injuries, and what are the recurrence rates?", "answer": "Sacral pressure injuries: Gluteus maximus muscle flap is the most common musculocutaneous option (can be superior or inferiorly based with rotation, advancement, or turnover). Fasciocutaneous flaps or partial gluteus may be needed in ambulatory patients since the gluteus maximus is not expendable. Recurrence rates: 17-21%. Ischial pressure injuries: V-Y hamstring advancement flap and gluteal rotation flap are preferred because they can be readvanced for recurrent disease. The posterior thigh musculocutaneous flap is reliable but has limited upward mobility (10-12 cm). Avoid placing incisions over weight-bearing prominences. Recurrence rates: 19-33%. Trochanteric pressure injuries: Tensor fascia lata (TFL) flap is most common. Pedicled ALT flap is also an option. TFL can be sensate via L1-L3 (lateral femoral cutaneous nerve) in SCI below L3. Key principles: Avoid primary closure (high dehiscence), skin grafts fail due to shear forces, myocutaneous and fasciocutaneous flaps have equivalent outcomes. Recurrence rates up to 80% reported overall.", "notes": "Chapter 99. Preoperative goals: albumin >3.0 g/dL, prealbumin >20 mg/dL. Autonomic dysreflexia is a medical emergency in SCI patients (T6 and above) triggered by stimuli below the lesion.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Genital/perineal surgery", "subtopic": "Transfeminine surgery (vaginoplasty)", "question": "What are the WPATH prerequisites for vaginoplasty, and what are the major complications of penile inversion vaginoplasty?", "answer": "WPATH prerequisites for vaginoplasty: (1) Two referral letters from independent qualified mental health professionals, (2) 12 continuous months of hormone therapy (estrogen), (3) 12 continuous months of living in congruent female gender role, (4) Persistent, well-documented gender dysphoria, (5) Patient must be 18 years old (with case-by-case exceptions). Major complications of penile inversion vaginoplasty: Wound dehiscence/tissue loss (25-39%), urethral stenosis and/or divergent urinary stream (20-55%), vaginal/introital stenosis (6-27%), pelvic floor spasm/dyspareunia (2%), rectovaginal fistula (0.01-2%), rectal perforation (2% intraoperative). Over 20% require revisionary surgery. Patients must dilate for life or the vagina will contract. Estrogen is held 3 weeks preoperatively to reduce VTE risk (transfeminine patients on estrogen have 14x greater VTE risk than cisgender women after 9 years of therapy).", "notes": "Chapter 100. The neoclitoris is constructed from a dorsal glans penis W-shaped flap based on the dorsal penile nerve, artery, and veins within Buck's fascia. Postoperatively, most patients can achieve orgasm.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Genital/perineal surgery", "subtopic": "Transmasculine surgery (phalloplasty and mastectomy)", "question": "What are the main techniques for transmasculine mastectomy, and what determines technique selection?", "answer": "Techniques determined by breast volume, skin excess, and ptosis: (1) Periareolar mastectomy - for small breasts (A cup), grade 0-I ptosis, good elasticity. Incision from 9 to 3 o'clock along inferior areola border. Favorable scar but limited nipple repositioning. (2) Circumareolar (concentric circle) mastectomy - for modest skin excess. Donut skin excision with NAC resizing, deepithelialized superior dermal pedicle. Scar tends to spread. (3) Double-incision with free nipple grafting - most common technique for significant breast volume. Superior and inferior incisions with en bloc parenchyma removal, free nipple grafts placed at lateral inferior pectoralis major border sized ~2.4 x 2.0 cm oval. Inframammary fold is oblated and scored. Revisionary surgery rate ~40%. One WPATH letter required, no duration of testosterone needed for adults. Testosterone does NOT need to be held perioperatively (no increased risk of wound healing, bleeding, or DVT based on evidence).", "notes": "Chapter 100. All breast tissue should be sent to pathology. Cancer screening continues postoperatively. For phalloplasty, the radial forearm free flap is the most commonly used donor, requiring Allen's test preoperatively. Urethral complications (stricture/fistula) occur in 33-77% of phalloplasty cases.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Genital/perineal surgery", "subtopic": "Facial gender surgery", "question": "What are the key differences between masculine and feminine facial morphology, and what are the main components of facial feminization surgery?", "answer": "Masculine facial features: Square/rectangular face shape, tall forehead with high hairline, pronounced posterior sloping forehead contour, prominent supraorbital ridges, wide and prominent mandibular angles, square chin, long upper lip, acute nasolabial angle, larger nose. Feminine facial features: Oval face shape, shorter vertically oriented forehead with lower hairline, minimal supraorbital ridges, shorter upper lip, narrower mandibular angles, more obtuse nasolabial angle, more pointed chin, smaller/more delicate nose. Main components of facial feminization surgery: (1) Forehead - hairline lowering via pretrichial incision, supraorbital ridge reduction (burring or formal frontal sinus recession with anterior table osteotomy), brow lift; (2) Midface - malar augmentation (implants or fat grafting), feminizing rhinoplasty (dorsal hump reduction, narrowing osteotomies, tip refinement); (3) Lower face - upper lip lift (gull-wing excision), narrowing genioplasty, mandibular angle reduction; (4) Thyrochondroplasty - reduction of Adam's apple through submental incision, conservative resection to avoid vocal cord injury.", "notes": "Chapter 100. Preoperative CT scan is essential for forehead recontouring to assess frontal bone thickness and frontal sinus. The anterior commissure of the vocal cords must be identified before thyroid cartilage shaving to prevent voice injury.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "General", "subtopic": "Gender-affirming surgery standards of care", "question": "What is WPATH and what are the key requirements for gender-affirming genital surgery versus chest surgery?", "answer": "WPATH (World Professional Association for Transgender Health) is an international society that issues Standards of Care (SOC, current Version 7 from 2011) defining best practices to prevent harm and regret. For genital surgery (vaginoplasty, phalloplasty, metoidioplasty): Two referral letters from qualified mental health professionals, 12 months of hormone therapy, 12 months of living in congruent gender role, persistent well-documented gender dysphoria, age 18+. For chest surgery (transfeminine breast augmentation): One referral letter, 12 months of estrogen therapy recommended but not required, no real-life experience requirement. For transmasculine mastectomy: One referral letter, testosterone therapy is NOT a prerequisite for adults. Gender dysphoria affects ~0.6% of the population (1.4 million in the US). Plastic surgeons cannot independently diagnose gender dysphoria - determination of surgical candidacy must be in a multidisciplinary setting per WPATH SOC.", "notes": "Chapter 100. Gender dysphoria is distinct from disorders of sexual development. Gender identity is largely biologically determined and independent of sexual orientation. Approximately 60% of preadolescent children with gender identity disorder may 'desist' - surgery is never indicated in children.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Syndactyly", "question": "How is syndactyly classified, and which webspace is most commonly affected in nonsyndromic cases?", "answer": "Syndactyly is classified by extent (complete vs. incomplete), tissue involvement (simple = soft tissue only; complex = bony/joint fusion; complicated = multiple tissues including bones, joints, tendons, muscles, or neurovascular bundles). The most common webspace in nonsyndromic syndactyly is the middle/ring finger (57%), followed by ring/little finger (27%). In syndromic cases, the thumb/index and index/middle webspaces are more common. Syndactyly is Type II (failure of differentiation) in the ASSH/IFSSH classification.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Syndactyly", "question": "What are the goals and key technical principles of syndactyly release surgery, and when should border digits be released?", "answer": "Goals: (1) creation of anatomically normal webspace, (2) tension-free soft tissue closure, (3) return of function. Key principles: Dorsal rectangular/trapezoidal flap designed two-thirds distance from MCP heads to PIP joints to reconstruct webspace. Zig-zag (Cronin) dorsal and volar flaps minimize scar contracture. Full-thickness skin grafts (from groin, NOT wrist/forearm) cover the 22-30% circumferential skin deficit but should be avoided over webspaces and PIP joints. Border digits (thumb/index, ring/little) should be released early (3-6 months) due to length discrepancy causing growth disturbance. Only one side of a digit should be released at a time to avoid neurovascular compromise.", "notes": "Web creep (distal migration of webspace) is the main long-term complication. Buck-Gramcko pulp flaps reconstruct paronychial folds in synonychia.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Polydactyly", "question": "Describe the Flatt (Wassel) classification of thumb duplication and the most common type. Which duplicate is typically preserved and why?", "answer": "The Flatt classification describes thumb duplication from distal to proximal: Type I = bifid distal phalanx; Type II = duplication at IP joint; Type III = bifid proximal phalanx; Type IV (MOST COMMON) = duplication at MCP joint; Type V = bifid metacarpal; Type VI = duplication at CMC joint; Type VII = triphalangeal thumb. Even numbers = complete phalangeal duplications; odd numbers = incomplete duplications. The ULNAR thumb is preferentially preserved because: (1) it is usually larger, and (2) it preserves the native ulnar collateral ligament essential for thumb-index pinch stability. The radial collateral ligament from the ablated thumb is preserved and secured to the retained ulnar thumb for varus MCP stability.", "notes": "Surgery performed between 9-15 months before development of pinch grasp. Options include ablation of one thumb, Bilhaut-Cloquet (sharing equal halves), or composite reconstruction.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Polydactyly", "question": "How does postaxial polydactyly differ in presentation and management between African Americans and Caucasians?", "answer": "Postaxial polydactyly is the most common type of polydactyly. In African Americans: incidence 1 in 143 births, autosomal dominant with incomplete penetrance, typically isolated. In Caucasians: incidence 1 in 1339 births, more frequently associated with a syndrome (should prompt genetics consultation). Type A = fully developed digit articulating with 5th/6th metacarpal (requires surgical reconstruction preserving UCL and adductor digiti minimi). Type B = rudimentary duplication on a thin stalk (can be treated with in-office vascular clip ligation at the base, causing dry gangrene and autoamputation). Suture ligation is discouraged as it leaves a residual stump requiring later excision.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Thumb hypoplasia", "question": "What is the Blauth classification of thumb hypoplasia, and what is the critical distinction that determines whether reconstruction vs. pollicization is indicated?", "answer": "Blauth classification: Type I = minor hypoplasia; Type II = first webspace narrowing, hypoplastic/absent thenar muscles, MCP instability; Type IIIA = hypoplastic metacarpal with STABLE CMC joint; Type IIIB = partial metacarpal aplasia with UNSTABLE CMC joint; Type IV = floating thumb (pouce flottant); Type V = absent thumb. The CRITICAL distinction is CMC joint stability: Types II and IIIA (stable CMC) can be reconstructed with webspace widening, opponensplasty, and MCP stabilization. Types IIIB, IV, and V (unstable or absent CMC) require thumb ablation and INDEX FINGER POLLICIZATION, as the thumb cannot be functionally reconstructed. Pollicization involves skeletal shortening of the index metacarpal, rotation/stabilization of the index finger, and transfer of the first dorsal and volar intrinsic muscles.", "notes": "All cases of radial longitudinal deficiency have associated thumb hypoplasia. Thumb hypoplasia can also exist without radial abnormality.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pediatric soft tissue and vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Syndactyly", "question": "What are the seven categories of congenital hand anomalies in the ASSH/IFSSH classification, and what embryologic axes control limb development?", "answer": "Seven categories: I = Failure of formation (radial dysplasia, phocomelia); II = Failure of differentiation (syndactyly, camptodactyly, clinodactyly, trigger digits); III = Duplication (polydactyly); IV = Overgrowth (macrodactyly); V = Undergrowth (hypoplastic thumb); VI = Congenital constriction band syndrome; VII = Generalized skeletal abnormalities (dwarfism). Three embryologic axes: (1) Proximodistal - controlled by apical ectodermal ridge (AER) via FGFs; (2) Anteroposterior (radio-ulnar) - controlled by zone of polarizing activity (ZPA) via sonic hedgehog protein; (3) Dorsoventral - controlled by dorsal ectoderm via Wnt-7a. Transplanting ZPA to radial side causes ulnar dimelia (mirror hand).", "notes": "Upper extremity development occurs weeks 5-8 of gestation. Digital separation occurs via apoptosis of the AER between days 47-53.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest wall and torso defects", "subtopic": "Sternal wound recon", "question": "Describe the Pairolero-Arnold classification of sternal wound infections and the management of each type.", "answer": "Type 1: Faint erythema with serosanguinous drainage in the first few postoperative days. Actually a misnomer as these are NOT infected - caused by mechanical failure of sternal wire closure. Treated with conservative debridement and irrigation. If progressing to symptomatic nonunion, wires can be removed and rigid titanium plating applied. Type 2: Occurs within first few weeks; frankly purulent drainage with significant cellulitis. Requires significant debridement and muscle flap reconstruction. Type 3: Chronic infection from osteomyelitis, costochondritis, or retained foreign body. Also requires debridement and muscle flap reconstruction. Mediastinitis occurs in 0.25-5% of cardiac surgery patients. Risk factors: age, COPD, smoking, diabetes, steroids, immunosuppression, obesity, reoperative surgery, off-midline sternotomy.", "notes": "All hardware and sternal wires should be removed during debridement. Negative pressure therapy can temporize wounds between debridement and definitive closure.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest wall and torso defects", "subtopic": "Pectoralis advancement", "question": "What are the flap options for sternal wound soft tissue reconstruction, and when is a turnover pectoralis flap contraindicated?", "answer": "First-line: Pectoralis major advancement flap (workhorse for sternal wounds). Based on thoracoacromial vessels, disinserted from humeral attachment and advanced medially. Uni- or bilateral advancement resurfaces the superior two-thirds of the sternum. For inferior third or significant dead space: Turnover pectoralis flap based on internal mammary perforators - CONTRAINDICATED if the internal mammary artery has been harvested for coronary artery bypass grafting. Second-line options: (1) Superiorly-based rectus abdominis flap (can include vertical or transverse skin paddle); (2) Omentum flap based on left or right gastroepiploic vessels. For large cutaneous defects (e.g., after oncologic sternectomy), free tissue transfer may be needed.", "notes": "The plastic surgeon must know which coronary bypass grafts were used to plan flaps accordingly.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest wall and torso defects", "subtopic": "Omental flap", "question": "What are the advantages and disadvantages of the omentum flap for chest wall and sternal reconstruction?", "answer": "Advantages: Large surface area of well-vascularized tissue; can fill and resurface the entire mediastinum; can be used for intrathoracic space (empyema/bronchopleural fistula); based on left or right gastroepiploic vessels; can be routed through the diaphragm or externally through the epigastric abdominal wall; can be elevated laparoscopically to minimize donor morbidity; native chest skin can be closed over it or it can be skin grafted. Disadvantages: Risk of epigastric or diaphragmatic hernia; requires entering the abdomen (ileus, bowel obstruction, visceral injury); unpredictable size/quality in thin patients or those with prior abdominal surgery. The omentum can also be tunneled through the retroperitoneum to fill dead space along the thoracic spine.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest wall and torso defects", "subtopic": "Oncologic chest wall recon", "question": "What are the indications for skeletal chest wall reconstruction, and how does prior radiation affect the choice of reconstruction material?", "answer": "Indications: Anterior/lateral defects involving 3+ adjacent ribs or >=5 cm in width benefit from skeletal reconstruction. Posterior defects tolerate larger resections without reconstruction (scapula and vertebrae provide stabilization). Previously irradiated chest walls may not need skeletal reconstruction (radiation fibrosis decreases compliance, reducing paradoxical motion). Material choice: Clean wounds with low complication risk: synthetic mesh (polyethylene, polypropylene, or ePTFE). Irradiated or high-risk wounds: BIOPROSTHETIC mesh preferred (can revascularize, resistant to infection). Large defects: methylmethacrylate sandwiched between synthetic mesh layers or titanium rib-spanning plates. Titanium plates should always be combined with a mesh underlay for pleural reconstruction and covered anteriorly with a well-vascularized muscle flap.", "notes": "Synthetic mesh has up to 5% infection rate and infection necessitates removal. Bioprosthetic mesh does not require removal if infected/exposed.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest wall and torso defects", "subtopic": "Spine wound recon", "question": "What is the workhorse flap for midline posterior trunk wounds, and how does management of infected spinal hardware differ from other hardware infections?", "answer": "The PARASPINOUS MUSCLE ADVANCEMENT FLAP is the workhorse for midline posterior trunk defects at any spinal level (cervical through lumbar). These are Mathes and Nahai Type 4 flaps perfused by segmental perforating vessels. Dissection proceeds superficial to the paraspinous muscles to their lateral border, the fascia is divided, and muscles are advanced medially and imbricated into the midline using a Lembert suture to direct tissue into dead space. CRITICAL DISTINCTION: Unlike other infected hardware scenarios, spinal instrumentation should be maintained at all costs. Hardware maintains spinal stability, protects the spinal cord, and eliminates micromotion. Early infections (<6 weeks) are treated with antibiotics, debridement, and muscle flap with hardware retention. Chronic infections (>6 months) may require hardware removal and replacement, with MRI to evaluate for vertebral osteomyelitis.", "notes": "Other flap options by level: Cervical = trapezius; Thoracic = latissimus dorsi; Lower thoracic/lumbar = reverse latissimus; Lumbosacral = gluteal flaps.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest wall and torso defects", "subtopic": "Hardware exposure", "question": "When should prophylactic spinal wound reconstruction with muscle flaps be considered, and what are the principles of debridement for infected spine wounds?", "answer": "Prophylactic flap reconstruction is indicated in high-risk situations: large resections/instrumentations, multiple previous spine surgeries, history of radiation to the spine, neoadjuvant chemotherapy, obesity, diabetes, or steroid use. Debridement principles: (1) Open entire incision and expose all instrumentation; (2) Know the initial surgery - if laminectomy/vertebrectomy was done, the spinal cord and dura are vulnerable; (3) Remove all nonviable soft tissue and unincorporated bone graft; (4) Copious antibiotic saline irrigation; (5) If adequately debrided, close over drains with muscle flap for dead space obliteration; (6) If wound still purulent, approximate paraspinous muscles loosely over hardware, leave skin open with negative pressure dressing, and return for definitive closure under general anesthesia. For osseous defects >4 cm, vascularized bone flaps (e.g., free fibula) may be needed as up to 50% of patients fail to fuse with standard bone graft alone.", "notes": "", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Staging", "question": "Describe the National Pressure Injury Advisory Panel staging system and the pathophysiology of pressure-induced tissue injury.", "answer": "Staging: Stage 1 = nonblanching erythema (treatment: pressure relief); Stage 2 = partial-thickness loss of dermis (pressure relief, wound care); Stage 3 = full-thickness loss with visible subcutaneous tissue but NO muscle/bone (possible surgical debridement); Stage 4 = full-thickness loss with exposed bone, tendon, or muscle (surgical debridement); Unstageable = full-thickness loss covered by eschar/slough (remove devitalized tissue to stage); Deep tissue pressure injury = purple/maroon intact skin or blood-filled blister (monitor, may need debridement); Mucosal membrane = at site of medical device, not staged. Pathophysiology: When external pressure exceeds capillary bed pressure (32 mmHg), perfusion is impaired. Injury occurs DEEP FIRST (muscle overlying bone) then superficial tissues then skin - called the 'tip of the iceberg' pattern.", "notes": "Stages 1-2 generally nonoperative. Stages 3-4 may require surgery. Relieving pressure for 5 minutes every 2 hours allows adequate perfusion.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Osteomyelitis workup", "question": "How should osteomyelitis be evaluated in the setting of pressure injuries, and what is the recommended approach to bone debridement?", "answer": "Osteomyelitis workup: MRI is the imaging modality of choice (97% sensitive, 89% specific) to evaluate extent of disease. BONE BIOPSY is the gold standard for diagnosis. Avoid superficial wound swabs due to contamination (only 22-36% concordance with deep/intraoperative cultures). Intraoperative deep tissue cultures are superior for tailoring antibiotic therapy. Lab markers: WBC, ESR, CRP for inflammation/infection; track with nutritional labs as inflammation may artificially suppress albumin/prealbumin. Bone debridement principles: Remove MINIMAL bone possible. Avoid radical ostectomy as it causes skeletal instability, excessive bleeding, and pressure point redistribution (e.g., unilateral ischiectomy leads to contralateral pressure injury). Osteomyelitis is extremely common: 56% of primary injuries and 79% of recurrent injuries have positive bone biopsies.", "notes": "NPWT is contraindicated in untreated osteomyelitis. HBOT may be adjunctive for chronic refractory osteomyelitis.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Nutrition", "question": "What are the nutritional optimization goals before surgical reconstruction of pressure injuries, and what laboratory parameters should be monitored?", "answer": "Serum albumin goal >3.0 g/dL before surgery (provides adequate protein for positive nitrogen balance). Albumin <3.5 g/dL is a risk factor for recurrence/reoperation and wound dehiscence/flap failure. Laboratory monitoring: serum albumin, prealbumin, and micronutrients (Zn, Ca, Fe, Cu, Vitamins A and C). IMPORTANT: Track inflammatory markers (ESR, CRP) alongside nutritional labs because inflammation may artificially suppress albumin and prealbumin levels. Glucose optimization: HgbA1c goal <6% (HgbA1c >6% is a risk factor for wound dehiscence). Consult nutritionist for dietary modifications to meet caloric goals (tube feeds, high-calorie shakes). May need colorectal diversion for wound hygiene AND to improve diet/nutrition. Swallow evaluation with or without feeding tube placement.", "notes": "Malnutrition correlates with both development of primary injuries and poor wound healing.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Flap options (gluteal/posterior thigh/hamstring/TFL)", "question": "What are the flap options for sacral, ischial, and trochanteric pressure injuries, and what are key planning considerations for each location?", "answer": "SACRAL: Common in bedridden/supine patients. Workhorse = gluteus maximus musculocutaneous flap (superior or inferior based; can rotate, advance, or turnover). For ambulatory patients, use fasciocutaneous flap or partial gluteus as the gluteus maximus is NOT expendable. Recurrence 17-21%. ISCHIAL: Common in wheelchair-bound patients. Highest recurrence (19-33%). Design should consider ambulatory status, future flap needs (high recurrence), and avoid incisions over weight-bearing prominences. Options: gluteal rotation flap, V-Y hamstring advancement (both can be readvanced). Avoid tension as hip flexion causes dehiscence. TFL may be considered but can be too thin distally. TROCHANTERIC: Common in laterally positioned patients. Most common flap = TFL. Pedicled ALT is also an option. TFL blood supply from underlying TFL muscle; distal flap is random pattern. If SCI below L3, TFL can be sensate via lateral femoral cutaneous nerve (L1-L3).", "notes": "No reported difference in success between myocutaneous vs. fasciocutaneous flaps. Avoid primary closure (high dehiscence) and skin grafts (cannot tolerate repeated pressure/shear).", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Recurrence prevention", "question": "What are the risk factors for pressure injury recurrence after surgical reconstruction, and what postoperative measures help prevent recurrence?", "answer": "Risk factors for recurrence: Young age (<45), low albumin <3.5 g/dL, African American race, ischial location, V-Y thigh flap (controversial due to tension), smoking, premature sitting, anemia requiring transfusion. Recurrence rates can reach 80% in some studies. Prevention measures: (1) Air-fluidized bed or low-air loss mattress postoperatively; (2) Bedrest for 2-6 weeks (balanced against risks of pneumonia, VTE, deconditioning); (3) Avoid sitting upright in bed; resume sitting gradually on pressure-reducing surface; (4) Behavioral modification: reposition every 2 hours, offloading devices; (5) Manage spasticity (baclofen, diazepam, botulinum toxin); (6) Manage incontinence; (7) Optimize nutrition continuously; (8) Design flaps anticipating future reoperations (flaps that can be readvanced). Chronic nonhealing wounds require monitoring for Marjolin ulcer (aggressive SCC, 2-25 years after wound).", "notes": "SCI patients above T6 are at risk for autonomic dysreflexia postoperatively. DVT prophylaxis is critical as VTE incidence in acute SCI is up to 11%.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Sacral/ischial/trochanteric ulcers", "question": "What are the most common sites for pressure injuries, and what is the 'tip of the iceberg' concept in pressure injury pathology?", "answer": "Most common sites: sacrum (supine patients), ischium (seated/wheelchair patients), heel, and trochanter (laterally positioned patients). Other sites include ears, scapula, and occiput. The 'tip of the iceberg' concept describes how pressure injury extends from deep to superficial: muscle overlying bone is injured FIRST, followed by subcutaneous tissue, and lastly the skin surface. Therefore, the visible skin wound underestimates the true extent of deep tissue destruction. This cone-shaped pattern is critical for surgical planning - the wound is always larger beneath the surface. External pressure exceeding 32 mmHg (capillary bed pressure) causes progressive ischemia with accumulation of metabolic waste and free radicals, leading to permanent tissue destruction. Contributing factors include friction, shear, moisture/incontinence, malnutrition, and neurologic injury.", "notes": "Pressure injuries account for the second most common hospital billing claim. Cost per stage 3-4 injury: $70,000-$150,000. Classified as 'never events' by CMS since 2008.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial gender surgery", "subtopic": "Forehead/frontal sinus setback", "question": "What are the key steps in forehead feminization surgery, and how does preoperative imaging guide the surgical approach to supraorbital ridge reduction?", "answer": "Forehead feminization includes hairline lowering and supraorbital ridge reduction. A lateral cephalograph or maxillofacial CT is ESSENTIAL preoperatively to determine frontal bone thickness over the frontal sinus and gauge the degree of reduction needed. Two approaches: (1) If frontal bone is sufficiently thick and setback required is modest: BURRING of the supraorbital ridges is sufficient. (2) If frontal bone is thin and/or significant setback required: FORMAL FRONTAL SINUS RECESSION - removing the anterior table of the frontal sinus completely, performing osteotomies on the excised bone segment, and replacing/rigidly fixing the bone in a reshaped feminine configuration. Access via pretrichial incision, which also allows hairline advancement (correcting widow's peak) with posterior scalp advancement and forehead skin excision. Hair grafting can disguise the scar and contour the hairline. This incision also provides access for a brow lift.", "notes": "Masculine forehead: tall, posterior-sloping, prominent supraorbital ridges. Feminine forehead: shorter, vertically oriented, minimal ridges, lower hairline.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial gender surgery", "subtopic": "Rhinoplasty", "question": "What are the goals of feminizing rhinoplasty and midface surgery in facial feminization?", "answer": "Feminizing rhinoplasty goals: (1) Correct dorsal hump reduction (masculine noses are generally larger); (2) Osteotomies to narrow the upper vault; (3) Cephalic trim to rotate the nasal tip and create a supratip break; (4) Interdomal sutures for more tip definition; (5) Achieve a more obtuse nasolabial angle (vs. acute angle in males). Midface feminization: Malar implants or fat grafting to define cheekbones and feminize the midface. The overall goal is to transform a 'less delicate' masculine nose and flatter midface into a more refined, delicate feminine appearance. Standard preoperative analysis of nasal airflow, anatomy, dry eye assessment, and negative orbital vector evaluation should be performed if rhinoplasty, brow lifting, or blepharoplasty are planned.", "notes": "Masculine: square/rectangular face, wide mandibular angles, long upper lip, acute nasolabial angle. Feminine: oval face, narrower mandible, shorter upper lip, obtuse nasolabial angle.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial gender surgery", "subtopic": "Mandible/chin contouring", "question": "What surgical techniques are used for feminization of the mandible, chin, and lower face?", "answer": "Chin feminization: Narrowing genioplasty via transverse and vertical wedge excision osteotomy to reduce prominence and create a more pointed chin (vs. square masculine chin). Mandibular angle reduction: Osteotomies or burring through INTRAORAL access incisions. Total mandibular height reduction: Resection of the entire inferior border of the mandible (if appropriate). Upper lip lift: Gull-wing excision of skin along the nasal sill to provide incisal tooth show at rest and increase vermillion fullness (addressing the longer masculine upper lip). Preoperative planning should include analysis of occlusion and X-ray to identify the mental foramen and inferior alveolar nerve position to avoid nerve injury during mandibular recontouring.", "notes": "Masculine features: wide/prominent mandibular angles, square chin, long upper lip. Feminine features: narrower mandibular angles, pointed chin, shorter upper lip with more tooth show.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Facial gender surgery", "subtopic": "Tracheal shave", "question": "Describe the technique for thyrolaryngoplasty (tracheal shave) in transfeminine patients and the key safety considerations.", "answer": "The thyroid cartilage is more prominent in males due to a more acute angle between paired laminae (90 degrees vs. 120 degrees in females). Technique: (1) Approach through a SUBMENTAL incision (not over the thyroid cartilage) to leave a scar not visible on frontal view; (2) Dissect to expose superficial surface of thyroid cartilage (aided by lighted retractors or endoscopy); (3) CRITICAL SAFETY STEP: Pass a flexible laryngoscope to locate the anterior commissure of the vocal cords by observing emergence of a needle through the cartilage, then mark with methylene blue; (4) Shave the external surface of the thyroid cartilage until reasonable contour is achieved (bur or rongeurs may be needed in adults with calcified cartilage); (5) Resection should be CONSERVATIVE to avoid vocal cord injury. The term 'tracheal shave' is technically a misnomer - the procedure involves the thyroid cartilage, not the trachea.", "notes": "The thyroid cartilage connects superiorly to hyoid via thyrohyoid membrane and inferiorly to cricoid via cricothyroid ligaments.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "General", "subtopic": "WPATH standards", "question": "What are the WPATH Standards of Care prerequisites for gender-affirming surgeries, and how do requirements differ between procedures?", "answer": "WPATH SOC (Version 7, 2011) requirements vary by procedure: BREAST AUGMENTATION (transfeminine): 1 referral letter, 12 months hormones recommended but not required. MASTECTOMY (transmasculine): 1 referral letter, no hormone prerequisite. VAGINOPLASTY: 2 referral letters, 12 months hormones, 12 months living in congruent gender role. ORCHIECTOMY/HYSTERECTOMY: 2 referral letters, 12 months hormones. PHALLOPLASTY/METOIDIOPLASTY: 2 referral letters, 12 months hormones, 12 months living in congruent gender role. All patients should be 18 years old and legally able to consent. Comorbid psychiatric conditions must be 'reasonably well controlled.' Key principle: Plastic surgeons CANNOT independently diagnose gender dysphoria - surgical candidacy must be determined by a multidisciplinary team in accordance with WPATH SOC.", "notes": "Referral letters should include diagnosis, relationship duration, endorsement of criteria fulfillment, informed consent confirmation, and adequately controlled mental health concerns.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "General", "subtopic": "Hormone therapy", "question": "What hormonal therapies are used for transfeminine and transmasculine patients, and what perioperative considerations exist regarding hormone management?", "answer": "Transfeminine patients: Estrogen + antiandrogens (spironolactone or finasteride). Transmasculine patients: Testosterone. Puberty suppression in adolescents uses GnRH agonists (safe and reversible), with cross-hormone therapy potentially initiated at age 15-16. PERIOPERATIVE CONSIDERATIONS: Estrogen should be HELD 3 weeks prior to surgery in transfeminine patients due to elevated VTE risk on hormonal therapy. Testosterone does NOT need to be discontinued perioperatively for transmasculine patients (studies show no effect on wound healing, bleeding, or DVT risk). Gender dysphoria affects 0.6% of the population (~1.4 million in the US). Gender identity is determined largely by biological factors and is independent of sexual orientation.", "notes": "Transfeminine patients over 40 on estrogen should have screening mammography and breast cancer risk assessment. Vaginoplasty is sterilizing - discuss sperm banking.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "General", "subtopic": "Multidisciplinary care", "question": "Why is multidisciplinary care essential for transgender patients, and what team members/services should be available?", "answer": "Multidisciplinary care is modeled after bariatric or transplant surgery programs and is critical for good patient outcomes. Required team members/services: Mental health counseling, social work, pediatric or adult endocrinology, fertility services, surgery, permanent hair removal providers, speech therapy, pelvic floor physiotherapy, and organized peer support for patients and families. This population is underserved with elevated rates of homelessness, joblessness, family estrangement, interpersonal violence, suicide, HIV, and mental health comorbidities. Suicidal ideation and attempts greatly exceed the general population. Environmental considerations: Staff education on preferred pronouns, preferred first names (especially pre-legal name change), and housing patients in their expressed gender during hospital admissions. Misgendering is particularly harmful to this population.", "notes": "Gender-affirming surgery is recognized as medically necessary by the AMA, ASPS, and other professional societies. Often covered by insurance including Medicare.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest surgery", "subtopic": "Masculinizing chest surgery", "question": "What are the surgical techniques for transmasculine chest surgery (top surgery), and how is the appropriate technique selected?", "answer": "Four main techniques based on breast volume, skin excess, ptosis, and elasticity: (1) PERIAREOLAR: Small breast (A cup), grade 0-I ptosis, good elasticity. Incision along inferior areola 9-3 o'clock. Limits nipple repositioning. Minimal scar. (2) CIRCUMAREOLAR: Modest skin excess. Concentric circle with NAC resizing and donut skin excision. NAC survives on superior deepithelialized dermal pedicle. Closure with spoke-wheel suture pattern. (3) DOUBLE-INCISION WITH FREE NIPPLE GRAFT: Most patients with significant volume/long-term binder use. First incision just inferior to IMF, second on top of breast. Nipple grafts ~2.4 x 2.0 cm oval. Best for grade II+ ptosis and moderate-poor elasticity. (4) INFERIOR PEDICLE: Additional option. All techniques: obliterate IMF, liposuction for contour (lateral chest wall, preaxillary fat), send all tissue to pathology. WPATH requires 1 letter; no testosterone prerequisite in adults.", "notes": "Revisionary surgery rate ~40%. Scar management with massage and silicone sheeting at 3 weeks. Delay revision 4-6 months for edema resolution.", "source": "grabbsmith"}, {"topic": "Chest surgery", "subtopic": "Feminizing breast augmentation", "question": "What are the unique considerations for transfeminine breast augmentation compared to cisgender women?", "answer": "Key anatomic differences: (1) Nipples more LATERAL than in cisgender women; (2) Sternum and chest wall are WIDER, making midline cleavage difficult to achieve (counsel patients); (3) IMF is higher and more transverse; (4) Breasts often constricted/tuberous-appearing, may need parenchymal scoring to redrape over implant; (5) Wider pectoralis major muscle limits medial implant extent in subpectoral plane. Technique: 6 cm IMF incision at desired IMF location (may be lower than existing). Implant placed with nipple centered on most projecting aspect. Subpectoral: more natural superior slope but limits medial placement. Subglandular: higher capsular contracture risk but better breast mount definition for wide sternums. WPATH requires 1 letter and recommends 12 months estrogen. Hold estrogen preoperatively for VTE prevention. Screening mammography for patients >40 on feminizing hormones.", "notes": "Postop: superior strap for subpectoral augmentations to keep implants low. Underwire bra to reinforce IMF if significant IMF work done.", "source": "grabbsmith"}];
